<BLOCK2><N>B.</N><TI>The Parties</TI>
<P>2. The plaintiff, Al Way (<BOLD>&ldquo;Way&rdquo;</BOLD>), is an individual residing in the City of Waterloo, in the Province of Ontario.</P>
<P>3. The plaintiffs, Kingsley Financial Inc. (<BOLD>&ldquo;Kingsley&rdquo;</BOLD>) and Triumph Financial Holdings Inc. (<BOLD>&ldquo;Triumph&rdquo;</BOLD>), are corporations incorporated pursuant to the laws of the Province of Ontario. Way is an officer and director of both Kingsley and Triumph.</P>
<P>4. The defendant Gordon Schembri (<BOLD>&ldquo;Schembri&rdquo;</BOLD>), is an individual residing in the City of Waterloo, in the Province of Ontario. At all times and in all respects, he was the directing mind and controlling principal of the corporate defendants.</P>
<P>5. The defendants, Schembri Financial Limited (<BOLD>&ldquo;Schembri Financial&rdquo;</BOLD>), 1765998 Ontario Inc., 41 Columbia Inc., King &amp; Columbia Inc., 69 Columbia St. Inc., 5 Rittenhouse Inc., The Block Inc., The Block I Inc. and The Block II Inc. are corporations incorporated pursuant to the laws of the Province of Ontario. Schembri is an officer and director of each of these companies.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><N>C.</N><TI>The Shareholder Agreement</TI>
<P>6. On or about April 2, 2008, Kingsley, Schembri Financial, Triumph, Way and Schembri entered into a shareholder agreement in respect of the shares of Triumph (the <BOLD>&ldquo;Shareholder Agreement&rdquo;</BOLD>).</P>
<P>7. Pursuant to the Shareholder Agreement, Schembri Financial, Schembri and any entity in which Schembri has an interest, agreed not to compete with Triumph or Kingsley. They further agreed to:
<P1>(a) present any and all prospective real estate development opportunities in the Regional Municipality of Waterloo to Kingsley and Triumph;</P1>
<P1>(b) provide both Kingsley and Triumph fifteen days to determine whether either of them were interested in any such prospective real estate development opportunities presented by Schembri Financial and Schembri; and</P1>
<P1>(c) only pursue any such prospective real estate development opportunities if and when fifteen days have passed after presenting same to Kingsley and Triumph and if neither of Kingsley and Triumph indicated in writing that one of them will pursue such prospective real estate development opportunity;</P1>
as expressly stipulated in Article 13 of the Shareholder Agreement (the <BOLD>&ldquo;Shareholder Agreement Provisions&rdquo;</BOLD>).</P>
<P>8. The plaintiffs state that Schembri Financial and Schembri breached the Shareholder Agreement Provisions and are liable to pay the plaintiffs damages arising therefrom (the <BOLD>&ldquo;Shareholder Agreement Breaches&rdquo;</BOLD>). Particulars of the Shareholder Agreement Breaches known to the plaintiffs at this time are set out in paragraphs 11 to 66 below.</P>
<P>9. Further, Schembri Financial and Schembri were fiduciaries of Triumph. They owed fiduciary duties as follows:
<P1>(a) to act honestly and openly having regard to the development opportunities that are governed by the Shareholder Agreement;</P1>
<P1>(b) not to appropriate for their benefit any development opportunity that was subject to the Shareholder Agreement Provisions; and</P1>
<P1>(c) to comply with the Shareholder Agreement Provisions.</P1>
(the <BOLD>&ldquo;Schembri Fiduciary Duties&rdquo;</BOLD>).</P>
<P>10. The plaintiffs state that Schembri Financial and Schembri breached the Schembri Fiduciary Duties and are liable to pay the plaintiffs damages arising therefrom (the <BOLD>&ldquo;Schembri Fiduciary Duty Breaches&rdquo;</BOLD>). Particulars of the Schembri Fiduciary Duty Breaches known to the plaintiffs at this time are set out in paragraphs 11 to 66 below.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><N>D.</N><TI>The Conspiracy, the Shareholder Agreement Breaches and the Schembri Fiduciary Duty Breaches Regarding 1765998 Ontario Inc.</TI>
<P>11. On or about August 22, 2008, Schembri caused 1765998 Ontario Inc. to be incorporated.</P>
<P>12. 1765998 Ontario Inc. is a corporation wholly-owned and controlled by Schembri.</P>
<P>13. On or about December 17, 2008, 1765998 Ontario Inc. purchased 61 Columbia.</P>
<P>14. On or about May 6, 2009, 1765998 Ontario Inc. purchased 59 Columbia.</P>
<P>15. In breach of the Shareholder Agreement Provisions and the Schembri Fiduciary Duties, neither Schembri Financial nor Schembri presented Kingsley or Triumph with the prospective real estate development opportunity in respect of 59 Columbia and 61 Columbia (the <BOLD>&ldquo;61 Columbia Opportunity&rdquo;</BOLD>).</P>
<P>16. Schembri Financial and Schembri conspired with 1765998 Ontario Inc. to purchase and develop 59 Columbia and 61 Columbia. Pursuant to this conspiracy, they intentionally failed to present the 61 Columbia Opportunity to Kingsley and Triumph with full knowledge of and in breach of the Shareholder Agreement Provisions and the Schembri Fiduciary Duties. To the contrary, they converted and misappropriated the 61 Columbia Opportunity for their own benefit to the exclusion of the plaintiffs. Consequently, the plaintiffs have suffered loss and damages. Full particulars of the conspiracy are within the knowledge of Schembri Financial, Schembri and 1765998 Ontario Inc. and not the plaintiffs.</P>
<P>17. 1765998 Ontario Inc. and Schembri hold title and beneficial interest in 59 Columbia and 61 Columbia, in trust, for the plaintiffs.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><N>E.</N><TI>The Conspiracy, the Shareholder Agreement Breaches and the Schembri Fiduciary Duty Breaches Regarding 41 Columbia Inc.</TI>
<P>18. On or about April 7, 2010, Schembri caused 41 Columbia Inc. to be incorporated.</P>
<P>19. 41 Columbia Inc. is a corporation wholly-owned and controlled by Schembri.</P>
<P>20. On or about April 30, 2010, 41 Columbia Inc. purchased 39 Columbia and 41 Columbia.</P>
<P>21. In breach of the Shareholder Agreement Provisions and the Schembri Fiduciary Duties, neither Schembri Financial nor Schembri presented Kingsley or Triumph with the prospective real estate development opportunity in respect of 39 Columbia and 41 Columbia (the <BOLD>&ldquo;41 Columbia Opportunity&rdquo;</BOLD>).</P>
<P>22. Schembri Financial and Schembri conspired with 41 Columbia Inc. to purchase and develop 39 Columbia and 41 Columbia. Pursuant to this conspiracy, they intentionally failed to present the 41 Columbia Opportunity to Kingsley and Triumph with full knowledge of and in breach of the Shareholder Agreement Provisions and the Schembri Fiduciary Duties. To the contrary, they converted and misappropriated the 41 Columbia Opportunity for their own benefit to the exclusion of the plaintiffs. Consequently, the plaintiffs have suffered loss and damages. Full particulars of the conspiracy are within the knowledge of Schembri Financial, Schembri and 41 Columbia Inc. and not the plaintiffs.</P>
