<BLOCK1><TI><UNDER>AMENDED</UNDER> STATEMENT OF DEFENCE</TI>
<P>1. The Defendants deny all allegations in the <UNDER>Fresh as Amended</UNDER> Statement of Claim unless otherwise expressly admitted herein.</P>
<BLOCK2><TI>Defendants' Position</TI>
<P>2. The Defendants Gordon Schembri (&ldquo;Schembri&rdquo;) and Schembri Financial Limited (&ldquo;Schembri Financial&rdquo;) acknowledge that they entered into the Shareholder Agreement as that term is defined in the Statement of Claim.</P>
<P>3. The Plaintiff's claim is based upon Article 13 of the Shareholder Agreement (the Non-Competition Provision).</P>
<P>4. The Defendants allege that the Non-Competition provision is contrary to public policy, ambiguous, too broad and unnecessary to protect the Plaintiffs' legitimate business or commercial interests and is, in law, of no force or effect and is unenforceable.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI>Background Leading Up to the Shareholder Agreement</TI>
<P>5. Between 2005 and 2007 Schembri assembled various parcels of land in the City of Waterloo, in the Province of Ontario (the &ldquo;345 King Street Lands&rdquo;).</P>
<P>6. Schembri's intention in assembling the 345 King Street Lands were to demolish the Premises thereon and redevelop same.</P>
<P>7. Ultimately, Schembri and the Plaintiff Al Way (&ldquo;Way&rdquo;) entered into a Joint Venture Agreement (the &ldquo;JVA&rdquo;) with respect to the redevelopment of the 345 King Street lands. At that time to the knowledge of Way, Schembri was not a person of means and accordingly it was understood that Way would be required to fund and finance the development.</P>
<P>8. The JVA provided, inter alia, as follows:
<P1>(a) Schembri would receive a return of his equity and then Schembri and Way, or their designated entities, would each receive 50% of the profits from the redevelopment of the 345 King Street Lands;</P1>
<P1>(b) By reason of Schembri's limited financial resources, it was agreed that Way and his entity would be responsible for obtaining financing for the redevelopment of the 345 King Street Lands;</P1>
<P1>(c) Construction contracts would be awarded by both Way or his designated entities through an &ldquo;open book concept&rdquo; except for work performed by Jamesway Construction, a company owned and controlled by Way, which was to be a fixed price contract reflected in the agreed upon budget;</P1>
<P1>(d) A budget was agreed upon and appended to the JVA. No increase in the agreed upon budget could be made without the unanimous written agreement of both Schembri and Way through their designated entities.</P1></P>
<P>9. Way and his corporations took control of the redevelopment of 345 King Street.</P>
<P>10. As a result of the JVA, Way and his corporations owed fiduciary duties to Schembri and his corporations.</P>
<P>11. Pursuant to the JVA and the agreed upon budget the profit anticipated through the redevelopment was approximately $10 million dollars.</P>
<P>12. Ultimately the redevelopment was completed and the redeveloped 345 King Street lands were sold for approximately $29 million dollars.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI>Background relating to Triumph Financial Holdings Inc. (&ldquo;Triumph Financial&rdquo;)</TI>
<P>13. The Shareholders Agreement provided, <EM>inter alia</EM>, as follows:
<P1>(a) The Plaintiff, Kingsley Financial Inc. (&ldquo;Kingsley&rdquo;) would own 55% of the shares of Triumph Financial and Schembri Financial would own the remaining 45%;</P1>
<P1>(b) Kingsley received 55% of the said share because it was recognized that Way and his entity would be required to fund and finance any development without contribution from Schembri. Schembri Financial received 45% in recognition of Schembri's offer to assemble, acquire and rezone and obtain all required permits for the properties;</P1>
<P1>(c) Each of Way and Schembri, or their respective nominees were directors;</P1>
<P1>(d) Way was president and Schembri was secretary-treasurer;</P1>
<P1>(e) Way, as President, had the ability to sign all contracts on behalf of Triumph Financial, except in respect of matters relating to land acquisition, mortgage financing, construction budgets and project feasibility, which required the signatures of both Way and Schembri or their designates;</P1>
<P1>(f) Each of the directors had one vote and Way, as chairman, did not have any additional or casting vote. Accordingly, if Way and Schembri did hot agree, then the board of directors would be deadlocked;</P1>
<P1>(g) Unanimous shareholder approval was required for Triumph Financial:
<P2>(i) to directly or indirectly make any loans or advances, or invest in or give security for, or guarantee the debts of any other Corporation or person;</P2>
<P2>(ii) to enter into any partnership or arrangement for the sharing of profits or joint venture with any person, firm, or corporation, except in the normal course of business;</P2>
<P2>(iii) to mortgage or encumber any of its assets;</P2>
<P2>(iv) to commit to any financing arrangement with any third parties;</P2>
<P2>(v) to undertake any project without initiating project feasibility studies and construction budget approvals.</P2></P1>
<P1>(h) The invalidity of any provision of the Shareholders Agreement or any covenant contained therein would not affect the validity of any other provision or covenant therein;</P1>
<P1>(i) It was expressly agreed and understood that the Shareholders Agreement did not constitute a partnership or joint venture or joint enterprise;</P1>
<P1>(j) Way agreed to provide or acquire all financing and guarantees for any projects undertaken by Triumph Financial.</P1></P>
<P>14. At the time the Shareholders Agreement was being negotiated. 345 Kang Street had not yet started to be constructed and, to the knowledge of Way, Schembri's financial situation had not changed.</P>
<P>15. In anticipation of entering into a Shareholder Agreement, Schembri assembled and acquired three properties, one in each of Oshawa, Waterloo and London, in the Province of Ontario, for redevelopment. This was all done before 345 King Street construction commenced and before and during the negotiations of the Shareholder's Agreement.</P>
<P>16. Pursuant to the Shareholders Agreement it was contemplated that the redevelopment of these properties would be through Triumph Financial's Subsidiary corporations being 359 King Ontario Inc., Oxford and First St. Inc. and Simcoe and Eastwood Ave Inc. (the &ldquo;Triumph Subsidiaries&rdquo;).</P>
<P>17. Schembri or his corporate entities only received $1,400,000.00 from the profits generated by the JVA. Schembri demanded an accounting from Way. He finally received one but it was inaccurate, incomplete and fraudulent. Way refused to provide full and accurate financial disclosure and continues to refuse as of the date of this pleading. To this date, notwithstanding being ordered by this Honourable Court to do so, Way had not done so.</P>
<P>18. As a result Schembri and various corporate entities owned or controlled by him commenced a proceeding against Way and various related corporations owned or controlled by him in the Ontario Superior Court of Justice in Toronto. This action was subsequently transferred to Kitchener and now bears Court File CV-42-11 (the &ldquo;First Action&rdquo;). In the First Action Schembri and the other Plaintiffs sought significant damages as against Way and his corporations and the appointment of a receiver with respect to Oxford and First St. Inc., Simcoe and Eastwood Ave Inc. and 359 King Ontario Inc. The Defendants plead and rely upon the allegations in the Statement of Claim in the First Action in defense of this action.</P>
<P>19. In September, 2010, Justice Roberts, of the Superior Court of Justice, granted Schembri's motion and appointed a receiver over the Triumph Subsidiaries as a result of the improper wrongful and fraudulent conduct of Way and his corporations. Way refused to provide financing for the Triumph Lands of guarantee financing so as to enable the redevelopment to proceed. In this regard, Way <UNDER>fundamentally</UNDER> breached the Shareholders' Agreement. Accordingly, as a result of Way's breaches, within the receivership proceedings the Commercial Court in Toronto ordered a two phase sales process for the lands owned by the Triumph Subsidiaries.</P>
<P>20. The first phase of the Court ordered sales process enabled both Way and Schembri to deliver to the Receiver sealed offers for the acquisition of any or all of the Triumph Lands pursuant to strict timelines. In the event that the Receiver did not recommend acceptance of any offer to the Court, then phase two of the sales process would be triggered which involved the marketing and sale of the Triumph Lands on the open market.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI>359 King Street Waterloo subject to prior Court proceedings</TI>
<P>21. As indicated above, within the receivership proceeding, there was hotly contested litigation with respect to the sales process to be undertaken by the Court appointed receiver with respect to the properties owned by Triumph Subsidiaries.</P>
<P>22. The 359 King Street property was owned by 359 King Ontario Inc. a Triumph subsidiary. This property formed part of the sales process litigation. Justice Mesbur of the Commercial Court, in the Superior Court of Justice in Toronto, made a Sales Process order which was on consent.</P>
<P>23. Schembri and his corporate entities complied with the sales process order and rendered an offer to purchase 359 King Street within the timeline contemplated by the Court ordered process. Way did not abide by the sales process order.</P>
<P>24. The Court appointed receiver recommended acceptance of Schembri's offer to acquire 359 King Street. In response, Way and his corporate entities brought a motion seeking a court order discharging the Court appointed receiver.</P>
<P>25. Thereafter, Way made an offer to purchase 359 King Street from the receiver, well outside the timelines established by the Sales Process order and at a price greater than that offered by Schembri.</P>
<P>26. Way then entered into an agreement with the Receiver whereby Way agreed to withdraw his motion seeking an order discharging the Court appointed receiver in exchange for the receiver agreeing to recommend to the Court acceptance of Way's out of time offer to purchase, inter alia, 359 King Street.</P>
<P>27. Although critical of Way's behaviour, Justice Mesbur nevertheless granted an order approving the receiver's decision to sell 359 King Street to Way and/or his corporations.</P>
<P>28. Schembri appealed Justice Mesbur's order to the Ontario Court of Appeal. The Ontario Court of Appeal overturned Justice Mesbur's order and ordered that the Receiver sell 359 King Street to Schembri or his corporate entities. The Court of Appeal was critical of Way's behavior during the sales process.</P>
<P>29. Ultimately, pursuant to an order by the Ontario Court of Appeal, the lands owned by the Triumph Subsidiaries were sold pursuant to a Court ordered sale process. Pursuant to the Order of the Ontario Court of Appeal Schembri or his corporate entities were awarded the right to purchase 359 King Street, in Waterloo Ontario. This is the property that forms part of the Plaintiff's complaint in the within action as particularized in paragraphs <UNDER>24&ndash;31</UNDER> of the <UNDER>Fresh as Amended</UNDER> Statement of Claim. Ultimately King and Columbia Inc., a Schembri corporation, acquired title to 359 King St.</P>
<P>30. Accordingly, in accordance with the Ontario Court of Appeal, the Receiver, with Court Approval, obtained a vesting order and completed the sale of 359 King Street to Schembri's corporate entity, being King &amp; Columbia Inc.</P>
<P>31. The vesting order by its express terms precludes the Plaintiffs from asserting any action with respect to the Defendants' acquisition of 359 King Street.</P>
<P>32. King &amp; Columbia Inc. acquired 359 King Street pursuant to a Court ordered sales process and the order of the Ontario Court of Appeal and the vesting order. This acquisition was hotly contested by Way and his corporate entities.</P>
<P>33. During the Court ordered sales process, the proceedings before the Court of Appeal and the motion for the vesting order, Way never raised the Non-Competition Provision as entitling him to in any way participate in the acquisition of 359 King Street.</P>
<P>34. The Defendants allege that the Plaintiffs are estopped from asserting any claim whatsoever with respect to 359 King Street by reason of the aforesaid Court proceedings, the order of the Ontario Court of Appeal and the vesting order.</P>
<P>35. Notwithstanding the foregoing the Plaintiffs have asserted a claim against the Defendants alleging conspiracy and breach of fiduciary duties by reason of the acquisition of 359 King Street pursuant to the aforesaid Court proceedings in the First Action.</P>
<P>36. The Defendants allege that the Plaintiffs could have acquired 359 King Street had they complied with the Court ordered sales process and not abused the process of the Court as was found by the Ontario Court of Appeal and Justice Mesbur.</P>
<P>37. The Defendants allege that the Plaintiffs are attempting a collateral attack on the order of the Ontario Court of Appeal and the vesting order by asserting a claim in relation to 359 King Street.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI>Columbia St.</TI>
<P>38. 41 Columbia St. was first under contract by Schembri in 2009 while Way and Schembri were still partners. Way attended at the site and walked the property. Way was advised by Schembri that Schembri intended to construct student housing on the site. Way advised Schembri that he had no interest in the property. Way also knew that Schembri was intending to acquire other properties within the vicinity of the universities and develop same as student housing.</P>
<P>39. Way advised Schembri that he had no interest in any acquisition or development of student housing in Waterloo Region. In fact, Triumph Financial or another Way entity had entered into an agreement of purchase and sale with respect to 61 Columbia St. Since Way had no interest in developing property on Columbia St. or in student housing he assigned the Agreement of Purchase and Sale to one of Schembri's corporate entities. Ultimately Schembri acquired 61 Columbia St. and constructed student housing thereon.</P>
<P>40. To Way's knowledge, Schembri, through his corporate entities, has acquired and developed student housing at 26, 35, 41, 61, 69 and 75 Columbia St.</P>
<P>41. Way was fully aware of Schembri's acquisition of these properties and the development of student housing thereon. In fact, as set out above, Way's corporate entity voluntarily assigned an Agreement of Purchase and Sale with respect to 61 Columbia St. to Schembri's corporate entity.</P>
<P>42. Accordingly, these Defendants allege that the Plaintiffs have no interest whatsoever with respect to any development by Schembri or his corporate entities in Waterloo, given the foregoing, and Way's express advice that he was not at all interested in pursuing student housing in the region of Waterloo.</P>
<P>43. <UNDER>The Plaintiffs are estopped from asserting their claim.</UNDER></P>
<P>44. <UNDER>The Plaintiffs' claim was asserted more than two years after they became aware that the Columbia properties were acquired and accordingly they are statute barred.</UNDER></P>
<P>45. <UNDER>The Defendants allege that the properties acquired by The Block Inc., The Block I Inc. and The Block II Inc. (the &ldquo;Block Properties&rdquo;) were acquired for purpose of development and construction of student housing. As set out above, the Plaintiffs have no interest in the Block Properties by reason of the fact that they are to be developed for student housing. The Non-Competition provision of the Shareholders Agreement (which terms defined below) while unenforceable on its own, does not, in any event, relate or affect any real estate development opportunity involving student housing.</UNDER></P>
<P>46. <UNDER>Furthermore, the Block Properties were acquired after:</UNDER>
<P1>(a) <UNDER>Way breached the JVA;</UNDER></P1>
<P1>(b) <UNDER>Way defrauded Schembri and his corporations;</UNDER></P1>
<P1>(c) <UNDER>The Triumph Subsidiaries were placed into receivership;</UNDER></P1>
<P1>(d) <UNDER>The relationship, both contractual and otherwise, as between Way and Schembri was irrevocably destroyed.</UNDER></P1></P>
<P>47. <UNDER>The Block Corporations owed no duty to the Plaintiffs as alleged and entered no conspiracy as alleged.</UNDER></P>
<P>48. <UNDER>5 Rittenhouse Inc. owes no duty to the Plaintiffs and entered into no conspiracy. The Plaintiffs have no claim with respect to any property owned by 5 Rittenhouse Inc.</UNDER></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI>The Shareholders Agreement</TI>
<P>49. By reason of the conduct of the Plaintiffs and the Defendants in the First Action, the Defendants allege that the Non-Competition Provision is not binding. The Plaintiffs have committed fundamental breaches of the Shareholder Agreement. As a result they cannot rely on Article 13 of the Shareholders Agreement.</P>
<P>50. Furthermore, there has been a fundamental and irrevocable destruction of the relationship between Way and Schembri and their respective corporations. It is inconceivable that they could or should ever be involved in any business venture together.</P>
<P>51. In this regard the Defendants allege that the Non-Competition Provision was predicated upon all parties acting in good faith and in compliance with their contractual and common law duties.</P>
<P>52. The Plaintiffs breached their contractual and common law duties owed to the Defendants and accordingly cannot rely upon or enforce the Non-Competition Provision.</P>
<P>53. Article 13 of the Shareholders Agreement is unenforceable.</P>
<P>54. The Non-competition Agreement, in its entirety, provides as follows:
<QUOTE><BLOCK2><N><EM>13</EM>.</N><TI><EM>NON-COMPETITION</EM></TI>
<P><EM>During the period which SCHEMBRI FINANCIAL is a shareholder of the Corporation, it shall have the ongoing obligation to present to KINGSLEY FINANCIAL and the Corporation all real estate development opportunities (the &ldquo;Project&rdquo;) which it may have acquired within the Regional Municipality of Waterloo. This obligation to KINGSLEY FINANCIAL and the Corporation shall also extend to GORDON SCHEMBRI personally and any other legal entity in which he has an interest, either directly or indirectly, financially or otherwise. KINGSLEY FINANCIAL and the Corporation shall have FIFTEEN (15) days following the presentation of the Project to them to determine if it is economically feasible using the typical budget model consistency utilized by them in such circumstances and, if at the expiry of the FIFTEEN (15) day period neither of them have indicated to SCHEMBRI FINANCIAL in writing that it is taking on the Project, then SCHEMBRI FINANCIAL (or its designate) shall be free to pursue the Project without the involvement of KINGSLEY FINANCIAL or the Corporation</EM>.</P></BLOCK2></QUOTE>
<P1>Shareholders Agreement, para. 13, p. 17.</P1></P>
<P>55. The Non-Competition provision is not enforceable for the following reasons:
<P1>(a) The Non-Competition provision has no temporal limits. It states that during the period which Schembri Financial is a shareholder of the Triumph Financial, it is bound by the Non-competition covenant. However, Schembri Financial cannot divest itself of the shares it owns in Triumph Financial without the consent of Way. Way can withhold his consent.</P1>
<P1>(b) The Shareholders Agreement is only terminated if Schembri and Way consent in writing.</P1>
<P1>(c) Accordingly, Way, and Way alone, can determine when and if Schembri Financial can cease to be a shareholder of Triumph Financial or when the Shareholders Agreement will terminate.</P1>
<P1>(d) The Defendants allege that a Non-competition provision that has no finite time limit is unreasonable and unenforceable as it is not necessary to protect the legitimate commercial interest of the party for whose benefit the Non-competition provision applies.</P1>
<P1>(e) There appears to be an obligation on Schembri Financial to &ldquo;present&rdquo; real estate development opportunities it may have acquired in Waterloo. The Agreement does not stipulate what had to be &ldquo;presented&rdquo; or for that matter disclosed or whether Way was required to compensate Schembri for such disclosure.</P1>
<P1>(f) The Non-Competition provision provides an ongoing obligation on Schembri Financial to present to <UNDER>both</UNDER> Kingsley Financial and Triumph Financial all real estate development opportunities (the &ldquo;Project&rdquo;) which it may have acquired within the Regional Municipality of Waterloo. Accordingly, the obligation is on Schembri Financial to present such opportunities to two entities. Either, none or both could accept. There is no mechanism or provision to determine what would occur if both Triumph Financial and Kingsley Financial advised that they were &ldquo;taking on the Project&rdquo;. There is no mechanism or provision to determine;
<P2>(i) What their involvement would be;</P2>
<P2>(ii) The percentage of their interests;</P2>
<P2>(iii) The requirement of each or both to fund;</P2>
<P2>(iv) The role of each or either or both of them; and</P2>
<P2>(v) The role, involvement or ownership interest of Schembri.</P2></P1>
<P1>(g) The obligation is triggered when a real estate development is acquired. However, &ldquo;acquired&rdquo; is not a defined term. It could mean a variety of things, for example:
<P2>(i) When Schembri became aware of a property's existence;</P2>
<P2>(ii) When Schembri made an offer to purchase a property;</P2>
<P2>(iii) When an offer to purchase was accepted;</P2>
<P2>(iv) When an offer to purchase became firm;</P2>
<P2>(v) When the property was purchased and closed.</P2></P1>
<P1>(h) The Non-Competition provision provides that this &ldquo;obligation&rdquo; extends to Schembri personally and &ldquo;any other legal entity in which he has an interest, either directly or indirectly, financial or otherwise&rdquo;. The Non-competition provision therefore purports to bind non-parties to the Shareholders Agreement. This is not enforceable. Furthermore, the term &ldquo;financial or otherwise&rdquo; is not defined and is ambiguous and incapable of enforcement. Furthermore, the Non-competition provision appears to bind, by way of example, a publicly traded corporation if Schembri owned a share in it. This is not enforceable; it is too broad, it is unnecessary to protect a legitimate business interest of the Plaintiffs.</P1>
<P1>(i) The Non-Competition provision provides that Kingsley Financial and Triumph Financial have 15 days following the &ldquo;presentation of the Project to them to determine if it is economically feasible using the typical budget model consistently utilized by them in such circumstances&rdquo;. With respect to this:
<P2>(i) The presentation of the &ldquo;Project&rdquo; would be the &ldquo;Project&rdquo; that Schembri Financial or Schembri, or any other legal entity in which Schembri has an interest, directly or indirectly, financial or otherwise, had already acquired. The Project could be any type of real estate development opportunity, such as a lease, purchase or lease of vacant land, or farm land or zoned land of any nature, or type or use and for any purpose.</P2>
<P2>(ii) Kingsley Financial and Triumph Financial are required to use the &ldquo;typical budget model consistently utilized by them in such circumstances&rdquo; in order to determine if the Project is economically feasible. However, there is no typical budget model consistently utilized by Triumph Financial or Kingsley Financial in existence. There is no typical budget model in existence. Triumph Financial has never had a typical budget model and never had a budget that was approved in accordance with the Shareholders Agreement.</P2>
<P2>(iii) Kingsley Financial has never had a typical budget model or budget model.</P2>
<P2>(iv) The only budget in which Schembri and Way were involved was with respect to 345 King Street. That was the budget that gave rise to the First Action by reason of Way's fraudulent manipulation of the budget and his fraudulent conduct in connection therewith.</P2>
<P2>(v) Even aside the fact that there are no typical budget models consistently utilized by Triumph Financial and Kingsley Financial or any typical budget models at all, the term &ldquo;in such circumstances&rdquo; is impossible to define. As stated above, the Non-competition provision purports to apply to all real estate development opportunities. Kingsley Financial and Triumph Financial have no typical budget models for &ldquo;such circumstances&rdquo;.</P2></P1>
<P1>(j) The Non-Competition provision goes on to state that at the expiry of 15 days if &ldquo;neither of them (Kingsley Financial and/or Triumph Financial) have indicated to Schembri Financial in writing that it is taking on the Project&rdquo; then Schembri Financial can pursue the Project without their involvement. The Non-Competition provision does not set out what &ldquo;taking on the Project&rdquo; means. It does not set out:
<P2>(i) Whether Kingsley Financial and/or Triumph Financial would develop the Project in partnership with Schembri Financial or as a joint venture, or as a limited partnership, or as a co-tenancy;</P2>
<P2>(ii) Whether Kingsley Financial and Triumph Financial would take over 100% of the Project, and if so, for what price;</P2>
<P2>(iii) What would happen if both Kingsley Financial and Triumph Financial decided to take on the project;</P2>
<P2>(iv) Whether the entities, being Triumph Financial, Kingsley Financial and Schembri, would own equal percentages or some other division, or what such divisions would be based upon;</P2>
<P2>(v) Who would fund the Project;</P2>
<P2>(vi) Who would provide the guarantees for the Project;</P2>
<P2>(vii) How Schembri Financial be compensated for its equity and time spent in acquiring the Project;</P2>
<P2>(viii) How Schembri Financial would be compensated in the event that it enhanced the value of the underlying real estate development by way of an assembly and re-zoning of property; and</P2>
<P2>(ix) What &ldquo;taking on the Project&rdquo; means or how it would be done.</P2></P1>
<P1>(k) Pursuant to the provisions of the Shareholders Agreement, Way cannot unilaterally make decisions on behalf of Triumph Financial with respect to matters relating to land acquisition, mortgage financing, construction budgets, and project feasibility, or decide to encumber Triumph Financial's assets, or commit to any financing arrangements with third parties, or undertake any project without project feasibility and construction budget approvals, all of which require the consent of Schembri Financial. It is impossible to determine how the Non-Competition provisions and the other conflicting provisions of the Shareholders Agreement would be reconciled.</P1>
<P1>(l) The Non-Competition provision is not necessary to protect the Plaintiffs' legitimate business and commercial interests.</P1>
<P1>(m) The Non-Competition provision makes no commercial or logical sense. In this regard, the Non-Competition provision does not address:
<P2>(i) Why the parties would agree that Schembri would be free to expend, what would be considerable time, effort and capital to acquire, assemble and re-zone a project only to potentially have Triumph Financial or Kingsley Financial advise in writing that it or they are &ldquo;taking on the Project&rdquo;;</P2>
<P2>(ii) Whether Schembri would be excluded from the development of a project if Kingsley Financial decided to &ldquo;take it on&rdquo;;</P2>
<P2>(iii) Whether Schembri Financial would be compensated if they did this, what compensation would be provided or whether or not compensation is even required;</P2>
<P2>(iv) Whether Schembri Financial would continue having an interest and if so, on what basis and in what percentage. For example, if Schembri Financial agreed that Triumph Financial would take on the Project and Kingsley Financial also wanted to take on the Project, the provision does not allow any determination of the division of ownership and profits or responsibility for liability;</P2></P1>
<P1>(n) The Non-Competition provision indicates that if the required written notice is not provided then Schembri Financial can proceed with the Project &ldquo;without the involvement of Kingsley Financial or the Corporation&rdquo;. However, nowhere in the Non-competition provision does it set out what, if any, involvement Kingsley Financial and/or the Corporation (Triumph Financial) would have in the Project had they provided written notice.</P1></P>
<P>56. Schembri Financial's and Schembri's main business is the development of student housing, primarily in the Regional Municipality of Waterloo. The Plaintiffs are not in that business. Accordingly, the Defendants are not competing with the Plaintiffs in any event.</P>
<P>57. The Defendants also allege that Way, as corporate entities, have ceased any activity in the real estate development business. Way is preparing to retire and in the process of divesting himself of his real estate assets. Such assets are currently for sale. Accordingly, the Non-competition provision provides no benefit to Way or his corporate entities, given his decision to withdraw from the business.</P>
<P>58. As a result of the Receivership proceedings in the First Action, Triumph Financial is effectively not carrying on any business. Way has committed material breaches of the shareholders Agreement and accordingly cannot rely on it in support of this claim.</P>
<P>59. The Defendants deny that they have breached any contract with the Plaintiffs.</P>
<P>60. The Defendants deny that they have converted or misappropriated any monies.</P>
<P>61. The Defendants deny they owe any fiduciary duty to any of the Plaintiffs and, in the alternative, that they have breached any such fiduciary duty.</P>
<P>62. The Defendants have not entered into any conspiracy.</P>
<P>63. The Defendants deny that the Plaintiffs have suffered any damages and put the Plaintiffs to the strict proof thereof.</P>
<P>71. The Plaintiffs' action is statute barred and the Defendants rely upon the <EM>Limitations Act</EM> of Ontario in this regard.</P>
<P>72. The Defendants therefore allege that the within action should be dismissed with costs on a substantial indemnity basis.</P>
