<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="I">AFFIDAVIT OF ALVEN J. WAY (sworn September 16, 2016)</TI>
<P><BOLD>I, ALVEN J. WAY,</BOLD> businessman, of the City of Waterloo, in the Province of Ontario, make oath and say as follows.</P>
<BLOCK2><N>A.</N><TI>Preliminary Comments</TI>
<P>1. I am a plaintiff, and a director of each of the corporate plaintiffs, in this proceeding (the <BOLD>&ldquo;ROFR Action&rdquo;</BOLD>), and a defendant, plaintiff by counterclaim in a related action bearing Court File No Court File No. C-42-11 (the <BOLD>&ldquo;Main Action&rdquo;</BOLD>). As such, I have personal knowledge of the facts deposed to herein except where knowledge of such facts is stated to be on information and belief and, where so stated, I verily believe those facts to be true.</P>
<P>2. This affidavit is sworn in support of a motion for an order:
<P1>(a) directing the defendants to deliver a further and better affidavit of documents;</P1>
<P1>(b) requiring the defendant, Gordon Schembri (<BOLD>&ldquo;Schembri&rdquo;</BOLD>) to attend an examination for discovery from November 28 to December 16, 2016, inclusive in the Main Action and in the ROFR Action;</P1>
<P1>(c) prohibiting the defendants from bringing a motion for summary judgment, in whole or in part;</P1>
<P1>(d) requiring Schembri to reimburse Way forthwith for his legal fees and disbursements incurred during the period from April 3 to September 4, 2014, inclusive; and</P1>
<P1>(e) costs of this motion on a substantial indemnity basis payable forthwith.</P1></P>
<P>3. This motion has been necessitated by the bully litigation tactics that Schembri has engaged in over many years, including, among other things, deceiving me, my counsel and the Court by representing repeatedly for several months that he was bringing a motion for summary judgement in the ROFR Action (the <BOLD>&ldquo;Schembri ROFR SJ Motion&rdquo;</BOLD>).</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><N>B.</N><TI>Background</TI>
<P>4. Schembri commenced the Main Action in Toronto in February, 2010. I caused the Main Action to be transferred to Kitchener in 2011. Schembri has been represented throughout by James Wortz man (<BOLD>&ldquo;Wortzman&rdquo;</BOLD>) at Teplitsky, Colson LLP.</P>
<P>5. Schembri has amended the Statement of Claim in the Main Action on two separate occasions. Presently in the Main Action, Schembri and his companies are claiming relief including damages exceeding $90 million.</P>
<P>6. The Main Action is defended. I (along with my companies) am represented by Heath Whiteley (<BOLD>&ldquo;Whiteley&rdquo;</BOLD>), formerly of Gowlings LLP in Toronto and now a sole practitioner. Whiteley has been involved in the Main Action since the fall of 2010.</P>
<P>7. In addition to defending the Main Action, I have asserted a counterclaim, initially in part, to the effect that Schembri breached the Shareholder Agreement by failing to comply with the right of first refusal provisions contained therein (the <BOLD>&ldquo;ROFR Provisions&rdquo;</BOLD>) so as to allow me to participate in the acquisition and development of other properties located in Waterloo.</P>
<P>8. The damages suffered by me resulting from Schembri's breach of the ROFR Provisions subsequently became the subject matter of the ROFR Action.</P>
<BLOCK3><TI>Documentary Disclosure</TI>
<P>9. I swore an affidavit of documents on February 27, 2014.</P>
<P>10. I was informed by Cole and believed that he notified Wortzman on February 20, 2014 of the types of documents we expected Schembri to produce. A copy of an email sent February 20, 2014 setting out an outline of the types of documents is attached hereto and marked as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;A&rdquo;.</BOLD></P>
<P>11. Schembri swore an affidavit of documents on September 30, 2014 (the <BOLD>&ldquo;Schembri AoD&rdquo;</BOLD>). A copy of the Schembri AoD is attached hereto and marked as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;B&rdquo;.</BOLD></P>
<P>12. The Schembri AoD ignored the outline set out in Exhibit &ldquo;A&rdquo; and, for the most part, lists court documents in the Main Action. Of note, Schembri did not even list the agreements of purchase and sale for the properties that are the subject matter of the ROFR Action. These agreements would reveal the dates on which Schembri offered to purchase the properties.</P></BLOCK3></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><N>C.</N><TI>The ROFR Timetable Order (Sept/14)</TI>
<P>13. Cliff Cole (<BOLD>&ldquo;Cole&rdquo;</BOLD>), a lawyer at Gowlings LLP in Toronto, and Whiteley made extensive efforts, unsuccessfully, over several months to conclude an agreement with Schembri in respect of numerous procedural matters in both the Main Action and the ROFR Action as reflected in the correspondence exchanged between them and Wortzman as follows:
