<P1>A copy of the foregoing correspondence is attached hereto and marked as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;C&rdquo;.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>14. I was informed by Cole and believed that he and Wortzman agreed that discoveries in the Main Action would be held in July and August, 2014. I then set aside those dates in my calendar and arranged for my absence from my business.</P>
<P>15. I was also informed by Cole and believed that Wortzman represented that Schembri would be bringing the Schembri ROFR SJ Motion.</P>
<P>16. I have reviewed the correspondence attached hereto and marked as Exhibit &ldquo;C&rdquo; and note the following:
<QUOTE><BLOCK2><TI>Wortzman's letter dated May 26, 2014</TI>
<P><EM>We have instructions now to bring a motion for summary judgment seeking a dismissal of [the ROFR Action]</EM>.</P>
<P>&ellipsis;</P>
<P><EM>Our motion for summary judgement can be served within the next two or three weeks. Accordingly, if Ms. Gupta can advise as to a potential return date we can agree upon a timetable for that motion</EM>.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI>Wortzman's letter dated June 4, 2014</TI>
<P><EM>I will endeavour to serve our Motion Record regarding summary judgment...by June 20, 2014. Once that Motion Record is served we will discuss how long you need to file responding material and the timetable required for the motion</EM>.</P></BLOCK2></QUOTE></P>
<P>17. I have also reviewed the letter from Wortzman dated July 9, 2014 (after my counsel served the motion record that led to the ROFR Timetable Order (defined in paragraph 21 below)), and note that Wortzman represented he was &ldquo;<EM>finalizing the motion record for partial summary judgment&rdquo;</EM>. A copy of the letter dated July 9, 2014 is attached hereto and marked as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;D&rdquo;.</BOLD></P>
<P>18. As a result of my counsel's extensive efforts being unsuccessful, I caused motions to be brought in both the Main Action and the ROFR Action for various relief, including another revised timetable in the Main Action and a timetable in connection with the Schembri ROFR SJ Motion.</P>
<P>19. Despite suggesting otherwise, Schembri did not serve any responding materials or conduct any cross-examination, and the orders in the Main Action and the ROFR Action were issued on consent.</P>
<P>20. By Order of Justice Broad dated September 4, 2014 in the Main Action (the <BOLD>&ldquo;Main Action Timetable Order&rdquo;</BOLD>), the Court, among other things, scheduled the examinations for discovery to be conducted on December 9 to 19, 2014, inclusive, and January 12 to 16, 2015, inclusive. I set aside those dates in my calendar and arranged for my absence from my business. A copy of the Main Action Timetable Order is attached hereto and marked as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;E&rdquo;.</BOLD></P>
<P>21. By Order of Justice Broad dated September 4, 2014 (the <BOLD>&ldquo;ROFR Timetable Order&rdquo;</BOLD>), the Court, among other things, imposed a timetable in paragraph 5 for the conduct of the Schembri ROFR SJ Motion, including the requirement that the motion record had to be served on or before September 30, 2014. A copy of the ROFR Timetable Order is attached hereto and marked as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;F&rdquo;.</BOLD></P>
<P>22. The timetable in the Main Action (for the examinations for discovery) had to accommodate the timetable for the Schembri ROFR SJ Motion (including the cross-examinations in connection therewith).</P>
<P>23. Schembri breached the ROFR Timetable Order by failing to serve his motion record by September 30, 2014.</P>
<P>24. I am informed by Whiteley and believe that Cole followed up with Wortzman, who responded on October 20, 2014 that his <EM>&ldquo;instructions are to proceed with a motion for summary judgment in the ROFR action&rdquo;</EM>. A copy of the correspondence between Cole and Wortzman in this regard is attached as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;G&rdquo;.</BOLD></P>
<P>25. But for Schembri's deception, the examinations for discovery in the Main Action would have been scheduled to start in July, 2014. I believe that Schembri perpetrated this deception for the purpose of avoiding his examination for discovery (thereby delaying the Main Action and the ROFR Action) and increasing the amount of costs being incurred by me in defending myself and my companies.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><N>D.</N><TI>My Examination for Discovery</TI>
<P>26. My examination for discovery in the Main Action commenced on December 15, 2014. Wortzman examined me for thirteen days over five months, and completed his examination for discovery on April 30, 2015. The last three days of my examination were all on dates requested by Wortzman and accommodated by me and my counsel. A copy of the correspondence evidencing such accommodation is attached hereto and marked as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;H&rdquo;.</BOLD></P>
<P>27. On or about the eleventh day of my examination for discovery, Wortzman began asking me questions about the ROFR Action. I did not expect him to do so because of his repeated representations about the Schembri ROFR SJ Motion, and the fact that the Notice of Examination he served on December 22, 2014 related to the Main Action only. I believe this is just another example of Schembri's bully litigation tactics. A copy of this notice of examination is attached hereto and marked as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;I&rdquo;.</BOLD></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><N>E.</N><TI>Relief Sought</TI>
<P>28. I believe the deficient documentary disclosure by Schembri warrants the relief sought in paragraph 2 (a). I further believe the extensive delay and the deceit perpetrated by Schembri warrants the relief sought in paragraph 2 (b), (c), (d) and (e).</P>
<P>29. I swear this affidavit for the purpose stated in paragraph 2 above, and for no other or improper purpose.</P>
