<BLOCK1><TI>NOTICE OF MOTION</TI>
<P>The Defendants will make a Motion to Mr. Justice Sloan at 10:00 a.m. on a date to be fixed by the Trial Co-ordinator, or as soon after that time as the Motion can be heard at the court house, 85 Frederick Street, Kitchener, Ontario, N2H 0A7.</P>
<P><BOLD>PROPOSED METHOD OF HEARING:</BOLD> The Motion is to be heard
<P1>[ ] in writing under subrule 37.12.1(1) because it is;</P1>
<P1>[ ] in writing as an opposed motion under subrule 37.12.1(4);</P1>
<P1>[X] orally.</P1></P>
<P><BOLD>THIS MOTION IS FOR</BOLD>
<P1>(a) An Order for summary judgment dismissing the within action;</P1>
<P1>(b) A declaration that Article 13 of the Agreement (as hereinafter defined) is unenforceable and is of no force and effect;</P1>
<P1>(c) In the alternative, partial summary judgment dismissing the within action as against any one or more of the Defendants;</P1>
<P1>(d) An order that any transcript of any cross-examinations of any party be treated for all purposes as a transcript of an Examination for Discovery at the trial of this action in the event this motion is dismissed;</P1>
<P1>(e) In the alternative, an order bifurcating the within proceeding so that the trial on the issue of liability proceeds first and if successful the issue of damages be heard along with an order bifurcating the discoveries and productions;</P1>
<P1>(f) In the alternative an order dismissing the action as against King &amp; Columbia Inc. and striking all reference to that property from the Statement of Claim;</P1>
<P1>(g) The costs of this motion on a substantial indemnity basis, plus any and all applicable taxes; and</P1>
<P1>(h) Such further and other relief as lawyers may advise and this Honourable Court deem just.</P1></P>
<P><BOLD>THE GROUNDS FOR THE MOTION ARE</BOLD></P>
<BLOCK2><TI>Background:</TI>
<P><P1>(a) The Defendant, Gordon Schembri (&ldquo;Schembri&rdquo;), is an individual residing in the City of Waterloo, in the Province of Ontario;</P1>
<P1>(b) The Corporate Defendants are corporations incorporated pursuant to the laws of the Province of Ontario and are controlled by Schembri;</P1>
<P1>(c) The Plaintiff, Al Way (&ldquo;Way&rdquo;), is an individual residing in the City of Kitchener, in the Province of Ontario;</P1>
<P1>(d) Kingsley Financial Inc. (&ldquo;Kingsley Financial&rdquo;) is a corporation incorporated pursuant to the laws of the Province of Ontario. Way owns and controls 100% of Kingsley Financial and is an officer and director of Kingsley Financial;</P1>
<P1>(e) Triumph Financial Inc. (&ldquo;Triumph Financial&rdquo;) is a corporation incorporated pursuant to the laws of the Province of Ontario;</P1></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI>The Shareholders' Agreement:</TI>
<P><P1>(f) On or about April 2, 2008, Kingsley Financial, Schembri Financial, Triumph Financial, Way, and Schembri entered into a Shareholders' Agreement (the &ldquo;Agreement&rdquo;) with respect to the shares of Triumph Financial;</P1>
<P1>(g) At the time of the Agreement, 100 Common shares of the authorized capital of Triumph Financial were issued, with Kingsley Financial holding 55 Common shares and Schembri Financial holding 45 Common Shares;</P1>
<P1>(h) Pursuant to the Agreement, the Board of Directors consists of two directors, being Way and Schembri or their respective nominees until such time as one or more of them ceased to be a shareholder of Triumph Financial;</P1>
<P1>(i) Pursuant to paragraph 2 of the Agreement, shares cannot be transferred without the consent of the shareholders representing not less than 100 hundred per cent of the voting shares of the capital stock of Triumph Financial;</P1>
<P1>(j) The Agreement also contains a right of first refusal or non-competition clause at Article 13 (the &ldquo;Non-Compete Clause&rdquo;), which states:
<QUOTE><P><EM>During the period which SCHEMBRI FINANCIAL is a shareholder of the Corporation</EM> [Triumph Financial], <EM>it shall have the ongoing obligation to present to KINGSLEY FINANCIAL and the Corporation all real estate development opportunities (the &ldquo;Project&rdquo;) which it may have acquired within the Regional Municipality of Waterloo. This obligation to KINGSLEY FINANCIAL and the Corporation shall also extend to GORDON SCHEMBRI personally and any other legal entity in which he has an interest, either directly or indirectly, financially or otherwise. KINGSLEY FINANCIAL and the Corporation shall have FIFTEEN (15) days following the presentation of the Project to them to determine if it is economically feasible using the typical budget model consistently utilized by them in such circumstances and, if at the expiry of the FIFTEEN (15) day period neither of them have indicated to SCHEMBRI FINANCIAL in writing that it is taking on the Project, then SCHEMBRI FINANCIAL (or its designate) shall be free to pursue the Project without the involvement of KINGSLEY FINANCIAL or the Corporation</EM>.</P></QUOTE></P1></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI>The Alleged Breaches:</TI>
<P><P1>(k) The Plaintiffs allege that Schembri Financial and Schembri have breached the terms of the Agreement by conspiring with the Corporate Defendants to purchase and develop various properties without first presenting the opportunities to Kingsley Financial or Triumph Financial;</P1></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI>Relief Sought by the Plaintiffs for the Alleged Breaches:</TI>
<P><P1>(l) The Plaintiffs claim for:
<P2>(i) damages in the amount of $30,000,000 for breach of contract, conversion, misappropriation, breach of fiduciary duty, and conspiracy in connection with certain transactions pertaining to various properties;</P2>
<P2>(ii) a declaration that various properties are held by the Defendants by a constructive trust for the Plaintiffs, or any of them;</P2>
<P2>(iii) an accounting of all profits and other benefits derived by the Defendants or any of them in connection with the acquisition and development of the Lands (the &ldquo;Accounting&rdquo;);</P2>
<P2>(iv) an order directing the Defendants to pay to the Plaintiffs all amounts found owing to them pursuant to the Accounting; and</P2>
<P2>(v) punitive, aggravated, and exemplary damages in the amount of $500,000;</P2></P1></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI>The Non-Compete Clause is Unenforceable</TI>
<P><P1>(m) As a result of the wrongful actions of Way, a Receiver was appointed by Court Order of all of the assets, undertakings and properties of Oxford &amp; First Street Inc., Simcoe &amp; Eastwood Ave. Inc. and 359 King Ontario Inc., being the Triumph Subsidiaries and representing all of Triumph's assets. Triumph no longer carries on business. In essence the Receiver has stepped into the shoes of Triumph Financial. The Receivership has effectively terminated the shareholder's Agreement or at the very least the Non-Compete Clause;</P1>
<P1>(n) The Non-Compete Clause is ambiguous with respect to the obligations it purports to impose on Schembri Financial and Schembri personally. Accordingly, it is unenforceable;</P1>
<P1>(o) Additionally, the duration of the Non-Compete Clause is indefinite or undeterminable. The clause applies during the period in which Schembri Financial is a shareholder of Triumph Financial. However, the Agreement prohibits Schembri Financial from transferring shares without the consent of Way through Kingsley Financial. In effect, Schembri Financial can only cease being a shareholder of Triumph Financial with the consent of Kingsley Financial;</P1>
<P1>(p) Accordingly, the Non-Compete Clause upon which the Plaintiffs are relying is unenforceable due to:
<P2>(i) the ambiguity of the terms;</P2>
<P2>(ii) the unreasonableness of the duration of the restriction. It is endless and purports to bind Schembri's heirs for all time;</P2>
<P2>(iii) the fact that it is too broad;</P2>
<P2>(iv) the inability of a court to enforce its terms;</P2>
<P2>(v) the fact that the Plaintiffs have committed a fraudulent breach of the Agreement;</P2>
<P2>(vi) the fact that it purports to bind persons and entities that are not a party to it. For example if Schembri invested in a publically traded REIT, such REIT would be bound by the Non-Competition Clause;</P2>
<P2>(vii) the fact that it is <EM>prima facie</EM> contrary to public policy; and</P2>
<P2>(viii) the fact that Way has ceased developing real estate in Ontario and has or is in the process of winding down his business;</P2></P1>
<P1>(q) The Non-Compete Clause is too broad, is unreasonable, and is incapable of being understood or enforced;</P1>
<P1>(r) The Non&mdash;Compete Clause is not reasonably necessary for Way to protect his legitimate interests;</P1>
<P1>(s) As the Non-Compete Clause is unenforceable, there is no basis on which the Plaintiffs can claim that Schembri Financial and Schembri breached their duties under the Agreement by failing to present opportunities to Kingsley Financial or Triumph Financial;</P1>
<P1>(t) There is no genuine issue requiring a trial with respect to the within Statement of Claim as it relates to any alleged breaches of the Agreement;</P1>
<P1>(u) The Plaintiffs have committed a fundamental breach of the Shareholder's Agreement and accordingly are estopped from relying upon the non-compete clause;</P1>
<P1>(v) The Plaintiffs have fundamentally breached the Shareholder's Agreement, the Defendants have accepted the Plaintiffs' repudiation and the Shareholder's Agreement is at an end as well as any and all obligations set out therein;</P1>
<P1>(w) The Plaintiffs have committed a fraud against Schembri and Schembri Financial and accordingly are not entitled to any equitable relief;</P1>
<P1>(x) The claims of the Plaintiffs are statute barred;</P1>
<P1>(y) The claims of the Plaintiffs as against King &amp; Columbia Inc. are estopped and constitute a collateral attack on the order of the Ontario Court of Appeal and constitute an abuse of the process of this Honourable Court;</P1>
<P1>(z) Schembri and Way have been embroiled in protracted and acrimonious litigation over the last six years. It is impossible for them to work together. Enforcement of the Non-Compete Clause would prevent Schembri from developing real estate in the market he is most familiar because he can never be Way's partner;</P1>
<P1>(aa) Such further and other grounds as are set out in the Affidavit of Gordon Schembri filed in support of this motion;</P1>
<P1>(bb) It is just and reasonable that the issue of liability be heard and determined before any issue of damages is considered as it will save tremendous time and money. The damage issue is extremely complex and ought not to be determined until the enforceability of the clause is determined;</P1>
<P1>(cc) Rules 1.04, 5.05, 30.94(8), 31.06(6) and 20 of the <EM>Rules of Civil Procedure</EM>;</P1>
<P1>(dd) Section 128, 129, and 131 of the <EM>Courts of Justice Act</EM>; and</P1>
<P1>(ee) Such further and other grounds as the lawyers may advise and this Honourable Court deem just.</P1></P>
