<P>19. I or my corporate entities only received $1,400,000.00 from the profits generated by the JVA. I demanded an accounting from Way. I finally received one but it was inaccurate, incomplete and fraudulent. Way refused to provide full and accurate financial disclosure and continues to refuse as of the date of this pleading. To this date, notwithstanding being ordered by this Honourable Court to do so, Way had not done so.</P>
<P>20. As a result I and various corporate entities owned or controlled by me commenced a proceeding against Way and various related corporations owned or controlled by him in the Ontario Superior Court of Justice in Toronto. This action was subsequently transferred to Kitchener and now bears Court File CV-42-11 (the &ldquo;First Action&rdquo;). In the First Action I and the other Plaintiffs sought significant damages as against Way and his corporations and the appointment of a receiver with respect to Oxford and First St. Inc., Simcoe and Eastwood Ave Inc. and 359 King Ontario Inc.</P>
<P>21. My May 14, 2010, affidavit (the &ldquo;May Affidavit&rdquo;) sets out my position relating to the development of the Triumph Subsidiary lands.</P>
<P>22. When I brought my motion to appoint a Receiver of the Triumph Subsidiaries, Way brought a cross motion seeking an order allowing the subsidiaries to proceed with the development of their lands and that Way have unfettered authority over Triumph Financial and the subsidiaries.</P>
<P>23. I opposed Way's motion as I did not want him to have any discretion or control because he had not respected my prior interest, had improperly misappropriated profits from the Waterloo Lands, improperly co-mingled monies, improperly failed to account for the profits arising from the Waterloo Lands and acted oppressively towards me. He failed to pay me half of the JVA profits. He acted as though he had no partner. He took money from the JVA and gave it to many of his own personal corporations that I had no interest in and Triumph Financial without my consent. He used the money as it was his own not ours.</P>
<P>24. Particulars of my complaints regarding Way are set out in my prior Affidavits.</P>
<P>25. Furthermore, I learned that in the development of the Waterloo Lands Way had improperly utilized corporations owned by him to do work at inflated rates so as to improperly syphon off and misappropriate profits that would have otherwise been paid to me. He also created fictitious invoices to his own corporations for exaggerated amounts for work that was never even done or approved to be done.</P>
<P>26. In this regard, Way committed a fraud against me and deliberately breached the JVA. It was as a result of his improper conduct in the Waterloo Development that I could not permit him to have any control over the development of the Triumph Subsidiary lands located in Oshawa, London and Waterloo.</P>
<P>27. In my April Affidavit I made it clear that I was not opposed to developing the Triumph Lands in the absence of involvement by Way. I stated I was in favour of it. I had done what was required of me. I located, assembled, acquired and rezoned the Lands. It was only fair that Way do what was required of him, which was to finance and/or guarantee the financing of the development. The reason why I did not want Way involved in the actual development is because I had fears that he would continue to misappropriate monies, co-mingle monies, fail to account, inflate invoices, and refuse to provide a proper accounting. This is why I wanted a Receiver involved. I can never be partners with Way again.</P>
<P>28. In fact, my fears came to fruition when Way started to develop the Oshawa property without my consent contrary to the Shareholder's Agreement. I sought an injunction in that regard.</P>
<P>29. It was clear that the relationship between Way and I was irrevocably harmed and damaged and we could no longer work together.</P>
<P>30. As set out in my May Affidavit Way was required to provide all financing for the development of the Triumph Lands. That was his role. My role was to locate, assemble and rezone the lands. Furthermore, through the course of the litigation, it became apparent that Way was already attempting to misappropriate further funds from the Triumph Subsidiaries and had grossly inflated what he represented to the Court as being his carrying costs with respect to those properties. My concerns grew when I saw that Way was attempting to develop the Oshawa Lands without my consent, was utilizing companies owned by him, and was intending to proceed with development at a time when he would not be able to provide occupancy to the students who were intended to be the tenants. Furthermore, he intended to proceed with the development while the municipality was considering altering the density which would significantly enhance the value of the land.</P>
<P>31. It was clear that Way was intent on proceeding notwithstanding what the Shareholder's Agreement said and notwithstanding what my rights were. Again Way was seizing improper control of these developments. I could not work with him. This again resulted in me attempting to have a Receiver appointed to stop Way's breach of the Shareholder's Agreement.</P>
<P>32. All of this is more particularly set out in my May Affidavit.</P>
<P>33. In September, 2010, Justice Roberts, of the Superior Court of Justice, granted my motion and appointed a receiver over the Triumph Subsidiaries as a result of the improper wrongful and fraudulent conduct of Way and his corporations. Way refused to provide financing for the Triumph Lands or guarantee financing so as to enable the redevelopment to proceed. In this regard, Way <UNDER>fundamentally</UNDER> breached the Shareholders' Agreement. Accordingly, as a result of Way's breaches, within the receivership proceedings the Commercial Court in Toronto ordered a two phase sales process for the lands owned by the Triumph Subsidiaries.</P>
<P>34. The first phase of the Court ordered sales process enabled both Way and me to deliver to the Receiver sealed offers for the acquisition of any or all of the Triumph Lands pursuant to strict timelines. In the event that the Receiver did not recommend acceptance of any offer to the Court, then phase two of the sales process would be triggered which involved the marketing and sale of the Triumph Lands on the open market.</P>
<P>35. Justice Roberts made significant findings with respect to the conduct of Way. Justice Roberts made the following findings:
<P1>(a) Having reviewed the extensive evidence submitted by the parties, including the transcripts from the numerous cross-examinations, I agree that, pursuant to Section 101(1) of the Courts of Justice Act, &ldquo;<EM>it would be just and convenient to appoint a Receiver and Manager to undertake the completion of the three real estate projects&rdquo;</EM>.</P1>
<P1>(b) &ldquo;<EM>The Plaintiffs have presented a strong prima facie case against Mr. Way and his companies of serious financial and accounting irregularities and improprieties. Indeed, the Defendants have not disputed the evidence provided by the Plaintiffs</EM>.&rdquo;</P1>
<P1>(c) &ldquo;<EM>In particular, the uncontested evidence of Regean Depuis, who had formally been employed by James Way Construction Corporation as the construction manager for the initial Waterloo Project, concerning the Defendants handling of that project, establishes a strong prima facie case that Mr. Way grossly inflated the amounts of various change orders that were charged against the profits of the initial Waterloo project to the benefit of the Defendants and to the detriment of the Plaintiffs. It is significant that, in the first Waterloo project, the vast majority of the work was carried out by Mr. Way's companies which did not tender for the work and over whose expenses and charges there was no independent control</EM>.&rdquo;</P1>
<P1>(d) &ldquo;<EM>Mr. Way added to change orders hundreds of hours for labour that were not expended on the Waterloo project and for the site supervision, scaffolding, heating and other amounts that seemed to have already been included in the fixed price contracts with Mr. Way's companies, and that Mr. Way grossed up each change order with unauthorized and excessive administrative fees. Mr. Depuis' unchallenged evidence was that Mr. Way told him to back charge all of the increased numbers as well as any costs due to overruns and mistakes to Mr. Schembri. Mr. Way admitted on his cross-examination that Mr. Schembri was not shown and therefore did not approve all of the written change orders, contrary to the provisions of their Joint Venture Agreement</EM>.&rdquo;</P1>
<P1>(e) &ldquo;<EM>Further, notwithstanding the requests of the Plaintiffs and their counsel and a court order for production, the Defendants have not provided a full and proper accounting to the Plaintiffs of the initial Waterloo project. As noted below, the Defendants are still resisting the Plaintiff's request for production of relevant financial and documentation and information</EM>.&rdquo;</P1>
<P1>(f) &ldquo;<EM>I agree with the Plaintiffs' submission that the Plaintiffs cannot have confidence in the accounting performed or disclosed by the Defendants. None of the financial statements pertaining to the joint venture is audited and their contents are based on the questionable numbers provided by Mr. Way to his accountants</EM>.&rdquo;</P1>
<P1>(g) &ldquo;<EM>Mr. Way's evidence on cross-examination in response to questions concerning relevant financial information was often incorrect and unhelpful</EM>.&rdquo;</P1>
<P1>(h) &ldquo;<EM>As a particular example, when questioned about the improper transfer of $6 million dollars of joint venture funds to Premier Project Consultants (a Way corporation) and subsidiary corporations, Mr. Way testified that it was the &ldquo;accountants&rdquo; who devised this paper trail; however Mr. Lund (the accountant) testified that he did not advise Mr. Way to transfer the funds in that fashion which had no accounting purpose, but only learned about it after it had been done</EM>.&rdquo;</P1>
<P1>(i) &ldquo;<EM>The evidence that had been produced by Mr. Lund revealed that Mr. Way had apparently improperly transferred funds from the joint venture to pay unrelated payroll expenses and supplies of his other companies, including companies not involved in these projects, over which he has exclusive control</EM>.&rdquo;</P1>
<P1>(j) &ldquo;<EM>I have no hesitation in concluding that the appointment of a Receiver and manager is a remedy necessary to right the wrongs apparently perpetrated by the Defendants</EM>.&rdquo;</P1>
<P1>(k) &ldquo;<EM>The uncontested evidence establishing a strong prima facie case that Mr. Way has an ability that he has already exercised to shuffle money around to numerous corporations over which he has exclusive control. Further, Mr. Way has not been fully compliant with court order production of relevant financial information and documentation to the Plaintiffs, and he seems to be willing to manipulate figures and disregard his accountant's advice</EM>.&rdquo;</P1>
<P1>(l) &ldquo;<EM>As strongly made out by the Plaintiffs unchallenged evidence, in particular, that of Mr. Depuis and Mr. Lund and the financial documentation produced, it appears that Mr. Way's intent on improperly excluding the Plaintiffs and maximizing profits for himself and his companies to the Plaintiffs' detriment</EM>.&rdquo;</P1>
<P1>(m) &ldquo;<EM>Based on the uncontested evidence before me and for the reasons already given, unless a Receiver and manager has the ultimate authority with respect to the monitoring and management of the remaining real estate projects, it is very unlikely that the Defendants will cooperate. Further, none of the remaining projects is &ldquo;shuffle ready&rdquo;; and design and other disputes between the parties mean that the projects are all at a standstill. As a result, this is a convenient juncture for the introduction of a Receiver and manager</EM>.&rdquo;</P1></P>
<P>36. With respect to costs, Justice Roberts then ordered Way to pay costs of $159,151.25 and granted the Plaintiffs leave to seek costs on a substantial indemnity basis on a further motion.</P>
<P>37. As a result of Justice Roberts' order Schwartz Levitsky Feldman was appointed as Receiver manager. Attached as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;A&rdquo;</BOLD> to this my affidavit is a true copy of the Order of Justice Roberts as issued and entered.</P>
<P>38. In the Receivership proceedings in the main action the parties consented to a &ldquo;sales process order&rdquo;. Attached and marked as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;B&rdquo;</BOLD> to this my affidavit is a true copy of the order of Justice Mesbur granted within the Receivership proceedings in Commercial Court in Toronto with respect to the sales process.</P>
<P>39. The Plaintiffs consented to the sales process insofar as it related to the London property and 359 King Ontario Inc. property located in Waterloo Ontario. Attached as Schedule &ldquo;A&rdquo; to Justice Mesbur's order was the sales process. It contemplated two stages. The first was solicitation of offers from Way and me to purchase the properties. In the event that no acceptable offers were received in stage one from Way or myself then the Receiver was to market and sell the properties on the open market.</P>
<P>40. Filed separately in support of this motion is a copy of my affidavit sworn June 7, 2011 (the &ldquo;June Affidavit&rdquo;).</P>
<P>41. The June Affidavit was filed in support of a motion brought by me before Justice Mesbur relating to the sales process. I rely on that affidavit in support of this motion.</P>
<P>42. I submitted an offer to the Receiver to purchase the Waterloo Lands in strict accordance with the sales process order. Way did not submit any offer to the Receiver in accordance with the sales process order.</P>
<P>43. After receipt of my offer to purchase the Waterloo Lands the Receiver obtained a second appraisal which was flawed. Accordingly the Receiver initially did not recommend acceptance of my offer. The Receiver then obtained a third appraisal of the Waterloo Lands because all parties agreed and acknowledged that the second appraisal was flawed.</P>
<P>44. After receiving the third appraisal, the Receiver concluded that my offer to purchase Waterloo was fair since it exceeded the value set by the first and third appraisals. As a result the Receiver recommended sale of the Waterloo lands to me pursuant to the offer that I delivered and accordingly brought a moton seeking court approval for the sale of the Waterloo lands to me. As a result, a 9:30a.m. appointment was made before Mr. Justice Campbell to schedule the Receiver's motion to approve the sale of the Waterloo Lands to me. The Receiver circulated a draft form of order approving the sale and vesting the property in accordance with such a sale.</P>
<P>45. I am advised by James Wortzman that during the Chamber's appointment before Justice Campbell on April 12, 2011, Way advised for the first time of his intention to seek an order removing the Receiver. The stated reason was because the Receiver had decided to accept my offer to purchase the Waterloo Lands and that this was some sort of &ldquo;flip flop&rdquo;.</P>
<P>46. Accordingly, Way attempted to derail the sales process and brought a motion seeking an order removing the Receiver. The motion to remove the Receiver derailed the sales process and the Receiver's motion to approve the sale of the Waterloo Lands to me was adjourned pending the hearing of Way's Removal motion.</P>
<P>47. I believe that Way brought a frivolous motion to remove the Receiver to buy time to submit new offers to purchase all of the Lands and to circumvent the Sales Process.</P>
<P>48. I believe that Way's motion to remove the Receiver was bound to fail. The reasons for that are set out in cost submissions submitted before the Court. Attached as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;C&rdquo;</BOLD> to this my affidavit is a true copy of those costs submissions which set out the history of the matter in an accurate fashion.</P>
<P>49. After Way succeeded in derailing the sales process and having the Receiver's motion to approve the sale of the Waterloo Lands to me adjourned, he submitted an offer to purchase the Waterloo Lands in an amount $500,000.00 greater than my offer and in a form identical to my offer and he also offered to purchase the Oshawa and London lands. None of these offers were made pursuant to the Sales Process order.</P>
<P>50. Way's motion to remove the Receiver was scheduled to be heard May 24, 2011. Way's new offers were submitted outside of the sales process order timelines. Way also made his offer when he was privy to information that he would not have been privy to had he complied with the original sales process order. This is particularized in my June 2011 affidavit.</P>
<P>51. On May 19, 2011, I learned of negotiations between Way and the Receiver which involved Way's offer to abandon his Removal motion in exchange for the Receiver approving Way's new offers to purchase the Lands. As part of this agreement the Receiver would not seek costs of the abandoned Removal motion and agreed to support Way's new proposed sales process.</P>
<P>52. Ultimately the Receiver and Way entered into an agreement in those terms. I was shocked that the Receiver would do this given the terms of the sales process order and the fact that the Receiver had already brought a motion to approve the sale of the Waterloo Lands to me. Attached as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;D&rdquo;</BOLD> to this my affidavit is a true copy of e-mail exchanges between Mr. Wortzman and Mr. Silver (the Receiver's lawyer) sent on May 20, 2011. Those e-mails set out my position regarding what had taken place which is:
<P1>(a) &ldquo;<EM>Very unfair to Gord, who folio-wed the court ordered process, only to have it hijacked by Way who didn't follow the process. Why would you ever recommend a break fee and why is Way the stalking horse, and why is the Receiver acting like a Trustee in bankruptcy rather than an officer of the court following a court ordered process in a dispute between 2 parties? More importantly why would the Receiver ever bargain advice to the court in exchange for the defendant withdrawing a motion to remove? Honestly I cannot believe what you have done. P.S. Sent with prejudice</EM>&rdquo;</P1>
<P1>(b) &ldquo;<EM>The withdrawal of the Removal Motion is not independent, but part and parcel of the deal. That is why I explained it was a mistake for you to tie them together</EM>. <BOLD><EM>The Receiver has lost his independence, and was obviously influenced/intimidated by the Removal motion, accordingly we will argue that his advice should not be given any deference by the Court. Doesn't it seem odd that the Receiver was unacceptable to Way until and unless the Receiver did what Way wanted?</EM></BOLD> <EM>Way's tactic worked because the Receiver didn't resist the motion independent of bargaining his advice to the Court. My client cannot understand the position you have taken and I am at a loss to explain it to him. Lastly how is it in the estate's best interest to allow Way to withdraw his tactical and meritless motion without costs? Why should the estate bear 1 penny</EM>? <BOLD><EM>The Receiver was acting in its interests and not the estate's interests because he thinks he will get paid either way, and we will contest that as well as his and your fees</EM>.</BOLD></P1>
<P1><EM>It is too bad it has come to this, because in the face of the Removal motion you ought to have advised the court of Way's last minute, out of time offers (all made when he knew our client had offered on Waterloo and the interest or lack of thereof regarding the other 2 properties), and merely sought directions and let Way argue why the court should indulge him, given the binding and in force order of Mesbur J</EM>. <BOLD><EM>You are recommending Way's offers that he made with knowledge he never would have had if Mesbur's order was followed. It's not just about money, but also process, fairness, and adhering to court orders. The entire process is now contaminated, unworkable and unfair, and you let it happen</EM>.&rdquo;</BOLD></P1>
<P1>(c) &ldquo;<EM>You seem to forget that the</EM> <BOLD><EM>&ldquo;estate&rdquo; is Gord and Way. Their interests were protected in Mesbur's order, and all you had to do was implement it. Rather you made up rules on the fly because Way finally made an offer after he knew what he ought not to have known and in the face of his abusive motion which achieved its objective of derailing the process</EM></BOLD> <EM>and distracting the Receiver. It is the objective that counts, not the subjective and this is what I unsuccessfully attempted to convey to you. Objectively, the Receiver's conduct is simply wrong and unfair. The whole processes save for our client's initial offer is now tainted and unworkable</EM>.&rdquo;</P1></P>
<P>53. In accordance with the deal that was made, Way did abandon the motion to remove the Receiver and the Receiver did not seek costs. The Receiver then brought a motion to have an amended sales process approved. That motion was ultimately heard by Justice Mesbur. Attached as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;E&rdquo;</BOLD> to this my affidavit is a true copy of Justice Mesbur's order dated June 24, 2011, wherein she approved the new sales process recommended by the Receiver in accordance with the deal the Receiver had made with Way. Attached as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;F&rdquo;</BOLD> is a true copy of Justice Mesbur's reasons for her decision.</P>
<P>54. Justice Mesbur made significant findings of fact regarding Way's conduct in connection with the sales process order. In this regard she made the following findings:
<P1>(a) Because of the falling out between Mr. Schembri and Mr. Way and the likelihood they would fail to cooperate with one another, both agreed that a neutral third party was necessary, but Mr. Way resisted appointing a receiver. Roberts J. found it just and convenient to appoint a receiver in order to &ldquo;<EM>protect the positions of the parties pending the completion of the projects and the final determination of the parties' disputes</EM>&rdquo;;</P1>
<P1>(b) Way &ldquo;<EM>attacked the Receiver's impartiality and integrity</EM>&rdquo;;</P1>
<P1>(c) &ldquo;<EM>I am troubled by the way the original sales process has got off the rails ... Mr. Schembri complied with the sales order. Mr. Way did not</EM>.&rdquo;</P1>
<P1>(d) &ldquo;<EM>Removing a Receiver is a serious matter. Mr. Way had called the Receiver's integrity into question, and this issue had to be determined. From Mr. Schembri's point of view, the removal motion was tactical, and designed to derail the sales process so that Mr. Way could gain an advantage in it. To some extent, I tend to agree</EM>.&rdquo;</P1>
<P1>(e) &ldquo;W<EM>hen I look at the timing of the removal motion, coupled with Mr. Way's later unsolicited bids for the three properties, I see a tactical move to rest control of the process from the Receiver, and to prevent Mr. Schembri from purchasing Waterloo or to force him to pay significantly more for it than its appraised value</EM>.&rdquo;</P1>
<P1>(f) &ldquo;<EM>What troubles me is that accepting the Receiver's recommendations in large part rewards Mr. Way and condones his behaviour. He had the opportunity to prevent a proper bid as contemplated by the sales order. He chose not to. Instead, he made unsolicited bids while attacking the Receiver's integrity</EM>.&rdquo;</P1>
<P1>(g) &ldquo;<EM>But this is not about Mr. Schembri and Mr. Way</EM>. <BOLD><EM>Their bitterness and ill will towards one another is palpable and will no doubt continue and colour all of their future decisions. It is not the Court's function to facilitate or enable their bitterness and anger</EM>.</BOLD> <EM>Instead, the Court must determine whether the Receiver's proposal is in the overall interest of the Estate and is commercially reasonable</EM>.&rdquo;</P1>
<P1>(h) &ldquo;<EM>As to the fairness or unfairness of the process, both parties have legitimate complaints</EM>. <BOLD><EM>Those complaints, however, have more to do with their own behaviour and wish to crush the other than with the Receiver's exercise of reasonable judgment on the context of the sales process</EM>.&rdquo;</BOLD></P1>
<P1>(i) &ldquo;<EM>Although this case cries out to be settled, the parties seem to have little appetite for a reasonable settlement</EM>, <BOLD><EM>and would prefer to litigate until all their assets have been spent&rdquo;</EM>.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>55. As a result of Justice Mesbur's decision I sought a motion for stay of her order before the Court of Appeal which was granted by the Court of Appeal. Furthermore, the Court of Appeal was able to expedite the hearing of the appeal of Justice Mesbur's order and such an appeal was heard on July 11, 2011, only 17 days after Justice Mesbur's decision.</P>
<P>56. The Court of Appeal unanimously set aside and overturned Justice Mesbur's order. Attached as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;G&rdquo;</BOLD> to this my affidavit is a true copy of the reasons of the Court of Appeal. The Court of Appeal made the following findings:
<P1>(a) &ldquo;<EM>The conduct of Mr. Way had a negative impact on the integrity of the Court supervised sales process</EM>&rdquo;;</P1>
<P1>(b) &ldquo;<EM>His (Way's) conduct, as it impacted on the integrity of the sales process, should have been given significant weight when deciding whether the Receiver's recommendation to accept Mr. Way's proposal should be approved by the Court</EM>.&rdquo;</P1></P>
<P>57. Accordingly, as a result of the Court of Appeal's decision, the Commercial Court in Toronto ordered that the sale of the Waterloo Lands to a company controlled by me be approved and that the Receiver be authorized to enter into and execute a sale agreement.</P>
<P>58. Furthermore the Court ordered that a vesting order in the form prescribed by the Land Titles Act and/or the Land Registry Reform Act be registered. Attached as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;H&rdquo;</BOLD> is a true copy of Justice Campbell's order dated August 2, 2011.</P>
<P>59. The sale of the Waterloo Lands was done pursuant to a court ordered process. The issue was ultimately determined by the Court of Appeal. Way never raised the Non-Competition Clause during this entire process. If Way wanted an opportunity to buy the Waterloo Lands then he should have complied with the sales process order. He did not. He tried to circumvent and frustrate the process and his efforts to do so were stopped by the Court of Appeal.</P>
<P>60. Pursuant to the vesting order this sale of the Waterloo Lands to my company was approved by the Court.</P>
<P>61. Of interest is paragraph 3 of the Order which states that once the Receiver delivers its certificate then all of the &ldquo;Receivers or 359 King Ontario Inc.'s right, title and interest in and to the property described in the Sale Agreement and listed on Schedule &ldquo;B&rdquo; hereto (the &ldquo;Purchase Property&rdquo;) hereto shall vest absolutely in the Purchaser, free and clear and from any and all security interest (whether contractual, statutory or otherwise), hypothecs, mortgages, trusts or deemed trusts (whether contractual, statutory or otherwise), liens, executions, levies, charges, or other financial or other monetary claims, whether or not they have attached or been perfected, registered or filed and whether secured, unsecured or otherwise (collectively the &ldquo;Claims&rdquo;).</P>
<P>62. It seems that Way's attempt to assert an interest in the Waterloo Lands seems to be a collateral attack on the order of the Court of Appeal of Ontario and the Order of Justice Campbell wherein the Property was vested in my company.</P>
<P>63. Subsequently Justice Mesbur ordered Way to reimburse the Estate for the Receiver's and its counsel's fees in relation to the abandoned motion to withdraw the Receiver in an amount of $52,545.07 because &ldquo;<EM>it seems to me it is completely unfair for the Plaintiff to bear these costs which were incurred as a result of the Defendant's attack on the Receiver's integrity&mdash;an attack without foundation</EM>.&rdquo;</P>
<P>64. This is not the first time that this matter in this action proceeded to the Court of Appeal. The Plaintiff attempted to seek an amendment to the Statement of Claim and this was partially rejected. Accordingly, an appeal was heard by the Court of Appeal.</P>
<P>65. Attached as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;I&rdquo;</BOLD> to this my affidavit is a copy of the reasons of the Court of Appeal dated September 20, 2012, wherein the Court of Appeal found:
<P1>(a) &ldquo;<EM>Based on this undisputed evidence, Roberts J. made a number of significant findings of wrong doing by Mr. Way and the companies he controlled. For instance, she found that Mr. Way had shuffled money around to his corporations, that he had not complied fully with Court order production and he was willing to manipulate figures and to ignore his accountant's advice</EM>.&rdquo;</P1></P>
<BLOCK2><TI>Present Action</TI>
<P>66. On or around May 25, 2012 the Plaintiffs commenced the within action by way of Statement of Claim. Attached hereto and marked as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;J&rdquo; and &ldquo;K&rdquo;</BOLD> to this my affidavit is a true copy of the Plaintiffs' Fresh as Amended Statement of Claim and our Amended Statement of Defence.</P>
<P>67. The Plaintiffs allege that Schembri Financial and I have breached the terms of the Agreement by conspiring with the Corporate Defendants to purchase and develop certain properties without first presenting the opportunities to Kingsley Financial or Triumph Financial.</P>
<P>68. In respect of these alleged breaches of the Agreement, the Plaintiffs have claimed:
<P1>(a) damages in the amount of $30,500,000 for breach of contract, conversion, misappropriation, breach of fiduciary duty, conspiracy and punitive damages in connection with certain transactions pertaining to the lands referenced in the Statement of Claim (the &ldquo;Lands&rdquo;);</P1>
<P1>(b) declarations that the Defendants hold the Lands by a constructive trust for the Plaintiffs, or any of them;</P1>
<P1>(c) an accounting of all profits and other benefits derived by the Defendants or any of them in connection with the acquisition and development of the Lands (the &ldquo;Accounting&rdquo;);</P1>
<P1>(d) an order directing the Defendants to pay to the Plaintiffs all amounts found owing to them pursuant to the Accounting; and</P1>
<P1>(e) punitive, aggravated, and exemplary damages in the amount of $500,000.</P1></P>
<P>69. Our position with respect to the applicability of the Non-Competition Clause in relation to 359 King Street is set out above. It is our position that the Plaintiff is estopped from asserting a claim with respect to that property because of the prior proceedings and the pronouncement of the Court of Appeal and the vesting order.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI>Columbia Street Lands</TI>
<P>70. Before my relationship with Way ended, I had 41 Columbia Street under contract. Way attended at that property with me and we walked the property. I told Way that I was intending to construct student housing on that site. Way advised me that he had no interest at all in that property. I told Way that I was intending to develop other student housing on Columbia Street and within the vicinity of the Universities to develop student housing.</P>
<P>71. Way advised me that he had no interest in the acquisition or development of student housing in the Waterloo region.</P>
<P>72. Evidence of this is that Triumph Financial or another Way entity had actually entered into an agreement of purchase and sale with respect to property known municipally as 61 Columbia Street. I asked Way to use the Triumph company to disguise myself from the vendor, because if they knew it was me purchasing the property they would have asked for a higher selling price. Way had no interest in developing that property and accordingly he agreed to assign the agreement of purchase and sale to one of my corporate entities. That corporate entity ended up purchasing 61 Columbia Street and building student housings thereon. This Agreement was entered into well before two years from when this action was commenced. I closed the purchase of the two houses that became 61 Columbia in 2009. Therefore the Plaintiffs were aware of this property well before two years prior to the commencement of this action.</P>
<P>73. To Way's knowledge, I, through my corporate entities have acquired and developed student housing on properties known municipally as 26, 35, 41, 61, 69 and 75 Columbia Street and 347 Spruce, in Waterloo.</P>
<P>74. Way was fully aware of my acquisition of those properties and the development of student housing thereon. Way never indicated to me that he had any interest in those properties or any interest in participating in the development of those properties. To the contrary Way asserted he is NOT a student developer and has no interest in developing student accommodations in Waterloo. Other than 345 King Way still to this day has never developed another Student development in Waterloo.</P>
<P>75. None of 41 Columbia Inc., King and Columbia Inc., 69 Columbia Street Inc. 5 Rittenhouse Inc., The Block Inc., The Block I Inc., or The Block II Inc. have any contractual relationship whatsoever with the Plaintiffs.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI>The Non-Competition Clause</TI>
<P>76. It is true that the Non-Competition Clause is in the Shareholder's Agreement.</P>
<P>77. As set out above, I do verily believe that Way has committed serious fundamental breaches of the Shareholder's Agreement and, by so doing, has repudiated same. I accept Way's repudiation of the Shareholder's Agreement and I am seeking damages against him as is evidenced in the Claim asserted in the Main Action. Several Courts have recognized that as a result of Way's dishonourable conduct towards me that it is not possible to work together.</P>
<P>78. The only assets that Triumph Financial has were the shares of the Triumph Subsidiaries. The Triumph Subsidiaries were all placed into receivership. Accordingly, the Shareholder's Agreement has been frustrated. Alternatively the Receiver has control of Triumph since it controls its assets.</P>
<P>79. To the best of my knowledge Triumph Financial has not carried on any business since the Receiver was appointed in September, 2010. It is dormant. There is no Corporate governance, no meetings have been held, no entitled financial statements have been prepared, no minutes have been prepared.</P>
<P>80. If this clause is still in effect it would significantly harm my business and my ability to provide for my family as I would be blocked from ever developing anything in the Waterloo region without Way's involvement. Way would have the ability to stop me from building as I could never work with him again as he surely would continue the misappropriation of funds as the Court has already proven.</P>
<P>81. Given the way Way has treated me there is no possibility that I would ever enter into any development with him or any business venture with him in the future.</P>
<P>82. I believe he feels the same about me. This was made clear during the course of the proceedings. This was recognized by various courts in the findings that they made and which are set out above or in the exhibits to this affidavit. In any event, Way has committed many breaches of the Shareholder's Agreement which are fundamental in nature, including but not limited to:
<P1>(a) There have been no annual general meetings;</P1>
<P1>(b) Triumph Financial has not produced audited statements as is required;</P1>
<P1>(c) Way is not allowed to sign any contracts with respect to matters relating to land acquisition, mortgage financial, construction budgets and project feasibility without my consent. He has done so in direct breach of the agreement;</P1>
<P1>(d) There cannot be a material change in the nature of Triumph Financial's business without my consent. Way refused to provide any financing for the development of the Oshawa Lands thereby creating a change in the nature of Triumph Financial's business. I did not consent. In fact I attempted to obtain a court order forcing Way to provide such financing. I was not successful. The Corporation does not carry on any business.</P1>
<P1>(e) Triumph Financial cannot directly or indirectly make loans or advances to invest in any other corporation or person unless I consent. I have not consented. Way has caused Triumph Financial to make loans or advances or invest in the Triumph Subsidiaries without my consent. He has utilized money from our initial joint venture, transferred it improperly and illegally into other WAY solely owned corporate entities along with Triumph Financial and then into the Triumph Subsidiaries without my consent.</P1>
<P1>(f) Triumph Financial cannot commit to any financing arrangements with third parties without my consent. Way did so with respect to the Triumph Subsidiaries without my consent thereby breaching the agreement.</P1>
<P1>(g) Triumph Financial cannot undertake any projects without project feasibility studies and construction budget approvals without my consent. Notwithstanding this Way proceeded to purport to spend significant monies on the Waterloo Lands, the Oshawa Lands and the London Lands without having construction budget approvals and without project feasibility studies. This was a fundament breach of the agreement by Way.</P1>
<P1>(h) Way improperly attempted to seize my shares in breach of the terms of the Shareholder's Agreement.</P1>
<P1>(i) Way has purported to charge interest on monies he has purported to advance to Triumph Financial contrary to the express provisions of the Shareholder's Agreement and attempted to seize my shares in part based upon interest he alleged was owing, when it was not.</P1>
<P1>(j) I believe there was an implied duty of good faith in Way and I entering into the Shareholder's Agreement. Way has not acted in good faith. There has been a complete breakdown of all trust.</P1>
<P1>(k) Way has committed various frauds against me.</P1>
<P1>(l) Way has caused his companies to send bogus and inflated invoices to Triumph for work that was either not done or never approved by me. He then tried to seize my shares based on these bogus invoices.</P1></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI>The Non-Competition Clause is Otherwise Unenforceable</TI>
<P>83. Paragraph 55&ndash;58 of my Statement of Defence set out additional reasons why the Non-Competition Clause is not enforceable. In this regard it is important to note that:
<P1>(a) The clause has no temporal limits and according to Way will bind my children and their children;</P1>
<P1>(b) The clause is not necessary to protect any legitimate commercial interest of Way;</P1>
<P1>(c) The clause is ambiguous and incapable of enforcement;</P1>
<P1>(d) The clause is internally inconsistent and incapable of enforcement;</P1>
<P1>(e) The clause is void for uncertainty;</P1>
<P1>(f) It is impossible to determine when any obligation pursuant to the clause is triggered;</P1>
<P1>(g) The clause is too broad in its scope and purports to bind entities who are not a party to the Shareholder's Agreement;</P1>
<P1>(h) The clause makes no commercial or logical sense;</P1>
<P1>(i) The clause does not distinguish between Triumph and Kingsley;</P1>
<P1>(j) The clause is not necessary to protect Way's business interest. In fact Way has developed real estate in Waterloo region on his own since he signed the Agreement.</P1></P>
<P>84. The Non-Competition Clause is ambiguous with respect to the obligations it purports to impose on Schembri Financial and myself personally. I do not understand how it could be implemented as it is worded. Real Estate development is complex, there are many &ldquo;moving parts&rdquo;, none of the particulars required for a development are set out.</P>
<P>85. For example, I have no knowledge of a &ldquo;typical budget model consistently utilized by [Kingsley Financial and Triumph Financial] in such circumstances&rdquo;. No such &ldquo;typical budget model&rdquo; exists.</P>
<P>86. The Non-Competition Clause is too broad, is unreasonable, and is incapable of being understood or enforced.</P>
<P>87. As the Non-Competition Clause is unenforceable, there is no basis on which the Plaintiffs can claim that Schembri Financial and I breached our duties under the Agreement by failing to present the Alleged Opportunities to Kingsley Financial or Triumph Financial.</P>
<P>88. Way was asked questions about the Non-Competition clause on his discovery and he could not explain how it would operate. If he cannot then it is difficult to imagine how a court could. Way testified that the right is that of Triumph. So, it could never be exercised because I would never agree to it.</P>
<P>89. There is no genuine issue requiring a trial with respect to the within Statement of Claim as it relates to any alleged breaches of the Agreement.</P>
<P>90. The transcripts of Way's discovery will be filed separately and relied upon by me on this motion.</P>
<P>91. I make this affidavit in support of an order granting summary judgment or in the alternative partial summary judgment and for no other or improper purpose.</P>
