<BLOCK1><TI>AFFIDAVIT OF ALVEN J. WAY (sworn March 16, 2018)</TI>
<P><BOLD>I, ALVEN J. WAY,</BOLD> businessman, of the City of Waterloo, in the Province of Ontario, make oath and say as follows.</P>
<P><BOLD>1.</BOLD> I am a plaintiff, and a director of both of the corporate defendants, in this proceeding (the <BOLD>&ldquo;ROFR Action&rdquo;)</BOLD>, and a defendant in a related action bearing Court File No. C-42-11 (the <BOLD>&ldquo;Main Action&rdquo;)</BOLD>. As such, I have personal knowledge of the facts deposed to herein except where knowledge of such facts is stated to be on information and belief and, where so stated, I verily believe those facts to be true.</P>
<P><BOLD>2.</BOLD> As this affidavit is lengthy, I have included at:
<P1>(a) <BOLD>Schedule &ldquo;A&rdquo;</BOLD> a table of contents; and</P1>
<P1>(b) <BOLD>Schedule &ldquo;B&rdquo; a</BOLD> glossary of the defined terms herein (and identifying the page and paragraph where such term is defined).</P1></P>
<P><BOLD>3.</BOLD> This affidavit is delivered in opposition to the defendants' motion for summary judgment (the <BOLD>&ldquo;ROFR SJ Motion&rdquo;)</BOLD> and in support of a motion for an order:
<P1>(a) declaring that the defendant, Schembri Financial Limited <BOLD>(&ldquo;Schembri Financial&rdquo;)</BOLD> is in breach of the Contribution Clause (defined in paragraph 146 below);</P1>
<P1>(b) declaring that Schembri Financial and the defendant, Gordon Schembri <BOLD>(&ldquo;Schembri&rdquo;)</BOLD> are in breach of the ROFR Clause (defined in paragraph 147 below);</P1>
<P1>(c) declaring that Schembri Financial and Schembri are in breach of the Arbitration Clause (defined in paragraph 148 below);</P1>
<P1>(d) authorizing and directing that the KPMG Portal (defined in paragraph 290 below) be closed immediately;</P1>
<P1>(e) requiring Schembri to serve a further and better affidavit of documents in the Main Action and in ROFR Action;</P1>
<P1>(f) requiring the corporate defendants in the ROFR Action (the <BOLD>&ldquo;ROFR Corporate Defendants&rdquo;)</BOLD> to serve an affidavit of documents in the ROFR Action;</P1>
<P1>(g) requiring Schembri to deliver answers to undertakings given at his examination for discovery in the Main Action conducted on June 28, 29 and 30, and July 27 and 28, 2017; and</P1>
<P1>(h) costs of this motion on a substantial indemnity basis payable forthwith.</P1></P>
<P><BOLD>4.</BOLD> The supporting affidavit of Schembri sworn May 17, 2017 (the <BOLD>&ldquo;Schembri ROFR SJ Affidavit&rdquo;)</BOLD> refers:
<P1>(a) in paragraph 3 to &ldquo;certain affidavits sworn and filed by&rdquo; Schembri, without identifying such affidavits; and</P1>
<P1>(b) in paragraph 4 to numerous additional materials, including affidavits sworn by Schembri in 2010 and 2011;</P1>
<P1>(collectively, the <BOLD>&ldquo;Additional Schembri ROFR SJ Materials&rdquo;)</BOLD>.</P1></P>
<P><BOLD>5.</BOLD> By letter dated February 12, 2018, my counsel requested identification of the Additional Schembri ROFR SJ Materials. A copy of this letter is attached hereto and marked as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;1&rdquo;</BOLD>.</P>
<P><BOLD>6.</BOLD> As at the date of this affidavit, a response to my counsel's letter has not been provided to my knowledge. Accordingly, I believe there are four such affidavits Schembri has apparently filed in support of the ROFR SJ Motion as follows:
<P1>(a) an affidavit sworn April 6, 2010 (the <BOLD>&ldquo;Schembri April 2010 Affidavit&rdquo;);</BOLD></P1>
<P1>(b) an affidavit sworn May 14, 2010 (the <BOLD>&ldquo;Schembri May 2010 Affidavit&rdquo;);</BOLD></P1>
<P1>(c) an affidavit sworn September 5, 2010 (the <BOLD>&ldquo;Schembri September 2010 Affidavit&rdquo;);</BOLD> and</P1>
<P1>(d) an affidavit sworn June 7, 2011 (the <BOLD>&ldquo;Schembri June 2011 Affidavit&rdquo;)</BOLD>.</P1></P>
<P><BOLD>7.</BOLD> I have tried to piece together the facts being alleged by the Schembri ROFR SJ Affidavit in support of the ROFR SJ Motion, which is exacerbated by:
<P1>(a) the amount of paper contained in the Additional Schembri ROFR SJ Materials; and</P1>
<P1>(b) Schembri (who is a businessman and not a lawyer) appearing to make legal arguments at times.</P1></P></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><N>1</N><TI>Plaintiffs Oppose the ROFR SJ Motion</TI>
<P><BOLD>8.</BOLD> The plaintiffs oppose the ROFR SJ Motion for the following reasons:
<P1>(a) with respect to the Shareholder Agreement (defined in paragraph 33(b) below):
<P2>(i) I made a deal with Schembri in the presence of our respective lawyers;</P2>
<P2>(ii) the ROFR Clause was a key term of our deal;</P2>
<P2>(iii) both Schembri and I acted in accordance with our deal while Schembri's lawyer drafted the agreement reflecting our deal;</P2>
<P2>(iv) more than two months after we made our deal, Schembri and I executed the Shareholder Agreement (drafted by and negotiated through our respective lawyers) that reflected our deal;</P2>
<P2>(v) thereafter, both Schembri and I continued to act in accordance with our deal until Schembri breached the Shareholder Agreement by failing to comply with:
<P3>(A) the Contribution Clause;</P3>
<P3>(B) the ROFR Clause; and</P3>
<P3>(C) the Arbitration Clause; and</P3></P2>
<P2>(vi) I did not breach the Shareholder Agreement (including as alleged in paragraph 33 of the Schembri ROFR SJ Affidavit);</P2></P1>
<P1>(b) with respect to the JV Agreement (defined in paragraph 33(a) below):
<P2>(i) I did not lie to Schembri as alleged in:
<P3>(A) paragraph 14 of the Schembri April 2010 Affidavit; and</P3>
<P3>(B) paragraph 10 of the Schembri ROFR SJ Affidavit;</P3></P2>
<P2>(ii) the profits resulting from the sale of 345 King were never anticipated to be $10,000,000 as alleged in:
<P3>(A) paragraph 43 of the Schembri April 2010 Affidavit; and</P3>
<P3>(B) paragraph 12 of the Schembri ROFR SJ Affidavit;</P3></P2>
<P2>(iii) I did not grossly inflate the amounts of various changes;</P2>
<P2>(iv) the vast majority of the work was not carried out by the Way Group;</P2>
<P2>(v) I did not add to change orders hundreds of hours for labour that were not expended on the JV Project;</P2>
<P2>(vi) there was no improper transfer of $6 million to Premier;</P2>
<P2>(vii) the Other Way Companies (defined in paragraph 20 below) did not receive any improper payments as alleged in paragraphs 61A to 61M of the <UNDER>Amended Amended</UNDER> Statement of Claim in the Main Action;</P2></P1>
<P1>(c) with respect to the court proceedings:
<P2>(i) I submitted an en bloc credit offer in good faith; (ii) I did not attempt to derail the sales process;</P2>
<P2>(iii) the motion to substitute the Receiver was well-founded and brought in good faith;</P2></P1>
<P1>(d) Schembri's unexplained inordinate delay that included a delay of three years after repeated representations over several months in 2014, which derailed the efforts of the Way Group (defined in paragraph 21 below) to conduct examinations for discovery in both the Main Action and the ROFR Action (as addressed in below).</P1></P></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><N>2</N><TI>The Parties to the Litigation</TI>
<BLOCK2><TI>The Way Group</TI>
<P><BOLD>9.</BOLD> I am sixty years old and have been involved in the development and construction industry for almost 40 years.</P>
<P><BOLD>10.</BOLD> I started my own construction company in 1986 that eventually evolved into Jamesway Construction Corporation <BOLD>(&ldquo;Jamesway&rdquo;)</BOLD>.</P>
<P><BOLD>11.</BOLD> As an adjunct to the construction services and role of Jamesway, Premier Project Consultants Ltd. <BOLD>(&ldquo;Premier&rdquo;)</BOLD> provides design and project management services. Premier was incorporated on November 13, 2008. However, prior to that, Premier operated for approximately 4 years as a division of Jamesway.</P>
<P><BOLD>12.</BOLD> Terra-Tec Excavating <BOLD>(&ldquo;Terra-Tec&rdquo;)</BOLD> is a division of Jamesway and, as the name suggests, is the excavation arm of Jamesway. I caused the business name &ldquo;Terra-Tec Excavating&rdquo; to be registered under the Business Names Act on or about December 12, 2006.</P>
<P><BOLD>13.</BOLD> I caused National Rent-All Inc. <BOLD>(&ldquo;National&rdquo;)</BOLD> to be incorporated on or about November 19, 1991. National:
<P1>(a) sells construction material, tools and equipment; and</P1>
<P1>(b) supplies construction tools and equipment to contractors, including Jamesway and Terra-Tec, on a rental basis.</P1></P>
<P><BOLD>14.</BOLD> Jamesway, Premier and Terra-Tec operated out of premises located at 274 Shirley Drive, Kitchener. Jamesway employed around 100 people during the time of the JV Project (defined in paragraph 33(a) below).</P>
<P><BOLD>15.</BOLD> National operated out of premises in a building next door at 260 Shirley Drive, Kitchener. National employed three people during the time of the JV Project.</P>
<P><BOLD>16.</BOLD> I am the President of Kingsley Financial Inc. <BOLD>(&ldquo;KFI&rdquo;)</BOLD>. KFI serves a banking function in that it looks after the cash in my various companies.</P>
<P><BOLD>17.</BOLD> I am the President of 1725030 Ontario Inc. <BOLD>(&ldquo;172&rdquo;)</BOLD>. I caused 172 to be incorporated in connection with the JV Agreement.</P>
<P><BOLD>18.</BOLD> I am the President of Triumph Financial Holdings Inc. <BOLD>(&ldquo;Triumph&rdquo;)</BOLD>. I caused Triumph to be incorporated in connection with the Shareholder Agreement.</P>
<P><BOLD>19.</BOLD> I am the President of each of 359 King Ontario Inc. <BOLD>(&ldquo;359 King&rdquo;)</BOLD>, Oxford &amp; First St. Inc. <BOLD>(&ldquo;Oxford &amp; First&rdquo;)</BOLD>, and Simcoe &amp; Eastwood Avenue Inc. <BOLD>(&ldquo;Simcoe &amp; Eastwood&rdquo;,</BOLD> and together with 359 King and Simcoe &amp; Eastwood, the <BOLD>&ldquo;Triumph Subsidiaries&rdquo;)</BOLD>. I caused the Triumph Subsidiaries to be incorporated in furtherance of the Shareholder Agreement.</P>
<P><BOLD>20.</BOLD> I am the President of each of 1581780 Ontario Ltd. <BOLD>(&ldquo;158&rdquo;)</BOLD>, 1604909 Ontario Inc., The Shores Ltd., Jameshill Developments Limited, The Spruce Street Lofts Inc. and Maple Hill Creeks Apts. Inc. (collectively, the <BOLD>&ldquo;Other Way Companies&rdquo;)</BOLD>. The Other Way Companies were added as defendants in the Main Action as granted by the Turnbull Decision (defined in paragraph 310 below).</P>
<P><BOLD>21.</BOLD> Jamesway, Premier, Terra-Tec, National, KFi, 172, Triumph, the Triumph Subsidiaries and the Other Way Companies (collectively, the <BOLD>&ldquo;Way Group&rdquo;)</BOLD> are defendants in the Main Action.</P>
<P><BOLD>22.</BOLD> The accounting department for the Way Group, headed by Greta Crozier <BOLD>(&ldquo;Crozier&rdquo;)</BOLD>, uses Jonas Construction accounting software <BOLD>(&ldquo;Jonas&rdquo;)</BOLD> in the administration of projects, including the JV Project (defined in paragraph 33(a) below). 1 do not have access to Jonas. I do not know how to use Jonas.</P>
<P><BOLD>23.</BOLD> Frank Volpini <BOLD>(&ldquo;Volpini&rdquo;)</BOLD>, of the Waterloo law firm Chris &amp; Volpini, was the lawyer for:
<P1>(a) 172 in connection with the JV Project; and</P1>
<P1>(b) the Triumph Subsidiaries in connection with their incorporation and acquisition of the Triumph Lands (defined in paragraph 33(b) below).</P1></P>
<P><BOLD>24.</BOLD> The accountants for the Way Group are Lund &amp; Associates Chartered Accountants <BOLD>(&ldquo;Lund &amp; Associates&rdquo;),</BOLD> who are located in Kitchener. The principal of Lund &amp; Associates is Brad Lund <BOLD>(&ldquo;Lund&rdquo;)</BOLD>.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI>Patterson</TI>
<P><BOLD>25.</BOLD> Faye Patterson <BOLD>(&ldquo;Patterson&rdquo;)</BOLD> has been employed as my executive assistant for about seventeen years. As Schembri knows, I have a personal relationship with Patterson. I believe Schembri sought to add Patterson as a defendant in the Main Action for tactical purposes; namely, to attempt to create upset in our relationship, to cause Patterson emotional distress, and to increase costs.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI>Farlow</TI>
<P><BOLD>26.</BOLD> Steve Farlow <BOLD>(&ldquo;Farlow&rdquo;)</BOLD> was the Executive Director of the Schlegel Centre for Entrepreneurship at Wilfred Laurier University, located in Waterloo, Ontario until his retirement in or around 2017. I have known Farlow for many years as a personal friend, and he is one of the trustees of the Way Family Trust I believe Schembri sought to add Farlow as a defendant in the Main Action for tactical purposes.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI>The Schembri Group</TI>
<P><BOLD>27.</BOLD> I met Schembri in late 2006 or early 2007, when I was in my late forties and Schembri was about twenty-seven years old. To my knowledge, Schembri's previous construction and development experience at that time was limited to only a few smaller, less complex, low-rise, wood frame buildings with much lower development and construction costs than those in issue in the Main Action. One of these developments (347 Spruce Street, Waterloo) was across the street from the properties that would later form the JV Lands (defined in paragraph 36 below).</P>
<P><BOLD>28.</BOLD> To my knowledge, Schembri is the controlling mind of Schembri Financial Limited <BOLD>(&ldquo;Schembri Financial&rdquo;)</BOLD>, Leaf Construction Management Inc. <BOLD>(&ldquo;Leaf&rdquo;)</BOLD> and 1784652 Ontario Inc. <BOLD>(&ldquo;178&rdquo;)</BOLD>.</P>
<P><BOLD>29.</BOLD> In the Schembri ROFR SJ Affidavit, Schembri states:
<P1>(a) in paragraph 1 that he is a representative of ROFR Corporate Defendants; and</P1>
<P1>(b) in paragraph 2 that the ROFR Corporate Defendants are controlled by him.</P1></P>
<P>I do not know what Schembri means by the term &ldquo;representative&rdquo;. I note that Schembri swore an affidavit of documents in the ROFR Action on September 30, 2014 (the <BOLD>&ldquo;Schembri ROFR AoD&rdquo;)</BOLD> on his own behalf only, and makes no reference to the ROFR Corporate Defendants. Accordingly, I am unclear as to what authority, if any, Schembri has to bring the ROFR SJ Motion on behalf of the ROFR Corporate Defendants. A copy of the Schembri ROFR AoD is attached hereto and marked as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;2&rdquo;</BOLD>.</P>
<P><BOLD>30.</BOLD> To my knowledge, Schembri had only one employee from the time we met until Schembri commenced the Main Action; his name was Tony Varriano.</P>
<P><BOLD>31.</BOLD> Fred Heimbecker <BOLD>(&ldquo;Heimbecker&rdquo;)</BOLD> was the lawyer for Schembri in connection with:
<P1>(a) the assembly of the JV Lands;</P1>
<P1>(b) the negotiation of the JV Agreement; and</P1>
<P1>(c) the negotiation of the Shareholder Agreement.</P1></P>
<P><BOLD>32.</BOLD> To my knowledge, Schembri did not have an accountant. However, Schembri did retain KPMG in or around the fall of 2009 in connection with what I refer to as JV Profit Dispute (defined in paragraph 34(a) below).</P>
<P><BOLD>33.</BOLD> Mike Milovick <BOLD>(&ldquo;Milovick&rdquo;)</BOLD> was a real estate agent in Kitchener who introduced Schembri to some of the properties that are the subject matter of the Main Action.</P></BLOCK2></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><N>3</N><TI>The Dispute</TI>
<P><BOLD>34.</BOLD> Schembri and I are now involved in a document intensive and protracted dispute that essentially revolves around:
<P1>(a) one completed real estate development at 345 King Street, Waterloo, Ontario <BOLD>(&ldquo;345 King&rdquo;)</BOLD> that was carried out as a joint venture (the <BOLD>&ldquo;JV Project&rdquo;)</BOLD> pursuant to a joint venture agreement (the <BOLD>&ldquo;JV Agreement&rdquo;)</BOLD> entered into in April, 2007 between 172 and 178; and</P1>
<P1>(b) three interrupted real estate developments&mdash;one each in Waterloo, London and Oshawa, Ontario (individually, the <BOLD>&ldquo;Waterloo Lands,</BOLD> the <BOLD>&ldquo;London Lands&rdquo;</BOLD> and the <BOLD>&ldquo;Oshawa Lands&rdquo;,</BOLD> respectively; and collectively, the <BOLD>&ldquo;Triumph Lands&rdquo;)</BOLD>&mdash;that were carried out pursuant to a shareholder agreement (the <BOLD>&ldquo;Shareholder Agreement&rdquo;)</BOLD> entered into in April, 2008 between KFI and Schembri Financial.</P1></P>
<P><BOLD>35.</BOLD> Our dispute (while complicated because of the numerous companies involved, the intertwined events and the number of documents), can be summarized as follows:
<P1>(a) Schembri is disputing the costs associated with the JV Project (the <BOLD>&ldquo;JV Profit Dispute&rdquo;)</BOLD>, in part based on a budget that formed part of the JV Agreement and related to a building never approved, financed, constructed, nor sold;</P1>
<P1>(b) Schembri is disputing 172's repayment of funds that my companies advanced prior to 172 obtaining construction financing (the <BOLD>&ldquo;JV Repayment Dispute&rdquo;);</BOLD></P1>
<P1>(c) Schembri is alleging that his receipt, directly or indirectly, of $1.4 million in the spring of 2009 was an advance against profits as opposed to a short-term loan (the <BOLD>&ldquo;Schembri Loan Dispute&rdquo;)</BOLD>;</P1>
<P1>(d) Schembri is disputing the use of monies from the sale of 345 King to fund the acquisition and commence the development of the Triumph Lands (the <BOLD>&ldquo;Rollover Dispute&rdquo;)</BOLD>;</P1>
<P1>(e) Schembri is disputing his obligation to contribute his proportionate share of the costs associated with the development of the Triumph Lands (the <BOLD>&ldquo;Triumph Contribution Dispute&rdquo;);</BOLD> and</P1>
<P1>(f) Schembri is disputing certain of the costs associated with the development of the Triumph Lands (the <BOLD>&ldquo;Triumph Costs Dispute&rdquo;)</BOLD>.</P1></P>
<P>In short, there are numerous disputes involving millions of dollars; put simply, we are involved in a multi-million dollar lawsuit.</P></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><N>4</N><TI>The JV Project</TI>
<BLOCK2><TI>Introduction to Schembri</TI>
<P><BOLD>36.</BOLD> I was informed by one of my site supervisors, Robert Tonin <BOLD>(&ldquo;Tonin&rdquo;)</BOLD>, and believed that Schembri approached him on a project (located at the corner of Erb Street and University Avenue in Waterloo) that Jamesway was constructing at the time. I was further informed by Tonin and believed that Schembri asked Tonin whether Jamesway would be interested in constructing a building on some lands that Schembri was in the process of assembling.</P></BLOCK2>
