<BLOCK2><TI>Schembri's Dealings with Jamesway/Premier Employees</TI>
<P><BOLD>43.</BOLD> After approaching Tonin, Schembri came to have dealings with Paul Vincent <BOLD>(&ldquo;Vincent&rdquo;)</BOLD>, an employee of Jamesway working in the Premier division. Their dealings led to a proposal by Premier dated November 8, 2006 <BOLD>(the &ldquo;Premier Proposal&rdquo;).</BOLD> Schembri did not accept the Premier Proposal. A copy of the Premier Proposal is attached hereto and marked as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;8&rdquo;.</BOLD></P>
<P><BOLD>44.</BOLD> Following Vincent's departure from Jamesway in late 2006 to return to Nova Scotia, Schembri then dealt primarily with Dan Bailey <BOLD>(&ldquo;Bailey&rdquo;),</BOLD> another employee of Jamesway working in the Premier division. Copies of various emails between Bailey and Schembri evidencing some of their dealings are attached hereto and marked as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;9&rdquo;.</BOLD></P>
<P><BOLD>45.</BOLD> In addition to dealing with Schembri, Bailey also dealt directly with Schembri's consultants. Copies of various emails between Bailey and:
<P1>(a) Guy Bellehumeur of GB Architect Inc.; and</P1>
<P1>(b) Gunter Nuessler of Progressive Engineering Services Ltd.; and</P1>
<P1>(c) Eric Chung of Chung &amp; Vander Doelen Engineering Ltd.</P1>
evidencing some of Bailey's direct dealings with each of them are attached hereto and marked as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;10&rdquo;.</BOLD></P>
<P><BOLD>46.</BOLD> Schembri's dealings with Bailey caused other employees of Jamesway to be involved with Schembri's efforts to redevelop the JV Lands. To the best of my recollection, such other employees of Jamesway included (in alphabetical order) Mike Bogias, Robert Corsi, Deepa Ganeshkumar, Ray Jacobs, Jeff King, Steve Silva, Mark Symons, and Adah Trabulsi. Copies of various handwritten notes of Ray Jacobs evidencing certain of these dealings are attached hereto and marked as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;11&rdquo;.</BOLD></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI>Financing Efforts</TI>
<P><BOLD>47.</BOLD> As stated in paragraph 27 above, I first met Schembri in or about late 2006 or early 2007, when Schembri was about 27 years old.</P>
<P><BOLD>48.</BOLD> From discussions with Schembri, I did not believe that he had the financial resources or the expertise to develop the JV Lands in the manner he was contemplating.</P>
<P><BOLD>49.</BOLD> I contacted John Pehlke <BOLD>(&ldquo;Pehlke&rdquo;),</BOLD> a mortgage broker. I introduced Pehlke to Schembri. I believe Pehlke attempted to source financing for Schembri, but was unsuccessful in doing so. A fax from Pehlke misdated January 31, 2006 is attached hereto and marked as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;12&rdquo;.</BOLD></P>
<P><BOLD>50.</BOLD> I attended a meeting with representatives of the Toronto-Dominion Bank <BOLD>(&ldquo;TD&rdquo;)</BOLD> on or about January 30, 2007. A handwritten note of this meeting with TD made by Ray Jacobs, a former employee of Jamesway, is attached hereto and marked as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;13&rdquo;.</BOLD></P>
<P><BOLD>51.</BOLD> I contacted Chris Cardno, who was my banker at CIBC. A copy of an email sent to me by Schembri attaching his net worth statement that I then forwarded to Mr. Cardno is attached hereto and marked as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;14&rdquo;.</BOLD></P>
<P><BOLD>52.</BOLD> I never promised Schembri that I would either:
<P1>(a) secure financing for him; or</P1>
<P1>(b) provide financing to him:</P1>
for the acquisition and development of the JV Lands. Rather, I assisted Schembri as he attempted to secure his own financing.</P></BLOCK2></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><N>5</N><TI>The JV Agreement</TI>
<P><BOLD>53.</BOLD> When it became apparent that Schembri could not obtain financing to complete the purchases of 341 King Street, 349 King Street and 340 Spruce Street, Waterloo, I offered to complete the acquisition of those properties and then develop the JV Lands in the manner contemplated by Schembri.</P>
<P><BOLD>54.</BOLD> I came to believe subsequently that a reason why Schembri may have been unable to obtain financing in his own name to complete any of these purchases was because Schembri had not attended to his personal tax filings and remittances. I learned this in or around the spring of 2009, when Schembri requested to borrow money for around a month to, in part, &ldquo;bridge&rdquo; him until he attended to his tax obligations which would then permit him to arrange mortgage financing on his personal residence that he was in the process of constructing. This borrowing by Schembri relates to the Schembri Loan Dispute (and is addressed below).</P>
<P><BOLD>55.</BOLD> Further to paragraph 53 above, it was my offer to Schembri that led to the suggestion that the development of the JV Lands be carried out by way of a joint venture.</P>
<P><BOLD>56.</BOLD> As stated in paragraph 8(b)(i) above, I did not lie to Schembri. Schembri knew that if my companies and I were going to take on the financial risk of the JV Project (then estimated at around $19,000,000) I required that my companies be in control of the development of the JV Lands.</P>
<P><BOLD>57.</BOLD> The negotiation of the JV Agreement occurred over a matter of days; not &ldquo;approximately 2 or 3 weeks&rdquo; as alleged in paragraph 16 of the Schembri April 2010 Affidavit.</P>
<P><BOLD>58.</BOLD> Patterson did not &ldquo;negotiate&rdquo; the JV Agreement as alleged in paragraph 16 of the Schembri April 2010 Affidavit; rather Patterson typed up certain wording negotiated between Schembri and me, and exchanged drafts by email with Heimbecker. Copies of the emails exchanged by Patterson and Heimbecker in this regard are attached hereto and marked as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;15&rdquo;</BOLD>.</P>
<P><BOLD>59.</BOLD> Based on the dates appearing on page two and page three of the JV Pro Forma, I believe Schembri and I executed the JV Agreement no earlier than April 29, 2007 (which was a Sunday according to the calendar). A copy of the JV Agreement is attached hereto and marked as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;16&rdquo;</BOLD>.</P>
<P><BOLD>60.</BOLD> The JV Agreement contained provisions for, among other things, the following:
<P1>(a) financing;</P1>
<P1>(b) planning, management and supervision;</P1>
<P1>(c) a pro forma and budget;</P1>
<P1>(d) a &ldquo;5 and 5&rdquo; fee;</P1>
<P1>(e) determination of profit; and</P1>
<P1>(f) distribution of funds;</P1>
which are addressed further below.</P>
<BLOCK2><TI>Financing of the JV</TI>
<P><BOLD>61.</BOLD> Paragraph 2(7) of the JV Agreement states:
<QUOTE><P><BOLD><EM>[172] shall be responsible for obtaining financing for the Joint Venture for the Project</EM>,</BOLD> <EM>including interim, bridge and permanent financing</EM>, <BOLD><EM>consistent with the sound business judgment and with loan rate, terms and conditions prevailing</EM>.</BOLD> (emphasis added)</P></QUOTE></P>
<P><BOLD>62.</BOLD> Paragraph 2(8) of the JV Agreement states, in part:
<QUOTE><P><BOLD><EM>[172] shall have the right to encumber the Lands or the Project</EM></BOLD> <EM>without the consent of the other</EM> <BOLD><EM>in amounts sufficient to cover the full contribution of [172]</EM>.</BOLD> (emphasis added)</P></QUOTE></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI>Planning, Management and Supervisory Services</TI>
<P><BOLD>63.</BOLD> Paragraph 2(10) of the JV Agreement states:
<QUOTE><P><BOLD><EM>The Joint Venturers appoint Jamesway Construction (Jamesway) to supervise and manage the construction process</EM>.</BOLD> <EM>Jamesway will complete the construction of the project</EM>. <BOLD><EM>Either Joint Venturer can</EM></BOLD> <EM>participate in the site management meetings during the construction process and</EM> <BOLD><EM>make decisions through the standard construction practice</EM>.</BOLD> (emphasis added)</P></QUOTE></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI>Pro Forma and Budget</TI>
<P><BOLD>64.</BOLD> Paragraph 2(9) of the JV Agreement states:
<QUOTE><P><EM>In managing the Joint Venture:</EM></P>
<P>(a) <EM>A Major Decision shall be made by both Joint Venturers. All other decisions shall be made by [172]</EM>.</P>
<P>(b) <BOLD><EM>It is agreed that the attached Project Budget and Performa, referred to as Schedule A, has been reviewed and agreed upon by both Joint Venturers</EM>.</BOLD></P>
<P>(c) <EM>Construction Contracts shall be agreed and awarded by both Joint Venturers through an open book concept save and except for any work performed by Jamesway. Any increase to Jamesway's contract shall be agreed to by both parties</EM>.</P>
<P>(d) <BOLD><EM>Any increase to the budgetshallbe agreedupon by both Joint Venturers</EM>.</BOLD> (emphasis added)</P></QUOTE></P>
<P><BOLD>65.</BOLD> The &ldquo;Project Budget and Performa&rdquo; attached as Schedule A to the JV Agreement is three pages (the <BOLD>&ldquo;JV Pro Forma&rdquo;).</BOLD></P>
<P><BOLD>66.</BOLD> The first page of the JV Pro Forma is a pro forma relating to a building containing a total of 374 bedrooms in 82 units, and having 82 parking spaces. This page was created by Pehlke, and subsequently revised by me in consultation with Schembri.</P>
<P><BOLD>67.</BOLD> The second page of the JV Pro Forma (bearing a date of April 29, 2007) is a budget for the construction costs. Construction costs are also referred to as hard costs. The cost per square foot at the bottom of the second page (namely, $96.07) appears in the line item calculation for &ldquo;Construction&mdash;Building and Site&rdquo; on the first page of the JV Pro Forma. I see that the budget for the construction costs did not include asphalt and masonry; both of which were necessary work.</P>
<P><BOLD>68.</BOLD> The third page of the JV Pro Forma (also bearing a date of April 29, 2007) provides a breakdown of the general conditions, which is a line item in the budget for the construction costs. General conditions relate to items not directly related to the physical construction activities. The winter conditions line item in the general conditions relates to providing heat inside a building for the benefit of all trades as they perform their respective construction activities. This is in contrast to winter construction, which relates to construction activities being performed during the winter by specific trades. Typically, the costs associated with winter construction are borne by those trades performing their work during winter. The JV Pro Forma did not contemplate winter construction for the superstructure and stucco. A copy of an article about winter construction is attached hereto and marked as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;17&rdquo;.</BOLD></P>
<P><BOLD>69.</BOLD> I have reviewed the drawings existing at the time Schembri and I executed the JV Agreement and see that the drawings provide for a building containing a total of 374 bedrooms and 163 bathrooms in 82 units, and having 83 parking spaces (the <BOLD>&ldquo;JV Pro Forma Building Design&rdquo;)</BOLD>. Copies of the following drawings dated March 29, 2007 are attached hereto and marked as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;18&rdquo;</BOLD>:
