as the work Schembri contracted them to perform was paid by my companies (after reissuance of invoices in some instances). Copies of the invoices rendered by Schembri's consultants and the cheques evidencing payment thereof are attached hereto and marked as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;23&rdquo;.</BOLD></P>
<P><BOLD>83.</BOLD> To my knowledge, the only document Schembri provided relating to payments he made in connection with the acquisition, carrying and development of the JV Lands is a letter dated May 31, 2008 stating that Schembri &ldquo;advanced $47,500&rdquo; to KFI. This letter is attached hereto and marked as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;24&rdquo;.</BOLD></P></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><N>7</N><TI>Maestro</TI>
<P><BOLD>84.</BOLD> Around the time that 172 acquired the JV Lands, I learned that an owner of student residences called Maestro (that was based in Quebec) was interested in the JV Project. A copy of an email sent to me on May 14, 2007 by Pierre Pelletier of Maestro is attached hereto and marked as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;25&rdquo;.</BOLD></P>
<P><BOLD>85.</BOLD> Maestro subsequently offered to pay $24,300,000 for the construction of a building: (a) containing a total of 360 bedrooms and 360 bathrooms in 94 units; and; (b) having 95 parking spaces (the <BOLD>&ldquo;Maestro Offer&rdquo;)</BOLD>. A copy of the Maestro Offer is attached hereto and marked as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;26&rdquo;.</BOLD></P>
<P><BOLD>86.</BOLD> Consequently, Premier redesigned the building to meet the requirements of Maestro, and prepared a pro forma and budget in connection therewith. Schembri agreed with doing so; and Schembri agreed with the pro forma and budget. A copy of this pro forma and budget is attached hereto and marked as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;27&rdquo;.</BOLD></P>
<P><BOLD>87.</BOLD> Schembri and I agreed to negotiate the Maestro Offer. In furtherance of our agreement, 172 retained Ian Wismer at Miller Thomson in Waterloo, and prepared a memorandum setting out the main business terms of a counteroffer. This memorandum was the subject of further negotiation between Maestro and 172. Copies of the memorandum dated July 9, 2007 and the subsequent revisions are attached hereto and marked as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;28&rdquo;.</BOLD></P>
<P><BOLD>88.</BOLD> Maestro withdrew from further negotiations following receipt of a market study dated September 11, 2007. A copy of this market study is attached hereto and marked as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;29&rdquo;.</BOLD></P></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><N>8</N><TI>JV Site Plan Meetings with City of Waterloo</TI>
<P><BOLD>89.</BOLD> In furtherance of the JV Project, 158 made the various payments to the City in the summer of 2007 on behalf of 172. Copies of the documents evidencing the foregoing payments by 158 are attached hereto and marked as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;30&rdquo;</BOLD>.</P>
<P><BOLD>90.</BOLD> The JV Project was considered by the City's Site Plan Review Committee on July 23, 2007. Attached hereto and marked as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;31&rdquo;</BOLD> is a copy of:
<P1>(a) a letter from the City to assist with the site plan application for the JV Project; and</P1>
<P1>(b) an excerpt from the minutes of this site plan meeting as it relates to the JV Project.</P1></P>
<P><BOLD>91.</BOLD> The JV Project was considered further by the City's Site Plan Review Committee on August 13, 2007. Attached hereto and marked as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;32&rdquo;</BOLD> is an excerpt from the minutes of this site plan meeting as it relates to the JV Project.</P>
<P><BOLD>92.</BOLD> As appears from the letter and excerpted minutes, Schembri knew that the City required various design changes, certain of which are summarized below.</P></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><N>9</N><TI>JV Demolition Permit</TI>
<P><BOLD>93.</BOLD> I believe that Bailey had to chase Schembri to sign the forms necessary to obtain demolition permits for the houses on the JV Lands. Copies of the emails sent by Bailey to Schembri forming the basis of my belief in this regard are attached hereto and marked as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;33&rdquo;</BOLD>.</P>
<P><BOLD>94.</BOLD> The City subsequently issued five demolition permits dated November 29, 2007 for the houses on the JV Lands (collectively, the <BOLD>&ldquo;JV Demolition Permits&rdquo;)</BOLD> following receipt of payment in the amount of $4,750 from 158 on behalf of 172 (the <BOLD>&ldquo;JV Demolition Permits Payment&rdquo;)</BOLD>. The JV Demolition Permits and the JV Demolition Permits Payment are attached hereto and marked as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;34&rdquo;.</BOLD></P>
<P><BOLD>95.</BOLD> I believe Schembri arranged for Sittler Environmental to demolish the houses on the JV Lands. Sittler Environmental did not render an invoice for the demolition until or around February, 2010. Copies of the purchase order, the invoice and the cheque evidencing payment are attached hereto and marked as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;35&rdquo;.</BOLD></P></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><N>10</N><TI>JV Construction Financing</TI>
<P><BOLD>96.</BOLD> Throughout the fall of 2007, I attempted to obtain construction financing for the JV Project. In furtherance of my efforts, I caused 172 to engage Murray &amp; Company to locate mezzanine financing in the approximate amount of $5 million.</P>
<P><BOLD>97.</BOLD> Murray &amp; Company sourced Trez as a potential lender of mezzanine financing.</P>
<P><BOLD>98.</BOLD> Murray &amp; Company then sourced Kingsett Capital as a potential lender of mezzanine financing. Following negotiations, 172 entered into a financing commitment from Kingsett Capital in the amount of $4,950,000 (the <BOLD>&ldquo;Kingsett Commitment&rdquo;)</BOLD>. Copies of the Kingsett Commitment and the prior proposals are attached hereto and marked as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;36&rdquo;.</BOLD></P>
<P><BOLD>99.</BOLD> One issue in the prior proposals of Kingsett related to their requirement that certain of the work to be performed requiring the contractors to be bonded, which would mean additional cost to 172 in carrying out the JV Project. 172 negotiated that term, and avoided that additional cost.</P>
<P><BOLD>100.</BOLD> As a consequence of the Kingsett Commitment, 172 finalized a construction financing commitment from CIBC in the amount of $14,600,000 (the <BOLD>&ldquo;CIBC Construction Commitment&rdquo;)</BOLD>. A copy of the CIBC Construction Commitment is attached hereto and marked as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;37&rdquo;.</BOLD></P>
