<BLOCK1><N>18</N><TI>Construction of JV Approved Building Design Commences</TI>
<P><BOLD>136.</BOLD> Following issuance of the JV Building Permit, Terra-Tec commenced performance of site servicing and earthworks.</P>
<P><BOLD>137.</BOLD> Around the time that construction of the JV Approved Building Design commenced, Schembri and I agreed that he would act as &ldquo;owner's rep&rdquo;, and that 172 would pay him $500 per week for doing so (the <BOLD>&ldquo;Owner's Rep Agreement&rdquo;).</BOLD></P>
<P><BOLD>138.</BOLD> Contrary to Schembri's allegation, the Owner's Rep Agreement was not incorporated as a line item in the breakdown of the general conditions (at the third page of the JV Pro Forma bearing a date of April 29, 2007, nearly one year prior to the Owner's Rep Agreement).</P>
<P><BOLD>139.</BOLD> Tonin was site superintendent, and as such was on site almost every day construction took place. John MacDonald was project manager, and worked primarily from Jamesway's offices.</P>
<P><BOLD>140.</BOLD> As stated in paragraph 57 and 59 of the Schembri April 2010 Affidavit, Schembri was: (a) onsite at 345 King; and (b) in contact with me; almost every day construction took place. In addition, Schembri attended at Jamesway's premises almost daily, and joked that he ought to have a desk beside Patterson.</P>
<P><BOLD>141.</BOLD> At some point during the early stages of construction, two things occurred. First, Schembri and I agreed to install security cameras in and on the building. This involved repurposing the security cameras previously purchased and installed on the site trailers, and purchasing additional security cameras. 172 entered into a purchase order with Leaf for this work. Copies of the documents relating to the foregoing are attached hereto and marked as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;50&rdquo;.</BOLD></P>
<P><BOLD>142.</BOLD> Secondly, Schembri decided that he wanted to reconfigure the ground floor and the basement of the JV Approved Building Design as he believed doing so would increase the value of 345 King. Subsequently, drawings were prepared providing for this reconfiguration.</P>
<P><BOLD>143.</BOLD> As a consequence of this reconfiguration, 172 had to submit revised drawings to the City for approval and pay a fee in the amount of $1,363.20 (the <BOLD>&ldquo;Reconfiguration Fee&rdquo;)</BOLD>. Copies of certain documents relating to the Reconfiguration Fee are attached hereto and marked as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;51&rdquo;.</BOLD></P>
