<BLOCK1><N>19</N><TI>The Shareholder Agreement</TI>
<P><BOLD>145.</BOLD> At some point before April 9, 2008, Schembri and I executed the Shareholder Agreement. A copy of an email sent April 9, 2008 forming the basis of my belief as to the timing of execution is attached hereto and marked as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;53&rdquo;.</BOLD> A copy of the Shareholder Agreement is attached hereto and marked as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;54&rdquo;.</BOLD></P>
<P><BOLD>146.</BOLD> The Shareholder Agreement provided for, among other things, the following:
<P1>(a) financing;</P1>
<P1>(b) non-competition (aka the ROFR Clause); and</P1>
<P1>(c) arbitration; and</P1>
<P1>(d) final agreement;</P1>
which are discussed further below.</P>
<BLOCK2><TI>Financing</TI>
<P><BOLD>147.</BOLD> Article 12 of the Shareholder Agreement (the <BOLD>&ldquo;Contribution Provision&rdquo;)</BOLD> states:
<QUOTE><P><BOLD><EM>All liabilities incurred by, arising from or in connection with [Triumph]</EM>,</BOLD> <EM>including any loans or overdrafts with any banks or lending institutions, which have been personally guaranteed by any of the parties hereto</EM>, <BOLD><EM>shall be shared on a pro rata basis by the parties hereto</EM></BOLD> <EM>based on a fraction the numerator of which shall be the number of shares held by each Shareholder and the denominator of which shall be the total issued and outstanding shares in the capital stock of [Triumph]</EM> <BOLD><EM>and if any of the parties hereto discharges any liabilities of [Triumph]</EM></BOLD> <EM>either</EM> <BOLD><EM>directly</EM></BOLD> <EM>or pursuant to a guarantee given by any of the parties hereto</EM>, <BOLD><EM>then the party discharging the liabilities shall have the right to be reimbursed</EM></BOLD> <EM>by the parties not so contributing</EM> <BOLD><EM>so that the in the end result, each of the parties hereto shall have contributed equally to all liabilities incurred</EM></BOLD> <EM>and/or guarantees given. Until such time that the parties not so contributing have reimbursed the party discharging the liability, the shares of the parties not so contributing shall be held by the accountants of [Triumph] acting as escrow agent and at the option of the party discharging the liability, said shares may be sold if the parties not so contributing have not reimbursed the party discharging the liabilities within THIRTY (30) days after the party discharging the liabilities has demanded reimbursement thereof and the proceeds from the sale of such shares after deduction of any expenses incurred in the sale, shall be applied on account of the debt owing from the parties not so contributing to the party discharging the liabilities, but any surplus of proceeds over and above the debt owing shall be distributed to the parties not so contributing</EM>. (emphasis added)</P></QUOTE></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI>Non-Competition (aka the ROFR Clause)</TI>
<P><BOLD>148.</BOLD> Article 13 of the Shareholder Agreement (the <BOLD>&ldquo;ROFR Clause&rdquo;)</BOLD> states:
<QUOTE><P><BOLD><EM>During the period which [Schembri Financial] is a shareholder of the Corporation, it shall have the ongoing obligation to present to [KFI] and [Triumph] all real estate development opportunities (the &ldquo;Project&rdquo;) which it may have acquired within the Regional Municipality of Waterloo</EM>.</BOLD> <EM>This obligation to [KFI] and [Triumph] shall also extend to [Schembri] personally, and any other legal entity in which he has an interest, either directly or indirectly, financially or otherwise. [KFI] and [Triumph] shall have FIFTEEN (15) days following the presentation of the Project to them to determine if it is economically feasible using the typical budget model consistently utilized by them in such circumstances and, if at the expiry of the FIFTEEN (15) day period neither of them have indicated to [Schembri Financial] in writing that it is taking on the Project, then [Schembri Financial] (or its designate) shall be free to pursue the Project without the involvement of [KFI] or [Triumph]</EM>. (emphasis added)</P></QUOTE></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI>Arbitration</TI>
<P><BOLD>149.</BOLD> Article 15 of the Shareholder Agreement (the <BOLD>&ldquo;Arbitration Provision&rdquo;)</BOLD> states:
<QUOTE><P><BOLD><EM>Any dispute</EM></BOLD> <EM>between the parties hereto, whether arising during the period of this Agreement or at any time thereafter</EM> <BOLD><EM>which touches upon the validity, construction, meaning, performance or effect of this Agreement or the rights and liabilities of the parties hereto</EM></BOLD> <EM>or any matter arising out of or connected with this Agreement</EM> <BOLD><EM>shall be subject to arbitration pursuant to the Arbitrations Act, 1991</EM>,</BOLD> <EM>as amended from time to time, and as provided for in this Article and the decision shall be final and binding between the parties hereto and shall not be subject to appeal</EM>. (emphasis added)</P></QUOTE></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI>Final Agreement</TI>
<P><BOLD>150.</BOLD> Article 23 of the Shareholder Agreement states:
<QUOTE><P><BOLD><EM>This Agreement expresses the final agreement between the parties hereto with respect to all matters herein</EM></BOLD> <EM>and its execution has not been induced by, nor do any of the parties hereto rely upon or regard as material, any representation or premises [sic] whatsoever not incorporated herein or made a part hereof, and any alteration, amendment or qualification thereof shall be null and void and shall not be binding upon any such party unless made and recorded as aforesaid</EM>. (emphasis added)</P></QUOTE></P>
<P><BOLD>151.</BOLD> Finally I note that the Shareholder Agreement does not require KFI (or me personally) to either:
<P1>(a) fund the development of the properties to be acquired through subsidiaries of Triumph; or</P1>
<P1>(b) guarantee third party financing for the development of such properties.</P1></P>
<P><BOLD>152.</BOLD> It is preposterous for Schembri to allege after the fact that I agreed to (a) above. Schembri is talking about tens of millions of dollars in funding that would cost millions of dollars in fees and interest if such funding was provided by third parties. Then there is the risk; I would have all the risk and Schembri would have none. I note that Schembri did not make this allegation until he sought to amend his statement of claim in the Main Action. Finally, to my knowledge Schembri has not sued Heimbecker for his failure to include such a significant term in the Shareholder Agreement.</P></BLOCK2></BLOCK1>
