<BLOCK1><N>23</N><TI>Construction of JV Approved Building Continues</TI>
<P><BOLD>166.</BOLD> In or around August, 2008, Rejean Dupuis <BOLD>(&ldquo;Dupuis&rdquo;)</BOLD> took over from John MacDonald as project manager for the JV Project.</P>
<P><BOLD>167.</BOLD> Over the summer and into the fall, a number of events occurred giving rise to agreements between Schembri and me, some of which resulted in additional costs to the JV Project.</P>
<P><BOLD>168.</BOLD> One such event related to people entering the building during the night and jumping out of the building and into the safety netting below (that had been erected over the area being worked on by the masons to protect them from anything that may fall while the stucco trades worked above them). As a consequence, Schembri and I agreed to hire security guards to attend onsite overnight. Copies of the invoices relating to the provision of security guards are attached hereto and marked as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;61&rdquo;.</BOLD></P>
<P><BOLD>169.</BOLD> Schembri and I agreed to provide and operate a man lift to assist trades working inside the building. A copy of the change order in this regard is attached hereto and marked as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;62&rdquo;.</BOLD></P>
<P><BOLD>170.</BOLD> Another event related to the identification of a grading issue that resulted in Patterson organizing an onsite meeting among the landscape designer (Guenter Nuessler), Tonin and MacDonald. A copy of the notes of this meeting is attached hereto and marked as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;63&rdquo;.</BOLD></P>
<BLOCK2><TI>Stucco Delay and The Fall</TI>
<P><BOLD>171.</BOLD> The most significant, and serious, event occurred when an employee of a stucco subcontractor fell off a scaffold in November, 2008 and suffered serious injuries (the <BOLD>&ldquo;Fall&rdquo;).</BOLD> As a consequence of the Fall, the Ministry of Labour issued a Stop Work Order (the <BOLD>&ldquo;MoL Stop Work Order&rdquo;)</BOLD>. The Ministry of Labour subsequently lifted the MoL Stop Work Order after imposing various safety measures. Copies of the documents relating to the Fall and the MoL Stop Work Order are attached hereto and marked as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;64&rdquo;.</BOLD> Pictures of the scaffolds are attached hereto and marked as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;65&rdquo;.</BOLD></P>
<P><BOLD>172.</BOLD> The stucco work had already been delayed as a result of the contractor, MIK Wall Systems Inc. <BOLD>(&ldquo;MIK&rdquo;)</BOLD> having insufficient labour onsite. The Fall further delayed the stucco work, and pushed it into wintertime. As a consequence of the delay in completing the stucco work, completion of the parkade was interrupted to accommodate the scaffold/lifts needed for the performance of the stucco work. This in turn required Jamesway employees to use hand tools to keep the exposed rebar in the parkade free of snow and ice. A picture of the exposed rebar in the parkade is attached hereto and marked as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;66&rdquo;.</BOLD></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI>Minutes of Construction Meetings</TI>
<P><BOLD>173.</BOLD> In connection with the construction of the JV Approved Building Design as reconfigured, Jamesway held thirty-seven (37) meetings with contractors between April 7, 2008 and January 26, 2009 (for the most part on a weekly basis). Minutes of these meetings would be prepared by an employee of Jamesway and distributed by facsimile transmission to the various trades. Attached hereto and marked as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;67&rdquo;</BOLD> is a table showing:
<P1>(a) the dates of these meetings; and</P1>
<P1>(b) whether Schembri, his father (Mario) and/or his employee (Tony Varriano) attended a particular meeting, and/or received a copy of the meeting minutes by facsimile transmission.</P1></P>
<P><BOLD>174.</BOLD> I addressed above certain of Schembri's direct involvement in the construction process. I now wish to address the direct involvement of Schembri's employee, Tony Varriano. As shown in Exhibit &ldquo;67&rdquo;, Tony Varriano attended site meetings. Tony Varriano also communicated with Dupuis and other Jamesway employees in connection with various construction activities. Copies of emails evidencing the direct involvement of Tony Varriano in the construction process are attached hereto and marked as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;68&rdquo;.</BOLD></P>
<P><BOLD>175.</BOLD> In connection with the financing requirements, 172 provided financial information to cm2r. I believe cm2r reviewed this information, verified that information (by among other things, attending at the building), and once satisfied incorporated that information into their reports to CIBC and Kingsett. cm2r prepared eleven such reports commencing January 31, 2008 and ending December 31, 2008 (collectively, the <BOLD>&ldquo;cm2r Reports&rdquo;)</BOLD> on a monthly basis, save and except for the month of February.</P></BLOCK2></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><N>24</N><TI>Incorporation of Oxford &amp; First and Simcoe &amp; Eastwood</TI>
