<BLOCK1><N>26</N><TI>Efforts to Close Maas APS</TI>
<P><BOLD>183.</BOLD> As stated in paragraph 161 above, closing of the Maas APS was to occur &ldquo;14 days following the date that occupancy approval is granted by the [City] for the intended project herein&rdquo;. In furtherance thereof, Jamesway worked hard to obtain occupancy approval as quickly as possible, and succeeded in doing so on or about February 6, 2009 and a closing date of February 20, 2009 was set. Copies of certain of the documents evidencing the foregoing efforts to close to set the closing date for February 20, 2009 are attached hereto and marked as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;75&rdquo;.</BOLD></P>
<P><BOLD>184.</BOLD> Another term of the Maas APS required 172 to use best efforts to rent out units, and that Maas would be entitled to hold back up to $400,000 pending renting up to 90% of the building by no later than October 31, 2009. In paragraph 38 of the Schembri April 2010 Affidavit, Schembri alleges that he located Wilfrid Laurier University as a tenant and negotiated a long-term for the entire building. This is not true. Others were involved in the effort to fulfill this term, and avoid any hold back; Schembri did not locate Wilfrid Laurier University, nor negotiate the lease. Copies of the documents relating to the lease with Wilfrid Laurier University are attached hereto and marked as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;76&rdquo;.</BOLD></P>
<P><BOLD>185.</BOLD> Around this time, Schembri and I learned that 172 may not be entitled to claim the new residential rental property rebate because we would be selling 345 King. Copies of emails evidencing the foregoing are attached hereto and marked as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;77&rdquo;.</BOLD></P></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><N>27</N><TI>Maas $6m Non-Refundable Deposit</TI>
<P><BOLD>186.</BOLD> Between the date of the Maas APS and the approaching closing date of February 20, 2009, the U.S. economy had weakened and there appeared to me, upon reflection, dissension in the Maas family.</P>
<P><BOLD>187.</BOLD> I came to be contacted by Terry Maas, the older half-brother of Sean Maas, and negotiated with him an extension of the Maas APS. Our negotiation began with a telephone discussion a few days before the approaching closing date. Schembri was in my office as I spoke with Terry Maas on speaker phone about the approaching closing date. Terry Maas wanted an extension. I told him that I had other deals that were set to close, and that I needed to use the proceeds from closing the Maas APS to complete those deals. After further discussion between Terry Maas and me (that Schembri heard as he sat in my office), we agreed to extend the closing of the Maas APS on the condition that 172 receive a non-refundable deposit in the amount of $6,000,000 (the <BOLD>&ldquo;$6 Million Non-Refundable Deposit&rdquo;).</BOLD></P>
<P><BOLD>188.</BOLD> To the best of my recollection, Volpini papered the deal for the $6 Million Non-Refundable Deposit. Copies of the documents evidencing the papering of this deal are attached hereto and marked as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;78&rdquo;.</BOLD></P>
<P><BOLD>189.</BOLD> After Terry Maas and I had agreed to extend the Maas APS on the condition that Maas pay the $6 Million Non-Refundable Deposit, Schembri, Patterson and I gathered in the boardroom of Jamesway's office and discussed how to receive the $6 Million NonRefundable Deposit.</P>
<P><BOLD>190.</BOLD> During the course of this discussion, we asked Crozier to join us to discuss our anticipated receipt of the $6 Million Non-Refundable Deposit and our need to use some of those funds to complete the acquisition of the Oshawa Lands.</P>
<P><BOLD>191.</BOLD> Upon hearing from Crozier, Schembri and I then agreed to put the $6 Million Non-Refundable Deposit into an account of Premier at the Bank of Montreal so that these funds would be readily available to complete the purchases of the Oshawa Lands.</P>
<P><BOLD>192.</BOLD> This is what Schembri and I agreed; and this is what we did.</P></BLOCK1>
