<P><BOLD>249.</BOLD> The scope and value of the construction work performed by third parties exceeds the scope and value of the construction work performed by the Way Group. That remains true even if we take into consideration the services provided by Premier in designing and project management, in respect of which Schembri's consultants contributed.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI>There Was No Improper Transfer of $6 Million</TI>
<P><BOLD>250.</BOLD> There was no &ldquo;improper transfer of $6 million dollars of joint venture funds to Premier Project Consultants&rdquo;. The agreement between Schembri and me as to how to receive the $6m Non-Refundable is detailed above.</P>
<P><BOLD>251.</BOLD> The &ldquo;paper trail&rdquo; for the $6m Non-Refundable Deposit was created by Crozier, and not Lund as I believed. Regardless, there is a paper trail and Crozier spoke to this in her affidavit sworn 23, 2011 (the <BOLD>&ldquo;Crozier Affidavit&rdquo;)</BOLD> in response to the First Amendment Motion (defined in paragraph 306 below). To my recollection, Crozier was not cross-examined on the Crozier Affidavit. A copy of the Crozier Affidavit is attached hereto and marked as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;110&rdquo;.</BOLD></P>
<P><BOLD>252.</BOLD> The Deloitte Report (defined in paragraph 307 below) corroborates the paper trail. Whereas, neither Schembri nor KPMG has disputed the Deloitte Report.</P></BLOCK2></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><N>43</N><TI>The Receivership Proceedings</TI>
<P><BOLD>253.</BOLD> The appointment of a Receiver by Madam Justice Roberts resulted in a court proceeding supervised by the Commercial List in Toronto (the <BOLD>&ldquo;Receivership Proceedings&rdquo;).</BOLD> There were numerous court attendances in the Receivership Proceedings.</P>
<P><BOLD>254.</BOLD> Listed below are the reports submitted by the Receiver to the court:
<TABLE>
<SGMLTBL>
<TBLBODY TBLWD="600">
