<BLOCK2><TI>The Claims Procedure</TI>
<P><BOLD>255.</BOLD> The Receiver conducted a claims procedure (the <BOLD>&ldquo;Claims Procedure&rdquo;)</BOLD> pursuant to an Order dated January 28, 2011 issued on consent (the <BOLD>&ldquo;Claims Procedure Order&rdquo;).</BOLD> A copy of the Claims Procedure Order is attached hereto and marked as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;112&rdquo;.</BOLD></P>
<P><BOLD>256.</BOLD> I caused seventeen unsecured claims to be filed, which were contained in a four volume claims brief that total 1,272 pages in pdf format (the <BOLD>&ldquo;Way Claims Brief&rdquo;).</BOLD></P>
<P><BOLD>257.</BOLD> Included among the seventeen claims were six claims filed by KFI and 172 in respect of funds they advanced through to the Triumph Subsidiaries (the <BOLD>&ldquo;Way Tracing Claims&rdquo;).</BOLD> In the Way Claims Brief, the Way Tracing Claims were illustrated in spreadsheets prepared by Crozier and supported by various banking records, including cancelled cheques assembled by Crozier. Copies of these spreadsheets are attached hereto and marked as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;113&rdquo;.</BOLD></P>
<P><BOLD>258.</BOLD> Following a request for clarification by the Receiver, I caused a supplementary claims brief (that totals 98 pages in pdf format) to be prepared and provided to the Receiver (the <BOLD>&ldquo;Supplementary Way Claims Brief&rdquo;).</BOLD></P>
<P><BOLD>259.</BOLD> A copy of the Way Claims Brief and the Supplementary Way Claims Brief will be filed separately as they consist of nearly 1,400 pages.</P>
<P><BOLD>260.</BOLD> The Receiver reported to the Court with respect to the Claims Procedure in the Fifth Report dated June 17, 2011 (the <BOLD>&ldquo;Fifth Report&rdquo;).</BOLD> As stated in paragraph 8 of the Fifth Report, the Receiver summarized &ldquo;<EM>the claims received, the Receiver's disallowances and revisions, disputed disallowances, and claims that have been accepted by the Receiver (in original or amended form) following disallowance and dispute</EM>&rdquo; in Appendix &ldquo;B&rdquo; to the Fifth Report. A copy of Appendix &ldquo;B&rdquo; to the Fifth Report is attached hereto and marked as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;114&rdquo;.</BOLD></P>
<P><BOLD>261.</BOLD> In January, 2012, my counsel and counsel for Schembri exchanged copies of the claims documentation filed with the Receiver by their respective clients; namely, my counsel sent the Way Claims Brief and Supplementary Way Claims Brief and received the claim documentation filed by Schembri (the <BOLD>&ldquo;Schembri Claims&rdquo;).</BOLD> A copy of the Schembri Claims is attached hereto and marked as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;115&rdquo;.</BOLD></P>
<P><BOLD>262.</BOLD> I reviewed the Schembri Claims. I found them confusing as:
<P1>(a) certain claims had multiple claimants which appear to be inconsistent with the supporting documentation;</P1>
<P1>(b) the same amount was initially sought on the same basis in separate claims against each of the Triumph Subsidiaries;</P1>
<P1>(c) certain claims were subsequently amended; and</P1>
<P1>(d) the same debt appeared in separate claims initially made by different claimants, and then subsequently amended to be claimed twice by the same claimant.</P1></P>
<P><BOLD>263.</BOLD> I also found certain of the Schembri Claims lacking because:
<P1>(a) the sole supporting documentation were invoices dated March 11, 2011 (being a week prior to the claims bar date); and/or</P1>
<P1>(b) no supporting documentation evidencing payments for which reimbursement was being sought was provided.</P1></P>
<P><BOLD>264.</BOLD> Finally, I learned that certain of the Schembri Claims were clearly improper as:
<P1>(a) a claim for $3,148.18 had already been reimbursed, with the proof of such reimbursement being contained in the Way Claims Brief; and</P1>
<P1>(b) a claim for $20,000 related to a deposit paid by one of my companies and not Schembri.</P1></P>
<P><BOLD>265.</BOLD> I addressed the Schembri Claims in my affidavits sworn January 31, 2012 and March 14, 2012. Copies of these affidavits are attached hereto and marked as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;116&rdquo;.</BOLD></P>
<P><BOLD>266.</BOLD> The Receiver accepted that the Schembri Claims in paragraph 265 above were improper.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI>Schembri's Motion re Oshawa Lands</TI>
<P><BOLD>267.</BOLD> During the course of the receivership proceedings, Schembri brought a motion seeking an order compelling me to guarantee construction financing for the development of the Oshawa Lands by the Receiver.</P>
<P><BOLD>268.</BOLD> By Endorsement dated July 18, 2011, Justice Mesbur dismissed Schembri's motion and awarded me costs in the amount of $37,500, all inclusive. A copy of this endorsement is attached hereto and marked as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;117&rdquo;.</BOLD></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI>Sale of the Triumph Lands</TI>
<P><BOLD>269.</BOLD> Contrary to paragraph 42 of the Schembri ROFR SJ Affidavit, I did submit an offer&mdash;an en bloc credit bid offer&mdash;that would have preserved the claims of creditors in full (including myself) while recognizing the more than $2 million KFI had contributed to the Triumph Subisidiaries (as shown in the Way Claims Brief) as compared to the thousands of dollars Schembri and his companies had contributed. A copy of an article about credit bids in Canadian insolvencies is attached hereto and marked as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;118&rdquo;.</BOLD></P>
<P><BOLD>270.</BOLD> Ultimately, the Triumph Lands were sold by the Receiver to:
<P1>(a) Schembri (Waterloo and London) as addressed in the Sixth Report; and</P1>
<P1>(b) me (Oshawa) as addressed in the Supplement to the Sixth Report;</P1>
resulting in significant losses. I believe Schembri developed the Waterloo Lands, but simply &ldquo;flipped&rdquo; the London Lands. I developed the Oshawa Lands.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI>Schembri's Opposition to the Fees of the Receiver and its Counsel</TI>
<P><BOLD>271.</BOLD> In the Seventh Report dated October 14, 2011, the Receiver sought approval of the fees of the Receiver and counsel to the Receiver totaling more than $400,000 for the period from February 1, 2011 to September 30, 2011 (the <BOLD>&ldquo;Fee Approval Request&rdquo;).</BOLD></P>
<P><BOLD>272.</BOLD> I did not oppose the Fee Approval Request.</P>
<P><BOLD>273.</BOLD> Schembri opposed the Fee Approval Request. Schembri swore an affidavit dated October 18, 2011, which prompted: (a) the Receiver to prepare additional materials (namely, the Supplement to the Seventh Report and a factum); and (b) me to swear an affidavit dated October 19, 2011.</P>
<P><BOLD>274.</BOLD> At the hearing of the Fee Approval Request on October 20, 2011, Justice Mesbur did not permit the plaintiffs to file the affidavit sworn by Schembri as her Honour ruled that &ldquo;<EM>it was totally unfair to attempt to do so at such a late date</EM>&rdquo; when the hearing date had been scheduled three months earlier. A copy of the handwritten endorsement of Justice Mesbur dated October 20, 2011 (along with a best efforts transcription by Whiteley) is attached hereto and marked as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;119&rdquo;.</BOLD></P></BLOCK2>
