<P><BOLD>276.</BOLD> Subsequently, the Receiver distributed approximately $165,000 to the third party unsecured creditors (in accordance with the amounts shown in Appendix &ldquo;D&rdquo; to the Eighth Report) leaving approximately $3,300,000 in total in the three receivership estates.</P>
<P><BOLD>277.</BOLD> As stated in paragraph 46 above, I swore two affidavits in connection with the Eighth Report. Schembri also swore two affidavits (namely, on February 29 and March 30, 2012).</P>
<P><BOLD>278.</BOLD> Shortly thereafter the Receivership Proceedings became dormant while the parties attempted, without success, to reach an agreement that would provide for the discharge of the Receiver.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI>Schembri's Error re Title to the Waterloo Lands</TI>
<P><BOLD>279.</BOLD> Following a nine-month dormancy, the Receiver submitted the Ninth Report dated January 29, 2013 in order to rectify Schembri's failure to include a piece of property in his offer for the Waterloo Lands that the Receiver subsequently accepted following court approval. I sought to protect the interests of the Way Group by requiring Schembri to bear the costs of the Receiver and its' counsel in connection with that motion as it appeared to result from Schembri's mistake. Ultimately a compromise was reached following a court attendance, and the Order of Justice Brown dated February 1, 2013 was issued subsequently. Copies of the documents evidencing the foregoing are attached hereto and marked as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;121&rdquo;.</BOLD></P>
<P><BOLD>280.</BOLD> To my knowledge there have been no further steps taken in the Receivership Proceedings. The Receiver continues to hold more than $3,000,000 following its' sale of the Triumph Lands that had cost the Triumph Subsidiaries more than $8,000,000 to acquire and commence development.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI>Settlement Offers Prior to Appointment of the Receiver</TI>
<P><BOLD>281.</BOLD> In the end, Schembri acquired the Waterloo Property and the London Property, while I acquired the Oshawa Property. This is precisely the division of properties that I proposed in my Offer to Settle dated April 21, 2010 and my amended Offer to Settle dated June 3, 2010. Copies of these offers are attached hereto and marked as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;122&rdquo;.</BOLD></P>
<P><BOLD>282.</BOLD> Had Schembri accepted either of these offers, the receivership would not have happened, and the dissipation of approximately $5,000,000<SUP>6</SUP> in value would not have occurred.</P></BLOCK2></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><N>44</N><TI>Documentary Disclosure</TI>
<P><BOLD>283.</BOLD> Schembri swore an affidavit of documents on October 6, 2010 listing 181 documents in Schedule &ldquo;A&rdquo; and no documents in Schedule &ldquo;B&rdquo; (the <BOLD>&ldquo;Schembri AoD&rdquo;).</BOLD> A copy of the Schembri AoD is attached hereto and marked as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;123&rdquo;.</BOLD></P>
<P><BOLD>284.</BOLD> In December, 2010, my counsel provided copies of the financial records of 172 in connection with the JV Project on a CD to counsel for Schembri. These 5,451 documents would later form Schedule A.l to my affidavit of documents sworn June 15, 2012 (the <BOLD>&ldquo;Way Main Action AoD&rdquo;).</BOLD></P>
<P><BOLD>285.</BOLD> In January, 2011, my counsel provided copies of: (a) the detailed cost ledger reports; (b) the backup documents; and (c) the time sheets of the then defendant corporations and related entities; in connection with the JV Project on a DVD to counsel for Schembri. These 3,421 documents would later form Schedule A.2 to the Way Main Action AoD.</P>
<P><BOLD>286.</BOLD> In addition to those 8,872 documents, I am informed by Crozier and believe that Schembri's financial advisor, KPMG, was provided access in January, 2011 through a portal (the <BOLD>&ldquo;KPMG Portal&rdquo;)</BOLD> using one of two user IDs to certain companies as follows:
<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>6. Acquisition, carrying and development costs less funds held by the Receiver following the sale of the Triumph Lands.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE>
<P1>(a) User ID: KPMG&mdash;purchase orders, job costing and subcontract control for JCC, PPC, 2081044 and 172; and</P1>
<P1>(b) User ID: KMPG 2&mdash;access to general ledger, accounts payable, purchase orders, job costing and subcontract control for 172.</P1></P>
<P>I am further informed by Crozier and believe that she checked within the past six months and determined that KPMG had not used the portal since the spring of 2011.</P>
<P><BOLD>287.</BOLD> Schedule A.3 of the Way Main Action AoD consists of 10,526 documents. Compiling these 10,526 documents took a lot of time by a lot of people at significant cost.</P>
<P><BOLD>288.</BOLD> I have not attached a copy of Schedule &ldquo;A&rdquo; to the Way Main Action AoD as it consists of 1,090 pages.</P>
<P><BOLD>289.</BOLD> I was informed by Clifford Cole <BOLD>(&ldquo;Cole&rdquo;)</BOLD>, a lawyer at Gowlings in Toronto, and believe that I incurred significant expense in having my Schedule &ldquo;A&rdquo; productions inputted into Summation between January, 2011 and June, 2012, with:
<P1>(a) scanning and coding performed by Records Managements Services Group at a cost of $33,656.84 (exclusive of H.S.T.); and</P1>
<P1>(b) clerical costs exceeding $100,000 (exclusive of the time spent reviewing documents for privilege and relevance).</P1></P>
<P><BOLD>290.</BOLD> I note Schembri had years to take similar steps but elected not to do so. I am not aware of any explanation being given by Schembri for not doing so.</P>
<P><BOLD>291.</BOLD> Schembri swore a supplementary affidavit of documents on August 1, 2012 listing:
<P1>(a) 146 documents in Schedule &ldquo;A&rdquo; (of which only 4 documents appear to be dated after the Schembri AoD); and</P1>
<P1>(b) 2 documents in Schedule &ldquo;B&rdquo; (that were listed Schedule A.3 of the Way Main Action AoD but not in the Schembri AoD);</P1>
(the <BOLD>&ldquo;Schembri Supplementary AoD&rdquo;).</BOLD> A copy of the Schembri Supplementary AoD is attached hereto and marked as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;124&rdquo;.</BOLD> Copies of the two documents in Schedule &ldquo;B&rdquo; will be provided separately at the hearing of the motion.</P>
<P><BOLD>292.</BOLD> Schembri did not provide his Schedule &ldquo;A&rdquo; productions in Summation format, and as a result I incurred a cost of $1,731.62 (exclusive H.S.T.) in having his Schedule &ldquo;A&rdquo; productions scanned and coded.</P>
<P><BOLD>293.</BOLD> During a court attendance on January 8, 2016,1 learned that the Court expressed the view that Schembri ought to receive my Schedule &ldquo;A&rdquo; productions in Summation format without making any contribution upfront and without having to explain why he had not done so himself. I acquiesced to this view as I wanted the Main Action to be set down for trial as soon as possible, and was relieved by the offer of case management which I had requested unsuccessfully in or around early 2011.</P>
<P><BOLD>294.</BOLD> In the last sentence of paragraph 19 of the Schembri ROFR SJ Affidavit, Schembri alleges that I have:
<QUOTE><P><EM>&ldquo;refused to provide full and accurate financial disclosure and continues to refuse as of the date of this pleading</EM>. <BOLD><EM>To this date, notwithstanding being ordered by this Honourable Court to do so, Way had not done so</EM>.</BOLD></P></QUOTE></P>
<P>This is not true. Schembri has alleged this untruth from time to time. Previously, Schembri alleged this untruth in early 2014, and my counsel responded and politely requested particulars but received no response. Copies of the correspondence exchanged between Wortzman and Cole at that time in connection with this untruth are attached hereto and marked as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;125&rdquo;.</BOLD></P>
<BLOCK2><TI>Schembri's Deficient Documentary Disclosure</TI>
<P><BOLD>295.</BOLD> I believe Schembri has failed to produce numerous relevant documents.</P>
<P><BOLD>296.</BOLD> The five-page document containing 35 paragraphs (marked as Exhibit &ldquo;115&rdquo;) asserts:
<P1>(a) in paragraph 25 that Leaf is owed $35,414.20 for construction services but produces no contract for such services or time sheets for either Tony Varriano or Schembri's father; and</P1>
<P1>(b) in paragraphs 27 and 30 that Schembri is owed $21,581.47 and Leaf is owed $24,387, respectively, but produces no invoices or evidence of payment.</P1></P>
<P>Regarding (b), I believe these claims relate to the same thing given the description and as the Leaf claim is exactly the amount of the Schembri claim plus tax. Regarding the &ldquo;Schedule&rdquo; marked as Tab 2, I am informed by Crozier and believe that she created this document based on what Schembri told her and that he did not provide supporting documents in some instances despite her requests for him to do so.</P>
<P><BOLD>297.</BOLD> The page marked as Tab 1 located in Exhibit &ldquo;115&rdquo; asserts that Schembri paid in connection with the JV Project:
<P1>(a) legal fees totaling almost $5,000 in connection with 341 King, 349 King and 340 Spruce;</P1>
<P1>(b) a commission in the amount of $10,700 in connection with Mario Schembri's purchase of 345 King;</P1>
<P1>(c) $25,000 for &ldquo;Property Maintenance (snow, grass, repairs, insur ect)&rdquo;; and</P1>
<P1>(d) legal fees in the amount of $4,280 for &ldquo;transfer into JV&rdquo;.</P1></P>
<P>There are no documents in the Schembri Claims that support or evidence the foregoing payments. Further, there is nothing listed in either the Schembri AoD or the Schembri Supplementary AoD that supports or evidences any of the foregoing payments other than (b); namely, the trust ledger statement relating to Mario Schembri's purchase of 345 King. Finally, regarding (c), Schembri did not make any payments on account of property taxes as stated in paragraph 81 above.</P>
<P><BOLD>298.</BOLD> Further to paragraph 223, the KPMG summary Schembri grabbed out of my hand is not listed in either the Schembri AoD or the Schembri Supplementary AoD. In addition, Schembri has objected to KPMG producing its working papers that have existed since November 13, 2009 despite my repeated efforts to obtain these documents in accordance with KPMG's letter dated November 13, 2009.</P></BLOCK2></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><N>45</N><TI>Amendments to Statement of Claim</TI>
<P><BOLD>299.</BOLD> As stated in paragraph 26 above, the plaintiffs commenced the within action in February 2010, and have subsequently amended their pleading on two separate occasions.</P>
<BLOCK2><TI>The First Amendment</TI>
<P><BOLD>300.</BOLD> In or around December, 2010, the plaintiffs brought a motion (the <BOLD>&ldquo;First Amendment Motion&rdquo;)</BOLD> to amend the Statement of Claim to, among other things:
<P1>(a) add the Other Way Companies, Patterson and the Way Family Trust; and</P1>
<P1>(b) compel me to guarantee financing in connection with the Triumph Lands.</P1></P>
<P><BOLD>301.</BOLD> During the course of this motion, my counsel engaged Deloitte &amp; Touche LLP <BOLD>(&ldquo;Deloitte&rdquo;)</BOLD> to investigate the allegation by Schembri that the Way Group misappropriated funds. By report dated April 25, 2011 (the <BOLD>&ldquo;Deloitte Report&rdquo;)</BOLD>, Deloitte determined:
<QUOTE><P><EM>Based on our initial review and analysis of the supporting documentation the proceeds of sale of 345 King would appear to be adequately accounted for. At this point in our analysis we could find no evidence of payments made directly to Al Way</EM>.</P>
<P><EM>The costs incurred by the Triumph project entities appear to be related to the development of the particular project and relate primarily to the purchase of the land, permits and licenses, consulting fees for design and development and financing charges. The books and records of the Al Way related companies that we reviewed would appear to be in good order and at this point in our engagement</EM> <BOLD><EM>we could find no evidence of inappropriate transactions</EM>.</BOLD> (emphasis added)</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>The Deloitte Report was provided to counsel for Schembri on or about April 25, 2011. A copy of the Deloitte Report is attached hereto and marked as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;126&rdquo;.</BOLD></P>
<P><BOLD>302.</BOLD> By endorsement dated June 29, 2011 (the <BOLD>&ldquo;Turnbull Decision&rdquo;),</BOLD> Justice Turnbull:
<P1>(a) granted leave to add the Other Way Companies;</P1>
<P1>(b) dismissed the motion to add the Way Family Trust and Patterson &ldquo;but without prejudice to the right of the plaintiffs to renew the motion if there is evidence which may support the allegations as presented&rdquo;; and</P1>
<P1>(c) limited the amendment sought to guarantee financing only in connection with the Oshawa Lands as to allow otherwise &ldquo;would constitute an abuse of the court in that they would be a collateral attack on an existing court order&rdquo;.</P1></P>
<P>A copy of the Turnbull Decision is attached hereto and marked as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;127&rdquo;.</BOLD></P>
<P><BOLD>303.</BOLD> Justice Turnbull discussed the Deloitte Report in paragraphs 24 to 28 of the Turnbull Decision, including stating at paragraph [24]:
<QUOTE><P><EM>It is clear from the record that KPMG have been retained by the plaintiffs to undertake an analysis of the Defendants' books and records as much as a year ago. To this date, for some reason not clear from the record, a report has not been produced</EM>.</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>In fact, Schembri retained KPMG in September, 2009. Now more than eight years later, the plaintiffs have still not produced any report by KPMG.</P>
<P><BOLD>304.</BOLD> Schembri appealed the dismissal of the motion to add the Way Family Trust and Patterson (but not the limitation in paragraph 303 (c) above), but did so tardily. The Court of Appeal granted the plaintiffs' appeal. Copies of the documents evidencing the foregoing are attached hereto and marked as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;128&rdquo;.</BOLD></P>
<P><BOLD>305.</BOLD> Eventually, counsel for Schembri arranged for the <UNDER>Amended</UNDER> Statement of Claim amended December 4, 2012.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI>The Second Amendment</TI>
<P><BOLD>306.</BOLD> By letter dated October 2, 2012 enclosing a draft &ldquo;<UNDER>Amended</UNDER> Statement of Claim ... in furtherance of the decision of the Ontario Court of Appeal&rdquo;, counsel for Schembri advised of four additional paragraphs he was also seeking to include.</P>
<P><BOLD>307.</BOLD> By email sent November 8, 2012, my counsel requested particulars in respect of one of the four paragraphs.</P>
<P><BOLD>308.</BOLD> Under cover of letter dated November 8, 2012, counsel for Schembri served a motion record returnable November 22, 2012 seeking to further amend the Statement of Claim (the <BOLD>&ldquo;Second Amendment Motion&rdquo;).</BOLD></P>
<P><BOLD>309.</BOLD> My counsel prepared and delivered responding motion materials. I was informed by Tina Resendes <BOLD>(&ldquo;Resendes&rdquo;),</BOLD> a law clerk at Gowlings LLP in Kitchener, and believed that she could not file my responding materials as the Second Amendment Motion had not been filed by Schembri.</P>
<P><BOLD>310.</BOLD> Following an exchange of correspondence, counsel for Schembri provided a revised paragraph containing particulars under cover of letter dated December 17, 2012.</P>
<P><BOLD>311.</BOLD> The proposed revised paragraph stated &ldquo;... Particulars of those fraudulent claims are set out in Tab D of the Receiver's Eighth Reprot [sic] dated February 1, 2012&rdquo;.</P>
<P><BOLD>312.</BOLD> I have compared Appendix &ldquo;D&rdquo; to the Eighth Report dated February 1, 2012 to Appendix &ldquo;B&rdquo; to the Fifth Report dated June 17, 2011 (attached hereto and marked as Exhibit &ldquo;114&rdquo;). They appear to be identical.</P>
<P><BOLD>313.</BOLD> By email sent December 21, 2012, my counsel responded to the proposed revised paragraph and indicated those claims that ought not to be listed given the Claims Procedure carried out by the Receiver, on consent, and participated in by Schembri and me, at significant expense. I believe this was another attempt by Schembri to perpetuate an abuse of court by collaterally attacking the Claims Procedure Order.</P>
<P><BOLD>314.</BOLD> Following an Order dated June 3, 2013 dismissing the Main Action for delay (the &ldquo;Dismissal Order&rdquo;), by letter dated June 7, 2013 counsel for Schembri requested the defendants consent to setting aside the Dismissal Order and proposed a new timetable.</P>
<P><BOLD>315.</BOLD> I consented promptly to setting aside the Dismissal Order. The agreement on a new timetable took more time. As a result of the discussions and subsequent Second Timetable Order (defined in paragraph 323 below), I set aside the weeks of November 25 and December 2, 2013 for examinations for discovery and arranged for my absence from my business.</P>
<P><BOLD>316.</BOLD> Copies of the documents referred to in paragraphs 307 to 315 above are attached hereto and marked as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;129&rdquo;.</BOLD></P>
<P><BOLD>317.</BOLD> Eventually, counsel for Schembri arranged for the <UNDER>Amended Amended</UNDER> Statement of Claim amended October 2, 2013.</P>
<P><BOLD>318.</BOLD> I compared paragraph 86A of the <UNDER>Amended Amended</UNDER> Statement of Claim to what my counsel proposed on December 21, 2012 and see that the two are identical.</P>
