<P><BOLD>329.</BOLD> I have also reviewed the letter from Wortzman dated July 9, 2014 (after my counsel served the motion record that led to the Third Timetable Order), and note that Wortzman represented he was &ldquo;<EM>finalizing the motion record for partial summary judgment</EM>&rdquo;. A copy of the letter dated July 9, 2014 is attached hereto and marked as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;134&rdquo;.</BOLD></P>
<P><BOLD>330.</BOLD> Despite suggesting otherwise, Schembri did not serve any responding materials or conduct any cross-examination, and the Third Timetable Order was eventually issued on consent, along with the Order of Justice Broad dated September 4, 2014 (the <BOLD>&ldquo;ROFR Timetable Order&rdquo;).</BOLD> A copy of the ROFR Timetable Order is attached hereto and marked as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;135&rdquo;.</BOLD></P>
<P><BOLD>331.</BOLD> Paragraph 5 of the ROFR Timetable Order imposed a timetable for the conduct of the Purported Schembri ROFR SJ Motion. Schembri did not serve his motion record, and to my knowledge Schembri neither said nor did anything for more than two years in connection with the Purported Schembri ROFR SJ Motion. Accordingly, I believe that Schembri, through Wortzman, deceived me, my counsel and the Court. I further believe that Schembri perpetrated this deceit for the purpose of avoiding his examination for discovery (thereby delaying the Main Action and the ROFR Action) and increasing the amount of costs being incurred by me in defending the Way Group.</P></BLOCK2></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><N>47</N><TI>Examinations for Discovery</TI>
<P><BOLD>332.</BOLD> As provided for in the Third Timetable Order, the examinations for discovery in the Main Action were scheduled to be conducted on December 9 to 19, 2014, inclusive, and January 12 to 16, 2015, inclusive. I had set aside those dates in my calendar back in September and arranged for my absence from my business.</P>
<P><BOLD>333.</BOLD> On or about December 2, 2014, Wortzman notified Cole that he needed to cancel his examination of me scheduled to commence on December 9, 2014 because he did not have copies of my Schedule &ldquo;A.3&rdquo; productions. I note that this was more than two years after delivery of the Way Main Action AoD, and Cole had confirmed in his email sent April 7, 2014 (forming part of Exhibit &ldquo;133&rdquo;) that Wortzman had &ldquo;all the affidavit of documents from the defendants in the main action&rdquo;.</P>
<P><BOLD>334.</BOLD> My counsel acknowledged this notification and promptly provided Wortzman with an USB stick containing a PDF of all 10,526 documents in Schedule A.3, as well as all:
<P1>(a) 5,451 documents in Schedule A.l (which documents had previously been provided on a CD in December, 2010); and</P1>
<P1>(b) 3,421 documents in Schedule A.2 (which documents had previously been provided on a DVD in January, 2011).</P1></P>
<P><BOLD>335.</BOLD> My counsel accommodated Wortzman further by providing him with my Schedule &ldquo;A&rdquo; listing in Excel format, which allowed him to search through the documents using the Excel search functions.</P>
<P><BOLD>336.</BOLD> As a result, I agreed to postpone my examination for discovery until December 15, 2014 provided that:
<P1>(a) mediation be held; and</P1>
<P1>(b) Schembri be discovered the week of January 12, 2015.</P1></P>
<P><BOLD>337.</BOLD> As agreed, mediation was held on December 9, 2014.</P>
<P><BOLD>338.</BOLD> Copies of the documents referred to in paragraphs 333 to 336 above are attached hereto and marked as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;136&rdquo;.</BOLD></P>
<BLOCK2><TI>My Examination for Discovery</TI>
<P><BOLD>339.</BOLD> As agreed, my examination for discovery commenced on December 15, 2014. Wortzman examined me for thirteen days over five months, and completed his examination on April 30, 2015. The last three days of my examination were all on dates requested by Wortzman and accommodated by me and my counsel.</P>
<P><BOLD>340.</BOLD> Schembri assisted Wortzman in doing so by using the USB stick and Excel spreadsheets on a laptop Schembri operated.</P>
<P><BOLD>341.</BOLD> Wortzman examined me for discovery not only in the Main Action but also in the ROFR Action. I did not expect him to do so because of his repeated representations about the Schembri ROFR SJ Motion, and the fact that the Notice of Examination he served on December 22, 2014 related to the Main Action only. I believe this is just another example of Schembri's tactics.</P>
<P><BOLD>342.</BOLD> According to the transcripts of my examination for discovery, Wortzman asked more than 15,000 questions.</P>
<P><BOLD>343.</BOLD> I do not recall Wortzman putting the Way Claims Brief or the Way Supplementary Claims Brief to me at any time during the thirteen days of my examination. I have reviewed a copy of the list of exhibits to my examination for discovery prepared by Resendes (the <BOLD>&ldquo;Way E/D Exhibit List&rdquo;)</BOLD> and do not see either listed thereon. I am informed by Whiteley and believe that Wortzman has not provided copies of certain exhibits in the Way E/D Exhibit List as he agreed to do. A copy of the Way E/D Exhibit List is attached hereto and marked as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;137&rdquo;.</BOLD></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI>Examinations of Patterson and Farlow</TI>
<P><BOLD>344.</BOLD> The last two days of my examination (namely, April 23 and 30, 2015) had previously been scheduled for the examination of Patterson thereby bumping her examination to June 9 and 10, 2015. Previously, the examination of Farlow had been scheduled for June 4, 2015 but Wortzman had rescheduled it to June 9, 2015.</P>
<P><BOLD>345.</BOLD> It appears to me that Wortzman had now &ldquo;double-booked&rdquo; June 9, 2015. Regardless of the apparent &ldquo;double-booking&rdquo;, the examinations for discovery of Patterson and Farlow had to be rescheduled as Wortzman had not made arrangements with a court reporter's office for June 9 and 10, 2014. A copy of the letter from Wortzman dated May 27, 2015 evidencing his failure to book these examinations is attached hereto and marked as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;138&rdquo;.</BOLD></P>
<P><BOLD>346.</BOLD> Patterson and Farlow accommodated Wortzman in rescheduling these examinations, and they were conducted on August 5, 6 and 7, 2015.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI>Examination for Discovery of Schembri</TI>
<P><BOLD>347.</BOLD> I expected that Schembri would be examined in the summer of 2015 as:
<P1>(a) the First Timetable Order, the Second Timetable Order and the Third Timetable each provided for all examinations for discovery to be completed by a particular date without regard to answers to undertakings;</P1>
<P1>(b) Wortzman agreed to produce Schembri the week of January 12, 2015 in exchange for my consent to postpone the commencement of my examination for discovery from December 9, 2014 to the week of December 15, 2014; and</P1>
<P1>(c) once Wortzman needed to continue my examination for discovery during the week of January 12, 2015, he provided dates for Schembri's examination in June, 2015.</P1></P>
<P>Regarding (c), a copy of an email sent by Wortzman to Whiteley on January 29, 2015 is attached hereto and marked as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;139&rdquo;.</BOLD></P>
<P><BOLD>348.</BOLD> Apparently, Schembri decided to resile from the requirement to attend his examination for discovery, and instead demanded that I first provide answers to my undertakings. I believe Schembri must have known that he was required to attend an examination for discovery prior to receiving my answers to undertakings as he brought a motion seeking relief from his obligation in this regard. A copy of the Notice of Motion returnable May 28, 2015 is attached hereto and marked as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;140&rdquo;.</BOLD></P>
<P><BOLD>349.</BOLD> I did not believe that the Court would permit him to do so, but given his prior successful efforts in avoiding his examination for discovery for years now I was not surprised that he was successful once again and has still not been examined for discovery.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI>My Undertakings</TI>
<P><BOLD>350.</BOLD> Compiling the answers to undertakings took more than a year at significant cost as should be apparent from the answers themselves. I am informed by Whiteley and believe that it was most practical to send all answers (or as many as possible) for any particular day rather than piecemeal. I am further informed by Whiteley and believe that his efforts were interrupted when he dislocated his shoulder in February, 2015 for the second time in less than a year.</P></BLOCK2>
