<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="I">PART I&mdash;INTRODUCTION</TI>
<P>1. The within action (the &ldquo;ROFR Action&rdquo; or &ldquo;This Action&rdquo;) is a companion action to Court File No. C-42-11 (the &ldquo;Main Action&rdquo;).</P>
<P>2. The Actions have been highly litigious as is evidenced by This Honourable Court, the Toronto Commercial Court and the Court of Appeal rendering over 43 Orders.</P>
<P>3. Way and his Companies have defrauded Schembri and breached their contractual and fiduciary duties owed to them. This has been found by the Courts and confirmed by the evidence of independent third parties.</P>
<P>4. In response to the Main Action, Triumph Financial, Kingsley Financial and Way commenced this Action seeking to enforce a Non-Competition Clause included in a Shareholder's Agreement entered into as between Schembri and Way (and/or corporate entities that they control) that required Schembri to present all real estate opportunities acquired in the Regional Municipality of Waterloo to Triumph Financial and Kingsley Financial. They seek $30,000,000.00 in damages arising from Schembri's alleged breaches of the said Clause. Way personally has no valid claim since he personally is not the beneficiary of the Non-Competition Clause, only Kingsley Financial and Triumph Financial are.</P>
<P>5. Schembri acquired property in Waterloo without inviting Kingsley Financial or Triumph Financial to participate because Way had defrauded him and he knew that he could never work or partner with Way again.</P>
<P>6. The Non-Competition Clause is not enforceable as it is (1) merely an agreement to agree, (2) ambiguous, (3) unreasonable, (4) practically unworkable, and (5) unnecessary to protect Way's legitimate business interests. Since the Non-Competition Clause is unenforceable this Action must be dismissed.</P>
<P>7. The Non-Competition Clause was intended only to apply to three specific development projects in London, Waterloo and Oshawa that were located and tied up by the parties prior to Schembri discovering Way's frauds. As a result of Way's fraudulent conduct the three aforementioned properties were eventually sold by a Receiver pursuant to a Court Ordered process in the Main Action.</P>
<P>8. Way's position is that although he cannot explain how it would work, the Non- Competition Clause is enforceable and applicable to any and all real estate development opportunities in Waterloo Region in perpetuity. Way's evidence is that the Clause will, even after the parties' death, continue to bind his and Schembri's children and grandchildren, and so on into perpetuity.</P>
<P>9. The problem is that a careful reading of the Non-Competition Clause results in unanswerable questions, but no answers. Way himself, through cross-examinations, could not explain or provide any insight as to how the future relationships as between the parties would look or operate, including with respect to who would participate, fund, finance or guarantee any future developments.</P>
<P>10. Way points to an Arbitration Clause in the Shareholder Agreement and suggests that it would be up to an arbitrator to decide or craft the terms and structure of future development agreements. Of course, that is not the arbitrator's function. It is commercially unreasonable and completely outside of the scope of the jurisdiction and function of an arbitrator or a Judge to do so.</P>
<P>11. It was the parties' intention that the Non-Competition clause would apply to the Waterloo, London and Oshawa properties that were known to the parties and approved as developments at the time that the Shareholder Agreement was entered into. Any further development opportunity would be the subject of further negotiation and necessitate the agreement as between the parties on all essential terms. This is evidenced by the inherent vagueness of the Non-Competition Clause that lacks the material terms necessary to structure any further legal relationship between the parties.</P>
<P>12. Despite Way's continued successes as a developer, Way is attempting, through the ROFR Action, to &ldquo;piggy-back&rdquo; upon Schembri's successes through an interpretation of the Non- Competition Clause in a manner that is not commercial reasonable and that fails to take into account the simple fact that it would be impossible for Way and Schembri to work together given the history between the parties and the serious frauds committed by Way.</P>
<P>13. In essence, Way is asking that the Court enforce a contractual relationship between the parties that has no temporal limits, that is vaguely and insufficiently outlined, that does not contain the necessary material terms, and that will undoubtedly result in continuous and sustained litigation as between the parties.</P>
<P>14. Based upon the record before This Honourable Court, it would be just, expedient and in the interests of justice to dismiss the ROFR Action summarily.</P></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="II">PART II&mdash;SUMMARY OF FACTS</TI>
<P>15. Between 2005 and 2007, Schembri assembled various parcels of land in the City of Waterloo (the &ldquo;345 King Street Lands&rdquo;) to redevelop same.
<P1><BOLD>Affidavit of Gordon Schembri sworn May 17, 2017 (the &ldquo;Schembri Affidavit sworn May 17, 2017&rdquo;), in the Defendants/Moving Party's Motion Record (&ldquo;DMR&rdquo;), Tab 2, at paras. 6 and 7.</BOLD></P1></P>
<BLOCK2><TI><UNDER>THE JOINT VENTURE AGREEMENT</UNDER></TI>
<P>16. Schembri contacted Way as a contractor. This resulted in Way and Schembri entering into a Joint Venture Agreement (the &ldquo;JVA&rdquo;) with respect to the redevelopment of the 345 King Street Lands. Pursuant to the JVA, it was understood and agreed that Way would be required to fund, finance, and guarantee the development and, through Jamesway, construct the superstructure and be responsible for general conditions.
<P1><BOLD>Schembri Affidavit sworn May 17, 2017, DMR, Tab 2, at para. 8; Affidavit of Gord Schembri sworn May 14, 2010, at paras. 11&ndash;13.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>17. The JVA provided, <EM>inter alia</EM>, as follows:
<P1>(a) Schembri would receive a return of his equity contribution associated with acquiring the 345 King Street Lands, following which Way and Schembri, or their designated entities, would each receive 50% of the profit from the redevelopment of the 345 King Street Lands;</P1>
<P1>(b) Way and his entities would be responsible for obtaining financing, guarantees, all equity required, and any and all financing contributions required until the completion of the redevelopment of the 345 King Street Lands;</P1>
<P1>(c) Construction contracts would be awarded by both Way or his designated entities through an &ldquo;<EM>open book concept</EM>&rdquo;, except for work performed by Jamesway Construction, which was to be a fixed price contract reflected in the agreed upon budget as appended to the JVA;</P1>
<P1>(d) No increase in the agreed upon budget could be made without the unanimous written agreement of both Schembri and Way.
<P2><BOLD>Schembri Affidavit sworn May 17, 2017, DMR, Tab 2 at para. 9. Affidavit of Al Way sworn March 16, 2018 (&ldquo;Way Affidavit sworn March 16, 2018&rdquo;), Plaintiffs/Responding Parties' Motion Record (&ldquo;PMR&rdquo;), Tab A, at para 59, Exhibit 16.</BOLD></P2></P1></P>
<P>18. At no time did the parties to the JVA agree that Way's corporations (aside from Jamesway) would perform any work with respect to the 345 King Street Lands. Article 2(9) (c) of the JVA clearly set out that all construction contracts were to be awarded through an &ldquo;<EM>open book concept</EM>&rdquo;. Article 2(9) (c) of the JVA states:
<QUOTE><P><EM>Construction Contracts shall be agreed and awarded by both Joint Venturers through an open book concept save and except for any work performed by Jamesway. Any increase to Jamesway's contract shall be agreed to by both parties</EM>.</P></QUOTE>
<P1><BOLD>Affidavit of Gordon Schembri sworn May 14, 2010, at paras 16&ndash;20</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>19. Pursuant to the JVA, and the agreed upon budget, the profit anticipated from the redevelopment of the 345 King Street Lands, was to be $10,000,000.00. Schembri anticipated earning a profit of approximately $5,000,000.00 from the 345 King Street Lands redevelopment in accordance with the JVA.
<P1><BOLD>Schembri Affidavit sworn May 17, 2017, DMR, Tab 2, at para. 12.</BOLD></P1></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI><UNDER>THE SHAREHOLDERS AGREEMENT</UNDER></TI>
<P>20. Prior to completion of the joint venture, and while they were on good terms, Schembri and Way also entered into a Shareholders Agreement for Triumph Financial Holdings Inc. (&ldquo;Triumph Financial&rdquo;), which provided, <EM>inter alia</EM>, as follows:
<P1>(a) The Plaintiff, Kingsley Financial Inc. (&ldquo;Kingsley Financial&rdquo;), would own 55% of the shares of Triumph Financial and Schembri Financial Limited (&ldquo;Schembri Financial&rdquo;) would own the remaining 45%. Kingsley Financial received a larger percentage of shares to reflect its agreement to finance and guarantee development;</P1>
<P1>(b) Schembri and Way were appointed as Directors of Triumph Financial and Way was President and Schembri was Secretary and Treasurer;</P1>
<P1>(c) Way, as President, had the ability to sign all contracts on behalf of Triumph Financial, except in respect of matters relating to land acquisition, mortgage financing, construction budgets and project feasibility, which required the signatures of both Way and Schembri;</P1>
<P1>(d) Each of the Directors had one vote and Way, as Chairman, did not have any additional or casting vote. Accordingly, if Way and Schembri did not agree, then the Board of Directors would be deadlocked;</P1>
<P1>(e) Unanimous shareholder approval was required for Triumph Financial:
<P2>a) To directly or indirectly make any loans or advances, or invest in or give security for, or guarantee the debts of any other corporation or person;</P2>
<P2>b) To enter into any partnership or arrangement for the sharing of profits or joint venture with any person, firm, or a corporation, except in the normal course of business;</P2>
<P2>c) To mortgage or encumber any of its assets;</P2>
<P2>d) To commit to any financing arrangements with any third parties;</P2>
<P2>e) To undertake any project without initiating project feasibility studies and construction budget approvals.</P2></P1>
<P1>(f) The invalidity of any provision of the Shareholders Agreement or any covenant contained therein would not affect the validity of any other provision or covenant therein. The parties therefor recognized that certain terms might be invalid;</P1>
<P1>(g) Way agreed to provide or acquire all financing, equity and guarantees for any projects undertaken by Triumph Financial;</P1>
<P1>(h) The Shareholder Agreement could not be amended except in writing.</P1></P>
<P>21. This Action concerns a Right of First Refusal, or Non-Competition Clause, at Article 13, in the Shareholders Agreement which states:
<QUOTE><P><EM>During the period which SCHEMBRI FINANCIAL is a shareholder of the Corporation [Triumph Financial], it shall have the ongoing obligation to present to KINGSLEY FINANCIAL and the Corporation</EM> <UNDER><EM>all real estate development opportunities (the &ldquo;Project&rdquo;) which it may have acquired</EM></UNDER> <EM>within the Regional Municipality of Waterloo. This obligation to KINGSLEY FINANCIAL and the Corporation</EM> <UNDER><EM>shall also extend to GORDON SCHEMBRI personally and any other legal entity in which he has an interest, either directly or indirectly, financially or otherwise</EM></UNDER>. <EM>KINGSLEY FINANCIAL and the Corporation shall have FIFTEEN (15) days following the presentation of the Project to them to determine if it is economically</EM> <UNDER><EM>feasible using the typical budget model consistently utilized by them in such circumstances</EM></UNDER> <EM>and, if at the expiry of the FIFTEEN (15) day period neither of them have indicated to SCHEMBRI FINANCIAL in writing that it is taking on the Project, then SCHEMBRI FINANCIAL (or its designate) shall be free to pursue the Project without the involvement of KINGSLEY FINANCIAL or the Corporation</EM>. [Emphasis added]</P></QUOTE>
<P1>(the &ldquo;Non-Competition Clause&rdquo;)</P1>
<P1><BOLD>Schembri Affidavit sworn May 17, 2017, DMR, Tab 2, at paras. 14&ndash;17; Affidavit of A. Way Sworn March 16, 2018, PMR, Tab A, at para 145, Exhibit 54.</BOLD></P1></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI><UNDER>ACQUISITION OF PSHAW A/WATERLOO/LONDON PROPERTIES</UNDER></TI>
<P>22. In anticipation of entering into the Shareholders Agreement, and based upon the said agreement, Schembri assembled and acquired three additional properties, in Oshawa (the &ldquo;Oshawa Property&rdquo;), Waterloo (the &ldquo;Waterloo Property&rdquo;), and London (the &ldquo;London Property&rdquo;).
<P1><EM>Schembri Affidavit sworn May 17, 2017, DMR Tab 2, at para. 16.</EM></P1></P>
<P>23. Triumph Financial was incorporated, the Shareholder Agreement was signed, and three subsidiary corporations of Triumph Financial were incorporated to take title to the said three properties as per the agreement between Way and Schembri. Accordingly, it was agreed that the Shareholder Agreement would govern the development of those three properties.</P>
<P>24. Schembri is adamant that when the Shareholder Agreement was negotiated in January of 2008, it was the parties' intention that the said agreement would only be in effect for the redevelopment of the Oshawa, Waterloo, and London Properties. This intention was clearly set out by Mr. Volpini, being counsel for Way, at the Shareholder Meeting held in January of 2008 who confirmed that the Shareholder Agreement bound the parties to the three aforementioned properties and that any further development of the properties would require their agreement (&ldquo;Shareholder Meeting&rdquo;).
<P1><BOLD>Transcript from the Examination of G. Schembri dated April 2, 2018 at p. 1759, q. 6819.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>25. When cross-examined, Way could not recall and had no memory of, <EM>inter alia</EM>, Mr. Volpini stating:
<P1>(a) That the Shareholder Agreement was intended to cover only the Oshawa, Waterloo, and London Properties;</P1>
<P1>(b) That the intent of the deal was that if Schembri and Way wanted to do other projects together they would have to negotiate the terms;</P1>
<P1>(c) that &ldquo;future deals, it could be 55/45 percent or 50/50. Whatever you negotiate&rdquo;;</P1>
<P1>(d) that &ldquo;<EM>this arrangement won't be like a marriage between you. You'll both have to agree if you want to go forward on future deals, This arrangement is just for the three deals that are on the table</EM>&rdquo;
<P2><BOLD>Transcript from the Cross-Examination of A. Way dated July 17, 2018, at pp. 160&ndash;163, qq. 640&ndash;645</BOLD>.</P2></P1></P>
<P>26. When Way was asked to undertake to ask Mr. Volpini if he made such statements, the questions were taken under advisement/refused. No answers have been produced.
<P1><BOLD>Transcript from the Cross-Examination of A. Way dated July 17, 2018, at pp.160&ndash;163, qq. 640&ndash;645.</BOLD></P1></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI><UNDER>ISSUES WITH RESPECT TO 345 KING STREET LANDS</UNDER></TI>
<P>27. Way and Schembri developed the 345 King Street Lands. In June of 2008, the 345 King Street Lands were sold to a third-party purchaser for $28,750,000.00. The sale closed on March 19, 2009.
<P1><BOLD>Affidavit of G. Schembri sworn April 6, 2010 at paras 34&ndash;39.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>28. At no time during the redevelopment of the 345 King Street Lands was Schembri advised, nor did he agree, that the cost of construction would be greater than the amount stipulated in the JVA. Schembri expected his profits to be approximately $5,000,000.00.
<P1><BOLD>Affidavit of G. Schembri sworn April 6, 2010 at paras 34&ndash;39.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>29. Despite what was anticipated from the budgets, Schembri or his corporate entities only received $1,400,000.00 from the profits generated. There was a shortfall of at least $3,600,000.00.
<P1><BOLD>Schembri Affidavit sworn May 17, 2017, DMR, Tab 2, at paras. 19-20.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>30. Schembri demanded an accounting from Way. The accounting provided by Way was incomplete and fraudulent. Way fraudulently used his other corporations to do work at inflated costs without Schembri's consent. As a result, Schembri commenced the Main Action seeking, damages for fraud as against Way and his corporations, and the appointment of a Receiver with respect to the Oshawa, London and Waterloo Properties.
<P1><BOLD>Schembri Affidavit sworn May 17, 2017, DMR, Tab 2, at paras. 19-20.</BOLD></P1></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI><UNDER>THE MAIN ACTION</UNDER></TI>
<P>31. Way and his companies have defrauded Schembri and breached the fiduciary duties owed including diverting $6,000,000.00 of Joint Venture profits to his own corporation. This position has been corroborated by both the Court (through various findings) and various independent third parties who have provided evidence with respect to the matters at issue in the Main Action.</P>
<BLOCK3><TI><UNDER>The Findings of Justice Roberts</UNDER></TI>
<P>32. In September 2010, Schembri sought an Order in the Main Action appointing a receiver and manager with respect to the Oshawa, London, and Waterloo Properties (the &ldquo;Receivership Motion&rdquo;).
<P1><BOLD>Schembri Affidavit sworn May 17, 2017, DMR, Tab 2, at para. 33; Affidavit of G. Schembri sworn April 5, 2018 (&ldquo;Schembri Affidavit sworn April 5, 2018&rdquo;), Defendants/Moving Parties' Reply Motion Record (&ldquo;RMR&rdquo;), Tab A, at paras. 71&ndash;74.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>33. Way brought a Cross-Motion seeking an Order, <EM>inter alia</EM>:
<P1>(a) Permitting the subsidiaries of Triumph Financial to proceed with redevelopment of the Waterloo, Oshawa and London Properties;</P1>
<P1>(b) That Way, as President of Triumph Financial, be granted &ldquo;<EM>unfettered authority to conduct [Triumph Financial's] affairs</EM>&rdquo;; and</P1>
<P1>(c) Restraining Schembri from interfering with the redevelopment of the Waterloo, Oshawa and London Properties.
<P2><BOLD>Transcript from the Examination of A. Way dated April 23, 2015, at pp. 2105&ndash;2108, qq.11039&ndash;11051, pp. 2114-2115, qq.11082&ndash;11048; Transcript from the Cross-Examination of A. Way dated July 17, 2018 at pp. 112-113, qq.451&ndash;454.</BOLD></P2></P1></P>
<P>34. Way made it abundantly clear during his cross-examinations pending the Receivership Motion that, with respect to the Waterloo, Oshawa and London Properties, <EM>inter alia</EM>:
<P1>(a) <EM>&ldquo;No other contractor's gonna work on these projects if I'm involved in them</EM>;</P1>
<P1>(b) If his companies can't build them he &ldquo;<EM>won't be developing them</EM>&rdquo;;</P1>
<P1>(c) The purpose of the motion for was to obtain control &ldquo;<EM>because these projects need to be built out, and I'm the person to do it</EM>&rdquo;;</P1>
<P1>(d) He would not guarantee any mortgages or loans if he was not building the projects out;</P1>
<P1>(e) He would just let the projects &ldquo;<EM>sit there for the next hundred years, it doesn't matter to me</EM>.&rdquo;
<P2><BOLD>Transcript from the Cross-Examination of A. Way dated June 28, 2010 at pp. 679&ndash;681, qq. 3830&ndash;3840.</BOLD></P2></P1></P>
<P>35. Justice Roberts dismissed the relief sought by Way and granted the relief sought by Schembri and appointed a Receiver over all of Triumph Financial's assets.
<P1><BOLD>Schembri Affidavit sworn April 5, 2018, RMR, Tab A, at para. 72; Transcript from the Cross-Examination of A. Way dated July 17, 2018 at p. 116, q.459.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>36. In this regard, Justice Roberts made significant findings with respect to the conduct of Way:
<P1>(a) Having reviewed the extensive evidence submitted by the parties, including the transcripts from the numerous cross-examinations, I agree that, pursuant to Section 101(1) of the Courts of Justice Act, &ldquo;<EM>it would be just and convenient to appoint a Receiver and Manager to undertake the completion of the three real estate projects</EM>&rdquo;.</P1>
<P1>(b) &ldquo;<EM>The</EM> <BOLD><EM>Plaintiffs have presented a strong prima facie case against Mr. Way and his companies of serious financial and accounting irregularities and improprieties. Indeed, the Defendants have not disputed the evidence provided by the Plaintiffs</EM>.&rdquo;</BOLD></P1>
<P1>(c) &ldquo;<EM>In particular, the uncontested evidence of</EM> <BOLD><EM>Regean Depuis</EM></BOLD>, <EM>who had formally been employed by James Way Construction Corporation as the construction manager for the initial Waterloo Project, concerning the Defendants handling of that project</EM>, <BOLD><EM>establishes a strong prima facie case that Mr. Way grossly inflated the amounts of various change orders that were charged against the profits of the initial Waterloo project to the benefit of the Defendants and to the detriment of the Plaintiffs. It is significant that, in the first Waterloo project, the vast majority of the work was carried out by Mr. Way's companies which did not tender for the work and over whose expenses and charges there was no independent control</EM>.&rdquo;</BOLD></P1>
<P1>(d) <BOLD>&ldquo;<EM>Mr. Way added to change orders hundreds of hours for labour that were not expended on the Waterloo project and for the site supervision, scaffolding, heating and other amounts that seemed to have already been included in the fixed price contracts with Mr. Way's companies, and that Mr. Way grossed up each change order with unauthorized and excessive administrative fees. Mr. Depuis' unchallenged evidence was that Mr. Way told him to back charge all of the increased numbers as well as any costs due to overruns and mistakes to Mr. Schembri. Mr. Way admitted on his cross-examination that Mr. Schembri was not shown and therefore did not approve all of the written change orders, contrary to the provisions of their Joint Venture Agreement</EM>.&rdquo;</BOLD></P1>
<P1>(e) &ldquo;<EM>Further, notwithstanding the requests of the Plaintiffs and their counsel and a court order for production</EM>, <BOLD><EM>the Defendants have not provided a full and proper accounting to the Plaintiffs</EM></BOLD> <EM>of the initial Waterloo project. As noted below, the Defendants are still resisting the Plaintiff's request for production of relevant financial and documentation and information.&rdquo;</EM></P1>
<P1>(f) &ldquo;<EM>I agree with the Plaintiffs' submission</EM> <BOLD><EM>that the Plaintiffs cannot have confidence in the accounting performed or disclosed by the Defendants</EM>.</BOLD> <EM>None of the financial statements pertaining to the joint venture is audited and their contents are based on the questionable numbers provided by Mr. Way to his accountants</EM>.&rdquo;</P1>
<P1>(g) <BOLD>&ldquo;<EM>Mr. Way's evidence</EM></BOLD> <EM>on cross-examination in response to questions concerning relevant financial information</EM> <BOLD><EM>was often incorrect and unhelpful</EM>.&rdquo;</BOLD></P1>
<P1>(h) &ldquo;<EM>As a particular example, when questioned about the</EM> <BOLD><EM>improper transfer of $6 million dollars of joint venture funds</EM></BOLD> <EM>to Premier Project Consultants (a Way corporation) and subsidiary corporations, Mr. Way testified that it was the &ldquo;accountants&rdquo; who devised this paper trail; however Mr. Lund (the accountant) testified that he did not advise Mr. Way to transfer the funds in that fashion which had no accounting purpose, but only learned about it after it had been done.&rdquo;</EM></P1>
<P1>(i) <BOLD>&ldquo;<EM>The evidence that had been produced by Mr. Lund revealed that Mr. Way had apparently improperly transferred funds from the joint venture to pay unrelated payroll expenses and supplies of his other companies, including companies not involved in these projects, over which he has exclusive control</EM>.&rdquo;</BOLD></P1>
<P1>(j) &ldquo;<EM>I have no hesitation in concluding that</EM> <BOLD><EM>the appointment of a Receiver and manager is a remedy necessary to right the wrongs apparently perpetrated by the Defendants</EM>.</BOLD>&rdquo;</P1>
<P1>(k) &ldquo;<EM>The uncontested evidence establishing a</EM> <BOLD><EM>strong prima facie case that Mr. Way has an ability that he has already exercised to shuffle money around to numerous corporations over which he has exclusive control</EM>.</BOLD> <EM>Further, Mr. Way</EM> <BOLD><EM>has not been fully compliant with court order production of relevant financial information</EM></BOLD> <EM>and documentation to the Plaintiffs, and he seems to be willing to manipulate figures and disregard his accountant's advice</EM>.&rdquo;</P1>
<P1>(1) &ldquo;<EM>As strongly made out by the Plaintiffs unchallenged evidence, in particular, that of Mr. Depuis and Mr. Lund and the financial documentation produced, it appears that</EM> <BOLD><EM>Mr. Way's intent on improperly excluding the Plaintiffs and maximizing profits for himself and his companies to the Plaintiffs' detriment</EM>.&rdquo;</BOLD></P1>
<P1>(m) &ldquo;<EM>Based on the uncontested evidence before me and for the reasons already given</EM>, <BOLD><EM>unless a Receiver and manager has the ultimate authority with respect to the monitoring and management of the remaining real estate projects, it is very unlikely that the Defendants will cooperate. Further, none of the remaining projects is &ldquo;shuffle ready&rdquo;; and design and other disputes between the parties mean that the projects are all at a standstill</EM>.</BOLD> <EM>As a result, this is a convenient juncture for the introduction of a Receiver and manager</EM>.&rdquo; [Emphasis added]
<P2><BOLD>Schembri Affidavit sworn May 17, 2017, DMR, Tab 2, at para. 35.</BOLD></P2></P1></P>
<P>37. Way's affidavit filed in support of the within Motion does not respect or accept the findings of Justice Roberts at the Receivership Motion (despite the fact that he did not appeal Her Honour's decision).</P>
<P>38. In this regard, Way deposes that he did not &ldquo;<EM>grossly inflate the amounts of various change orders</EM>&rdquo; and that &ldquo;<EM>there was no improper transfer of $6 million dollars of joint venture funds</EM>&rdquo;. Way's evidence is, however, contradicted by:
<P1>(a) Justice Roberts' findings;</P1>
<P1>(b) the evidence of Regean Dupuis, an independent witness and Way's Project Manager, who swore his oath to the fact, <EM>inter alia</EM>, that Jamesway did in fact fraudulently inflate the amounts of various change orders with respect to 345 King Street lands;
<P2><BOLD>Schembri Affidavit sworn April 5, 2018, RMR, Tab A, at paras. 75&ndash;79. Way Affidavit sworn March 16, 2018, DMR, Tab A, at paras. 241&ndash;243.</BOLD></P2></P1>
<P1>(c) the evidence of Way's accountant, Brad Lund, who, during his examination as a witness to the Receivership Motion, and by way of answers to undertakings:
<P2>a) outlined how the $6,000,000.00 in Joint Venture funds was deposited into an account operated by one of Way's companies, Premier Project Consultants; and</P2>
<P2>b) provided evidence as to how:
<P3>(1) $15,000.00 of the joint venture funds were utilized by Premier Project Consultants to pay its payroll; and</P3>
<P3>(2) Over $800,000.00 was diverted by Premier Project Consultants to 5 or 6 of way's corporations that had nothing to do with the Development and was used to pay invoices and payroll.</P3></P2>
<P2><BOLD>Schembri Affidavit sworn April 5, 2018, RMR, Tab A, at paras. 80&ndash;93; Way Affidavit sworn March 16, 2018, DMR, Tab A, at paras. 250&ndash;254.</BOLD></P2></P1></P>
<P>39. The Court of Appeal adopted the reasoning of Justice Roberts with respect to Way's conduct which he continues to deny:
<QUOTE><P><EM>Based on the undisputed evidence</EM>, <BOLD><EM>Roberts J. made a number of significant findings of wrongdoing by Mr. Way and the companies he controlled. For instance, she found that Mr. Way had shuffled money around to his corporations, that he had not complied fully with Court ordered production and he was willing to manipulate figures and to ignore his accountant's advice</EM>.</BOLD></P></QUOTE>
<P1><BOLD>Schembri Affidavit sworn May 17, 2017, DMR, Tab 2, at para. 65.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>40. The Honourable Justice Sloan (&ldquo;Justice Sloan&rdquo;) has also made findings regarding Way's conduct including, <EM>inter alia</EM>, that Way:
<P1>(a) failed to comply with Court ordered timetables on various occasions;</P1>
<P1>(b) repeatedly failed to comply with Orders of the Court;</P1>
<P1>(c) failed to comply with undertakings given to the Court;</P1>
<P1>(d) repeatedly failed to comply with the <EM>Rules of Civil Procedure</EM>; and</P1>
<P1>(e) has not explained or apologized for his conduct to the Court.
<P2><BOLD>Endorsement of Justice Sloan dated December 23, 2016 at para 52.</BOLD></P2></P1></P>
<P>41. The cost submissions of Way filed in support of the costs arising from Justice Sloan's December 23, 2016 decision, again evidence that Way does not accept or respect the findings of Justice Sloan but rather continues to dispute them, rather than appeal them.
<P1><BOLD>Schembri Affidavit sworn April 5, 2018, RMR, Tab A, at paras. 94&ndash;99.</BOLD></P1></P></BLOCK3></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI><UNDER>THE WITHIN ACTION</UNDER></TI>
<P>42. Way commenced the within action by way of Statement of Claim on May 25, 2012, seeking, <EM>inter alia</EM>, damages for breach of the Non-Competition Clause.</P>
<P>43. Despite the clear findings of the Court (as set out above), Way insists that Schembri and his companies should continue to work with him with respect to any and all real estate developments in the Region of Waterloo on an indeterminate and undefined basis as per the Shareholder Agreement. This would be an unmitigated disaster.
<P1><BOLD>Schembri Affidavit sworn May 17, 2017, DMR, Tab 2, at paras. 35, 54, and 56.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>44. The Non-Competition Clause is contrary to public policy, ambiguous, unreasonable, unnecessary to protect any of the parties' legitimate interests and, therefore, unenforceable. In any event, given Way's fraudulent conduct, he has materially breached the Shareholder Agreement and cannot rely upon the Non-competition Clause. Accordingly, the within action ought to be summarily dismissed based upon the Record before this Honourable Court.</P>
<P>45. It is important to note at the outset that the Non-Competition Clause is in favour of only Triumph Financial and Kingsley Financial and not Way personally. Of course Triumph Financial includes both Schembri and Way and is deadlocked, defunct, not carrying on business, and its only assets are with a Receiver. Kingsley Financial has never been in the development business. It is merely used by Way as a conduit for the transfer of funds between his companies.</P></BLOCK2></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="III">PART III&mdash;STATEMENT OF ISSUES, LAW &amp; AUTHORITIES</TI>
<BLOCK2><TI><UNDER>SUMMARY JUDGMENT PRINCIPLES</UNDER></TI>
<P>46. There will be no genuine issue requiring a trial when a Judge hearing a summary judgment motion is able to reach a fair and just determination on the merits, and that this will be the case where the process (1) allows the judge to make the necessary findings of fact, (2) allows the judge to apply the law to the facts, and (3) is a proportionate, more expeditious and less expensive means to achieve a just result.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Hryniak v. Mauldin</SOC><CITE>2014 SCR 87</CITE></CASEREF> <BOLD>(&ldquo;<EM>Hryniak</EM>&rdquo;) at para 49, Defendants/Moving Parties' Book of Authorities (&ldquo;DBA&rdquo;) at Tab 1; <EM>Rules of Civil Procedure</EM>, RRO 1990, Reg. 194 at Rule 20.04.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>47. <EM>Hryniak</EM> provided a roadmap to be followed by Judges hearing motions for summary judgment. The Judge should first determine if there is a genuine issue requiring trial based only on the evidence before her, without using the new fact-finding powers in sub rules 20.04(2.1) and (2.2). There will be no genuine issue requiring a trial if the summary judgment process provides the motions Judge with the evidence required to fairly and justly adjudicate the dispute and is a timely, affordable and proportionate procedure. If there appears to be a genuine issue requiring a trial, the Judge should then determine if the need for a trial can be avoided by using the new powers under sub rules 20.04(2.1) and (2.2). While summary judgment must be granted if there is no genuine issue requiring a trial, the decision to use either the expanded fact-finding powers or to call oral evidence is discretionary.
<P1><BOLD><EM>Hryniak</EM>, <EM>supra</EM>, at paras 66&ndash;68, DBA at Tab 1; <EM>Rules of Civil Procedure</EM>, RRO 1990, Reg. 194 at Rule 20.04.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>48. The only motion before This Honourable Court is Schembri's motion seeking, <EM>inter alia</EM>, a declaration that the Non-Competition Clause is unenforceable and of no force and effect, and granting summary judgment as a result thereof.</P>
<P>49. Way has attempted to hijack the within Motion by stating in Way's affidavit that he is seeking relief that (1) was not contemplated by the parties or addressed before the Honourable Mr. Justice Sloan at the time that the within motion was scheduled, (2) is not the subject matter of any motion, and (3) is not properly before the Court. This behaviour by Way is not new to the proceedings. He tried to do this before and hijack the Sales Process and Schembri's motion to compel answers to undertakings. The Court of Appeal and Justice Sloan refused to permit him to do that and ordered significant costs against him. This should be no different.
<P1><BOLD>Schembri Affidavit sworn April 5, 2018, RMR, Tab A, at paras 38&ndash;68, 111.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>50. The discreet issue that is to be determined on this Motion is whether the Non-Competition Clause is enforceable, and, if not, should the Court grant Summary Judgment?</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI><UNDER>RESTRICTIVE COVENANTS</UNDER></TI>
<BLOCK3><TI>GENERAL PRINCIPLES</TI>
<P>51. The Non-Competition Clause is a restrictive covenant. Restrictive covenants give rise to a tension in the common law between the concept of freedom to contract and public policy considerations against the restraint of trade. At common law, restraints of trade are contrary to public policy because they interfere with individual liberty of action and because the exercise of trade should be encouraged and should be free.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Shafron v. ERG Insurance Brokers (Western) Inc.</SOC><CITE>[2009] 1 SCR 157</CITE></CASEREF> <BOLD>(&ldquo;<EM>Shafron</EM>&rdquo;) at para 16, DBA at Tab 2.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>52. There is strong public interest in &ldquo;<EM>discouraging restraints on trade and, maintaining free and open competition unencumbered by the fetters of restricted covenants</EM>&rdquo;.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Martin v. Con Create USL Limited Partnership</SOC><CITE>[2013] OJ No 515</CITE></CASEREF> <BOLD>(&ldquo;<EM>Martin</EM>&rdquo;) at para 53, DBA at Tab 3.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>53. The Courts have, however, recognized that there must be exceptions to restraints against trade to allow parties the freedom to contract with each other. Accordingly, the exception to the general rule against trade is where the restraint of trade is found to be reasonable. Despite the presumption that restrictive covenants are <EM>prima facie</EM> unenforceable, a reasonable restrictive covenant will be upheld.
<P1><BOLD><EM>Shafron</EM>, <EM>supra</EM>, at para 17, DBA at Tab 2.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>54. The party that seeks to enforce a restrictive covenant has the onus of demonstrating that the covenants are reasonable as between the parties. The party seeking to avoid enforcement of the covenant bears the onus of demonstrating that it is not reasonable with respect to the public interest.
<P1><BOLD><EM>Martin</EM>, <EM>supra</EM>, at para 50, DBA at Tab 3.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>55. In a commercial context, flexibility and latitude is required in interpreting restrictive covenants in order to protect freedom of trade and promote the stability of commercial agreements. Restrictive covenants in the commercial context are considered lawful, unless it can be established on a balance of probabilities that its scope is unreasonable
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Payette v. Guay Inc.</SOC><CITE>[2013] SCC 45</CITE></CASEREF> <BOLD>[&ldquo;<EM>Payette</EM>&rdquo;) at para 58, DBA at Tab 4.</BOLD></P1></P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI>FIRST STEP/ ANALYSIS</TI>
<P>56. Before the Court can perform an analysis of the reasonableness of a restrictive covenant, it must first be determined that the covenant is unambiguous as &ldquo;<EM>the reasonableness of a covenant cannot be determined without first establishing the meaning of the covenant</EM>.&rdquo;
<P1><BOLD><EM>Shafron</EM>, <EM>supra</EM>, at para 27, DBA at Tab 2;</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>Mason v Chem-Trend Limited Partnership</SOC><CITE>2011 ONCA 344</CITE></CASEREF> <BOLD>[&ldquo;<EM>Mason</EM>&rdquo;) at para 14, DBA at Tab 5.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>57. An ambiguous restrictive covenant will be <EM>prima facie</EM> unenforceable because the party seeking enforcement will be unable to demonstrate reasonableness in the face of an ambiguity. The Non-Competition Clause is ambiguous on its plain reading, as it does not set out the materials terms required. It is an agreement to agree and as such is unenforceable on that basis alone.
<P1><BOLD><EM>Shafron</EM>, <EM>supra</EM>, at para 27, DBA at Tab 2.</BOLD></P1></P></BLOCK3></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI><UNDER>THE RESTRICTIVE COVENANT IS AMBIGUOUS</UNDER></TI>
<P>58. The Non-Competition Clause is ambiguous with respect to the obligations it purports to impose on Schembri.</P>
<P>59. The Non-Competition Clause provides, <EM>inter alia</EM>, that:
<QUOTE><P><EM>During the period which SCHEMBRI FINANCIAL is a shareholder of the Corporation [Triumph Financial], it shall have the ongoing obligation</EM> <UNDER><EM>to present to</EM></UNDER> <EM>KINGSLEY FINANCIAL and the Corporation</EM> <BOLD><UNDER><EM>all real estate development opportunities (the &ldquo;Project&rdquo;) which it may have acquired</EM></UNDER></BOLD> <EM>within the Regional Municipality of Waterloo. This obligation to KINGSLEY FINANCIAL and the Corporation shall also extend to GORDON SCHEMBRI personally and any other legal entity in which he has an interest, either directly or indirectly, financially or otherwise. KINGSLEY FINANCIAL and the Corporation shall have FIFTEEN (15) days following the presentation of the Project to them to determine if it is economically feasible</EM> <BOLD><UNDER><EM>using the typical budget model consistently utilized by them in such circumstances</EM></UNDER></BOLD> <EM>and, if at the expiry of the FIFTEEN (15) day period neither of them have indicated to SCHEMBRI FINANCIAL in writing that it is taking on the Project, then SCHEMBRI FINANCIAL (or its designate) shall be free to pursue the Project without the involvement of KINGSLEY FINANCIAL or the Corporation</EM>. [Emphasis added]</P></QUOTE></P>
<BLOCK3><TI><UNDER>The &ldquo;Regional Municipality of Waterloo&rdquo;</UNDER></TI>
<P>60. The Non-Competition Clause purportedly applies to the all real estate development within the &ldquo;<EM>Regional Municipality of Waterloo</EM>.&rdquo;</P>
<P>61. Pursuant to the <EM>Regional Municipality of Waterloo Act</EM>, RSO 1990, c. R17, the <EM>Regional Municipality of Waterloo</EM> refers to the Regional Corporation. The terms has no relation to any definitive or finite spatial area.
<P1><BOLD><EM>Regional Municipality of Waterloo Act</EM>, RSO 1990, c. R17, Section 1.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>62. In <EM>Shafron</EM>, the Supreme Court of British Columbia found, as it relates to a restrictive covenant, that there was no legal or judicial definition of the term &ldquo;Metropolitan City of Vancouver&rdquo; and accordingly found that the language was neither clear nor certain and dismissed the claim.
<P1><BOLD><EM>Shafron</EM>, <EM>supra</EM>, at para 44, DBA at Tab 2.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>63. The British Columbia Court of Appeal overturned the Trial Judge's decision, and found that while the meaning of the &ldquo;Metropolitan City of Vancouver&rdquo; was ambiguous, there was no doubt that the parties intended (and that it was likely in the reasonable contemplation of the parties) to prevent competition in the &ldquo;City of Vancouver and an area beyond the City&rdquo;.
<P1><BOLD><EM>Shafron</EM>, <EM>supra</EM>, at paras 45-46, DBA at Tab 2.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>64. The Supreme Court of Canada overturned the decision of the Court of Appeal and found that:
<P1>(a) The Court should not attempt to resolve ambiguity in the term &ldquo;Metropolitan City of Vancouver&rdquo; by reading down the covenant according to the Court's notion of reasonableness and what it thought the parties might have intended;</P1>
<P1>(b) Severance was not applicable to remove the word &ldquo;Metropolitan&rdquo; as there was no evidence that the parties would have unquestionably agreed to remove the term without varying other terms of the contract or varying the bargain; and</P1>
<P1>(c) Rectification could not apply as in order to get rectification it is necessary to show that the parties were in complete agreement on the term, but by error, wrote down the agreement wrongly.
<P2><BOLD><EM>Shafron</EM>, <EM>supra</EM>, at paras 47&ndash;55, DBA at Tab 2.</BOLD></P2></P1></P>
<P>65. There is no evidence before this Court that the parties had turned their minds to this facet of the agreement and that the parties would have unquestionably agreed as to what was included in the &ldquo;Regional Municipality of Waterloo&rdquo; as included in the Non-Competition Clause. This was not addressed in the affidavits or through cross-examinations. In fact, Schembri was never questioned about his at all.
<P1><BOLD><EM>Shafron</EM>, <EM>supra</EM>, at para 50, 55, DBA at Tab 2.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>66. The term &ldquo;Regional Municipality of Waterloo&rdquo; is ambiguous and its application unclear in the circumstances. The Non-Completion Clause ought to be found to be unenforceable on that ground alone.</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI><UNDER>The Presentation of Real Estate Development Opportunities Acquired</UNDER></TI>
<P>67. The Non-Competition Clause sets out that Schembri is to &ldquo;<EM>present</EM>&rdquo; to Kingsley Financial and Triumph Financial &ldquo;<EM>all real estate development opportunities</EM>&rdquo;, which it may have &ldquo;<EM>acquired</EM>&rdquo;.</P>
<P>68. From the examinations of Way, it is clear that he does not understand and/or cannot explain the plain meaning of what the clause purports to govern. Schembri acknowledges in his affidavit that he also cannot understand the clause except to say that he and Way would have to mutually agree to any future deals on terms to be negotiated. He was never challenged on this in cross-examination.
<P1><BOLD>Transcript from the Examination of A. Way dated January 16, 2015, p. 1864, q. 1842; Schembri Affidavit sworn May 17, 2017, DMR, Tab 2, at paras. 84&ndash;89.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>69. In this regard, Way could not answer when the obligation to <EM>present</EM> arose or when an <EM>opportunity</EM> would be deemed to have been <EM>acquired</EM> in accordance with the Non-Competition Clause. Whether it is when an APS is signed, or when it is conditional or unconditional or closed is uncertain.</P>
<P>70. What is clear is that Way is uncertain as to when Schembri would be deemed to have &ldquo;<EM>acquired</EM>&rdquo; a real estate opportunity and when the obligation to &ldquo;<EM>present</EM>&rdquo; that real estate opportunity would arise.
<P1><BOLD>Transcript from the Examination of A. Way dated January 16, 2015, pp. 1864&ndash;1875, qq. 1844&ndash;1902.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>71. Ultimately, when asked his understanding of Schembri's obligation under the Non-Competition Clause to &ldquo;<EM>present</EM>&rdquo; to him, Way admitted that: &ldquo;<EM>It's not definitive</EM>&rdquo;.
<P1><BOLD>Transcript from the Examination of A. Way dated January 16, 2015, p. 1875, q. 1902.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>72. The Non-Competition Clause is also ambiguous as to what is meant by the phrase &ldquo;<EM>all real estate development opportunities</EM>&rdquo;.</P>
<P>73. Way's position is that the Non-Competition Clause applies to <EM>all</EM> real estate development opportunities of Schembri and any other legal entity in which he has an interest directly or indirectly (whether such an opportunity constituted a legitimate business interest of Kingsley Financial or Triumph Financial), which he says would include, <EM>inter alia</EM>::
<P1>(a) If Schembri owned or bought shares in a publically traded real estate investment trust (REIT), which purchased property in the Waterloo Region;</P1>
<P1>(b) A house that Schembri purchases and renovates for his kids to live in;</P1>
<P1>(c) The addition of a second floor to a bungalow for the purpose of resale;</P1>
<P1>(d) The acquisition of a freehold single-family dwelling;</P1>
<P1>(e) A cottage in the region of Waterloo;</P1>
<P1>(f) A gas station;</P1>
<P1>(g) The opportunities of any company in which Schembri is a shareholder;</P1>
<P1>(h) A situation where Schembri donated money to a university that developed lands.
<P2><BOLD>Transcript from the Cross-Examination of A. Way dated July 18, 2018, at pp.206&ndash;210, qq. 773&ndash;787; Transcript from the Examination of A. Way dated January 16, 2015, p. 1855, q. 1785, pp. 1872-1873, qq. 1888&ndash;1893.</BOLD></P2></P1></P>
<P>74. The scope of the proposed restriction which includes &ldquo;all real estate opportunities&rdquo; is ambiguous, commercially absurd, not necessary to protect Triumph Financial or Kingsley Financial's legitimate interests and cannot be enforced.</P>
<P>75. Additionally, it would be impossible for Schembri to know if a publically traded REIT or any other public company in which he purchased shares in would participate in development in the Regional Municipality of Waterloo or whether Article 13 would apply.</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI><UNDER>The Typical Budget Model</UNDER></TI>
<P>76. The Non-Competition Clause is also ambiguous with respect to the manner by which it is contemplated that Kingsley Financial and Triumph Financial will determine the economic feasibility of a real estate opportunity presented by Schembri. In this regard, the Non-Competition Clause states, <EM>inter alia</EM>:
<QUOTE><P><EM>KINGSLEY FINANCIAL and the Corporation shall have FIFTEEN (15) days following the presentation of the Project to them to determine if it is economically feasible</EM> <UNDER><EM>using the typical budget model consistently utilized by them in such circumstances</EM>.</UNDER></P></QUOTE></P>
<P>77. The problem here is that there was no &ldquo;typical budget&rdquo; in existence. Nowhere in the Shareholder Agreement is there any obligation upon anyone to prepare or present a typical budget model. In fact, Schembri has sworn his oath to the fact that no such &ldquo;typical budge model&rdquo; exists. How can the parties be compelled to use a budget model that does not exist? How can the parties proceed with a development in the absence of approved let alone typical budget? They cannot do so unless they reach an agreement to do so.
<P1><BOLD>Schembri Affidavit sworn May 17, 2017, DMR, Tab 2, at paras. 84-85.</BOLD></P1></P></BLOCK3></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI><UNDER>THE RESTRICTIVE COVENANT IS UNWORKABLE</UNDER></TI>
<BLOCK3><TI><UNDER>The Agreement is void of Necessary Terms and Details</UNDER></TI>
<P>78. Any contract must contain the essential material terms or it is merely an agreement to agree. Courts cannot write in or create missing material contractual terms. It is clear that the Non-Competition Clause is at best an agreement to agree on the terms of any future developments.</P>
<P>79. In addition to the fact that the obligations imposed by the Non-Competition Clause are ambiguous (for the reasons as set out above), Schembri submits that the said Clause is also practically unworkable and hence unenforceable by a Court. This is because the Clause does not address a myriad of material terms that are essential for a binding contract.
<P1><BOLD><EM>Mason</EM>, <EM>supra</EM>, at para. 19, DBA at Tab 5.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>80. In this regard, the Clause does not speak to and Way admitted on cross-examinations that, absent an agreement between Schembri and Triumph Financial/Kingsley Financial, he did not know and/or could not articulate how the Clause would practically work. The Clause does not address what would happen, <EM>inter alia</EM>:
<P1>(a) If both Kingsley Financial and Triumph Financial determined that the real estate opportunities presented by Schembri were economically feasible, or the type of ownership interests the various parties would have, or the roles they would play (including the role of any new entities that would have to be incorporated and take title to the development opportunity)?</P1>
<P1>(b) If Triumph Financial wanted to pursue a project and Kingsley Financial did not?</P1>
<P1>(c) If the parties could not agree on a budget (there is no typical budget model) or if Kingsley Financial's budget was different from Triumph Financial's budget and they both wanted to proceed?</P1>
<P1>(d) Regarding the structure of the new companies that would have to be incorporated, the nature of the by-laws or articles of incorporation, or who would be officers, directors and shareholders?</P1>
<P1>(e) Regarding the method of funding for any project or who would provide and/or guarantee the financing?</P1>
<P1>(f) Regarding the source and infusion of the required equity into the real estate developments?</P1>
<P1>(g) Regarding what would happen if the parties could not agree on compensation for initial equity (sweat, money or recognition of creating value through a land assembly) that was put in to acquire the lands?</P1>
<P1>(h) Whether decisions regarding re-zoning would be the subject matter of negotiation?</P1>
<P1>(i) What would happen if Schembri asked for a fee (for example $5 million dollars) for presenting the real estate opportunity as the agreement does not prevent that?</P1>
<P1>(j) Who was to prepare the &ldquo;<EM>typical budget model</EM>&rdquo; referenced at paragraph 13 of the Non-Competition Clause?
<P2><BOLD>Transcript from the Examination of A. Way dated January 16, 2015, pp. 1881&ndash;1895, qq. 1937&ndash;2010; Transcript from the Examination of A. Way dated July 17, 2015, pp. 137&ndash;140, qq. 559&ndash;569; Transcript from the Cross-Examination of A. Way dated July 18, 2018 at p.228&ndash;231, qq. 852&ndash;860.</BOLD></P2></P1></P>
<P>81. Since the Clause does not address these fundamental terms and Way could not provide insight it is crystal clear and commercially reasonable to interpret the Clause as requiring Schembri to present opportunities to Triumph Financial and Kingsley Financial and then and only if all parties agree on all terms of a new opportunity, they would proceed. Absent agreement they could not proceed and an arbitrator or Judge would not and could not impose a deal upon them, structured and drafted by way of Judicial Order.</P>
<P>82. In an attempt to answer these ambiguities and lack of details, Way relies solely upon the arbitration clause contained at paragraph 15 of the Shareholder Agreement:
<QUOTE><P><EM>Q. Well if I understand your position, in the absence of an agreement an arbitrator would decide all aspects of the development that you and Mr. Schembri couldn't agree upon?</EM></P>
<P><EM>A.I believe that would be the purpose of the arbitrator</EM>.</P></QUOTE>
<P1><BOLD>Transcript from the Cross-Examination of A. Way dated July 18, 2018 at p.232, q. 863.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>83. During Cross-examinations, Mr. Wortzman directly addressed the issue of whether or not Way would be prepared to provide an arbitrator with effective control over his developments, <EM>inter alia</EM>:
<QUOTE><P><EM>Q. Are you seriously suggesting that you would be prepared to enter into a real estate development and have an arbitrator tell you what you have to do and what you can't do? Is that what you are saying?</EM></P>
<P><EM>Q. . . . Are you telling me that you would be content to have an arbitrator determine your obligations and liabilities under a real estate development pursuant to the shareholders agreement?</EM></P></QUOTE>
<P1><BOLD>Transcript from the Cross-Examination of A. Way dated July 18, 2018 at pp. 233&ndash;235, qq. 866&ndash;868.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>84. These questions posed by Mr. Wortzman although proper given Way's evidence were refused. Way did, however, admit that he did not even know what an arbitrator could impose. An adverse inference should be drawn that Way would never agree to an arbitrator crafting the terms of joint venture for him; who would?
<P1><BOLD>Transcript from the Cross-Examination of A. Way dated July 18, 2018 at pp. 233&ndash;235, qq. 866&ndash;868.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>85. It is commercially unreasonable that an arbitrator or Judge could or would, in effect, create the material terms of a contractual relationship and impose those material contractual terms on the parties and ultimately decide the process and structure pursuant to which a redevelopment (or multiple redevelopments) would proceed.</P>
<P>86. It is equally unbelievable that Way would ever be prepared to give up full control over any possible redevelopment projects to an arbitrator's discretion when, <EM>inter alia</EM>:
<P1>(a) during the Receivership Motion in the Main Action, Way brought a cross-motion seeking &ldquo;<EM>unfettered control</EM>&rdquo; and restraining Schembri from participating with respect to the Waterloo, London and Oshawa Properties' redevelopment; and</P1>
<P1>(b) Way himself has stated that he would not proceed with the Waterloo, Oshawa and London Projects unless he had control. He would rather &ldquo;<EM>let them sit there for the next hundred years</EM>&rdquo;.
<P2><BOLD>Transcript from the Cross-Examination of A. Way dated June 28, 2010 at pp. 679&ndash;681, qq. 3830&ndash;3840.</BOLD></P2></P1></P>
<P>87. It is submitted that, even if Way was prepared to relinquish control (which Schembri refutes), an arbitrator's role is not to decide (1) whether a new company should do the development, (2) who the officers and directors would be, (3) what shares would be owned by whom and in what percentage, (4) what financing would be required, (5) who would guarantee the financing, (6) who would fund the equity, (7) how much equity would be required, (8) the value of sweat equity, (9) upon a tendering process, and (9) the myriad of other terms required for a development to proceed. It is also not the arbitrator's role to approve or create budgets. An arbitrator cannot enforce the performance of a whole contract where it would involve creating, drafting or implying terms upon which the parties did not agree or turn their minds. The Courts will not even engage in such an exercise.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Bitton v. Cheeroune et al</SOC><CITE>2017 ONSC 2434</CITE></CASEREF> <BOLD>(&ldquo;<EM>Bitton</EM>&rdquo;), at para 58, DBA at Tab 9;</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>Kloepfer Wholesale Hardware v. Roy</SOC><CITE>[1952] 2 SCR 465</CITE></CASEREF> <BOLD>(&ldquo;<EM>Kloepfer</EM>&rdquo;), at pg. 468, DBA at Tab 10.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>88. Schembri submits that there is no valid or enforceable contract as between the parties. For a valid contract to exist, the courts must find that the parties had a mutual intention to create a legally binding contract and reach an agreement with respect to all of the essential terms of the contract. An agreement is unenforceable if essential provisions intended to govern the contractual relationship are uncertain and have not been settled or agreed upon.
<P1><BOLD><EM>Bitton</EM>, <EM>supra</EM>, at para 58, DBA at Tab 9;</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>Demir v. Kilic</SOC><YEAR>2018</YEAR><CITE>ONSC 949</CITE><PARANUM>19</PARANUM></CASEREF>, <BOLD>DBA at Tab 11.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>89. Here, it is clear that the parties have not reached an agreement which includes the essential terms necessary to govern their contractual relationship. At most, the Non-Competition Clause represents an &ldquo;<EM>agreement to possibly agree</EM>&rdquo; with respect to future real estate development opportunities. This is consistent with Schembri' recollection of Mr. Volpini's statements at the January 2008 Shareholder Meeting that it was the parties' intention that the said agreement would only be in effect for the redevelopment of the Oshawa, Waterloo, and London Properties. Way and Schembri had already agreed to proceed with these developments. Any other or future developments would also require their consent and agreement. This is the only commercially reasonable way to interpret the Non-Competition Clause.</P>
<P>90. It is trite law that agreements to agree are not enforceable. Accordingly, the Non-Competition Clause which creates an &ldquo;<EM>agreement to possibly agree</EM>&rdquo; cannot stand.
<P1><BOLD><EM>Bitton</EM>, <EM>supra</EM>, at para 57, DBA at Tab 9.</BOLD></P1></P></BLOCK3></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI><UNDER>THE RESTRICTIVE COVENANT IS UNREASONABLE</UNDER></TI>
<P>91. Even if this Honourable Court finds that the Non-Competition Clause is unambiguous and capable of being enforced, Schembri submits that the said Clause is unreasonable and unlawful and therefore ought to be struck.</P>
<P>92. The Supreme Court of Canada has held that it is only after the restrictive covenant has been found to <UNDER>not</UNDER> be ambiguous, that, as a general rule, the following elements should be analyzed in determining whether or not a restrictive covenant is otherwise reasonable:
<P1>(a) The geographic coverage of the covenant;</P1>
<P1>(b) The period of time in which the covenant is effective; and</P1>
<P1>(c) The extent of the activity sought to be prohibited.
<P2><BOLD><EM>Shafron</EM>, <EM>supra</EM>, at para 26, DBA at Tab 2.</BOLD></P2></P1></P>
<P>93. Of overarching importance to the reasonableness inquiry is whether or not the restrictive covenant's term, territory and activities to which it applies, is restricted <UNDER>to whatever is necessary for the protection of the legitimate interest of the party in whose favour it was granted</UNDER>.
<P1><BOLD><EM>Payette</EM>, <EM>supra</EM>, at para 61, DBA at Tab 4;</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>853947B.C. Ltd. v. Source Office Furniture and Systems Ltd.</SOC><CITE>[2016] BCSC 2233</CITE></CASEREF> <BOLD>(&ldquo;<EM>Source Office</EM>&rdquo;), at para 32, DBA at Tab 6;</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>Tank Lining Corp. v. Dunlop Industrial Ltd.</SOC><CITE>[1982] CarswellOnt 780</CITE><PARANUM>16</PARANUM></CASEREF>, <BOLD>DBA at Tab 7;</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>94. If a covenant is not clear as to activity, time, or geography, it is not possible to demonstrate that it is reasonable. It is therefore unreasonable and unenforceable.
<P1><BOLD><EM>Martin</EM>, <EM>supra</EM>, at para 51, DBA at Tab 3.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>95. The reasonableness of a restrictive covenant is fact-specific and can only be determined after looking at the overall context of the covenant and the relationship between the parties.
<P1><BOLD><EM>Source Office</EM>, <EM>supra</EM>, at para 30, DBA at Tab 6.</BOLD></P1></P>
<BLOCK3><TI><UNDER>The Geographic Scope</UNDER></TI>
<P>96. If this Court finds that the term &ldquo;Region of Waterloo&rdquo; is not ambiguous, then the geographic scope of the Non-Competition Clause is not at issue.</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI><UNDER>The Temporal Limits are Unreasonable</UNDER></TI>
<P>97. The Non-Competition Clause is in effect according to the express words of Article 13:
<QUOTE><P>. . . . <UNDER><EM>During the period which SCHEMBRI FINANCIAL is a shareholder of the Corporation [Triumph Financial]</EM></UNDER>, <EM>it shall have the ongoing obligation to present to KINGSLEY FINANCIAL and the Corporation all real estate development opportunities (the &ldquo;Project&rdquo;) which it may have acquired within the Regional Municipality of Waterloo. This obligation to KINGSLEY FINANCIAL and the Corporation</EM> <UNDER><EM>shall also extend to GORDON SCHEMBRI personally and any other legal entity in which he has an interest, either directly or indirectly, financially or otherwise</EM></UNDER>.</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>98. The Shareholder Agreement also states that it is binding on Schembri and Way's heirs in perpetuity.</P>
<P>99. The Non-Competition Clause is in force until such time as Schembri Financial divests its shares in Triumph Financial. As constituted, the Shareholder Agreement does not allow Schembri or Schembri Financial to divest of its shares in Triumph Financial without the consent of Way. Therefore the clause is in effect until Way consents otherwise and is purportedly binding on future generations of the Way and Schembri families.
<P1><BOLD>Transcript from the Examination of A. Way dated January 16, 2015, p. 1864, q. 1839&ndash;1841.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>100. During cross-examinations, Way was asked for his understanding of when the Non-Competition Clause terminates. According to Way there is no end date to the clause's application.
<P1><BOLD>Transcript from the Examination of A. Way dated January 16, 2015, p. 1861, q. 1822.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>101. In fact, Way has taken the position that the Non-Competition Clause extends beyond his and/or Schembri's death and applies to both Way and Schembri's heirs:
<QUOTE><P><EM>Q.Just so I understand your perspective, this is binding on you and Gord and it's binding on your daughter and Gord's kids and your daughter's kids and Gord's kids' kids and potentially, their kids' kids; is that where we are?</EM></P>
<P><EM>A. That is what it says</EM>.</P></QUOTE>
<P1><BOLD>Transcript from the Examination of A. Way dated January 16, 2015, p. 1864, q. 1838.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>102. The Supreme Court of Canada has affirmed that a Non-Competition Clause in a commercial contract must have a temporal limit. In this regard, the Court in <BOLD><EM>Payette</EM></BOLD> stated as follows:
<QUOTE><P><EM>A non-competition clause in a commercial contract must of course be limited as to time, or it will be found to contrary to public order and a Court will refuse to give effect to it</EM>.</P></QUOTE>
<P1><BOLD><EM>Payette</EM>, <EM>supra</EM>, at para 63, DBA at Tab 4.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>103. Additionally, the Court of Appeal has found that a restrictive covenant has no temporal limits where it is dependent upon a party to make a determination as to its end. Such clauses are unenforceable for that reason alone.
<P1><BOLD><EM>Martin</EM>, <EM>supra</EM>, at paras. 6, 59, DBA at Tab 3.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>104. There is no basis to support the necessity or enforceability of the indefinite time period in the Non-Competition Clause or that it is necessary to protect any legitimate business interest of Triumph Financial and Kingsley Financial while binding Schembri and Way's children and grandchildren. The time period is indeterminate and accordingly unreasonable and must be deemed unenforceable as against public interest, in accordance with the binding authority of the Supreme Court of Canada in <EM>Payette</EM> and the Court of Appeal in <EM>Martin</EM>.
<P1><BOLD><EM>Payette</EM>, <EM>supra</EM>, at para 63, DBA at Tab 4; <EM>Martin</EM>, <EM>supra</EM>, at paras. 6, 59, DBA at Tab 3.</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>United Rentals of Canada Inc. v. Brooks</SOC><CITE>2016 ONSC 6854</CITE><PARANUM>74&ndash;79</PARANUM></CASEREF>, <BOLD>DBA at Tab 8.</BOLD></P1></P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI><UNDER>An Inherent Stalemate</UNDER></TI>
<P>105. Additionally, the Shareholder Agreement expressly provides at Article 2 (c) (xv):
<QUOTE><SEC><N>2.</N><SECP>The parties hereto agree,
<PARA><N>(c)</N><PARAP>that during the currency of this Agreement, the parties agree that without the consent of the shareholders representing not less than ONE HUNDRED (100%) per cent of the voting shares of the capital stock of the corporation:
<SPARA><N>(xv)</N><SPARAP>no projects will be undertaken or initiated by the Corporation [Triumph Financial] without project feasibility studies and construction budget approvals.</SPARAP></SPARA></PARAP></PARA></SECP></SEC></QUOTE></P>
<P>106. Through his examinations for discovery, Way has confirmed that without Schembri's approval of a project feasibility study and construction budget, no projects could be pursued by Triumph Financial. This supports Schembri's interpretation of the Clause that it would only apply if the parties agreed to all terms.
<P1><BOLD>Transcript from the Examination of A. Way dated January 16, 2015 at pp.1897&ndash;1900, qq.2021&ndash;2035.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>107. Accordingly, without Schembri's approval, no future development is possible. Schembri has made clear that he will not work with Way in the future and so no approval will be granted.</P>
<P>108. The Non-Competition Clause is again practically unworkable unless the parties agree to develop together and agree on all terms of such a development.</P></BLOCK3></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI><UNDER>CLAUSE UNNECESSARY TO PROTECT LEGITIMATE INTERESTS</UNDER></TI>
<P>109. As set out by the Supreme Court of Canada in <BOLD><EM>Payette</EM></BOLD>, a non-competition covenant is unreasonable if it is not necessary to protect the legitimate interest of the party in whose favour it was granted. Since all of its assets were placed in Receivership, Triumph Financial is no longer in business and accordingly has no legitimate interests to protect. Kingsley Financial is not and never was a developer. It is a company used solely by Way as a conduit for the movement of monies. It has no legitimate interest to protect.
<P1><BOLD><EM>Payette</EM>, <EM>supra</EM>, at para 61, DBA at Tab 4.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>110. Way and the Way Group have continued conduct significant business since entering into the Shareholder Agreement without Schembri's involvement.</P>
<P>111. During the course of the Main Action, the corporate tax returns filed by Triumph Financial, for the period June 1, 2013 to May 31, 2016, were produced. They listed approximately 36 of Way's &ldquo;related and associated corporations.&rdquo; Way, during cross-examination, admitted that the assets of those associated companies is accurately listed a just over $172,000,000.00, the capital is $88,169,000.00, the revenues are $24,773,000.00, and that a portion of the said capital, assets, and revenues generated, were generated through Way's real estate development business.
<P1><BOLD>Schembri Affidavit sworn April 5, 2018, RMR, Tab A, at paras. 103 and 104, Exhibit 21; Transcript from the Cross-Examination of A. Way dated July 17, 2018, at pp. 89&ndash;94, qq. 323&ndash;340.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>112. Since it is only Triumph Financial and Kingsley Financial that have the benefit of the Non-Competition Clause, Way's other business interests do not require protection.</P>
<P>113. Additionally, during his examinations, Way admitted that:
<P1>(a) Prior to meeting Schembri, he had never &ldquo;as an investment, went out, acquired land, assembled it, re-zoned it, developed it as a student housing business</P1>
<P1>(b) Except in the joint venture with Schembri, never carried on the business of student housing in the Waterloo Region;</P1>
<P1>(c) Since the development of 345 King Street, (1) he continues to carry on business as a developer, (2) he has the resources necessary to carry on business, (3) he has continued to build apartment buildings, some of which have students in them, (4) he has not been restricted from looking for properties for development purposes in the Waterloo area, and (5) nothing that Schembri did or didn't do in breach of the Non-Competition Clause prevented him from further development.
<P2><BOLD>Schembri Affidavit sworn April 5, 2018, RMR, Tab A, at para. 107.</BOLD></P2>
<P2><BOLD>Transcript from the Examination of A. Way dated January 16, 2015, pp. 1850&ndash;1853, qq. 1755&ndash;1772, p. 1964, qq. 10295&ndash;10297; Transcript from the Examination of A. Way dated January 18, 2017, p. 2985, q. 14942.</BOLD></P2></P1></P>
<P>114. In fact, the Region of Waterloo Planning, Development and Legislative Services, Community Planning Report prepared with respect to &ldquo;<EM>2017 Building Permit Activity and Growth Monitoring</EM>&rdquo; sets out that there has been approximately $10-11 billion dollars of value in building permits issued between 2008 and 2017. In the face of this information at cross-examinations, Way refused to answer whether there was a &ldquo;<EM>lack of opportunities for [him] to develop real estate in the Region of Waterloo</EM>&rdquo; and refused to agree that there is &ldquo;<EM>plenty of development opportunities in the Region of Waterloo</EM>.&rdquo; This Court ought to draw an adverse inference from Way's refusals. In any event, Way's own financial filings suggest that there are plenty of opportunities for Way and/or his entities to develop real estate.
<P1><BOLD>Transcript from the Cross-Examination of A. Way dated July 17, 2018, at pp. 154&ndash;159, qq. 623&ndash;636; Exhibit &ldquo;8&rdquo; marked at the Cross-Examination of Way dated July 17, 2018&mdash;Region of Waterloo Planning Development Legislative Services, Community Planning Report, re: 2017 Building Permit Activity and Growth Monitoring.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>115. Although Way does not personally receive the benefit of the Non-Competition Clause he has joined as a Plaintiff in any event. Way has:
<P1>(a) Acknowledged that he does not have the capacity to do an endless number of developments. He confirmed that he can only develop 1-2 properties in a given year and that since 2009, he has developed at least 8 properties. In this regard, Way has been operating at max capacity and has suffered no losses as he would not have been able to participate in any development in the Waterloo Region proposed by Schembri or he replaced them with his own development opportunities. If he has damages, he has mitigated them;
<P2><BOLD>Transcript from the Examination of A. Way dated January 19, 2017, pp. 2994&ndash;2997, qq. 14947&ndash;14964.</BOLD></P2></P1>
<P1>(b) Stated that he is not aware of any legitimate business interest that he was protecting when entering into the Restrictive Covenant; and
<P2><BOLD>Transcript from the Examination of A. Way, dated January 16, 2015, pp. 1854&ndash;1857, qq. 1779&ndash;1795.</BOLD></P2></P1>
<P1>(c) Attempted to revise his evidence two years later by saying that the legitimate business interest that he was protecting was his interest with respect to &ldquo;redevelopment&rdquo;. Way again confirmed that Triumph Financial is defunct and Kingsley Financial is not a developer, and despite the Clause he remains free to develop any property that he wants in the Region of Waterloo.
<P2><BOLD>Transcript from the Examination of A. Way, dated January 18, 2017, pp. 2980&ndash;2983, qq. 14916&ndash;14930.</BOLD></P2></P1></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI><UNDER>TRIUMPH AND KINGLEY FINANCIALS' BUSINESS</UNDER></TI>
<BLOCK3><TI><UNDER>Triumph Financial</UNDER></TI>
<P>116. Triumph Financial has not carried on any business since the Receiver was appointed over all of its assets in September of 2010.
<P1><BOLD>Schembri Affidavit sworn May 17, 2017, DMR, Tab 1, at para. 79.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>117. Way admitted during his cross-examinations that Triumph Financial is dormant, does not have any assets or employees, and has not carried on any real estate development or other business since the Receiver was appointed.
<P1><BOLD>Transcript from the Cross-Examination of A. Way dated July 17, 2018, pp. 24&ndash;27, qq. 25&ndash;41., pp.32-33, qq. 69-70; Affidavit of Schembri sworn April 5, 2018, RMR, Tab A, at para 103, Exhibit 21.</BOLD></P1></P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI><UNDER>Kingsley Financial</UNDER></TI>
<P>118. Way has confirmed that Kingsley Financial never carried on any real estate development business. Instead Kingsley Financial acts as a bank or conduit for the monies that flow in and out of Way's other corporations.</P>
<P>119. There is no need to protect Kingsley Financial from Schembri as it is not in the business of real estate development, in Waterloo or elsewhere.
<P1><BOLD>Transcript from the Cross-Examination of A. Way dated July 17, 2018 at pp. 22&ndash;24, qq.16&ndash;24.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>120. On the Way side, the only two parties to the Non-Competition Clause, Triumph Financial and Kingsley Financial, are not in the business of real estate development in Waterloo. There is no interest to protect.</P></BLOCK3></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI><UNDER>359 KING STREET AND 61 COLUMBIA STREET</UNDER></TI>
<P>121. To the extent that this Court finds that Schembri is not entitled to summary judgment on the basis that the Non-Competition Clause is enforceable, Schembri submits that this Court ought to grant partial summary judgment with respect to Way's claims regarding the properties known municipally as 359 King Street (i.e. the Waterloo Property) and 61 Columbia Street.</P>
<BLOCK3><TI><UNDER>359 King Street (i.e. the &ldquo;Waterloo Property&rdquo;)</UNDER></TI>
<P>122. Way's Affidavit sworn March 16, 2018, states that Schembri was in breach of the Non-Competition Clause for failure to present to Kingsley Financial or Triumph Financial a prospective real estate opportunity with respect to 359 King Street (the Waterloo Property&rdquo;).
<P1><BOLD>Way Affidavit sworn March 16, 2018, PMR, Tab A, at para. 398.</BOLD></P1></P>
<BLOCK4><TI>The Receivership Proceedings relating to the Waterloo Property</TI>
<P>123. Way includes the Waterloo Property in This Action notwithstanding that it was the subject of numerous Court Orders and the fact that the Court of Appeal ordered that the Receiver sell it to Schembri</P>
<P>124. The parties in the Receivership Proceedings consented to a &ldquo;Sales Process Order&rdquo; with respect to the London and Waterloo Properties.
<P1><BOLD>Schembri Affidavit sworn May 17, 2017, DMR, Tab 2, at paras. 37-38.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>125. The Honourable Justice Mesbur's (&ldquo;Justice Mesbur&rdquo;) Sale Process Order contemplated a two stage sales process. The first stage was solicitation of offers from Way and Schembri to purchase the said Properties. In the event that no acceptable offers were received in stage one from Way or Schembri, then the Receiver was to market and sell the Properties on the open market.
<P1><BOLD>Schembri Affidavit sworn May 17, 2017, DMR, Tab 2, at para. 39.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>126. Schembri complied with Justice Mesbur's Sales Process Order and submitted an offer to the Receiver to purchase the Waterloo Property. Way did not submit any offer. The Receiver accordingly brought a motion to approve the sale of the Waterloo property to Schembri.
<P1><BOLD>Schembri Affidavit sworn May 17, 2017, DMR, Tab 2, at para. 42.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>127. Instead, of complying with the agreed upon Sales Process Order:
<P1>(a) Way brought a frivolous motion to remove the Receiver (the &ldquo;Removal Motion&rdquo;) and derailed the Sales Process with respect to Schembri's purchase of the Waterloo Property;</P1>
<P1>(b) Well after the Court imposed deadline and after Schembri had disclosed his offers, Way submitted confusing offers to purchase the Waterloo, London and Oshawa Properties. None of the offers made by Way were made pursuant to the Sales Process Order; and</P1>
<P1>(c) Used the Removal Motion tactically, and engaged in secret negotiations with the Receiver (without Schembri's knowledge) convincing the Receiver to support and approve Way's offers to purchase the Properties in exchange for Way's agreement to abandon the Removal Motion without costs.
<P2><BOLD>Schembri Affidavit sworn May 17, 2017, DMR, Tab 2, at paras. 44-45, 49&ndash;53.</BOLD></P2></P1></P>
<P>128. Way abandoned the Removal Motion and the Receiver brought a motion to have an amended Sales Process approved before Justice Mesbur.
<P1><BOLD>Schembri Affidavit sworn May 17, 2017, DMR Tab 2, at para. 53.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>129. In her Endorsement, Justice Mesbur made significant findings of fact regarding Way's conduct and the relationship as between Way and Schembri. In this regard, Justice Mesbur found, <EM>inter alia</EM>:
<P1>(a) <BOLD>Because of the falling out between Mr. Schembri and Mr. Way and the likelihood they would fail to cooperate with one another, both agreed that a neutral third party was necessary, but Mr. Way resisted appointing a receiver.</BOLD> Roberts J. found it just and convenient to appoint a receiver in order to &ldquo;<EM>protect the positions of the parties pending the completion of the projects and the final determination of the parties' disputes</EM>&rdquo;;</P1>
<P1>(b) Way <BOLD>&ldquo;<EM>attacked the Receiver's impartiality and integrity</EM>&rdquo;</BOLD>;</P1>
<P1>(c) &ldquo;<EM>I am troubled by the way the original sales process has got off the rails</EM> ... <BOLD><EM>Mr. Schembri complied with the sales order. Mr. Way did not.&rdquo;</EM></BOLD></P1>
<P1>(d) &ldquo;<EM>Removing a Receiver is a serious matter. Mr. Way had called the Receiver's integrity into question, and this issue had to be determined. From Mr. Schembri's point of view, the removal motion was tactical, and designed to derail the sales process so that Mr. Way could gain an advantage in it. To some extent, I tend to agree</EM>.&rdquo;</P1>
<P1>(e) <BOLD>&ldquo;<EM>When I look at the timing of the removal motion, coupled with Mr. Way's later unsolicited bids for the three properties, I see a tactical move to rest control of the process from the Receiver, and to prevent Mr. Schembri from purchasing Waterloo or to force him to pay significantly more for it than its appraised value</EM>.&rdquo;</BOLD></P1>
<P1>(f) &ldquo;<EM>What troubles me is that accepting the Receiver's recommendations in large part rewards Mr. Way and condones his behaviour. He had the opportunity to prevent a proper bid as contemplated by the sales order. He chose not to. Instead, he made unsolicited bids while attacking the Receiver's integrity</EM>.&rdquo;</P1>
<P1>(g) &ldquo;<EM>But this is not about Mr. Schembri and Mr. Way</EM>. <BOLD><EM>Their bitterness and ill will towards one another is palpable and will no doubt continue and colour all of their future decisions. It is not the Court's function to facilitate or enable their bitterness and anger</EM>.</BOLD> <EM>Instead, the Court must determine whether the Receiver's proposal is in the overall interest of the Estate and is commercially reasonable</EM>.&rdquo;</P1>
<P1>(h) &ldquo;<EM>As to the fairness or unfairness of the process, both parties have legitimate complaints</EM>. <BOLD><EM>Those complaints, however, have more to do with their own behaviour and wish to crush the other than with the Receiver's exercise of reasonable judgment on the context of the sales process</EM>.&rdquo;</BOLD></P1>
<P1>(i) &ldquo;<EM>Although this case cries out to be settled, the parties seem to have little appetite for a reasonable settlement</EM>, <BOLD><EM>and would prefer to litigate until all their assets have been spent&rdquo;</EM>.</BOLD>
<P2><BOLD>Schembri Affidavit sworn May 17, 2017, DMR, Tab 2, at para. 55.</BOLD></P2></P1></P>
<P>130. Despite Justice Mesbur's findings, the revised Sales Process was approved and the Sales Process Order amended. Justice Mesbur's decision was, however, quickly overturned by the unanimous decision of the Court of Appeal which ordered that Schembri was entitled to buy the Waterloo Property from the Receiver and also made adverse findings with respect to Way's conduct:
<P1>(a) <BOLD><EM>&ldquo;The conduct of Mr. Way had a negative impact on the integrity of the Court supervised sales process&rdquo;;</EM></BOLD></P1>
<P1>(b) &ldquo;<EM>His (Way's) conduct, as it impacted on the integrity of the sales process, should have been given significant weight when deciding whether the Receiver's recommendation to accept Mr. Way's proposal should be approved by the Court</EM>.&rdquo;
<P2><BOLD>Schembri Affidavit sworn May 17, 2017, DMR, Tab 2, at para. 56.</BOLD></P2></P1></P>
<P>131. Ultimately, because it was impossible for Way and Schembri to be partners, the Waterloo and London Properties were sold to Schembri and/or corporations which he controlled pursuant to the Sales Process Order. Way and/or a numbered company which he controls purchased the Oshawa Property.</P>
<P>132. Of significance and the reason why this is relevant is that at no time did Way raise the issue of or even reference the Non-Competition Clause during the Sales Process as it relates to the Waterloo Property.
<P1><BOLD>Schembri Affidavit sworn May 17, 2017, MMR Tab 2, at para. 59.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>133. Additionally, Way consented to the Honourable Mr. Justice Campbell signing a Vesting Order in the form prescribed by the <EM>Land Titles Act</EM> and/or the <EM>Land Registry Reform Act</EM> be registered, vesting the sale to Schembri clean of any claims.
<P1><BOLD>Schembri's Affidavit sworn May 17, 2017, DMR, Tab 1, at para. 58.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>134. Accordingly, the sale of the Waterloo Property to Schembri was done pursuant to a Court Ordered process. The issue was determined by the Court of Appeal. Way never raised the Non-Competition Clause during the entire process. Way had the opportunity to purchase the Waterloo Lands, if he wished, subject to compliance with the Sales Process Order. Way chose not to do so.
<P1><BOLD>Schembri's Affidavit sworn May 17, 2017, DMR, Tab 1, at para. 59.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>135. Importantly, paragraph 3 of the Vesting Order expressly states, <EM>inter alia</EM>:
<QUOTE><P><EM>3. THIS COURT ORDERS AND DECLARES that upon the delivery of a Receiver's certificate to the Purchaser substantially in the form attached as Schedule A hereto (the &ldquo;Receiver's Certificate&rdquo;), all of the Receiver's or 359 King Ontario Inc.'s right, title and interest in and to the property described in the Sale Agreement and listed on Schedule B hereto (the &ldquo;Purchased Property&rdquo;) hereto shall vest absolutely in the Purchaser</EM>, <BOLD><EM>free and clear of and from any and all security interests (whether contractual, statutory, or otherwise), hypothecs, mortgages, levies, charges, or other financial or monetary claims, whether or not they have attached or been perfected, registered or filed and whether secured, unsecured or otherwise (collectively, the &ldquo;Claims&rdquo;)</EM>.</BOLD> [Emphasis added]</P></QUOTE>
<P1><BOLD>Schembri's Affidavit sworn May 17, 2017, DMR, Tab 1, at paras. 58&ndash;61, Exhibit H.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>136. Way's attempts to obtain an interest in the Waterloo Property through this Action is an abuse of process and a collateral attack on the Order of the Court of Appeal of Ontario and the Order of Justice Campbell, wherein the Waterloo Property was vested in a company operated by Schembri. In this regard, Way continues his practice of ignoring or disregarding Court Orders.
<P1><BOLD>Schembri's Affidavit sworn May 17, 2017, DMR, Tab 1, at para. 62.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>137. During his cross-examinations, Way was asked why he never raised the Non-Competition Clause with Justice Mesbur or the Court of Appeal. Way refused to answer.</P>
<P>138. Despite the fact that Way has confirmed that &ldquo;<EM>paragraph 3</EM> [of Justice Campbell's Order dated August 2, 2012] <EM>speaks for itself</EM>&rdquo;, and that he consented to the Sales Process and Vesting Orders, Way still refuses to dismiss the action with connection to the Waterloo Property.
<P1><BOLD>Transcript from the Cross-Examination of A. Way dated July 17, 2018, at pp. 79&ndash;85, qq. 287&ndash;310.</BOLD></P1></P></BLOCK4></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI><UNDER>The Columbia Street Lands</UNDER></TI>
<P>139. Way's Action as it relates to 61 Columbia Street ought to be summarily dismissed as Way chose not to participate in the development. The record before this Court is also clear that the claim is statute barred pursuant to the <EM>Limitations Act</EM>.</P>
<P>140. Prior to Schembri's discovery of Way's frauds, Schembri advised Way that he was intending to develop student housing on Columbia Street. Way advised Schembri that he had no interest at all in the acquisition or development of student housing in the Waterloo Region.
<P1><BOLD>Schembri's Affidavit sworn May 17, 2017, DMR, Tab 1, at paras. 70, 71.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>141. This is particularly so with respect to 61 Columbia Street. The evidence is clear that it was in fact Triumph Financial that entered into the Agreement of Purchase and Sale for 61 Columbia Street. Schembri asked Way to use Triumph Financial as purchaser in an effort to disguise him as the real purchaser from the vendor in an attempt to keep the cost of acquisition down. Way did so. Way had no interest in developing 61 Columbia Street and accordingly he agreed to assign the Agreement of Purchase and Sale from Triumph Financial to one of Schembri's corporate entities, 1765998 Ontario Inc. (&ldquo;176&rdquo;). 176 ended up purchasing 61 Columbia Street and building student houses thereon.
<P1><BOLD>Schembri's Affidavit sworn May 17, 2017, DMR, Tab 1, at para. 72.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>142. Through cross-examination, Way has admitted that 61 Columbia Street was under contract with Triumph Financial in trust and it was eventually purchased by a company controlled by Schembri, being 1765998 Ontario Inc.
<P1><BOLD>Transcript from the Cross-Examination of A. Way dated July 17, 2018, at pp. 144&ndash;148, qq. 579&ndash;597.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>143. It is difficult to understand Way's Action regarding this property since he knew of it, tied it up, assigned the APS to Schembri and &ldquo;took a pass&rdquo; on the development. Additionally, the APS with respect to 61 Columbia Street was entered into more than two years from the date upon which the within Action was commenced. This action as it relates to 61 Columbia is statute barred pursuant to the <EM>Limitations Act</EM>.</P></BLOCK3></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI><UNDER>BIFURCATION&mdash;LIABILITY AND DAMAGES</UNDER></TI>
<P>144. Schembri submits that if this motion is dismissed the issue of liability ought to be bifurcated from the issue of damages.</P>
<P>145. Rule 6.1.01 of the <EM>Rules of Civil Procedure</EM> sets out as follows:
<QUOTE><P><EM>With the consent of the parties, the court may order a separate hearing on one or more issues in a proceeding, including separate hearings on the issues of liability</EM>.</P></QUOTE>
<P1><BOLD><EM>Rules of Civil Procedure</EM>, RRO 1990, Reg. 194, Rule 6.1.01</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>146. Despite the text of Rule 6.1.01, the Court has held that in non-jury cases, the Court has discretion to order bifurcation without the consent of the parties.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Duggan v. Durham Region Non-Profit Housing Corporation</SOC><CITE>2018 ONSC 1811</CITE></CASEREF> <BOLD>(&ldquo;Duggan&rdquo;), DBA at Tab 12.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>147. In his <EM>Civil Reform Project: Summary of Findings &amp; Recommendations</EM>, the Honourable Coulter A. Osborne stated as follows with respect to the bifurcation of proceedings:
<QUOTE><P><EM>While I view bifurcation to be the exception, cost considerations militate in favour of bifurcation in some cases</EM>. <BOLD><EM>In commercial litigation, for example, when dealing with damages will expose a party and sometimes all parties to significant costs, it may make sense to separate the issues of liability and damages and deal with liability first</EM>.</BOLD> <EM>Upon the determination of one issue, the parties may be inclined to settle the balance of the issues in dispute. This can result in a significant savings of time, money and judicial resources. It would also be of a particular benefit to those litigants who cannot afford a trial of all issues</EM>. [Emphasis added]</P></QUOTE>
<P1><BOLD><EM>Duggan</EM>, <EM>supra</EM>, at para 3, DBA at Tab 12.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>148. In this Action, Way seeks significant production with respect to various properties acquired by Schembri and/or his entities following entering into the Shareholder Agreement. Similarly, Schembri would require production by way of all of the documents relating to developments his companies did to see if he mitigated damages. None of the requested information is required to determine whether or not the Non-Competition Clause is enforceable or if Schembri is liable to Way for any breaches thereof.</P>
<P>149. Schembri respectfully submits that bifurcating the issues of liability and damages in the present Action is, <EM>inter alia</EM>:
<P1>(a) efficient and may promote settlement; and</P1>
<P1>(b) in the interests of justice; and</P1>
<P1>(c) consistent with the overarching purpose enunciated in Rule 1.04 which provides that the <EM>Rules of Civil Procedure are to &ldquo;be liberally construed to secure the just, most expeditious and least expensive determination of every civil proceeding on its merits.&rdquo;</EM> [para 69]
<P2><BOLD><EM>Duggan</EM>, <EM>supra</EM>, at para 69, DBA at Tab 12; <EM>Rules of Civil Procedure</EM>, RRO 1990, Reg. 194 at Rule 1.04.</BOLD></P2></P1></P></BLOCK2></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="IV">PART IV&mdash;ORDER REQUESTED</TI>
<P>150. Schembri respectfully seeks:
<P1>(a) A declaration that the Non-Competition Clause is unenforceable and of no force and effect;</P1>
<P1>(b) An Order that the within action be dismissed summarily;</P1>
<P1>(c) In the alternative, an Order that the Action be dismissed as it relates to the properties known as 359 King Street and 61 Columbia Street;</P1>
<P1>(d) Costs of the Motion and Action; and</P1>
<P1>(e) Such other relief as This Honourable Court deems just.</P1></P>
<P><BOLD>ALL OF WHICH IS RESPECTFULLY SUBMITTED</BOLD> this 9<SUP>th</SUP> day of October, 2018.</P>
