<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="I">PART I&mdash;OVERVIEW</TI>
<P><BOLD>1.</BOLD> This motion involves, among other things, the duties owed by the defendant, Gordon Schembri <BOLD>(&ldquo;Schembri&rdquo;)</BOLD> in his capacity as a director and officer of the plaintiff, Triumph Financial Holdings Inc. <BOLD>(&ldquo;Triumph&rdquo;);</BOLD> a company that he incorporated with the plaintiff, Al Way <BOLD>(&ldquo;Way&rdquo;),</BOLD> his fellow director and officer, to carry out multi-million dollar real estate developments.</P>
<P><BOLD>2.</BOLD> Schembri and his companies, commenced an action in February, 2010 against, among others, Way and Triumph (the <BOLD>&ldquo;Main Action&rdquo;).</BOLD></P>
<P><BOLD>3.</BOLD> The plaintiffs commenced the within action (the <BOLD>&ldquo;ROFR Action&rdquo;)</BOLD> six years ago in respect of Schembri's numerous independent premediated breaches of certain of his fiduciary duties over many years, and consequent diversion of corporate opportunities (individually, a <BOLD>&ldquo;ROFR Breach&rdquo;;</BOLD> and collectively, the <BOLD>&ldquo;ROFR Breaches&rdquo;).</BOLD></P>
<P><BOLD>4.</BOLD> By orders on consent, the Main Action and the ROFR Action are to be tried together. Schembri set the Main Action down for trial in June, 2017.</P>
<P><BOLD>5.</BOLD> Schembri orchestrated the ROFR Breaches both before and after the Main Action by acquiring twenty-seven properties at a cost of more than $15 million (as particularized in <BOLD>Schedule &ldquo;C&rdquo;</BOLD> hereto) that he subsequently developed into six separate properties that have made him very wealthy; concurrently, the funds belonging to Mr. Way from the JV Project (defined in paragraph 13(a) below) remain tied up in the receivership proceedings, while Schembri refuses to comply with documentary disclosure requirements in furtherance of his efforts to bankrupt Way.</P>
<P><BOLD>6.</BOLD> After failing to bankrupt Way (together with the plaintiffs, Kingsley Financial Inc. <BOLD>(&ldquo;KFI&rdquo;)</BOLD> and Triumph, the <BOLD>&ldquo;Way Group&rdquo;)</BOLD> by:
<P1>(a) refusing to provide approximately $3 million as required by the Contribution Clause (defined in paragraph 27 below);</P1>
<P1>(b) breaching his fiduciary duties as an officer and director of Triumph and its' three subsidiaries; and</P1>
<P1>(c) engaging in scorched earth litigation tactics;</P1></P>
<P>Schembri has brought belatedly the within motion seeking summary dismissal of the ROFR Action in an attempt to avoid: (i) complying with his disclosure obligations; (ii) scrutiny of his oppressive conduct; and (iii) liability for the ROFR Breaches.</P>
<P><BOLD>7.</BOLD> Schembri (together with the corporate defendants, the <BOLD>&ldquo;Schembri Group&rdquo;)</BOLD> is doing so:
<P1>(a) while refusing to produce numerous relevant documents and answer relevant questions (in breach of the Rules of Civil Procedure) that will:
<P2>(i) expose the scope of the ROFR Breaches; and</P2>
<P2>(ii) reveal the quantum of damages suffered by the Way Group; and</P2></P1>
<P1>(b) without ever explaining his inordinate delay after representing to the Way Group and the Court in 2014 that they were bringing a motion for summary judgment in the ROFR Action that year (the <BOLD>&ldquo;2014 Schembri ROFR SJ Motion&rdquo;).</BOLD></P1></P>
<P><BOLD>8.</BOLD> The Schembri Group seeks to persuade this Honourable Court that the dispute in the ROFR Action is simply an issue of contract interpretation; a contract (namely, a unanimous shareholder agreement (described in paragraphs 27 and 28 below)) that Schembri has and continues to seek to uphold and enforce against the Way Group throughout the course of eight years of litigation in the Main Action.</P>
<P><BOLD>9.</BOLD> Schembri's assertion that the ROFR Clause (defined in paragraph 27 below) in the unanimous shareholder is ambiguous is inconsistent with:
<P1>(a) Schembri's conduct prior to commencement of the Main Action; and</P1>
<P1>(b) Schembri's position asserted in the Reply and Defence to Counterclaim delivered in the spring of 2010.</P1></P>
<P><BOLD>10.</BOLD> While commencing and participating in various motions in the Main Action over several years, Schembri concealed the ROFR Breaches and never sought to be relieved of his obligation under the ROFR Clause.</P>
<P><BOLD>11.</BOLD> Schembri attempts to support the within motion on the basis of his unproven allegations in the Main Action, and the improper use of interlocutory decisions in the Main Action.</P></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="II">PART II&mdash;SUMMARY OF FACTS</TI>
<BLOCK2><N>I.</N><TI>Background</TI>
<BLOCK3><N>A.</N><TI>The Dispute</TI>
<P><BOLD>12.</BOLD> The events that are the subject matter of the Main Action date back to 2006; whereas, the events that are the subject matter of the ROFR Action date back to 2008. At the material times, Way's companies employed around 100 people; whereas Schembri had one employee.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Affidavit of Alven J. Way sworn March 16, 2018 (the <BOLD>&ldquo;Way Affidavit&rdquo;),</BOLD> Responding Motion Record <BOLD>(&ldquo;RMR&rdquo;),</BOLD> Volume 1, Tab A, pages 7 and 10, paragraphs 14 to 30</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P><BOLD>13.</BOLD> The document intensive and protracted dispute between Way and Schembri revolves around:
<P1>(a) one completed real estate development at 345 King Street, Waterloo, Ontario <BOLD>(&ldquo;345 King&rdquo;)</BOLD> that was carried out as a joint venture (the <BOLD>&ldquo;JV Project&rdquo;)</BOLD> pursuant to a joint venture agreement (the <BOLD>&ldquo;JV Agreement&rdquo;)</BOLD> entered into in April, 2007 (as depicted in <BOLD>Schedule &ldquo;D&rdquo;</BOLD> hereto); and</P1>
<P1>(b) three interrupted real estate developments in Waterloo, London and Oshawa, Ontario (individually, the <BOLD>&ldquo;Waterloo Lands&rdquo;,</BOLD> the <BOLD>&ldquo;London Lands&rdquo;</BOLD> and the <BOLD>&ldquo;Oshawa Lands&rdquo;,</BOLD> respectively; and collectively, the <BOLD>&ldquo;Triumph Lands&rdquo;)</BOLD> that were carried out pursuant to a shareholder agreement (the <BOLD>&ldquo;Shareholder Agreement&rdquo;)</BOLD> entered into in April, 2008 (as depicted in <BOLD>Schedule &ldquo;E&rdquo;</BOLD> hereto).<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Way Affidavit, RMR, Volume 1, Tab A, pages 10 and 11, paragraph 34</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P1></P>
<P><BOLD>14.</BOLD> Schembri is:
<P1>(a) disputing the costs associated with the JV Project, in part based on the budget that formed part of the JV Agreement (the <BOLD>&ldquo;JV Accounting Dispute&rdquo;);</BOLD></P1>
<P1>(b) disputing the use of monies from the sale of 345 King to fund the acquisition and commence the redevelopment of the Triumph Lands (the <BOLD>&ldquo;Rollover Dispute&rdquo;)</BOLD> pursuant to an oral agreement between Way and Schembri to do so (the <BOLD>&ldquo;Rollover Agreement&rdquo;);</BOLD></P1>
<P1>(c) alleging that his receipt, directly or indirectly, of $1.4 million in the spring of 2009 was an advance against profits as opposed to a short-term loan (the <BOLD>&ldquo;Loan Dispute&rdquo;);</BOLD></P1>
<P1>(d) disputing 172's repayment of funds advanced by Way's companies prior to 172 obtaining construction financing (the <BOLD>&ldquo;JV Repayment Dispute&rdquo;);</BOLD></P1>
<P1>(e) disputing certain of the costs associated with the redevelopment of the Triumph Lands (the <BOLD>&ldquo;Triumph Costs Dispute&rdquo;);</BOLD></P1>
<P1>(f) disputing his obligation to contribute to the costs associated with the redevelopment of the Triumph Lands (the <BOLD>&ldquo;Triumph Contribution Dispute&rdquo;)</BOLD> as provided for in the Contribution Clause; and</P1>
<P1>(g) disputing his obligation to present all real estate development opportunities which he acquired in the Regional Municipality of Waterloo to the Way Group (the <BOLD>&ldquo;ROFR Dispute&rdquo;)</BOLD> as required by the ROFR Clause.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Way Affidavit, RMR, Volume 1, Tab A, pages 11 and 12, paragraph 35</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P1></P>
<P><BOLD>15.</BOLD> This motion by the Schembri Group seeks to dispose of the ROFR Dispute only.</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>B.</N><TI>The JV Agreement</TI>
<P><BOLD>16.</BOLD> Between November, 2005 and November, 2006, Schembri undertook a five-house land assembly (the <BOLD>&ldquo;JV Lands&rdquo;).</BOLD> Prior to completing the purchase of any of the properties, Schembri approached an employee of Way. Way and a number of his employees assisted Schembri over several months in his efforts to develop the JV Lands. At no time did Way promise Schembri that he would finance or secure financing for the development of the JV Lands then projected to cost approximately $19 million.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Way Affidavit, RMR, Volume 1, Tab A, pages 12 to 17, paragraphs 36 to 52</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P><BOLD>17.</BOLD> When it became apparent that Schembri could not obtain financing to complete the purchases of three of the five properties, Way offered to complete the acquisition of those properties and then develop the JV Lands in the manner contemplated by Schembri. Way's offer to Schembri led to the suggestion that the development of the JV Lands be carried out by way of a joint venture.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Way Affidavit, RMR, Volume 1, Tab A, pages 17 and 18, paragraphs 53 and 55</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P><BOLD>18.</BOLD> The negotiation of the JV Agreement occurred over a matter of days, primarily through Schembri's lawyer. Patterson did not &ldquo;negotiate&rdquo; the JV Agreement as alleged by Schembri in the Main Action.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Way Affidavit, RMR, Volume 1, Tab A, pages 10 and 18, paragraphs 31, 57 and 58</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P><BOLD>19.</BOLD> Way and Schembri executed the JV Agreement (no earlier than April 29, 2007) that provided for, among other things, the following<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Way Affidavit, RMR, Volume 1, Tab A, pages 18 to 23, paragraphs 59 to 64 and 72 to 74 Way Affidavit, RMR, Volume 1, Tab 16, Exhibit &ldquo;16&rdquo;</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE>:
<QUOTE><P><BOLD>Financing of the JV</BOLD> [Paragraphs 2(7) and 2(8)]
<QUOTE><P><BOLD><EM>[172] shall be responsible for obtaining financing for the Joint Venture for the Project</EM>,</BOLD> <EM>including interim, bridge and permanent financing</EM>, <BOLD><EM>consistent with the sound business judgment and with loan rate, terms and conditions prevailing</EM>.</BOLD> (emphasis added)</P>
<P><BOLD><EM>[172] shall have the right to encumber the Lands or the Project</EM></BOLD> <EM>without the consent of the other</EM> <BOLD><EM>in amounts sufficient to cover the full contribution of [172]</EM>.</BOLD> (emphasis added)</P></QUOTE></P>
<P><BOLD>Planning, Management and Supervisory Services</BOLD> [Paragraph 2(10)]
<QUOTE><P><BOLD><EM>The Joint Venturers appoint Jamesway Construction (Jamesway) to supervise and manage the construction process</EM>.</BOLD> <EM>Jamesway will complete the construction of the project</EM>. <BOLD><EM>Either Joint Venturer can participate</EM></BOLD> <EM>in the site management meetings during the construction process</EM> <BOLD><EM>and make decisions through the standard construction practice</EM></BOLD>. (emphasis added)</P></QUOTE></P>
<P><BOLD>Pro Forma and Budget</BOLD> [Paragraph 2(9)]</P>
<P><EM>In managing the Joint Venture:</EM></P>
<P>(a) <EM>A Major Decision shall be made by both Joint Venturers. All other decisions shall be made by [172]</EM>.</P>
<P>(b) <BOLD><EM>It is agreed that the attached Project Budget and Performa, referred to as Schedule A, has been reviewed and agreed upon by both Joint Venturers</EM>.</BOLD></P>
<P>(c) <EM>Construction Contracts shall be agreed and awarded by both Joint Venturers through an open book concept save and except for any work performed by Jamesway. Any increase to Jamesway's contract shall be agreed to by both parties</EM>.</P>
<P>(d) <BOLD><EM>Any increase to the budget shall be agreed upon by both Joint Venturers</EM>.</BOLD> (emphasis added)</P>
<P><BOLD>The &ldquo;5 and 5&rdquo;</BOLD> [Page 2 of Schedule A (i.e. the Project Budget and Performa)]</P>
<P>172 is to pay:</P>
<P>(a) five percent (5%) of construction costs for office administration; and</P>
<P>(b) five percent (5%) of construction costs and office administration as profit.</P>
<P><BOLD>Determination of Profit</BOLD> [Paragraph 1(5)]
<QUOTE><P><BOLD><EM>&ldquo;Proportionate Share&rdquo; means with respect to each Joint Venturer its undivided interest in the profit made from the completed project</EM></BOLD> <EM>and in the Joint Venture, expressed as a percentage</EM>. <BOLD><EM>Each Joint Venturer shall have a Fifty (50%) percent share of the profit as may be determined by [172] acting reasonably and in accordance with General Accounting Principals</EM></BOLD> [<EM>sic</EM>] <BOLD><EM>(&ldquo;GAAP&rdquo;)</EM></BOLD>. (emphasis added)</P></QUOTE></P>
<P><BOLD>Distribution of Funds</BOLD> [Paragraph 2(12)]
<QUOTE><P><EM>When surplus funds from receipts of the Joint Venturer [sic] are available which are not required for the normal operation of the Joint Venture they shall be applied in the following order:</EM></P>
<P><EM>(a) first, to pay any expenses or charges due in respect of the Lands and Project;</EM></P>
<P><EM>(b) secondly, to pay any interest incurring at the rate of prime plus 3% on the item set out in 15(a) [sic] made by the Joint Venturers outside of any third party financing; and</EM></P>
<P><EM>(c) thirdly, to distribute any balance remaining between the Joint Venturers in accordance with their Proportionate Shares</EM>.</P></QUOTE></P></QUOTE></P>
<P><BOLD>20.</BOLD> In furtherance of the JV Agreement:
<P1>(a) arrangements were made to extend the closing date for each of the three properties that Schembri did not have the funds to close; and</P1>
<P1>(b) Way arranged for an increase in his company's line of credit with CIBC (the <BOLD>&ldquo;CIBC LoC Increase&rdquo;)</BOLD> in order to complete the acquisition of the JV Lands by 172.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Way Affidavit, RMR, Volume 1, Tab A, page 23, paragraphs 75 and 76</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P1></P>
<P><BOLD>21.</BOLD> On or about May 11, 2007, 172 acquired the JV Lands.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Way Affidavit, RMR, Volume 1, Tab A, page 23, paragraphs 77</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P><BOLD>22.</BOLD> Way, through 172, carried out the development of the JV Lands, to the satisfaction of:
<P1>(a) the lenders, Canadian Imperial Bank of Commerce and Kingsett Capital;</P1>
<P1>(b) the City of Waterloo and the Regional Municipality of Waterloo; and</P1>
<P1>(c) the purchaser, who paid the purchase price in full without deduction.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Way Affidavit, RMR, Volume1, Tab A, pages 57, 58 and 60, paragraphs 200 to 205 and 215</P>
<P>Way Affidavit, RMR, Volumes 5 and 6, Tabs 83 to 87 and 92, Exhibits &ldquo;83&rdquo; to &ldquo;87&rdquo; and &ldquo;92&rdquo;</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P1></P>
<P><BOLD>23.</BOLD> More than ten years later, Schembri has still not:
<P1>(a) revealed the total amount he paid, or caused to be paid, prior to 172's acquisition of the JV Lands; nor</P1>
<P1>(b) produced all relevant documents related to his payments;</P1>
in connection with the acquisition, carrying and development of the JV Lands.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Way Affidavit, RMR, Volume 1, Tab A, pages 24 to 26, paragraphs 79 to 83</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>C.</N><TI>The Shareholder Agreement</TI>
<P><BOLD>24.</BOLD> At a meeting on January 29, 2008 (the <BOLD>&ldquo;January 2008 Meeting&rdquo;),</BOLD> Way and Schembri (in the presence of their lawyers) agreed to a deal (the <BOLD>&ldquo;Triumph Deal&rdquo;)</BOLD> whereby:
<P1>(a) they would incorporate Triumph as a holding company, in which Way would have a fifty-five percent (55%) interest and Schembri would have a forty-five percent (45%) interest;</P1>
<P1>(b) they would incorporate subsidiaries of Triumph to acquire and develop the Waterloo Lands and the London Lands in the manner that they were developing the JV Lands (namely, Premier doing the design work in conjunction with various consultants, and Jamesway doing the project management, including the general conditions); and</P1>
<P1>(c) Schembri would look for other lands in Kitchener and Waterloo for Triumph to acquire and develop.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Way Affidavit, RMR, Volume 1, Tab A, page 32, paragraphs 109 and 110</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P1></P>
<P><BOLD>25.</BOLD> Contrary to Schembri's allegations in the Main Action, Way did not agree at the January 2008 Meeting to either:
<P1>(a) fund the development of the properties to be acquired through subsidiaries of Triumph; or</P1>
<P1>(b) guarantee third party financing for the development of such properties.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Way Affidavit, RMR, Volume 1, Tab A, page 32, paragraph 111</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P1></P>
<P><BOLD>26.</BOLD> Following the January 2008 Meeting and prior to the execution of the Shareholder Agreement, Way and Schembri acted in accordance with Triumph Deal by, among other things:
<P1>(a) incorporating Triumph and 359 King Ontario Inc. (the <BOLD>&ldquo;Waterloo Subsidiary&rdquo;)</BOLD> on or about February 28, 2008, wherein Schembri was appointed a director and officer of both companies;</P1>
<P1>(b) extending the closing dates for the Waterloo Lands;</P1>
<P1>(c) amending the agreement for the purchase of the London Lands; and</P1>
<P1>(d) looking at and, in some instances, submitting offers for other lands in Kitchener and Waterloo.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Way Affidavit, RMR, Volume 1, Tab A, pages 33 and 34, paragraphs 112 to 117</P>
<P>Way Affidavit, RMR, Volume 3, Tabs 41 to 44, Exhibits &ldquo;41&rdquo; to &ldquo;44&rdquo;</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P1></P>
<P><BOLD>27.</BOLD> At some point before April 9, 2008, Way and Schembri, among others, executed the Shareholder Agreement that provided for, among other things, the following<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Way Affidavit, RMR, Volume 1, Tab A, pages 44 to 46, paragraphs 145 to 150</P>
<P>Way Affidavit, RMR, Volume 3, Tab 54, Exhibit &ldquo;54&rdquo;</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE>:
<QUOTE><P><BOLD>Article 12&mdash;Financing</BOLD> (the <BOLD>&ldquo;Contribution Clause&rdquo;)</BOLD>
<QUOTE><P><BOLD><EM>All liabilities incurred by, arising from or in connection with [Triumph]</EM>,</BOLD> <EM>including any loans or overdrafts with any banks or lending institutions, which have been personally guaranteed by any of the parties hereto</EM>, <BOLD><EM>shall be shared on a pro rata basis by the parties hereto</EM></BOLD> <EM>based on a fraction the numerator of which shall be the number of shares held by each Shareholder and the denominator of which shall be the total issued and outstanding shares in the capital stock of [Triumph]</EM> <BOLD><EM>and if any of the parties hereto discharges any liabilities of [Triumph]</EM></BOLD> <EM>either</EM> <BOLD><EM>directly</EM></BOLD> <EM>or pursuant to a guarantee given by any of the parties hereto</EM>, <BOLD><EM>then the party discharging the liabilities shall have the right to be reimbursed</EM></BOLD> <EM>by the parties not so contributing</EM> <BOLD><EM>so that the in the end result, each of the parties hereto shall have contributed equally to all liabilities incurred</EM></BOLD> <EM>and/or guarantees given. Until such time that the parties not so contributing have reimbursed the party discharging the liability, the shares of the parties not so contributing shall be held by the accountants of [Triumph] acting as escrow agent and at the option of the party discharging the liability, said shares may be sold if the parties not so contributing have not reimbursed the party discharging the liabilities within THIRTY (30) days after the party discharging the liabilities has demanded reimbursement thereof and the proceeds from the sale of such shares after deduction of any expenses incurred in the sale, shall be applied on account of the debt owing from the parties not so contributing to the party discharging the liabilities, but any surplus of proceeds over and above the debt owing shall be distributed to the parties not so contributing</EM>. (emphasis added)</P></QUOTE></P>
<P><BOLD>Article 13&mdash;Non-Competition</BOLD> (the <BOLD>&ldquo;ROFR Clause&rdquo;)</BOLD>
<QUOTE><P><BOLD><EM>During the period which [Schembri Financial] is a shareholder of the Corporation, it shall have the ongoing obligation to present to [KFI] and [Triumph] all real estate development opportunities (the &ldquo;Project&rdquo;) which it may have acquired within the Regional Municipality of Waterloo. This obligation to [KFI] and [Triumph] shall also extend to [Schembri] personally</EM>,</BOLD> <EM>and any other legal entity in which he has an interest, either directly or indirectly, financially or otherwise. [KFI] and [Triumph] shall have FIFTEEN (15) days following the presentation of the Project to them to determine if it is economically feasible using the typical budget model consistently utilized by them in such circumstances and, if at the expiry of the FIFTEEN (15) day period neither of them have indicated to [Schembri Financial] in writing that it is taking on the Project, then [Schembri Financial] (or its designate) shall be free to pursue the Project without the involvement of [KFI] or [Triumph]</EM>. (emphasis added)</P></QUOTE></P>
<P><BOLD>Article 15&mdash;Arbitration</BOLD> (the <BOLD>&ldquo;Arbitration Clause&rdquo;)</BOLD>
<QUOTE><P><BOLD><EM>Any dispute</EM></BOLD> <EM>between the parties hereto, whether arising during the period of this Agreement or at any time thereafter</EM> <BOLD><EM>which touches upon the validity, construction, meaning, performance or effect of this Agreement or the rights and liabilities of the parties hereto</EM></BOLD> <EM>or any matter arising out of or connected with this Agreement</EM> <BOLD><EM>shall be subject to arbitration pursuant to the Arbitrations Act, 1991</EM>,</BOLD> <EM>as amended from time to time, and as provided for in this Article and the decision shall be final and binding between the parties hereto and shall not be subject to appeal</EM>. (emphasis added)</P></QUOTE></P>
<P><BOLD>Article 23&mdash;Final Agreement</BOLD>
<QUOTE><P><BOLD><EM>This Agreement expresses the final agreement between the parties hereto with respect to all matters herein</EM></BOLD> <EM>and its execution has not been induced by, nor do any of the parties hereto rely upon or regard as material, any representation or premises [sic] whatsoever not incorporated herein or made a part hereof, and any alteration, amendment or qualification thereof shall be null and void and shall not be binding upon any such party unless made and recorded as aforesaid</EM>. (emphasis added)</P></QUOTE></P></QUOTE></P>
<P><BOLD>28.</BOLD> Contrary to Schembri's allegations in the Main Action, the Shareholder Agreement does not require KFI (or Way personally) to either:
<P1>(a) fund the development of the properties to be acquired through subsidiaries of Triumph; or</P1>
<P1>(b) guarantee third party financing for the development of such properties.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Way Affidavit, RMR, Volume 1, Tab A, page 46, paragraph 151</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P1></P>
<P>Recently, Schembri admitted under oath that there is no clause in the Shareholder Agreement imposing an obligation on any member of the Way Group to do either (a) or (b).<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Transcript of the cross-examination of Gordon Schembri held September 17, 2018 (the <BOLD>&ldquo;Schembri X/E Transcript&rdquo;),</BOLD> pages 13 and 14, question 14</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P><BOLD>29.</BOLD> Following the execution of the Shareholder Agreement, Way and Schembri, among other things:
<P1>(a) completed the purchase of the Waterloo Lands in April, 2008;</P1>
<P1>(b) incorporated Oxford &amp; First St. Inc. (the <BOLD>&ldquo;London Subsidiary&rdquo;)</BOLD> on or about November 13, 2009, wherein Schembri was appointed a director and officer;</P1>
<P1>(c) incorporated Simcoe &amp; Eastwood Ave Inc. (the <BOLD>&ldquo;Oshawa Subsidiary&rdquo;)</BOLD> on or about November 17, 2009, wherein Schembri was appointed a director and officer;</P1>
<P1>(d) completed the purchase of the Oshawa Lands in February, 2009; and</P1>
<P1>(e) completed the purchase of the London Lands in April, 2009.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Way Affidavit, RMR, Volume 1, Tab A, pages 48, 52, 53, 56, 58 and 59, paragraphs 157 to 159, 176 to 181, 193 to 195, and 206 to 208</P>
<P>Way Affidavit, RMR, Volumes 4 and 5, Tabs 56 to 58, 69 to 72, 79, 80, 88 and 89, Exhibits &ldquo;56&rdquo; to &ldquo;58&rdquo;, &ldquo;69&rdquo; to &ldquo;72&rdquo;, &ldquo;79&rdquo;, &ldquo;80&rdquo;, &ldquo;88&rdquo; and &ldquo;89&rdquo;</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P1></P></BLOCK3></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><N>II.</N><TI>The Litigation</TI>
<BLOCK3><N>A.</N><TI>The Main Action</TI>
<P><BOLD>30.</BOLD> Schembri commenced the Main Action in Toronto in February, 2010. Way caused the Main Action to be transferred to Kitchener in 2011. Schembri amended the Statement of Claim in the Main Action in 2012 and again in 2013 to, among other things, add defendants and increase the amount of damages being sought.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Way Affidavit, RMR, Volume 1, Tab A, pages 63 and 84 to 88, paragraphs 226 and 229 to 318</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P><BOLD>31.</BOLD> At present, Schembri is claiming more than $30 million in general damages, along with various other relief, in connection with the JV Project ($5 million) and the Triumph Lands ($25 million).<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Way Affidavit, RMR, Volume 1, Tab A, page 88, paragraph 319</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P><BOLD>32.</BOLD> The Main Action is defended. In addition, Way asserts a counterclaim, initially in part, to the effect that Schembri breached the Shareholder Agreement by failing to comply with the ROFR Clause so as to allow the Way Group to participate in the acquisition and development of other properties located in the Regional Municipality of Waterloo. Schembri's breach of the ROFR Clause is now the subject matter of the ROFR Action.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Way Affidavit, RMR, Volume 1, Tab A, page 63, paragraphs 227 and 228</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P><BOLD>33.</BOLD> There are orders, on consent, in both the Main Action and the ROFR Action that these actions are to be tried together, that Way obtained after prolonged delay by Schembri.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Way Affidavit, RMR, Volume 1, Tab A, page 91, paragraph 325</P>
<P>Way Affidavit, RMR, Volume 1, Tabs 132 and 135, Exhibits &ldquo;132&rdquo; and &ldquo;135&rdquo;</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P><BOLD>34.</BOLD> Schembri set the Main Action down for trial in June, 2017 after completing his examinations for discovery in the Main Action and the ROFR Action.</P>
<P><BOLD>35.</BOLD> Way has not completed his examination for discovery of Schembri in either the Main Action or the ROFR Action. To date, Schembri has not answered a single undertaking given at his examination for discovery.</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>B.</N><TI>The Receivership of the Triumph Subsidiaries</TI>
<P><BOLD>36.</BOLD> In September 2010, the court appointed a receiver over the three subsidiaries of Triumph based, in part, on the evidence of Reg Dupuis, a disgruntled former employee of Way. In so appointing, Justice Roberts expressly noted that <BOLD><EM>&ldquo;as this is an interlocutory proceeding, I have not made any final conclusions</EM></BOLD>...<EM>It is therefore premature at this stage to award substantial indemnity costs on the basis of facts that have not been finally determined.&rdquo;</EM> [emphasis added]<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Way Affidavit, RMR, Volume 1, Tab A, pages 66 and 67, paragraph 238, 239 and 241 to 243</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P><BOLD>37.</BOLD> There were numerous court attendances between January, 2011 and February, 2012, in respect of which the Receiver filed eight reports and two supplemental reports.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Way Affidavit, RMR, Volume 1, Tab A, page 73, paragraphs 253 and 254</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P><BOLD>38.</BOLD> During the course of the receivership proceedings:
<P1>(a) Schembri filed improper claims with the Receiver (addressed in paragraphs 59 to 66 below);</P1>
<P1>(b) Schembri sought an order compelling Way to guarantee construction financing for the development of the Oshawa Lands that Justice Mesbur dismissed with costs to Way;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Way Affidavit, RMR, Volume 1, Tab A, page 76, paragraphs 267 and 268</P>
<P>Way Affidavit, RMR, Volume 9, Tab 117, Exhibit &ldquo;117&rdquo;</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P1>
<P1>(c) Schembri objected to the Receiver's request for approval of its fees and those of its counsel (totaling more than $400,000 over eight months). Justice Mesbur rejected Schembri's objections and admonished Schembri for his litigation tactics;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Way Affidavit, RMR, Volume 1, Tab A, page 77, paragraphs 271 to 274</P>
<P>Way Affidavit, RMR, Volume 9, Tab 119, Exhibit &ldquo;119&rdquo;</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> and</P1>
<P1>(d) Schembri attempted to saddle Way with the costs incurred by the Receiver and its counsel in rectifying Schembri's error in connection with his acquisition of the Waterloo Lands from the Receiver.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Way Affidavit, RMR, Volume 1, Tab A, page 79, paragraph 279</P>
<P>Way Affidavit, RMR, Volume 9, Tab 121, Exhibit &ldquo;121&rdquo;</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P1></P>
<P><BOLD>39.</BOLD> The Receiver sold: (i) the Waterloo Lands and the London Lands to Schembri; and (ii) the Oshawa Lands to Way.</P>
<P><BOLD>40.</BOLD> The receivership proceedings have been dormant since the spring of 2012, but for the steps taken in early 2013 to rectify Schembri's error in connection with his acquisition of the Waterloo Lands.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Way Affidavit, RMR, Volume 1, Tab A, pages 78 and 79, paragraphs 277 to 280</P>
<P>Way Affidavit, RMR, Volume 9, Tab 121, Exhibit &ldquo;121&rdquo;</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> These steps occurred shortly before Schembri's acquisition of nineteen of the twenty properties detailed in paragraph 74(b) below.</P>
<P><BOLD>41.</BOLD> As a result of the sale of the Triumph Lands, there is approximately $3,000,000 being held by the Receiver in the receivership proceedings.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Way Affidavit, RMR, Volume 1, Tab A, page 78, paragraph 275</P>
<P>Way Affidavit, RMR, Volume 9, Tab 120, Exhibit &ldquo;120&rdquo;</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>C.</N><TI>The ROFR Action</TI>
<P><BOLD>42.</BOLD> The Way Group commenced the ROFR Action in May, 2012.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Affidavit of Gordon Schembri sworn May 17, 2017 (the <BOLD>&ldquo;Schembri Affidavit&rdquo;),</BOLD> Motion Record <BOLD>(&ldquo;MR&rdquo;),</BOLD> Exhibit &ldquo;J&rdquo;</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P><BOLD>43.</BOLD> The Schembri Group did not deliver a Statement of Defence to the ROFR Action until July, 2014.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Way Affidavit, RMR, Volume 10, Tab 134, Exhibit &ldquo;134&rdquo;</P>
<P>Schembri Affidavit, MR, Tab K, Exhibit &ldquo;K&rdquo;</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P><BOLD>44.</BOLD> By Order dated September 4, 2014, the plaintiffs amended the ROFR Action on consent to add additional defendants.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Way Affidavit, RMR, Volume 10, Tab 135, Exhibit &ldquo;135&rdquo;</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P><BOLD>45.</BOLD> For reasons not known to the Way Group, the Schembri Group omitted 1765998 Ontario Inc. from: (i) the Amended Statement of Defence; (ii) the ROFR AoD; and (iii) the within Notice of Motion.</P></BLOCK3></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><N>III.</N><TI>Schembri's Breaches of his Fiduciary Duties</TI>
<BLOCK3><N>A.</N><TI>Schembri's Initial Compliance with the ROFR Clause</TI>
<P><BOLD>46.</BOLD> In accordance with the Triumph Deal, Schembri presented to Way several &ldquo;real estate development opportunities...within the Regional Municipality of Waterloo&rdquo;.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Way Affidavit, RMR, Volume 1, Tab A, page 33, paragraph 113</P>
<P>Way Affidavit, RMR, Volume 3, Tab 41, Exhibit &ldquo;41&rdquo;</P>
<P>Transcript of the examination for discovery of Gordon Schembri held March 28, 2018 (the <BOLD>&ldquo;Schembri Day 8 E/D Transcript&rdquo;),</BOLD> page 1340, question 5157</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P><BOLD>47.</BOLD> One such opportunity was 61 Columbia Street West. On or about July 31, 2008, Schembri caused Triumph to enter into an agreement of purchase and sale for this property. Schembri told Way he wanted to construct a triplex with 15 bedrooms.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Way Affidavit, RMR, Volume 1, Tab A, page 105, paragraphs 380 and 381</P>
<P>Way Affidavit, RMR, Volume 10, Tab 142, Exhibit &ldquo;142&rdquo;</P>
<P>Transcript of the cross-examination of Al Way held July 17, 2018, pages 143 to 147, questions 576 to 592</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>B.</N><TI>ROFR Breach #1&mdash;1765998 Ontario Inc.</TI>
<P><BOLD>48.</BOLD> Unbeknownst to Way, Schembri orchestrated a premediated breach of the ROFR Clause by completing the acquisition of the property known municipally as 59 Columbia Street West, Waterloo on or about May 6, 2009 after entering into an agreement of purchase and sale dated March 4, 2009 (nearly a year before he commenced the Main Action); that Schembri subsequently consolidated with 61 Columbia Street West, Waterloo, and on which he constructed a three-storey building containing &ldquo;5 bedroom suites with 2 full bathrooms&rdquo;.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Way Affidavit, RMR, Volume 1, Tab A, page 105, paragraphs 380 and 382</P>
<P>Way Affidavit, RMR, Volume Exhibit &ldquo;143&rdquo;</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>C.</N><TI>Schembri Breaches his Fiduciary Duties at Directors' Meetings</TI>
<P><BOLD>49.</BOLD> Under cover of letter dated April 7, 2010 from counsel for Way to counsel for Schembri, notices were sent for: (i) a Meeting of the Directors of Triumph; and (ii) a Meeting of the Directors of the Oshawa Subsidiary; to be held on April 12, 2010.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Way Affidavit, RMR, Volume 1, Tab A, page 64, paragraph 231</P>
<P>Way Affidavit, RMR, Volume 7, Tab 101, Exhibit &ldquo;101&rdquo;</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P><BOLD>50.</BOLD> The Meeting of the Directors of the Oshawa Subsidiary occurred first, and lasted approximately one hour. It dealt with the status of the development of the Oshawa Lands and the issues relating to proceeding with that project, which was effectively ready to commence from a construction perspective as noted by the Receiver in the First Report.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Way Affidavit, RMR, Volume 7, Tab 102, Exhibit &ldquo;102&rdquo; at pages 1918 to 1923</P>
<P>Way Affidavit, RMR, Vo 111, Exhibit &ldquo;111&rdquo; at page 2179, paragraph 10</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P><BOLD>51.</BOLD> The Meeting of the Directors of Triumph followed, and lasted twenty-five minutes. During this meeting Schembri acknowledged the Rollover Agreement but said he did not know the amount of his contribution to Triumph because of the JV Accounting Dispute.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Way Affidavit, RMR, Volume 7, Tab 102, Exhibit &ldquo;102&rdquo; at pages 1924 and 1925</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P><BOLD>52.</BOLD> Way discovered subsequently that at that time of the two Director's meetings Schembri had:
<P1>(a) acquired and was developing a property municipally known as 33 Taylorwood Road, Oshawa (the <BOLD>&ldquo;Taylorwood Property&rdquo;),</BOLD> which was located approximately four hundred feet (400') from the Oshawa Lands; and</P1>
<P1>(b) tied up the properties known municipally as 39 and 41 Columbia Street West, Waterloo.</P1></P>
<P><BOLD>53.</BOLD> Schembri did not disclose his interest in the Taylorwood Property to Way at either of the Director's Meetings, or to the Court in connection with his motions seeking: (i) the appointment of a receiver; and (ii) that Way guarantee financing for the redevelopment of the Oshawa Lands (addressed in paragraph 67 below).<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Way Affidavit, RMR, Volume 1, Tab A, page 64, paragraph 232 and 233</P>
<P>Way Affidavit, RMR, Volume 7, Tab 103, Exhibit &ldquo;103&rdquo;</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P><BOLD>54.</BOLD> Schembri did not disclose his interests in the properties known municipally as 39 and 41 Columbia Street West, Waterloo at the Director's Meeting of Triumph.</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>D.</N><TI>ROFR Breach # 2&mdash;41 Columbia Inc.</TI>
<P><BOLD>55.</BOLD> Unbeknownst to Way, Schembri orchestrated another premediated breach of the ROFR Clause by completing the acquisitions of the properties known municipally as 39 and 41 Columbia Street West, Waterloo on or about April 30, 2010; that Schembri subsequently consolidated and on which he constructed a four-storey building containing 4 bedroom and 5 bedroom suites.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Way Affidavit, RMR, Volume 1, Tab A, page 105, paragraphs 383 and 384</P>
<P>Way Affidavit, RMR, Volume 10, Tabs 144 and 145, Exhibits &ldquo;144&rdquo; and &ldquo;145&rdquo;</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>E.</N><TI>Schembri Refuses to Contribute</TI>
<P><BOLD>56.</BOLD> Following the closing of the sale of 345 King on March 19, 2009, Way provided Schembri with an estimate of the required contribution to Triumph: (a) based on the estimated profit from the JV Project: and (b) having regard to the Rollover Agreement. Way followed up with Schembri from time to time about Schembri contributing his share to Triumph in accordance with the Contribution Clause.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Way Affidavit, RMR, Volume 1, Tab A, pages 59 and 60, paragraphs 209 and 212</P>
<P>Way Affidavit, RM Volume 5, Tabs 90 and 91, Exhibits &ldquo;90&rdquo; and &ldquo;91&rdquo;</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P><BOLD>57.</BOLD> By Notice of Payment of Liabilities of Triumph dated May 2, 2010, Way caused Triumph to issue a demand for contribution pursuant to the Contribution Claus e in an effort to compel Schembri to pay the amount necessary to get the 55/45 split balanced so that they were both carrying their proportionate share. Contrary to Schembri's allegations, Way did so to compel Schembri to pay and not to seize Schembri's shares. Schembri refused to pay. Way did not seize his shares.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Way Affidavit, RMR, Volume 1, Tab A, page 65, paragraph 234 and 235</P>
<P>Way Affidavit, RMR, Volume 5, Tabs 90 and 91, Exhibits &ldquo;90&rdquo;</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>F.</N><TI>Schembri Blocks Arbitration</TI>
<P><BOLD>58.</BOLD> In furtherance of the Arbitration Clause, Way caused Triumph to serve a Notice Demanding Arbitration dated June 25, 2010. Schembri then served a notice of motion dated July 26, 2010 seeking to stay arbitration that alleged, among other things, that the Main Action was at an advanced stage. Schembri never swore the supporting affidavit, and never filed the motion. This is one example of Schembri's scorched earth litigation tactics.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Way Affidavit, RMR, Volume 1, Tab A, paragraphs 236 and 237</P>
<P>Way Affidavit, RMR, Volume 7, Tabs 104 to 106, Exhibits &ldquo;104&rdquo; to &ldquo;106&rdquo;</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>G.</N><TI>Schembri Files Improper Claims with the Receiver</TI>
<P><BOLD>59.</BOLD> The Receiver conducted a claims procedure pursuant to a court order issued on consent.</P>
<P><BOLD>60.</BOLD> Schembri filed claims totaling $16,145,505.83 (the <BOLD>&ldquo;Schembri Claims&rdquo;)</BOLD>. Of the Schembri Claims, the Receiver initially allowed a mere $39,377.75 (less than 0.3%).<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Way Affidavit, RMR, Volume 1, Tab A, pages 74 and 75, paragraphs 255 and 260 to 264</P>
<P>Way Affidavit, RMR, Volume 8, Tabs 112 to 115, Exhibits &ldquo;112&rdquo; to &ldquo;115&rdquo;</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P><BOLD>61.</BOLD> Several of the Schembri Claims were not supported by any documents whatsoever; others were improper at best, and fraudulent at worst. Among the these Schembri Claims<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Way Affidavit, RMR, Volume 1, Tab A, pages 75 and 76, paragraphs 262 to 266</P>
<P>Way Affidavit, RMR, Volume 9, Tab 116, Exhibit &ldquo;116&rdquo; at pages 2408 and 2409, paragraphs 73(a) to (c)</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> were:
<P1>(a) a claim for $20,000 relating to a deposit paid by one of Way's companies and not Schembri or any of his companies;</P1>
<P1>(b) a claim for $3,148.18 that had already been reimbursed, which the Receiver subsequently recognized resulting in the allowed Schembri Claims being reduced to $36, 229.57;</P1>
<P1>(c) duplicate claims for the same alleged debt in the amount of $21,587.47 (in respect of which no documentation has been provided in support of either claim);</P1>
<P1>(d) a claim for H.S.T. on reimbursement of expenses;</P1>
<P1>(e) a claim for H.S.T. for alleged services rendered before H.S.T. came into effect; and</P1>
<P1>(f) claims for $5 million in triplicate without deduction for the $1.4 million that Schembri alleges he received as an advance against his profits in the JV Project, which are duplicative of claims filed by Way (for the funds advanced by 172 pursuant to the Rollover Agreement) and allowed by the Receiver.</P1></P>
<P><BOLD>62.</BOLD> Way filed claims totaling $8,489,030.13 (the <BOLD>&ldquo;Way Claims&rdquo;)</BOLD>. Of the Way Claims, the Receiver:
<P1>(a) allowed the amount of $7,029,638.99 (nearly 83%)<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Way Affidavit, RMR, Volume 1, Tab A, page 74, paragraph 260</P>
<P>Way Affidavit, RMR, Volume 8, Tab 114, Exhibits &ldquo;114&rdquo; at pages 2239 to 2241</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE>; and</P1>
<P1>(b) acknowledged that the remaining claims related to actual services provided but it was unable to quantify the value of such services.</P1></P>
<P><BOLD>63.</BOLD> Of note, the estate of the Waterloo Subsidiary (a defendant in the Main Action) has approximately $600,000 following the sale of the Waterloo Lands. In that estate, the Receiver has allowed claims of: (a) Way companies totaling $1,632,826.76; (b) a Schembri company totalling $36,229.57 (as stated in paragraph 61(b) above); and (c) Triumph totalling $277,000. The result being that Way companies stand to receive approximately $500,000 from the estate of the Waterloo Subsidiary.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Way Affidavit, RMR, Volume 8, Tab 114, Exhibit &ldquo;114&rdquo; at page 2239</P>
<P>Way Affidavit, RMR, Volume 9, Tab 120, Exhibit &ldquo;120&rdquo; at page 2464</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P><BOLD>64.</BOLD> Of further note, Schembri has no allowed claims in the estates of:
<P1>(a) the London Subsidiary (a defendant in the Main Action), which has approximately $975,000 following the sale of the London Lands; and</P1>
<P1>(b) the Oshawa Subsidiary (a defendant in the Main Action), which has approximately $1.8 million following the sale of the Oshawa Lands.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Way Affidavit, RMR, Volume 8, Tab 114, Exhibit &ldquo;114&rdquo; at pages 2240 and 2241</P>
<P>Way Affidavit, RMR, Volume 9, Tab 120, Exhibit &ldquo;120&rdquo; at pages 2463 and 2465</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P1></P>
<P><BOLD>65.</BOLD> Regardless of allocation issues, any distribution will be much less than 50 cents on the dollar. It is plain and obvious that the receivership proceedings have resulted in significant losses that harm Way far more than Schembri (as was Schembri's intention in carrying out his scorched earth litigation tactics).<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Way Affidavit, RMR, Volume 1, Tab A, page 76 and 78, paragraphs 270 and 275</P>
<P>Way Affidavit, RMR, Volume 8, Tab 114, Exhibit &ldquo;114&rdquo;</P>
<P>Way Affidavit, RMR, Volume 9, Tab 120, Exhibit &ldquo;120&rdquo;</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P><BOLD>66.</BOLD> As a consequence of the Schembri Claims, there has been no distribution in respect of the $7,029,638.99 in Way Claims allowed by the Receiver.</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>H.</N><TI>Schembri's Failed Motion re the Oshawa Lands</TI>
<P>67. During the course of the receivership proceedings, Schembri brought a motion seeking an order compelling Way to guarantee construction financing for the development of the Oshawa Lands by the Receiver. Justice Mesbur dismissed Schembri's motion and awarded Way costs in the amount of $37,500, all inclusive.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Way Affidavit, RMR, Volume 1, Tab A, page 76, paragraphs 267 and 268</P>
<P>Way Affidavit, RMR, Volume 9, Tab 117, Exhibit &ldquo;117&rdquo;</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>I.</N><TI>ROFR Breaches #3 &amp; 4&mdash;1 Columbia Inc. &amp; 69 Columbia St. Inc.</TI>
<P><BOLD>68.</BOLD> Further to paragraph 39 above, Schembri completed the acquisition of the Waterloo Lands from the Receiver on or about August 2, 2011. Prior to completing this acquisition, the Way Group put Schembri Financial Limited and Schembri on notice that the Shareholder Agreement obliged them to present KFI and Triumph with this real estate development opportunity. Schembri Financial Limited and Schembri ignored this notice and proceeded to complete the acquisition of the Waterloo Lands, and on which he subsequently constructed a high-rise apartment building containing &ldquo;5-bedroom suites, each having their own private ensuite and coming fully furnished&rdquo;.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Way Affidavit, RMR, Tab A, Volume 1, page 106, paragraphs 385 to 389</P>
<P>Way Affidavit, RMR, Volume 10, Tab 146, Exhibit &ldquo;146&rdquo;</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P><BOLD>69.</BOLD> A month later, Schembri completed the acquisitions of the properties known municipally as 69 and 71 Columbia Street West, Waterloo on or about September 9, 2011; that Schembri subsequently consolidated and on which he constructed a four-storey building containing a mix of 2 and 5-bedroom suites.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Schembri X/E Transcript, pages 127 to 129, question 170</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>J.</N><TI>Schembri's Failed Objection to the Fees of the Receiver</TI>
<P><BOLD>70.</BOLD> In the Seventh Report dated October 14, 2011, the Receiver sought approval of the fees of the Receiver and counsel to the Receiver totaling more than $400,000 for the period from February 1, 2011 to September 30, 2011 (the <BOLD>&ldquo;Fee Approval Request&rdquo;)</BOLD>. Schembri swore an affidavit on the eve of the motion opposing the Fee Approval Request; prompting the Receiver to prepare additional materials.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Way Affidavit, RMR, Tab A, Volume 1, page 77, paragraphs 271 and 273</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P><BOLD>71.</BOLD> At the hearing of the Fee Approval Request, Justice Mesbur: (a) did not permit the filing of the Schembri affidavit as <EM>&ldquo;it was totally unfair to do so at such late date&rdquo;</EM> when the hearing date had been scheduled three months earlier; and (b) granted the Fee Approval Request.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Way Affidavit, RMR, Tab A, Volume 1, page 77, paragraph 274</P>
<P>Way Affidavit, RMR, Volume 9, Tab 119, Exhibit &ldquo;119&rdquo;</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>K.</N><TI>Schembri Blocks Payment to CRA</TI>
<P><BOLD>72.</BOLD> Way caused an application to brought to have approximately $275,000 held in trust released to CRA. Schembri blocked Way's efforts for more than six months before withdrawing his opposition on the eve of the court attendance without delivering any responding materials (despite obtaining an adjournment for that purpose). Justice Gordon ordered costs against Schembri.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Way Affidavit, RMR, Volume 1, Tab A, page 100, paragraph 357</P>
<P>Way Affidavit, RMR, Volume 10, Tab 141, Exhibit &ldquo;141&rdquo; at pages 2807 to 2809</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P><BOLD>73.</BOLD> There remains an outstanding claim by CRA in the approximate amount of $300,000 that continues to accrue interest and penalties. Schembri opposed the Receiver paying CRA's Requirement to Pay despite it having priority over Way and Schembri. This is another example of Schembri's scorched earth litigation tactics.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Way Affidavit, RMR, Volume 1, Tab A, page 100, paragraph 357</P>
<P>Way Affidavit, RMR, Volume 10, Tab 141, Exhibit &ldquo;141&rdquo; at pages 2811 to 2814</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>L.</N><TI>ROFR Breaches #5 and 6&mdash;5 Rittenhouse Inc. &amp; The Block Inc.</TI>
