<BLOCK3><N>B/F.</N><TI>The Triumph Contribution Dispute and the Rollover Dispute</TI>
<P><BOLD>92.</BOLD> These two disputes are intertwined.</P>
<P><BOLD>93.</BOLD> Regarding the Triumph Contribution Dispute, Schembri has alleged that Way was required to fund the Triumph Lands, at no interest, unless Way obtained financing elsewhere supported, if necessary, by guarantees from Way and his companies but not Schembri or his companies. As Schembri has now admitted, there is no such requirement in the Shareholder Agreement. Moreover, Schembri's allegation in this regard was not asserted in the Statement of Claim, but rather the Amended Statement of Claim.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Way Affidavit, RMR, Volume 1, Tab A, page 102, paragraphs 362 and 363</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P><BOLD>94.</BOLD> Regarding the Rollover Dispute, Schembri has acknowledged he injected funds into Triumph pursuant to the Rollover Agreement (as stated in paragraph 51 above). The only issue is the amount of the amount of his injection, which Schembri alleges depends on the determination of the JV Accounting Dispute.</P>
<P><BOLD>95.</BOLD> It is absurd to suggest that Way would bear the risk of funding the development of the Triumph Lands (estimated to cost approximately $74,000,000 in the aggregate) in exchange for a 55% interest in Triumph, while Schembri would have no risk (according to his alleged interpretation of the Contribution Clause) in exchange for a 45% interest in Triumph.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Way Affidavit, RMR, Volume 1, Tab A, page 102, paragraph 364</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>C.</N><TI>The Loan Dispute</TI>
<P><BOLD>96.</BOLD> Regardless of whether the $1.4 million was a short term loan (as it was) or an advance against his share of the profits from the JV Project (as Schembri alleges), the fact is that Schembri received the benefit of $1.4 million. Moreover, Schembri still filed claims for $5 million in the receivership proceedings as against each of the Triumph subsidiaries.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Way Affidavit, RMR, Volume 1, Tab A, page 102, paragraph 364</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>D.</N><TI>The JV Repayment Dispute</TI>
<P><BOLD>97.</BOLD> Schembri knows that 172 did not have any funds of its own to purchase the five properties that he had tied up previously. Schembri also knows that the JV Agreement permitted 172 to repay advances prior to any distribution. Both were addressed in the Deloitte Report and commented upon by Justice Turnbull.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Way Affidavit, RMR, Volume 1, Tab A, page 102, paragraph 366</P>
<P>Way Affidavit, RMR, Volume 9, Tab 126, Exhibit &ldquo;126&rdquo;</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>E.</N><TI>The Triumph Costs Dispute</TI>
<P><BOLD>98.</BOLD> As stated above, the Receiver conducted a claims procedure. Both Way and Schembri consented to the claims procedure and caused substantial claims to be filed. The Receiver reviewed the claims filed, made certain determinations and reported on these activities to the Court. The Court approved the activities of the Receiver, without exception. The Receiver allowed various third party claims and paid them in full, on consent of Way and Schembri and with the approval of the court.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Way Affidavit, RMR, Volume 1, Tab A, page 103, paragraphs 369 to 371</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P><BOLD>99.</BOLD> Subsequently, Schembri sought to amend the Amended Statement of Claim in the Main Action to allege fraud in respect of claims Way caused to be filed with the Receiver for &ldquo;unauthorized and unapproved services&rdquo; as asserted in paragraph 86A (a), (b) and (c) of the Amended Amended Statement of Claim. Only Premier provided services; whereas &lsquo;Kingsley Financial&rsquo; and &lsquo;1725030 Ont.&rsquo; provided funds. This was addressed in the Deloitte Report.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Way Affidavit, RMR, Volume 1, Tab A, page 103, paragraphs 372 and 373</P>
<P>Way Affidavit, RMR, Volume 2, Tab 23, Exhibit &ldquo;23&rdquo; (at pages 461 to 464)</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>G.</N><TI>The ROFR Dispute</TI>
<P><BOLD>100.</BOLD> Way never told Schembri that he had no interest in the acquisition or development of student housing in Waterloo region. The JV Project was student housing. Way and Schembri planned to develop both the Oshawa Lands and London Lands as student housing.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Way Affidavit, RMR, Volume 1, Tab A, page 104, paragraph 375</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P><BOLD>101.</BOLD> Schembri is not an employee of Triumph; he is a director and officer. As such, Schembri owes fiduciary duties to Triumph and his fellow director and officer, Way. Schembri also has a contractual obligation to KFI pursuant to the ROFR Clause.</P>
<P><BOLD>102.</BOLD> Schembri admits that he did not comply with the ROFR Clause when he acquired twenty-six properties in the Regional Municipality of Waterloo that he has since developed. There are likely more properties that Schembri has acquired.</P>
<P><BOLD>103.</BOLD> It is clear that Schembri has breached his: (a) fiduciary duties to Triumph; (b) fiduciary duties to Way; and (c) contractual duty to KFI.</P>
<P><BOLD>104.</BOLD> It is essential to note that Schembri breaches of his duties above both preceded the Main Action and continued for at least four more years, while he reaped the financial benefits and Way laboured under the financial burden of having millions of dollars in capital stranded in the receivership proceedings.</P></BLOCK3></BLOCK2></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="III">PART III&mdash;STATEMENT OF ISSUES, LAW &amp; AUTHORITIES</TI>
<P><BOLD>Issue 1: Does Schembri owe a duty to Triumph?</BOLD></P>
<P><BOLD>Issue 2: What is the impact of the ROFR Clause in the Shareholder Agreement on Schembri's duty to Triumph?</BOLD></P>
<P><BOLD>Issue 3: What is the applicable test on this motion?</BOLD></P>
<P><BOLD>Issue 4: What is the impact of Schembri's conduct, including his breaches of the Rules of Civil Procedure, on this motion?</BOLD></P>
<BLOCK2><N>1.</N><TI>Fiduciary Duty of a Director</TI>
<P><BOLD>105.</BOLD> As stated in paragraphs 26(a), and 29(b) and (c) above, Schembri is an officer and director of Triumph and each of its' three subsidiaries. As stated in paragraph 24(a) above, Schembri, through Schembri Financial Limited, is a forty-five percent (45%) shareholder of Triumph, which itself is the sole shareholder of the three subsidiaries.</P>
<P><BOLD>106.</BOLD> The fiduciary duty of a director and officer to a corporation arises from statute and common law. Section 134(1) of the Ontario <EM>Business Corporations Act</EM> provides that:
<QUOTE><P>Every director and officer of a corporation in exercising his or her powers and discharging his or her duties shall,</P>
<P>(a) act honestly and in good faith with a view to the best interests of the corporation; and</P>
<P>(b) exercise the care, diligence and skill that a reasonably prudent person would exercise in comparable circumstances.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Business Corporations Act</EM>, R.S.O. 1990, c. B.16, as amended, s. 134(1)</P>
<P><CASEREF><SOC>Peoples Department Stores Inc. (Trustee of) v. Wise</SOC><CITE>2004 SCC 68</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>[2004] 3 SCR 461</CITE></CORRELAT></CASEREF> [Peoples].</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></QUOTE></P>
<P><BOLD>107.</BOLD> As stated by the SCC in <CASEREF><SOC>Peoples Department Stores Inc. (Trustee of) v. Wise</SOC></CASEREF><FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Peoples</EM>, <EM>supra</EM>, at para 35</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE>,
<QUOTE><P>&ldquo;The statutory fiduciary duty requires directors and officers to act honestly and in good faith vis-&ag;-vis the corporation. They must respect the trust and confidence that have been reposed in them to manage the assets of the corporation in pursuit of the realization of the objects of the corporation. They must avoid conflicts of interest with the corporation. They must avoid abusing their position to gain personal benefit. They must maintain the confidentiality of information they acquire by virtue of their position. Directors and officers must serve the corporation selflessly, honestly and loyally see K. P. McGuinness, The Law and Practice of Canadian Business Corporations (1999), at p. 715.</P></QUOTE></P>
<P><BOLD>108.</BOLD> A director's fiduciary obligation to the corporation obliges that director to avoid both actual and potential conflicts of interest<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Korz v. St. Pierre</SOC><YEAR>1987</YEAR><CITE>61 O.R. (2d) 609</CITE><COURTJUR>Ont. C.A.</COURTJUR></CASEREF>; leave to appeal refused (1988), 62 O.R. (2d) ix (note) (S.C.C.)</P>
<P>Ellis, Fiduciary Duties in Canada (1988)</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE>; and specifically &ldquo;precludes the diversion of any of the company's business opportunities either to the fiduciary personally or to another business&rdquo;.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Giionna v. Stiller</SOC><CITE>2015 ONSC 243</CITE><PARANUM>77</PARANUM></CASEREF></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P><BOLD>109.</BOLD> The fiduciary obligation of a director is applied strictly.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Canadian Aero Service Ltd. v. O'Malley</SOC><CITE>1972 Carswell Ont 236</CITE><COURTJUR>S.C.C.</COURTJUR></CASEREF> at p 607</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><N>2.</N><TI>Impact of the ROFR Clause on Schembri's Fiduciary Duty</TI>
<P><BOLD>110.</BOLD> A party may define the scope of their fiduciary obligation by contract.</P>
<P><BOLD>111.</BOLD> As stated by Lederman J. in <CASEREF><SOC>Audience Communication v. Sguassero</SOC></CASEREF>, the &ldquo;scrutiny that the common law applies to non-competition clauses depends in large measure on the nature of the contract in which the clause is found&rdquo;.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Audience Communication inc. v. Sguassero</SOC><CITE>2008 CanLII 17303</CITE><COURTJUR>ONSC</COURTJUR></CASEREF> at para 31</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P><BOLD>112.</BOLD> The contract in issue in the ROFR Action (namely, the Shareholder Agreement) is a unanimous shareholder agreement.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Business Corporations Act</EM>, R.S.O. 1990, c. B.16, as amended, ss. 1 and 108(2)</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> It is neither an employment agreement, nor an agreement for the sale of assets; being the nature of the contracts found in the authorities relied upon by the Schembri Group.</P>
<P><BOLD>113.</BOLD> Section 134(2) of the Ontario <EM>Business Corporations Act</EM> provides that:
<QUOTE><P><BOLD><EM>Every director and officer of a corporation shall comply with</EM></BOLD> this Act, the regulations, articles, by-laws and <BOLD><EM>any unanimous shareholder agreement</EM></BOLD>. [emphasis added]</P></QUOTE></P>
<P><BOLD>114.</BOLD> The Way Group has not been able to find much authority analyzing s. 134(2) of the OBCA. One authority the Way Group did find, stated simply that <EM>&ldquo;the directors were required by s.134(2) of the OBCA to comply with&rdquo;</EM> the unanimous shareholder agreement.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Fiorillo v. Krispy Kreme Doughnuts Inc.</SOC><CITE>2009 Carswell Ont 3344</CITE><PARANUM>161</PARANUM></CASEREF></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> The Way Group submits that the absence of authority on section 134(2) suggests that disputes involving the duty of a director vis a vis a unanimous shareholder agreement are not litigated on that issue.</P>
<P><BOLD>115.</BOLD> That said, non-competition clauses (i.e the ROFR Clause) may encode a party's fiduciary obligation such that a breach of that clause necessarily implies breach of fiduciary duty.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Reservoir Group Partnership v. 1304613 Ontario Ltd.</SOC><YEAR>2007</YEAR><PARANUM>65</PARANUM></CASEREF></P>
<P><CASEREF><SOC>Norbar Insurance Agencies Inc. v. Freeman</SOC><CITE>[2005] O.J. No. 3704</CITE><COURTJUR>Ont. S.C.J.</COURTJUR></CASEREF></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P><BOLD>116.</BOLD> As stated in paragraph 27 above, Schembri agreed in the Shareholder Agreement (that confirmed his appointment as a director and officer of Triumph) to present to Triumph all real estate development opportunities which he may have acquired within the Regional Municipality of Waterloo. Schembri admits he did not present to Triumph twenty-six properties in the Regional Municipality of Waterloo that he acquired and developed.</P>
<P><BOLD>117.</BOLD> It is clear that Schembri breached his fiduciary duties to Triumph repeatedly over many years by:
<P1>(a) committing a ROFR Breach in March, 2009 (as detailed in paragraph 48 above);</P1>
<P1>(b) failing to disclose his interest in the Taylorwood Property at the Director's Meeting held on April 12, 2010 (as detailed in paragraph 53 above);</P1>
<P1>(c) committing a ROFR Breach in April, 2010 (as detailed in paragraph 55 above);</P1>
<P1>(d) refusing to contribute (as detailed in paragraphs 56 and 57 above);</P1>
<P1>(e) blocking arbitration in July, 2010 (as detailed in paragraph 58 above);</P1>
<P1>(f) filing improper claims in the receivership proceedings in March, 2011 (as detailed in paragraphs 59 to 66 above);</P1>
<P1>(g) committing a ROFR Breach in August, 2011 (as detailed in paragraph 68 above);</P1>
<P1>(h) committing a ROFR Breach in September, 2011 (as detailed in paragraph 69 above);</P1>
<P1>(i) committing a ROFR Breach in May, 2012 (as detailed in paragraph 74(a) above);</P1>
<P1>(j) committing numerous ROFR Breaches between February and May, 2013 (as detail ed in paragraph 74(b) above); and</P1>
<P1>(k) committing a ROFR Breach in May, 2014 (as detailed in paragraph 74(b) above).</P1></P>
<P><BOLD>118.</BOLD> It is also clear that Schembri's breaches of his fiduciary duties to Triumph in subparagraphs (a), (b), and (g) to (k) above are also breaches of his contractual obligation to KFI pursuant to the ROFR Clause.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><N>3.</N><TI>The Applicable Test on the Motion</TI>
<P><BOLD>119.</BOLD> Rule 20.01(3) provides that:
<QUOTE><P><EM>A defendant may, after delivering a statement of defence, move with supporting affidavit material or other evidence for summary judgment dismissing all or part of the claim in the statement of claim</EM>.</P></QUOTE></P>
<P><BOLD>120.</BOLD> The defendant, 176 5998 Ontario Inc. has not delivered a statement of defence.</P>
<P><BOLD>121.</BOLD> Rule 20.04(2) provides that:
<QUOTE><P><EM>The court shall grant summary judgment if</EM>,</P>
<P><EM>(a) the court is satisfied that there is no genuine issue requiring a trial with respect to a claim or defence; or</EM></P>
<P><EM>(b) the parties agree to have all or part of the claim determined by a summary judgment and the court is satisfied that it is appropriate to grant summary judgment</EM>.</P></QUOTE></P>
<P><BOLD>122.</BOLD> The parties have not agreed to have all or part of the ROFR Action determined by summary judgment.</P>
<P><BOLD>123.</BOLD> The Supreme Court of Canada in <CASEREF><SOC>Hryniak v. Mauldin</SOC></CASEREF> concluded that &ldquo;summary judgment rules must be interpreted broadly, favouring proportionality and fair access to the affordable, timely and just adjudication of claims.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Hryniak v. Mauldin</SOC><CITE>[2014] 1 S.C.R. 87</CITE><COURTJUR>SCC</COURTJUR></CASEREF> at para 5</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P><BOLD>124.</BOLD> &ldquo;While the Supreme Court of Canada's decision in <CASEREF><SOC>Hryniak v. Mauldin</SOC><CITE>[2014] 1 S.C.R. 87</CITE><COURTJUR>SCC</COURTJUR></CASEREF>, was certainly meant to mark a culture shift in relation to the use of motions for summary judgement as an efficient and cost effective tool for addressing the merits of civil claims, the Court of Appeal for Ontario has noted on a number of occasions since the decision in <EM>Hryniak</EM> that motions for partial summary judgement can defeat these objectives and are inappropriate in many cases: <CASEREF><SOC>Baywood Homes Partnership v. Haditaghi</SOC><CITE>2014 ONCA 450</CITE><COURTJUR>Ont. C.A.</COURTJUR></CASEREF>; <CASEREF><SOC>Canadian Imperial Bank of Commerce v. Deloitte &amp; Touche</SOC><CITE>2016 ONCA 922</CITE><COURTJUR>Ont. C.A.</COURTJUR></CASEREF>; and <CASEREF><SOC>Butera v. Chown, Cairns LLP</SOC><CITE>2017 ONCA 783</CITE><COURTJUR>Ont. C.A.</COURTJUR></CASEREF>.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Espresso Tax Credit Fund III Partnership v. Arc Stainless Inc.</SOC><CITE>2014 ONSC 415</CITE><PARANUM>38</PARANUM></CASEREF></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P><BOLD>125.</BOLD> As stated in paragraphs 14 and 15 above, this motion seeks to dispose of only one of the seven disputes between Way and Schembri.</P>
<P><BOLD>126.</BOLD> The Court of Appeal for Ontario has been clear that summary judgment is an inappropriate procedure to dispose of this single dispute<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Butera v. Chown, Cairns LLP</SOC><CITE>2017 ONCA 783</CITE><COURTJUR>Ont C.A.</COURTJUR></CASEREF></P>
<P><CASEREF><SOC>Canadian Imperial Bank of Commerce v. Deloitte &amp; Touche</SOC><CITE>2016 ONCA 922</CITE><COURTJUR>Ont. C.A.</COURTJUR></CASEREF></P>
<P><CASEREF><SOC>Baywood Homes Partnership v. Haditaghi</SOC><CITE>2014 ONCA 450</CITE><COURTJUR>Ont. C.A.</COURTJUR></CASEREF></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> as:
<P1>(a) it causes the resolution of the Main Action to be delayed;</P1>
<P1>(b) it is very expensive;</P1>
<P1>(c) judges are required to spend time hearing the motion and writing comprehensive reasons that do not dispose of all of the issues in the litigation; and</P1>
<P1>(d) the record available to the motion judge will not be as expansive as the record at trial, therefore increasing the danger of inconsistent findings.</P1></P>
<P><BOLD>127.</BOLD> Additionally, the Court of Appeal for Ontario has stated that a &ldquo;summary judgment motion judge commits an error in principle when he or she fails to assess the advisability of the summary judgment process in the context of the litigation as a whole.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Hamilton (City) v. Their + Curran Architects Inc.</SOC><CITE>2015 ONCA 64</CITE><PARANUM>22</PARANUM></CASEREF></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P><BOLD>128.</BOLD> <EM>Hryniak</EM> itself noted that a <EM>&ldquo;motion for summary judgment will not always be the most proportionate way to dispose of an action&rdquo;</EM>.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Hyrniak</EM>, <EM>supra</EM>, at para 73</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><N>4.</N><TI>Schembri's Scorched Earth Litigation Tactics and Breach of the Rules of Civil Procedure</TI>
<P><BOLD>129.</BOLD> Schembri has engaged in the following scorched earth litigation tactics;
<P1>(a) blocking arbitration in July, 2010 by failing to swear the affidavit referred to in the Notice of Motion that was served but never filed (as detailed in paragraph 58 above);</P1>
<P1>(b) filing fraudulent and improper claims in the receivership proceedings in March, 2011 (as detailed in paragraph 61 above);</P1>
<P1>(c) objecting to the fees of the Receiver (as detailed in paragraphs 70 and 71 above);</P1>
<P1>(d) blocking payment to CRA (as detailed in paragraphs 72 and 73 above); and</P1>
<P1>(e) the 2014 Schembri ROFR SJ Motion (as detailed in paragraphs 76 to 80 above).</P1></P>
<P><BOLD>130.</BOLD> Regarding the 2014 Schembri ROFR SJ Motion, Schembri never explained his deception, nor sought any amendments to the ROFR Timetable Order. Instead, Schembri carried on as if:
<P1>(a) he never represented repeatedly that he was bringing the 2014 Schembri ROFR SJ Motion;</P1>
<P1>(b) there was no schedule for the 2014 Schembri ROFR SJ Motion in the ROFR Timetable Order;</P1>
<P1>(c) it is just a game to represent repeatedly that a motion for summary judgment is being brought to dismiss a claim seeking damages in the amount of $30 million dollars; and</P1>
<P1>(d) he is above the Rules of Civil Procedure and orders of this Honourable Court.</P1></P>
<P><BOLD>131.</BOLD> Schembri has breached the following Rules of Civil Procedure:
<P1>(a) Rule 30.02(1) which requires Schembri to disclose &ldquo;[e]very document relevant to any matter in issue in an action that is or has been in [his] possession, control or power&rdquo;;</P1>
<P1><BOLD>(b) Rule 30.07(b) which requires, after serving the ROFR AoD, discovers that it is inaccurate or incomplete must &ldquo;forthwith serve a supplementary affidavit specifying the extent to which the affidavit of documents requires modification and disclosing additional docuents;</BOLD></P1>
<P1>(c) Rule 31.06(1) which requires Schembri to &ldquo;answer, to the best of his...knowledge, information and belief, any proper question relevant to any matter in issue in the action&rdquo;; and</P1>
<P1>(d) Rule 31.07(1)(c) which requires Schembri to provide an answer to an undertaking within 60 days.</P1></P>
<P><BOLD>132.</BOLD> As a consequence of Schembri's breaches of the Rules of Civil Procedure, this Honurable Court has the authority to make such order as is just.</P>
<P><BOLD>133.</BOLD> The Way Group submits that it is just for this Honourable Court to make an order:
<P1>(a) declaring that the defendant, Schembri Financial Limited <BOLD>(&ldquo;Schembri Financial&rdquo;)</BOLD> is in breach of the Contribution Clause;</P1>
<P1>(b) declaring that Schembri Financial and Schembri are in breach of the ROFR Clause;</P1>
<P1>(c) declaring that Schembri Financial and Schembri are in breach of the Arbitration Clause;</P1>
<P1>(d) authorizing and directing that the KPMG Portal be closed immediately;</P1>
<P1>(e) requiring Schembri to serve a further and better affidavit of documents in the Main Action and in ROFR Action;</P1>
<P1>(f) requiring the corporate defendants in the ROFR Action to serve an affidavit of documents in the ROFR Action.</P1></P>
<P><BOLD>134.</BOLD> The Way Group provided notice to the Schembri Group of its intention to seek the foregoing relief in March, 2018. It was not an attempt to &ldquo;hijack&rdquo; the Schembri Group's belated motion for summary judgment; rather, it simply seeks to achieve the most <EM>&ldquo;affordable, timely and just adjudication of&rdquo;</EM> the ROFR Action as espoused by the Supreme Court of Canada.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Hyrniak</EM>, <EM>supra</EM>, at para 5</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></BLOCK2></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="IV">PART IV&mdash;ORDER REQUESTED</TI>
<P><BOLD>135.</BOLD> Way therefore requests an order:
<P1>(a) dismissing the motion of the Schembri Group for summary judgment;</P1>
<P1>(b) declaring that Schembri Financial is in breach of the Contribution Clause;</P1>
<P1>(c) declaring that Schembri Financial and Schembri are in breach of the ROFR Clause;</P1>
<P1>(d) declaring that Schembri Financial and Schembri are in breach of the Arbitration Clause;</P1>
<P1>(e) authorizing and directing that the KPMG Portal be closed immediately;</P1>
<P1>(f) requiring Schembri to serve a further and better affidavit of documents in the Main Action and in ROFR Action;</P1>
<P1>(g) requiring the corporate defendants in the ROFR Action to serve an affidavit of documents;</P1>
<P1>(h) for costs of the motion of the Schembri Group for summary judgment on a substantial indemnity basis payable forthwith; and</P1>
<P1>(i) such other relief as this Honourable Court deems just.</P1></P>
<P><BOLD>ALL OF WHICH IS RESPECTFULLY SUBMITTED</BOLD> this 17<SUP>th</SUP> day of October, 2018.</P>
