<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="III">PART III&mdash;STATEMENT OF ISSUES, LAW &amp; AUTHORITIES</TI>
<P><BOLD>Issue 1: What are the consequences of the Withdrawn Fraud Allegations and the Abandoned Fallback Position?</BOLD></P>
<P><BOLD>Issue 2: Is the ROFR Clause invalid and unenforceable as asserted by Schembri?</BOLD></P>
<BLOCK2><TI>The Consequences of the Withdrawn Fraud Allegations and the Abandoned Fallback Position</TI>
<P><BOLD>15.</BOLD> Rule 20.06 provides that:
<QUOTE><P><EM>The court may fix and order payment of the costs of a motion for summary judgment by a party on a substantial indemnity basis if</EM>,</P>
<P><EM>(a) the party acted unreasonably by making or responding to the motion; or</EM></P>
<P><EM>(b) the party acted in bad faith for the purpose of delay</EM>.</P></QUOTE></P>
<P><BOLD>16.</BOLD> It is plain and obvious that Schembri made a calculated decision to allege fraud by Way in:
<P1>(a) the Notice of Motion dated May 11, 2017 (as detailed in paragraph 4 above);</P1>
<P1>(b) his affidavit sworn May 17, 2017 (as detailed in paragraph 5 above);</P1>
<P1>(c) his affidavit sworn April 5, 2018 (as detailed in paragraph 7 above);</P1>
<P1>(d) the position taken at his cross-examination on September 17, 2018 (as detailed in paragraph 8 above); and</P1>
<P1>(e) the Schembri Factum dated October 9, 2018 (as detailed in paragraph 9 above);</P1>
in an effort to smear Way, thereby distracting this Honourable Court from Schembri's own wrongful conduct. This is not surprising as Schembri has failed to comply with his disclosure obligations under the Rules of Civil Procedure, and is attempting to avoid liability for his repeated breaches of his fiduciary duty estimated at $30 million.</P>
<P><BOLD>17.</BOLD> It is trite law that the Withdrawn Fraud Allegations may attract an award of substantial indemnity costs<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Future Health Inc. v. General Accident Assurance et al</SOC><CITE>2016 ONSC 4834</CITE><PARANUM>9</PARANUM></CASEREF></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE>; and such &ldquo;<EM>allegations have been found to be prejudicial to characters or reputations of those to whom they are directed and to attract a higher scale of costs</EM>&rdquo;.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Hawkins v. Hawkins Estate</SOC><CITE>2015 ONSC 1106</CITE><PARANUM>15</PARANUM></CASEREF></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P><BOLD>18.</BOLD> In <CASEREF><SOC>1312217 Ontario Ltd v. Atrens</SOC></CASEREF>, the Court found the defendant entitled to costs on a substantial indemnity basis as a result of the Plaintiff discontinuing allegations of conspiracy, but leaving the rest of the claim intact. Justice Kiteley wrote: <EM>&ldquo;For over four years, [the Defendant] was confronted with those serious allegations</EM>. <BOLD><EM>Equally serious cost consequences ought to befall litigants who make such allegations</EM>.</BOLD>&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>1312217 Ontario Ltd v. Atrens</SOC><CITE>2004 CanLii 11363</CITE><COURTJUR>ON SC</COURTJUR></CASEREF> at para 30</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> [emphasis added]</P>
<P><BOLD>19.</BOLD> In <CASEREF><SOC>Re Cogan</SOC></CASEREF>, the Court wrote:
<QUOTE><P><EM>In summary, a major financial institution has alleged fraud against a solicitor and when the solicitor responded vigorously to defend his reputation, the proceedings (but not the allegations) were abandoned</EM>, <BOLD><EM>thereby depriving the solicitor of the opportunity of obtaining any adjudication or vindication. This course of action is unacceptable and is to be condemned</EM>.</BOLD><FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Re Cogan</SOC><CITE>2005 CarswellOnt 79</CITE><PARANUM>8</PARANUM></CASEREF></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> [emphasis added]</P></QUOTE></P>
<P><BOLD>20.</BOLD> The Way Group submits that imposing serious costs consequences on Schembri for the Withdrawn Fraud Allegations and the Abandoned Fallback Position is inadequate condemnation of Schembri's unacceptable course of action.</P>
<P><BOLD>21.</BOLD> The Way Group submits further that the only adequate condemnation of Schembri's unacceptable course of action (in alleging fraud and advancing that allegation until responding oral submissions) is to dismiss Schembri's motion, so that the Main Action and the ROFR Action may proceed to be tried together (in accordance with the Order of Justice Broad dated September 4, 2014) and afford Way the opportunity to obtain vindication.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI>The ROFR Clause is valid and enforceable</TI>
<P><BOLD>22.</BOLD> The Way Group reiterates their position that the ROFR Clause is valid and enforceable.</P>
<P><BOLD>23.</BOLD> The ROFR Clause is valid and enforceable as it merely makes clear that Schembri's statutory fiduciary duty (and that of Schembri Financial, a company he controls and is a 45% shareholder of Triumph) to <EM>&ldquo;act honestly and in good faith with a view to the best interests of [Triumph]&rdquo;</EM> includes presenting to Triumph (and KFI, the 55% shareholder of Triumph) all real estate development opportunities which he (through Schembri Financial or otherwise) may have acquired within the Regional Municipality of Waterloo.</P>
<P><BOLD>24.</BOLD> It is not in dispute that Schembri complied initially with his statutory fiduciary duty in this regard. However, Schembri subsequently wilfully breached this fiduciary duty in March, 2009; almost one year before he commenced the Main Action.</P>
<P><BOLD>25.</BOLD> The Way Group submits that the ROFR Clause is not a restrictive covenant<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>British Columbia Forest Products Limited v. Gay et ux.</SOC><CITE>1978 CarswellBC 116</CITE></CASEREF></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE>, and therefore the analysis and case law presented by Schembri is inapplicable.</P>
<P><BOLD>26.</BOLD> It is trite law that an alleged restrictive covenant is assessed using a four-stage inquiry as follows:
<P1>(a) Stage One&mdash;is the covenant under review in restraint of trade?;</P1>
<P1>(b) Stage Two&mdash;is the restraint one which is against public policy and, therefore, void?;</P1>
<P1>(c) Stage Three&mdash;can the restraint be justified as reasonable in the interest of the parties?; and</P1>
<P1>(d) Stage Four&mdash;can it be justified as reasonable with reference to the interests of the public?<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Tank Lining Corp. v. Dunlop Industries Ltd.</SOC><CITE>1982 CarswellOnt 780</CITE><PARANUM>13</PARANUM></CASEREF></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P1></P>
<P><BOLD>27.</BOLD> The standard of the assessment to be applied differs according to the contract at issue and the relative bargaining power of the parties to that contract. More specifically, the common law distinguishes between non-competition clauses found in employment agreements and those found elsewhere.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI>Stage One</TI>
<P><BOLD>28.</BOLD> The generally accepted definition of restraint on trade is as follows:
<QUOTE><P><EM>A contract in restraint of trade is one in which a party (the covenantor) agrees with any other party (the covenantee) to restrict his liberty in the future to carry on trade with other persons not parties to the contract in such a manner as he chooses</EM>.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Petrofina (Great Britain) Ltd. v. Martin</SOC><CITE>[1966] Ch. 146</CITE><PAGENUM>at p 180</PAGENUM></CASEREF> cited in <CASEREF><SOC>Stephens v. Gulf Oil Canada Ltd.</SOC><CITE>1975 CarswellOnt 809</CITE><PARANUM>24</PARANUM></CASEREF></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></QUOTE></P>
<P><BOLD>29.</BOLD> The ROFR Clause does not restrict Schembri (or Schembri Financial) from carrying on trade with other persons not a party to the Shareholder Agreement in such a manner as he chooses; rather, it imposes on Schembri (and Schembri Financial) a specific fiduciary duty to present real estate development opportunities in the Regional Municipality of Waterloo to Triumph (and KFI). The result being that Schembri (directly or indirectly) will have either:
<P1>(a) a 45% interest in the real estate development opportunity if Triumph (or KFI) indicates in writing within 15 days that it is taking on the real estate development opportunity; or</P1>
<P1>(b) a 100% interest in the real estate development opportunity if Triumph (and KFI) does not indicate in writing within 15 days that it is taking on the real estate development opportunity.</P1></P>
<P>Neither (a) nor (b) affects other persons not a party to the Shareholder Agreement.</P>
<P><BOLD>30.</BOLD> The Way Group submits that it is disingenuous and improper for Schembri, as a director and officer of Triumph, to assert that:
<P1>(a) he ought to be able to acquire a real estate development opportunity in the Regional Municipality of Waterloo;</P1>
<P1>(b) present it to Triumph (and KFI) as required by the ROFR Clause; and then</P1>
<P1>(c) subvert the ROFR Clause, and his fiduciary duty, by withholding his consent for Triumph to indicate in writing within 15 days that Triumph is taking on the real estate development opportunity.</P1></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI>Stage Two</TI>
<P><BOLD>31.</BOLD> The second stage of the inquiry assesses whether the restraint is against public policy as <EM>&ldquo;not every restraint of trade is void&rdquo;</EM>.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Tank Lining Corp. v. Dunlop Industries Ltd.</SOC></CASEREF>, <EM>supra</EM> at para 13</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P><BOLD>32.</BOLD> The Way Group submits that public policy has been expressed insections 1(1), 108(2), 115(1) and 134(1) and (2) of the <EM>Business Corporations Act</EM>. As a result, even if the ROFR Clause is found to be in restraint of trade, it is not against public policy; and, therefore, continues to be valid and enforceable.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI>Stages Three and Four</TI>
<P><BOLD>33.</BOLD> Only if the ROFR Clause is found to be a restrictive covenant (Stage 1) that is void against public policy (Stage 2), does the court then assess whether the ROFR Clause is justified as reasonable in the interests of:
<P1>(a) Way and Schembri, and their companies, KFI and Schembri Financial (Stage Three); and</P1>
<P1>(b) public policy (Stage Four).</P1></P>
<P><BOLD>34.</BOLD> Often stages three and four are considered together.</P>
<P><BOLD>35.</BOLD> It is at stage three that the court considers:
<P1>(a) geographic coverage (i.e. spatial)</P1>
<P1>(b) duration (i.e. temporal); and</P1>
<P1>(c) extent of activity (i.e. scope).</P1></P>
<P><BOLD>36.</BOLD> Regarding geographic coverage, it is limited to the Regional Municipality of Waterloo.</P>
<P><BOLD>37.</BOLD> The &ldquo;Regional Municipality of Waterloo&rdquo; imposes clearly defined geographic limits that are set out in the <EM>Regional Municipality of Waterloo Act</EM> (the <BOLD>&ldquo;Act&rdquo;</BOLD>). Those geographic limits include:
<P1>(a) the City of Cambridge;</P1>
<P1>(b) the City of Kitchener;</P1>
<P1>(c) the City of Waterloo;</P1>
<P1>(d) the Township of North Dumfries;</P1>
<P1>(e) the Township of Wellesley;</P1>
<P1>(f) the Township of Wilmot; and</P1>
<P1>(g) the Township of Woolwich.</P1></P>
<P><BOLD>38.</BOLD> The properties that are the subject matter of the ROFR Action are located in: (a) the City of Kitchener (i.e. 5 Rittenhouse); and (b) the City of Waterloo (i.e. 61 Columbia, 41 Columbia, 1 Columbia, 69 Columbia and 274 Larch). There is no ambiguity that these properties are within the Region of Waterloo, and the geographic limits overseen by the Regional Municipality of Waterloo in accordance with the Act.</P>
<P><BOLD>39.</BOLD> Regarding duration, a distinction must be made between S [Missing text] Schembri.</P>
<P><BOLD>40.</BOLD> The ROFR Clause requires Schembri Financial:
<QUOTE><P><EM>&ldquo;to present to [KFI] and [Triumph] all real estate development opportunities (the &ldquo;Project&rdquo;) which it may have acquired within the Regional Municipality of Waterloo&rdquo; ... &ldquo;during the period which [Schembri Financial] is a shareholder of [Triumph]</EM>.</P></QUOTE></P>
<P><BOLD>41.</BOLD> Based on the evidence before the court on this motion, Schembri Financial has not acquired any real estate development opportunities within the Regional Municipality of Waterloo. Regardless, if Schembri Financial wishes to be relieved of its' obligation to present real estate development opportunities it should take steps to cease being a shareholder of Triumph. Instead of doing so, Schembri Financial is taking steps in the Main Action to increase its' shareholding interest in Triumph from 45% to 55%.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Compendium of the Defendants, Amended Amended Statement of Claim, Tab E, page 495, subparagraph (k)</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P><BOLD>42.</BOLD> Based on the evidence before the court on this motion, Schembri has acquired many real estate development opportunities within the Regional Municipality of Waterloo, through other companies he controls<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Motion Record, Schembri May, 2017 Affidavit, Tab 2, page 12, paragraph 2</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE>. If Schembri wishes to be relieved of his fiduciary obligation to Triumph he should resign as an officer and director. Schembri has elected not to resign, and, as a result, he continues to owe a fiduciary duty to Triumph as mandated by the <EM>Business Corporations Act</EM> and specified by the ROFR Clause.</P>
<P><BOLD>43.</BOLD> Regarding extent of activity, the ROFR Clause requires Schembri Financial and Schembri:
<QUOTE><P><EM>to present to [KFI] and [Triumph] all real estate development opportunities (the &ldquo;Project&rdquo;) which it may have acquired within the Regional Municipality of Waterloo</EM><BOLD><EM>...[KFI] and [Triumph] shall have FIFTEEN (15) days following the presentation of the Project to them to determine if it is economically feasible using the typical budget model consistently utilized by them in such circumstances</EM>...</BOLD></P></QUOTE></P>
<P><BOLD>44.</BOLD> It is clear that the activity is:
<P1>(a) restricted to real estate development opportunities; and</P1>
<P1>(b) such opportunities are to be assessed <EM>&ldquo;using the typical budget model consistently utilized by them in such circumstances&rdquo;</EM>.</P1></P>
<P><BOLD>45.</BOLD> Way and Schembri had a typical budget model that they used to determine economic feasibility of, among other opportunities, the Waterloo Lands, the London Lands and the Oshawa Lands<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Affidavit of Alven J. Way sworn March 16, 2018 (the <BOLD>&ldquo;Way Affidavit&rdquo;),</BOLD> Responding Motion Record <BOLD>(&ldquo;RMR&rdquo;),</BOLD> Volume 1, Tab A, pages 33 and 34, paragraph 113</P>
<P>Way Affidavit, RMR, Exhibit &ldquo;41&rdquo;, Volume 3, Tab 41, pages 705 to 717, and 728 to 746</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE>.</P>
<P><BOLD>46.</BOLD> More importantly, it hardly lies in Schembri's mouth to assert that a &ldquo;real estate opportunity&rdquo; that he had acquired was not &ldquo;economically feasible&rdquo;, after proceeding with multiple &ldquo;real estate opportunities]&rdquo; to the exclusion of Triumph (and KFI)<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Way Affidavit, RMR, Volume 1, pages 105 to 110, paragraphs 380 to 400</P>
<P>Way Affidavit, RMR, Exhibits &ldquo;142&rdquo; to &ldquo;154&rdquo;, Volume 10, Tabs 142 to 154</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE>. Doing so is simply another attempt by Schembri to subvert the ROFR Clause.</P>
<P><BOLD>47.</BOLD> Finally, it is clear from the independent evidence of Frank Volpini (obtained by Schembri under oath and submitted to the court on this motion) that the ROFR Clause is justified as reasonable in the interests of Way and Schembri, and their companies (KFI and Schembri Financial).</P>
<P><BOLD>48.</BOLD> Counsel for Schembri examined Mr. Volpini under oath in connection with Schembri's motion to compel Way to guarantee construction financing for the development of the Oshawa Lands (which motion Justice Mesbur dismissed and awarded costs to Way).<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Way Affidavit, RMR, Tab A, page 76, paragraphs 267 and 268</P>
<P>Way Affidavit, RMR, Tab 117, Exhibit &ldquo;117&rdquo;</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P><BOLD>49.</BOLD> During that examination, the following exchanged occurred<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Examination of Frank Volpini, Exhibit &ldquo;1&rdquo;, questions 44 to 47, and 49</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE>:
<QUOTE><P>[Mr. Wortzman] <EM>&ldquo;...you said 55/45 was because of their roles at the time and it was fair. What were the roles at the time that made the unequal shareholding split fair?&rdquo;</EM></P>
<P>&ellipsis;</P>
<P>[Mr. Volpini] <EM>&ldquo;It was presented in the following manner</EM>. <BOLD><EM>Mr. Schembri seemed to have a knack for finding and locating and tying down land for prospective projects, but presented as not having the financial wherewithal to see those projects through&rdquo;</EM>.</BOLD></P>
<P>&ellipsis;</P>
<P>[Mr. Volpini] <EM>&ldquo;On the other hand, Mr. Way had wealth of experience, both in construction and development and in addition to that was successful so that he had established a wide range of access to - to lending institutions for financing. And further had the financial wherewithal or asset backing to provide any guarantees that would be needed invariable for any kind of financing commitment</EM>. <BOLD><EM>So to reflect the fact that Mr. Way had more to bring to the table</EM>,</BOLD> <EM>at that time at least</EM>, <BOLD><EM>it was thought that the 55/45 split was fair&rdquo;</EM>.</BOLD></P>
<P>[Mr. Wortzman] <EM>&ldquo;All right. Thank you</EM>. <BOLD><EM>Do I take it that the idea then was that Mr. Schembri would continue in his role and you said his knack of finding, locating and assembling properties?&rdquo;</EM></BOLD></P>
<P>[Mr. Volpini] <BOLD><EM>&ldquo;Absolutely.&rdquo;</EM></BOLD></P>
<P>&ellipsis;</P>
<P>[Mr. Wortzman] <EM>&ldquo;All right. Let's go to number three&rdquo;</EM>.</P>
<P>[Mr. Volpini] <BOLD><EM>&ldquo;Gord required to not compete&mdash;all other projects to newco.&rdquo;</EM></BOLD> [emphasis added]</P></QUOTE></P>
<P><BOLD>50.</BOLD> In conclusion, even if the ROFR Clause is found to be a restrictive covenant (Stage 1) that is void against public policy (Stage 2), the ROFR Clause is justified as reasonable in the interests of:
<P1>(a) Way and Schembri, and their companies, KFI and Schembri Financial (Stage Three); and</P1>
<P1>(b) public policy (Stage Four).</P1></P></BLOCK2></BLOCK1>
