<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="I">PART I&mdash;INTRODUCTION</TI>
<P>1. This factum is being filed with leave of the Court in reply to the Supplementary Factum of Way dated October 31, 2018, wherein he takes the position that Section 134 of the <EM>Business Corporations Act (&ldquo;OBCA&rdquo;)</EM>, prevents Schembri from conducting business independent of Triumph Financial. There is no evidentiary or legal basis for this position. A full and careful reading of the Statement of Claim clearly indicates that Way's claim is grounded on an alleged breach of the Non-Competition Clause. Way's action therefore stands or falls on the enforceability of the Non-Competition Clause in the Shareholder Agreement. If the Non-Competition Clause is unenforceable, then the action fails.
<P1><BOLD><EM>Business Corporations Act</EM>, RSO 1990, c.B.16 (&ldquo;<EM>OBCA</EM>&rdquo;), Section 134; Schembri Affidavit sworn May 17, 2017, DMR, Tab 2, at para. 66. Compendium filed by the Defendant/Moving Party (&ldquo;Compendium&rdquo;) at Tab E, pg. 487&ndash;581.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>2. While Schembri acknowledges the duty imposed by Section 134, he has not breached it and there is no evidence to suggest he has. Accordingly, Way's &ldquo;new&rdquo; argument does not change the result. The Non-Competition Clause is unenforceable and the action ought to be dismissed.</P>
<P>3. In any event, Schembri is only an officer and director of Triumph. Way and Kingsley Financial can have no Section 134 claim. The question is, does Triumph Financial have a Section 134 claim? It does not.</P>
<P>4. Section 134 imposes a duty on a director to act honestly and in good faith. It does not restrict a director's ability to earn a living independent of his role as director. At common law a director cannot misappropriate a &ldquo;mature&rdquo; or &ldquo;ripe&rdquo; business opportunity of the corporation. Schembri did not do that and there is no evidence that any of the properties he acquired constituted a mature or ripe business opportunity of Triumph Financial. Even on this new theory the action fails.</P>
<BLOCK3><TI><UNDER>Way's filing of a Supplementary Factum</UNDER></TI>
<P>5. The entire &ldquo;law portion&rdquo; of Schembri's Factum (being paragraphs 51&ndash;149), related to the legal arguments regarding the enforceability of the Non-Competition Clause. Way's first Factum ignored these legal issues raised and these issues still remain, by and large, unaddressed.</P>
<P>6. Way submits that the Supplementary Factum was <EM>requested</EM> by the Honourable Justice Sloan in his email of October 22, 2018. This is incorrect. Justice Sloan only sought Mr. Whiteley's <UNDER>confirmation or correction</UNDER> with respect to the fact that Way's Original Factum did not address the Non-Competition Clause:
<QUOTE><P><EM>Would Mr. Whitely please confirm or correct the following</EM>.</P>
<P><EM>3&mdash;Way's factum does not appear to address the issues raised by Schembri in paragraph 2 above</EM>.</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>7. Justice Sloan was correct that Way's original Factum did not address Schembri's arguments as to why the Non-Competition Clause is unenforceable. Justice Sloan has subsequently granted leave and accepted delivery of Way's Supplementary Factum.</P>
<P>8. Way also submits that his Supplementary Factum is necessary as a result of Schembri's withdrawal of allegations of fraud. This is a misstatement of what occurred. Schembri did not withdraw such allegations, rather he advised the Court that he would not rely on his &ldquo;fallback&rdquo; legal argument that the Non-Competition Clause is unenforceable because of Way's repudiation of the Agreement by reason of his &ldquo;bad conduct&rdquo; (the &ldquo;Fallback Position&rdquo;). Schembri did this to ensure that the Motion could be heard in the 2 days allocated and agreed upon. The Fallback Position was addressed in a very minor fashion in Schembri's Factum (only 1 paragraph).</P>
<P>9. The allegations of fraud remain very much alive in the Main Action. To the extent that Mr. Whiteley wants to make submissions as to costs at the conclusion of the Motion, that does not require the delivery of a Supplementary Factum at this time.</P></BLOCK3></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="II">PART II&mdash;SUMMARY OF FACTS</TI>
<P>10. The only motion before This Honourable Court is Schembri's Motion seeking, <EM>inter alia</EM>, a declaration that the Non-Competition Clause is unenforceable and of no force and effect, and granting summary judgment as a result thereof.</P>
<P>11. Way has attempted to hijack the Motion by seeking various relief not contemplated by the Parties when this Motion was timetabled by the Court on February 8, 2018.
<P1><BOLD>Schembri Affidavit sworn April 5, 2018, RMR, Tab A, at paras 38&ndash;68, 111;</BOLD></P1>
<P1><BOLD>Schembri Affidavit sworn April 5, 2018, RMR, Tab A, at paras 6&ndash;11, Exhibit 1.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>12. Instead of responding to Schembri's Motion, Way decided to focus upon the relief that he had not properly sought from the Court. This is evident from:
<P1>a. Way's 10 volume, Responding Motion Record, which contains a 110 page, 404 paragraph affidavit, which appends 154 Exhibits, which does not address the enforceability of the Non-Competition Clause; and</P1>
<P1>b. Way's 63 page original Factum which does not respond to the Defendant's arguments.</P1></P>
<BLOCK3><TI><UNDER>The Commencement of the Motion and Reason for the Withdrawal of the Fallback Position</UNDER></TI>
<P>13. The Motion was to commence on October 18, 2018, at 10:00 a.m. Mr. Whiteley lost his car keys and was approximately 90 minutes late. Mr. Wortzman finished his oral argument in the one day that was allocated to him.</P>
<P>14. Mr. Whiteley's oral argument responded to the Fallback Position and little else.</P>
<P>15. Given that the time period for arguing the Motion (as agreed upon by the parties) was running out, and the disproportionate amount of time spent by Mr. Whiteley on the Fallback Position, Mr. Wortzman advised the Court that Schembri was prepared to withdraw the Fallback Position.</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI><UNDER>Schembri's Position at the Original Attendance</UNDER></TI>
<P>16. As was made clear to the Court at the return of the Motion and in written correspondence, it is Schembri's position that Way's ROFR Action stands or falls on the enforceability of the Non-Competition Clause and that the Non-Competition Clause is not valid or enforceable for the following seven reasons:
<P1>(a) It is contrary to public policy (paras. 51&ndash;55 of Schembri's Factum);</P1>
<P1>(b) Since it is ambiguous on its face and, Way cannot satisfy his onus of demonstrating the reasonableness of the clause in the face of such ambiguity (paras. 56-57 of Schembri's Factum);</P1>
<P1>(c) It is ambiguous in relation to geographical location, development opportunities acquired and the absence of a typical budget model (paras. 58&ndash;77 of Schembri's Factum);</P1>
<P1>(d) If the Court finds that the said Clause is not contrary to public policy and is not ambiguous, then it is unenforceable because it is merely an agreement to agree, (paras. 78&ndash;90 of Schembri's Factum);</P1>
<P1>(e) If the Court finds that the said Clause is not contrary to public policy, is not ambiguous, and is not merely not an agreement to agree, then the Clause is enforceable because it is unreasonable on its face with respect to geographic scope, temporal limits and activities prohibited (paras. 91&ndash;108 of Schembri's Factum);</P1>
<P1>(f) If the Court finds that the said Clause is not contrary to public interest, is not ambiguous, is not an agreement to agree, and is not unreasonable, then the Clause is unenforceable because it is not necessary to protect the legitimate business interests of Triumph Financial and Kingsley Financial (paras. 109&ndash;120 of Schembri's Factum); and</P1>
<P1>(g) From a practical point of view, the said Clause is unworkable and of no force or effect.</P1></P>
<P>17. None of these issues were addressed in Way's original Factum. Schembri will not re-visit those submissions herein.</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI><UNDER>Way's New Issue&mdash;Section 134</UNDER></TI>
<P>18. The within factum assumes that the Non-Competition Clause is unenforceable for the reasons stated in paragraph 16 herein. Accordingly, this Factum addresses Way's argument that even if the said Clause is unenforceable, Schembri is precluded from doing business (outside of the business contemplated by the Shareholder Agreement) as a result of a Section 134 statutory duty.</P>
<P>19. Way's position is not supported by the evidence or the law and is commercially unreasonable.</P>
<P>20. Way has no claim arising from the alleged breach of the Non-Competition Clause since he is not a party to it. Kingsley Financial (Schembri is not an officer or director of Kingsley Financial) and Way (who is not a corporation) can have no claim arising out of a breach of Section 134 as a matter of law. Therefore the only question is whether Triumph Financial has a claim grounded on the theory that Section 134 prohibited Schembri from conducting business independent of Triumph Financial.</P></BLOCK3></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="III">PART III&mdash;STATEMENT OF ISSUES, LAW &amp; AUTHORITIES</TI>
<P>21. This Reply Factum addresses the following issues raised in Way's Responding Factum:
<P1>a) Did Schembri breach any fiduciary duty owed to Triumph Financial?</P1>
<P1>b) What are the consequences (if any) of Schembri withdrawing his Fallback Position?</P1></P>
<BLOCK3><TI><UNDER>No Breach of Fiduciary Duty</UNDER></TI>
<P>22. A review of the jurisprudence with respect to a director's breach of the fiduciary duty owed to the corporation highlight various principles applicable to the relationship between Schembri and Triumph Financial. In summary a director cannot misappropriate a mature or ripe corporate opportunity without breaching his Section 134 duty:
<P1>(a) Directors of a corporation <EM>are precluded by their fiduciary duty from obtaining, for themselves, &ldquo;either secretly or without approval of the company, any property or business advantage</EM> <UNDER><EM>either belonging to the company or for which it has been negotiating</EM></UNDER>, <EM>and especially is this so where the director or officer is a participant in the negotiations on behalf of the company.&rdquo;;</EM>
<P2><CASEREF><SOC>Tracey v. Tracey</SOC><CITE>2012 ONSC 3144</CITE><PARANUM>55</PARANUM></CASEREF>, <BOLD>Defendant's Supplementary Book of Authorities (&ldquo;DSBA&rdquo;) at Tab 1;</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>Canadian Aero Services Limited v. O'Malley</SOC><CITE>[1974] SCR 592</CITE><PARANUM>24-25</PARANUM></CASEREF>, <BOLD>DSBA at Tab 2;</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>D'Elia Estate v. D'Elia</SOC><CITE>[2008] OJ No 5772</CITE><PARANUM>175</PARANUM></CASEREF> <BOLD>[emphasis added], DSBA at Tab 3.</BOLD></P2></P1>
<P1>(b) <EM>A director or senior officer is disqualified, &ldquo;from usurping for himself or diverting to another person or company with whom or with which he is associated a</EM> <UNDER><EM>maturing business opportunity which his company is actively pursuing</EM></UNDER>;
<P2><CASEREF><SOC>D'Elia Estate v. D'Elia</SOC><CITE>[2008] OJ No 5772</CITE><PARANUM>175</PARANUM></CASEREF>, <BOLD>DSBA at Tab 3;</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>Tracey v. Tracey</SOC><CITE>2012 ONSC 3144</CITE><PARANUM>55</PARANUM></CASEREF>, <BOLD>DSBA at Tab 1.</BOLD></P2></P1>
<P1>(c) A mere idea is not a business opportunity. It is a &ldquo;maturing&rdquo; or &ldquo;ripe&rdquo; business opportunity, immediately available to the corporation that constitutes a business advantage or opportunity that the fiduciary may not appropriate to himself;
<P2><CASEREF><SOC>Tracey v. Tracey</SOC><CITE>2012 ONSC 3144</CITE><PARANUM>56</PARANUM></CASEREF>, <BOLD>DSBA at Tab 1;</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>Donor Gateway Inc. v. Passero</SOC><CITE>2007 CanLII 3677</CITE><PARANUM>12</PARANUM></CASEREF>, <BOLD>DSBA at Tab 4.</BOLD></P2></P1>
<P1>(d) A &ldquo;ripe&rdquo; business opportunity has been described by the Court as follows:
<QUOTE><P><EM>By &ldquo;ripe&rdquo;, I understand the case law to mean that the opportunity available to the corporation is a prize ready for immediate grasping&mdash;not a general course of future conduct which is merely being explored</EM>.</P></QUOTE>
<P2><CASEREF><SOC>Pizza Pizza Ltd. v. Gillespie</SOC><YEAR>1990</YEAR><CITE>75 OR (2d) 225</CITE><PARANUM>82</PARANUM></CASEREF>, <BOLD>DSBA at Tab 5;</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>Donor Gateway Inc. v. Passero</SOC><CITE>2007 CanLII 3677</CITE><PARANUM>12-13</PARANUM></CASEREF>, <BOLD>DSBA at Tab 4.</BOLD></P2></P1></P>
<P>23. Schembri acknowledges that directors owe a fiduciary duty to the corporation for which they serve. The new issue before this Court is whether the conduct of Schembri contravened such duty owed to Triumph Financial. Put another way, did Schembri's development of real estate contravene his Section 134 duty to Triumph Financial. It did not, because such developments did not &ldquo;belong&rdquo; to Triumph Financial and did not constitute a maturing business opportunity of Triumph Financial. Section 134 does not prevent a director from conducting business outside the Corporation without more. The &ldquo;more&rdquo; is evidence of dishonesty or bad faith. There is none here.</P>
<P>24. It is clear from these principles that Schembri did not breach his Section 134 duties owed to Triumph Financial. There is no general prohibition on directors from having other business interests. Way has developed numerous properties since the action was commenced. By so doing, he has not breached his Section 134 duty owed to Triumph Financial. That is because such development opportunities were not ripe or mature opportunities of Triumph Financial. Way is legally entitled to pursue other business opportunities. So is Schembri. What is good for the goose is good for the gander.
<P1><BOLD>Schembri Affidavit sworn April 5, 2018, RMR, Tab A, at paras 103&ndash;107 Exhibit 21; Transcript from the Cross-Examination of A. Way dated July 17, 2018, at pp.89&ndash;94, qq.323&ndash;340; Transcript from the Examination of A. Way dated January 16, 2015, pp. 1964, qq.10295&ndash;10297, Compendium at Tab D, pg. 395; Transcript from the Exa mination of A. Way dated January 18, 2017, pp. 2985, qq.14942, Compendium at Tab D, pg. 397</BOLD></P1></P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI><UNDER>Schembri did not Usurp any Maturing Opportunities</UNDER></TI>
<P>25. Despite Way's lengthy affidavit (110 pages with 154 exhibits), there is no evidence whatsoever before This Honourable Court that Schembri usurped for himself or for another person or company <BOLD><EM>a maturing business opportunity</EM></BOLD> of Triumph Financial. This is because it never happened. In the absence of such evidence there can be no breach of any duty.
<P1><BOLD>Affidavit of A. Way sworn March 16, 2018, PMR, Tab A</BOLD></P1></P>
<BLOCK4><TI>The Oshawa, London and Waterloo Properties</TI>
<P>26. The parties to the Shareholder Agreement agreed that the Non-Competition Clause would govern the development of only the Oshawa, Waterloo, and London Properties. In this regard, the Oshawa, Waterloo, and London Properties can be seen as the only <EM>maturing</EM> or <EM>ripe</EM> business opportunities of the corporation.
<P1><BOLD>Transcript from the Examination of G. Schembri dated April 2, 2018, at p. 1759, q. 6819, Compendium at Tab D, pg. 313.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>27. Those <EM>ripe</EM> business opportunities were sold pursuant to a consent Sales Process Order during a Commercial Court supervised liquidation of Triumph Financial's assets. The Waterloo and London Properties were sold to Schembri corporations. The Oshawa Property was sold to a Way company. Particulars of the Sales Process Order are included at paragraphs 121&ndash;138 of Schembri's original Factum. Vesting Orders were made. Acquisitions of these properties by Way and Schembri which were sanctioned by Court orders (that were not appealed) cannot constitute a breach of any Section 134 duties. Way's acquisition of the Oshawa Property and Schembri's acquisition of the Waterloo and London Properties could not constitute any breach of Section 134 duties.
<P1><BOLD>Schembri Affidavit sworn May 17, 2017, DMR Tab 2, paras. 37&ndash;42, 56&ndash;61; Compendium at Tab B, pg. 195&ndash;232; Transcript form the Cross-Examination of A. way dated July 17, 2018, at pp.79&ndash;85, qq.287&ndash;310, Compendium at Tab D, p.429</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>28. Schembri did not usurp any maturing business opportunity of Triumph with respect to any properties. Any claim that he did is without evidentiary foundation and constitutes a collateral attack on the Order of the Court of Appeal and the Vesting Orders.</P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><TI>61 Columbia Street</TI>
<P>29. The only potential <EM>maturing</EM> or <EM>ripe</EM> business opportunity is with respect to the property known as 61 Columbia Street.</P>
<P>30. As particularized at paragraphs 139&ndash;143 of Schembri's Factum, the evidence before this Honourable Court is clear that any claim is statute barred and that it was in fact Triumph Financial that entered into the Agreement of Purchase and Sale for 61 Columbia Street. Schembri asked Way to use Triumph Financial as purchaser in an effort to disguise him as the real purchaser from the vendor in an attempt to keep the acquisition costs down. Way did so. Way had no interest in developing 61 Columbia Street, and accordingly he assigned the said Agreement of Purchase and Sale from Triumph Financial to one of Schembri's corporate entities which purchased 61 Columbia Street. 61 Columbia Street was pursued by Schembri with informed consent and not in breach of any Section 134 duty.
<P1><BOLD>Schembri Affidavit sworn May 17, 2017, DMR Tab 2, paras 70&ndash;72; Transcript from the Cross-Examination of A. Way dated July 17, 2018 at pp.144&ndash;148, qq.579&ndash;597, Compendium at Tab D, pg. 437;</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>D'Elia Estate v. D'Elia</SOC><CITE>[2008] OJ No 5772</CITE><PARANUM>176</PARANUM></CASEREF>, <BOLD>DBSA at Tab 3.</BOLD></P1></P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><TI>Article 22 of the Shareholder Agreement Expressly Permits Way and Schembri to Conduct Other Business</TI>
<P>31. Additionally, it is important to note that the Shareholder Agreement, at Article 22, is clear that the agreement as between the parties would not create any partnership whatsoever. In this regard, Article 22 of the Shareholder Agreement stated as follows:
<QUOTE><P><EM>Nothing in this Agreement shall be deemed in any way or for any purpose to constitute any party a partner of any other party to this Agreement in the conduct of any business or otherwise, or a member of a joint venture or joint enterprise with any other party to this Agreement</EM>.</P></QUOTE>
<P1><BOLD>Affidavit of A. Way sworn March 16, 2018, PMR, Tab A, at para 145, Exhibit 54; Compendium at Tab A, pg. 11&ndash;36.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>32. This is consistent with Schembri's evidence that the Shareholder Agreement was only to apply to the Oshawa, Waterloo and London Properties (being the projects contemplated by the parties at the time that the Shareholder Agreement was entered into).
<P1><BOLD>Transcript from the Examination of G. Schembri dated April 2, 2018 at p.1759, q.6819, Compendium at Tab D, pg.313.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>33. Article 22 clearly indicates that it was the parties' intentions and express agreement that both Way and Schembri could pursue other business interests. By so doing they cannot be in breach of any Section 134 duties.</P></BLOCK4></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI><UNDER>Why Section 134 Cannot Apply</UNDER></TI>
<P>34. The evidence before This Honourable Court is also clear that:
<P1>(a) Triumph Financial has not carried on any business whatsoever since the Receiver was appointed over all of its assets in September of 2010. It is defunct, has no employees, and is not active; and</P1>
<P1>(b) The reality is that Triumph Financial had no &ldquo;maturing&rdquo; or &ldquo;ripe&rdquo; business opportunities since 2010 and has not even been engaged in the business of real estate development since 2010.
<P2><BOLD>Schembri Affidavit sworn May 17, 2017, DMR, Tab 1 at para 79; Transcript from the Cross-Examination of A. Way dated July 17, 2018, pp. 24-25, qq.25&ndash;31, pp.32&ndash;33, qq 69-70.</BOLD></P2></P1></P>
<P>35. Triumph Financial seeks the benefit of all of Schembri's hard work over the last 8 years without having carried on business, invested any capital, taken any risks, or performed any services.</P>
<P>36. Schembri is entitled to use the skills, talent, and knowledge that he brought into the Shareholder Agreement with Way, and following a complete breakdown of their relationship, to earn a living for him and his family.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Donor Gateway Inc. v. Passero</SOC><CITE>2007 CanLII 3677</CITE><PARANUM>18</PARANUM></CASEREF>, <BOLD>DSBA at Tab 4.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>37. It is commercially unreasonable to maintain that Schembri is unable to pursue any real estate development opportunities, on the sole basis that he is a director of Triumph Financial. There is no legal rationale let alone evidence to support such a principle.</P>
<P>38. To interpret Section 134 as Way seeks to interpret it, being that a director cannot conduct business independent of a corporation, would create significant new law, impose an impossible and unacceptable burden on directors, and cause considerable upheaval and confusion within corporate law. It would also create havoc in that business people would no longer be willing to act as directors of corporations for the fear that the Section 134 duty owed to the corporation would bar them from acting independently of the corporation to secure new business opportunities. Clearly, this is not the meaning of or the intention of Section 134 of the <EM>OBCA</EM>.</P>
<P>39. In any event, the Non-Competition Clause purports to bind Schembri as a &ldquo;shareholder&rdquo; of Triumph Financial not as a director of Triumph Financial. Shareholders owe no fiduciary duty to the corporation. There is no evidence that Schembri breached his Section 134 duty because he never acted dishonestly or contrary to the best interests of Triumph Financial. In fact, Justice Roberts found it was in Triumph Financial's best interests for a Receiver to be appointed.
<P1><BOLD>Schembri Affidavit sworn May 17, 2017, DMR, Tab 1 at para 35; Endorsement of Justice Roberts dated September 24, 2010 at para 5, Compendium at Tab B, pg. 105&ndash;112.</BOLD></P1></P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI><UNDER>Way Misinterprets the Non-Competition Clause</UNDER></TI>
<BLOCK4><TI>Stage One</TI>
<P>40. Way states that the Non-Competition Clause imposes on Schembri a specific fiduciary duty to present real estate opportunities (Way's Supplementary Factum at paragraph 29). This is not so and it begs the question as to the Non-Competition Clause's enforceability. The Non-competition Clause is merely a contractual term in a Shareholders Agreement. Whether the Non-Competition Clause is enforceable or not is a matter of contract law. The Non-Competition Clause cannot and does not impose a fiduciary duty on Schembri. It imposes a contractual obligation if and only if the Non-Competition Clause is enforceable. It is not.</P>
<P>41. Way says that the Non-Competition Clause affects no persons not a party to the Shareholder Agreement (Way's Supplementary Factum at paragraph 29). This is not so. It effects any entity with which Schembri is directly or indirectly related (including public companies) and Schembri's offspring, and his offspring's offspring and so on.</P>
<P>42. Way says that it is improper for Schembri to withhold his consent to Triumph Financial taking on a real estate opportunity (Way's Supplementary Factum at paragraph 30(c)). This is not so. The Shareholders Agreement specifically and expressly requires both of Schembri's and Way's consent for Triumph Financial to take on any real estate opportunity:
<QUOTE><P><EM>The parties hereto agree:</EM></P>
<P><EM>(c) That during the currency of this Agreement, the parties agree that without the consent of the shareholders representing not less than ONE HUNDRED (100%) per cent of the voting shares of the capital stock of the Corporation:</EM></P>
<P><EM>(xiv) the Corporation shall not commit to any financing arrangements with third parties;</EM></P>
<P><EM>(xv) no projects will be undertaken or initiated by the Corporation without project feasibility studies and construction budget approvals</EM>.</P></QUOTE>
<P1><BOLD>Affidavit of A. Way sworn March 16, 2018, PMR, Tab A, at para 145, Exhibit 54; Compendium at Tab A, pg. 11&ndash;36.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>43. It also makes no commercial sense for Schembri or Way to be forced to do future deals with each other if they choose not to do so based on the express provision in the Shareholder Agreement.</P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><TI>Stage Two</TI>
<P>44. This was addressed in Schembri's original Factum. The Non-Competition Clause is contrary to public policy.</P>
<P>[Missing text]</P>
<P>support that proposition. Firstly, Way personally does not receive the benefit of the Non-Competition Clause, only Triumph Financial and Kingsley Financial do. Secondly, Way left out a significant portion of Volpini's evidence that immediately preceded the passage he quoted:
<QUOTE><P><BOLD>Q.43.</BOLD> <EM>&ldquo;All right. Do you recall any discussion that if Mr. Way didn't agree to a 50/50 shareholder split in the event that the corporation was self-financing, then Mr. Schembri could just say no more developments?&rdquo;</EM></P>
<P><BOLD>A.</BOLD> <EM>&ldquo;Yes. The two of them could say that at any time.&rdquo;</EM></P></QUOTE>
<P1><BOLD>Transcript from the Examination of Frank Volpini, dated February 14, 2011, q.43, pg. 7.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>49. This is completely consistent with Schembri's evidence that both he and Way must agree on the terms of any future development or they could walk away. It is also completely consistent with commercial reality and common sense. Unless the parties come to an agreement on many issues, no future development could proceed or be possible. It is also completely consistent with the only commercially reasonable manner in which the Non-Competition Clause can be construed.</P></BLOCK4></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI><UNDER>The Consequences of Withdrawing the Fraud Allegations</UNDER></TI>
<P>50. The Fallback Position was withdrawn by Schembri in an effort to expedite the hearing of the within Motion. It is Schembri's main position that the Non-Competition Clause is void, because it is against public policy, ambiguous, unreasonable, and impractical. The allegations of fraud were for the purposes of providing necessary background facts to explain why Schembri terminated his relationship with Way and why a Receiver had to be appointed.</P>
<P>51. Way argues that the &ldquo;<EM>only adequate condemnation of Schembri's unacceptable course of action (in alleging fraud and advancing that allegation into responding oral submissions) is to dismiss Schembri's motion, so that the Main Action and the ROFR Action may proceed to be tried together and afford Way the opportunity to obtain vindication</EM>.&rdquo;</P>
<P>52. There is no reason let alone need to &ldquo;condemn&rdquo; Schembri's decision to withdraw a single fallback legal argument. The Non-Competition Clause is enforceable or not. Schembri's withdrawal of a position was intended to facilitate and expedite the hearing of the motion. Such decisions ought to be commended not condemned by the Court.</P>
<P>53. This is merely an attempt by Way to avoid an interpretation of the Non-Competition Clause by This Court and to prolong the ROFR Action.</P>
<P>54. Despite the fact that the Fallback Position has now been withdrawn with respect to the Summary Judgment Motion, the issue of fraud will be squarely before the trier of fact in the Trial of the Main Action (and the Trial of this Action, if it proceeds). At either Trial, Way will have the opportunity to seek <EM>vindication</EM> for himself and to address any allegations of fraud made against him by Schembri and as has already been found by the Courts. This is not a reason to dismiss Schembri's Motion.</P>
<P>55. To the extent that Way wishes to argue that the withdrawal of the Fallback Position has resulted in wasted costs with respect to the Motion, he can do so. The proper time and forum for that argument is after a decision is rendered in the Summary Judgment Motion and when the parties make their costs submissions.</P></BLOCK3></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="IV">PART IV&mdash;ORDER REQUESTED</TI>
<P>56. Schembri respectfully seeks:
<P1>(a) All of the relief set out at paragraph 150 of Schembri's Original Factum; and</P1>
<P1>(b) The costs of the Motion and ROFR Action; and</P1>
<P1>(c) Such other relief as This Honourable Court deems just.</P1></P>
<P><BOLD>ALL OF WHICH IS RESPECTFULLY SUBMITTED</BOLD> this 19 day of December, 2018.</P>
