<DATE YYYYMMDD="20190228" LABEL="Date: ">28 February, 2019</DATE>
<CASEREF><SOC>Way v. Schembri</SOC><CITE>2019 CarswellOnt 1449</CITE></CASEREF>
<DOCKET>*****START OF COURT DOCUMENT*****</DOCKET>
<DOCKET LABEL="Court File No. ">C-457-12</DOCKET>
<COURTJUR>ONTARIO SUPERIOR COURT OF JUSTICE</COURTJUR>
<PARTYBLOCK>
<LINE>BETWEEN:</LINE>
<PARTY>AL WAY, KINGSLEY FINANCIAL INC. and TRIUMPH FINANCIAL HOLDINGS INC.</PARTY>
<PARTYROLE>Plaintiffs</PARTYROLE>
<CONNECTOR>&mdash;and&mdash;</CONNECTOR>
<PARTY>GORDON SCHEMBRI, SCHEMBRI FINANCIAL LIMITED, 41 COLUMBIA INC., KING &amp; COLUMBIA INC. 69 COLUMBIA ST. INC., <UNDER>5 RITTENHOUSE INC., THE BLOCK INC., THE BLOCK I INC., THE BLOCK II INC.</UNDER></PARTY>
<PARTYROLE>Defendants</PARTYROLE>
</PARTYBLOCK>
<COUNSELBLOCK>
<P>Counsel not indicated.</P>
</COUNSELBLOCK>
<FREEFORM>
<P><BOLD>1.</BOLD> The Defendants (collectively, <BOLD>&ldquo;Schembri&rdquo;)</BOLD> seek costs in the amount of $499,933.06 on a partial indemnity basis.</P>
<P><BOLD>2.</BOLD> The Plaintiffs (collectively, <BOLD>&ldquo;Way&rdquo;)</BOLD> submit that the amount sought is grossly excessive as it is based on, among other things: (a) an arbitrary approach in determining the time spent (as well as disbursements incurred) and applying greater than maximum rates, without providing any dockets or invoices; and (b) is inconsistent with section 131(1) of the <EM>Courts of Justice Act</EM> (the <BOLD>&ldquo;CJA&rdquo;)</BOLD> and the factors contained in Rule 57.01. Put simply, the amount sought is unfair, unreasonable, disproportionate and ignores Schembri's allegations of fraud withdrawn, without notice, while Way's counsel was in the midst of oral submissions (the <BOLD>&ldquo;Withdrawn Fraud Allegations&rdquo;).</BOLD></P>
<BLOCK2><TI>Arbitrary Approach to Determining Time Spent (and Disbursements)</TI>
<P><BOLD>3.</BOLD> Schembri seeks costs based on 1296.8 hours (as summarized in Schedule &ldquo;A&rdquo; hereto) having been spent &ldquo;in relation to the ROFR Action&rdquo; with certain items being &ldquo;shared 50%&mdash;50% with the Main Action&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Defendants' Cost Submissions, paragraph 19 and Tab A, Costs Outline</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE>. Such shared items (Second and Third Fee Items) total 959.3 hours, and represent 74% of the total hours certified.</P>
<P><BOLD>4.</BOLD> A 50/50 split with respect to the Second and Third Fee Items is arbitrary and inconsistent with: (a) the number of disputes in the litigation between Way and Schembri: and (b) the time spent at the examinations for discovery of Way (and Schembri conducted to date) regarding these disputes.</P>
<P><BOLD>5.</BOLD> Regarding (a) in paragraph 4 above, there are seven disputes; six in the Main Action and one in the ROFR Action<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Responding Factum of Way, pp. 8 and 9, paras 14 and 15</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE>. As such, there is limited impact on the litigation between the parties. Moreover, the &ldquo;further productions&rdquo; Schembri has now avoided producing had been required to be disclosed by Schembri under Rule 30 of the Rules of Civil Procedure.</P>
<P><BOLD>6.</BOLD> Regarding (b) in paragraph 4 above, Way was examined for thirteen days and gave approximately 600 undertakings. A review of the transcripts and related &lsquo;Undertakings and Refusals Charts&rsquo; reveal that Schembri's counsel spent little time on the ROFR Action (at times during Day 11 and 13) with few undertakings given. This was also the situation at the five days of re -attendance arising from answers to undertakings. In contrast, the majority of time spent and undertakings given related to a single dispute in the Main Action (namely, the &lsquo;JV Accounting Dispute&rsquo;).</P>
<P><BOLD>7.</BOLD> The situation described in the paragraph 6 above is similar for the examinations for discovery of Schembri conducted to date.</P>
<P><BOLD>8.</BOLD> Regarding the Second Fee Item totaling 402.1 hours, included therein is 69.5 hours for Mr. Kulathungam. To Way's knowledge, Mr. Kulathungam's involvement has been limited to &lsquo;Fee items&rsquo; in respect of which the court received submissions and awarded costs that footnote 1 in the Costs Outline states has &ldquo;been deducted and not included&rdquo;. If so, this means that Mr. Kulathungam has purportedly spent at least 240 hours on the litigation between Way and Schembri<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>69.5 hours x 2 (based on the 50/50 split) plus 101.7 hours (based on Schembri's Summary of Costs submitted in connection with the Cost Endorsement of Mr. Justice Sloan dated January 30, 2017 (Appendix A) and aggregated in Tab B to the Cost Submissions of Way (Appendix B))</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE>. That cannot be 4 correct. There appears to be significant double-counting.</P>
<P><BOLD>9.</BOLD> Further, the Second Fee Item references &ldquo;Motion preparation and Court Attendances&rdquo; without particularizing such motions and attendances. Way is not aware of any prior motions where costs of such motions were ordered reserved to the trial judge<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>There is an order in the Receivership Proceedings made &ldquo;without prejudice to the rights of [Way and Schembri] to ultimately argue who or what should be responsible for the cost of the Receivership&rdquo; (Responding Motion Record, Volume 9, Tab 119, Exhibit &ldquo;119&rdquo;)</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE>, which is consistent with the &ldquo;pay as you go&rdquo; scheme under the current costs regime in place since 2009.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Hession v. Black Construction Services Inc.</SOC><CITE>2015 ONSC 7047</CITE><PARANUM>40</PARANUM></CASEREF> (Appendix C)</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Moreover, &ldquo;when a matter is disposed of on a motion...with no mention of costs, it is as though the judge had said that he &lsquo;saw fit to make no order as to costs.&rsquo;&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Mark M. Orkin, <EM>The Law of Costs</EM> (Canada Law Books: 2001) at pp. 1 to 15 (Appendix D)</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P><BOLD>10.</BOLD> Consequently, the time spent in respect of the Second and Third Fee Items and the disbursements in Schedule &ldquo;A&rdquo; to the Costs Outline are overstated significantly.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI>Greater Than Maximum Rates</TI>
<P><BOLD>11.</BOLD> The Costs Sub-Committee of the Civil Rules Committee published an Information Notice in July of 2005 which provides some guidance as to maximum partial indemnity rates. The rates are shown in Schedule &ldquo;B&rdquo; hereto.</P>
<P><BOLD>12.</BOLD> Not only will courts treat the rates shown in Schedule &ldquo;B&rdquo; as maximum rates, [i]t is further anticipated that the maximum rates would apply only to the more complicated matters and to the more experienced counsel within each category.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Watson &amp; McGowan's Ontario Civil Practice</EM> (Thomson Reuters; 2019) at p. 1248 (Appendix E)</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P><BOLD>13.</BOLD> Even adjusting for inflation<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>First Capital (Canholdings) Corp v. North American Property Group</SOC><CITE>2012 ONSC 1359</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>2012 CarswellOnt 2609</CITE></CORRELAT></CASEREF> (Appendix F)</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE>, the partial indemnity rates charged for the 634.6 hours spent by Mr. Wortzman and the 182 hours spent by &ldquo;Student&rdquo; are excessive and well above the maximums established by the Rules Committee.</P>
<P><BOLD>14.</BOLD> Regarding footnotes 1 and 2 in the Costs Outline<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Schembri's Cost Submissions, Tab A, Costs Outline, p. 2</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE>, it is not clear what opposing counsel means when they state &ldquo;an average lawyer rate has been utilized for the calculation&rdquo; as no calculation has been disclosed.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI>No Dockets or Invoices Provided</TI>
<P><BOLD>15.</BOLD> Contrary to Way's entitlement<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>1312217 Ontario Ltd. v. Atrens</SOC><CITE>2004 CarswellOnt 2548</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>[2004] O.J. No. 2646</CITE></CORRELAT><CORRELAT><CITE>[2004] O.T.C. 524</CITE></CORRELAT><CORRELAT><CITE>131 A.C.W.S. (3d) 816</CITE></CORRELAT></CASEREF> at para 20 (Appendix G)</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE>, Schembri has elected not to provide any dockets or invoices in support of his request for costs in the amount of $499,933.06. Absent such provision, neither Way nor the court is afforded the opportunity to assess whether the amount sought is &ldquo;fair, reasonable and proportionate&rdquo;.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI>Section 131(1) of the <EM>Courts of Justice Act</EM></TI>
<P><BOLD>16.</BOLD> Section 131 of the CJA states:
<QUOTE><P><EM>Subject to the provisions of an Act or rules of court, the costs of and incidental to a proceeding or a step in a proceeding are in the discretion of the court, and the court may determine by whom and to what extent the costs shall be paid</EM>.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Courts of Justice Act</EM>, s. 131(1)</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></QUOTE></P>
<P><BOLD>17.</BOLD> The Court of Appeal has interpreted this section to mean that:
<QUOTE><P><EM>the court hearing a proceeding or a step in a proceeding will fix those costs. The use of the definite article &ldquo;the&rdquo; before the word &ldquo;court&rdquo; as opposed to the indefinite article &ldquo;a&rdquo; reinforces that implication. This implies that the court hearing the appeal should decide the costs of the appeal. Nothing in the CPA suggests the contrary</EM>.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Amyotrophic Lateral Sclerosis Society of Essex v. Windsor (City)</SOC><CITE>2013 ONCA 254</CITE><PARANUM>16</PARANUM></CASEREF> (Appendix H)</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></QUOTE></P>
<P><BOLD>18.</BOLD> Accordingly, this court does not have jurisdiction to fix or award costs in a matter that is not before it. There is a significant risk that the court will do so if it accepts Schembri's arbitrary 50/50 split with the Main Action.</P>
<P><BOLD>19.</BOLD> Given the foregoing, Schembri's partial indemnity costs without considering the Withdrawn Fraud Allegations ought to be less than $100,000.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI>The Withdrawn Fraud Allegations</TI>
<P><BOLD>20.</BOLD> Schembri alleged fraud and other &ldquo;bad behaviour&rdquo; by Way in the Notice of Motion and the supporting affidavit causing Way to respond vigourously in his affidavit. In his reply affidavit, Schembri reiterated his allegation that Way defrauded him. During cross-examination, Schembri's counsel made it clear that Schembri was seeking from this court a finding of fraud by Way. Schembri then reiterated his allegations of fraud in his factum. Finally, Schembri's counsel made submissions before the court in support of Schembri's allegations of fraud.</P>
<P><BOLD>21.</BOLD> It was only when Way's counsel was about to continue addressing the allegations of fraud following the afternoon break, that Schembri's counsel announced, without prior notice, the Withdrawn Fraud Allegations.</P>
<P><BOLD>22.</BOLD> Given the Withdrawn Fraud Allegations, it is clear that Schembri was not entirely successful on the motion.</P>
<P><BOLD>23.</BOLD> It is trite law that the Withdrawn Fraud Allegations may attract an award of substantial indemnity costs<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Future Health Inc. v. General Accident Assurance et al</SOC><CITE>2016 ONSC 4834</CITE><PARANUM>9</PARANUM></CASEREF> (Appendix I)</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE>, as such &ldquo;<EM>allegations have been found to be prejudicial to characters or reputations of those to whom they are directed and to attract a higher scale of costs</EM>&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Hawkins v. Hawkins Estate</SOC><CITE>2015 ONSC 1106</CITE><PARANUM>15</PARANUM></CASEREF> (Appendix J)</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P><BOLD>24.</BOLD> Way submits it is just and appropriate to impose &ldquo;<EM>serious cost consequences</EM>&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Ibid, <CASEREF><SOC>1312217 Ontario Ltd v. Atrens</SOC></CASEREF>, at para 30 (Appendix G)</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> on Schembri for the Withdrawn Fraud Allegations. Way submits further that such imposition by the court ought to offset fully Schembri's partial indemnity costs (of less than $100,000), and result in no costs being awarded on the motion.</P>
<P><BOLD>ALL OF WHICH IS RESPECTFULLY SUBMITTED</BOLD> this 28<SUP>th</SUP> day of February 2019.</P>
<P>&ldquo;Heath P.L. Whiteley&rdquo;</P>
<P><BOLD>Heath P.L. Whiteley</BOLD></P>
<P>&ellip35; <BOLD>Laughlin J. Campbell</BOLD></P></BLOCK2>
</FREEFORM>
