<FREEFORM>
<P>1. While Way submits that Schembri's Cost Submissions are &ldquo;grossly excessive,&rdquo; &ldquo;unfair,&rdquo; &ldquo;unreasonable,&rdquo; and &ldquo;unsubstantiated,&rdquo; he has not produced his own Cost Outline or any other documentation whatsoever which supports that position. An adverse inference ought to be drawn that Way incurred as much or more in costs (he had 3 gowned lawyers at the Motion).</P>
<P>2. Way submits that the costs sought by Schembri are &ldquo;arbitrary&rdquo; and &ldquo;disproportionate&rdquo;. Yet, Way was seeking $30,500,000.00 against Schembri based upon serious allegations of conversion, misappropriation, breach of fiduciary duty and conspiracy. Essentially, Way tried to turn the tables against Schembri by utilizing the strategy &ldquo;<EM>the best defence is a good offence</EM>.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Similar conduct by Way has been previously identified by Justice Sloan in his Endorsement dated December 23, 2016 at para 58.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Way's decision was costly and ultimately unsuccessful. Way ought to pay the price.</P>
<BLOCK2><TI><UNDER>Schembri's Approach is Not Arbitrary</UNDER></TI>
<P>3. Since the Actions were Ordered Tried together with common discoveries by Justice Broad on September 4, 2014, the costs incurred have related to the matters at issue in both Actions. It is impossible to divide such costs with precision. Way accuses Schembri of being arbitrary in calculating costs yet he has not provided the Court with any assistance or alternative method to do so. The issues in the Main Action regarding Way's &ldquo;bad&rdquo; conduct were all relevant to the enforceability of the Non-Competition Clause.</P>
<P>4. Way submits that the costs &ldquo;<EM>ought to be less than $100,000</EM>&rdquo; without providing any rationale (This submission is without merit as Justice Sloan awarded over $94,000 in costs against Way on an undertakings motion). The &ldquo;<EM>50/50 split</EM>&rdquo; for post September 2014 work as proposed by Schembri is the most efficient, fair and reasonable way to apportion the costs of Schembri and Way's competing claims and to indemnify Schembri for his costs of the unmeritorious litigation pursued by Way.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI><UNDER>The Cost Calculations are Accurate</UNDER></TI>
<P>5. At paragraph 8, Way submits that it cannot be correct that Mr. Kulathungam has spent &ldquo;<EM>at least 240 hours on the litigation between Way and Schembri</EM>&rdquo;. The time set out in Schembri's Cost Outline was carefully calculated. Mr. Kulathungam worked 240.6 hours on this Action over the last 5 years. Schembri seeks no costs that were subject to the Cost Endorsement of Justice Sloan dated January 30, 2017. There is no duplication.</P>
<P>6. At paragraph 9, Way submits that he is not aware of any prior motions where costs were ordered reserved. This is inaccurate. The parties attended at a Motion for Directions before Justice Sloan on February 8, 2018. The motion was resolved on consent and Justice Sloan's Endorsement specifically provided that costs would be in the cause.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Endorsement of Justice Sloan dated February 8, 2018 appending the executed Consent. See paragraph 11 <BOLD>(Tab 1)</BOLD>.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> These costs are now payable to Schembri.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI><UNDER>The Lawyer Rates are Reasonable</UNDER></TI>
<P>7. Way wrongly states the maximum rates that apply to counsel fees. Way cites commentary from Watson &amp; McGowan's Ontario Civil Practice (&ldquo;Commentary&rdquo;) for that proposition.</P>
<P>8. The Commentary expressly states that it is &ldquo;<EM>anticipated</EM>&rdquo; that in considering rates &ldquo;<EM>courts will normally treat the rates as maximum rates</EM>&rdquo; Professor Watson was incorrect. The cost grid was abolished in 2005. The case produced by Way confirms the fact that the <UNDER>guidelines are not mandatory and are outdated</UNDER>. In this regard, in <EM>First Capital</EM>, Justice R. Smith approved hourly rates in excess of those included in the guidelines stating as follows, <EM>inter alia</EM>:
<P1>(a) <EM>The maximum hourly rates . . .</EM> <UNDER><EM>are intended to provide guidance and are not mandatory</EM></UNDER>;</P1>
<P1>(b) <EM>The</EM> <UNDER><EM>amount involved in the dispute was substantial</EM></UNDER> <EM>as the matter involved a commercial dispute related to a shopping centre with</EM> <UNDER><EM>31 million dollars</EM></UNDER>;</P1>
<P1>(c) <UNDER><EM>Both parties retained well respected Toronto firms</EM></UNDER> <EM>where hourly rates and office overhead costs are higher than the provincial average. I also infer that both parties would be incurring similar full indemnity costs and</EM> <UNDER><EM>their reasonable expectations of the unsuccessful party would be to partial indemnity costs in excess of the maximum</EM></UNDER>...<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>First Capital (Canholdings) Corp. v. North American Property Group</SOC><CITE>2012 ONSC 1359</CITE></CASEREF> (&ldquo;<EM>First Capital</EM>&rdquo;) at Paras 13&ndash;16, <BOLD>Appendix F</BOLD> to Way's Responding Cost Submissions [emphasis added].</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P1></P>
<P>9. The amount at issue in the ROFR Action was $30,500,000.00. Way and Schembri retained well respected Toronto firms.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Mr. Whiteley was formerly a Partner of Gowlings LLP who had or assisted with carriage of this matter.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Way has two law firms acting on his behalf and had three gowned lawyers attending at the Motion.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Mr. Whiteley and Laughlin J. Campbell and Trevor Moum of Campbell Bader LLP attended on behalf of Way.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Way did not produce a Cost Outline to assist the Court in determining the reasonableness of the rates claimed by Schembri's counsel. In the circumstances, it is apparent that (1) Way knew (or reasonably ought to have known) that if unsuccessful in the ROFR Action, he would be ordered to pay Schembri's partial indemnity costs in the amount sought,<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>First Capital</EM>, <EM>supra</EM>, at paras 14-15.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> and (2) that if Way's counsel had prepared a Cost Outline, it would have not been of any assistance to him.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI><UNDER>No Dockets or Invoices Provided</UNDER></TI>
<P>10. Rule 57.01 (7) mandates that the Court &ldquo;<EM>shall</EM>&rdquo; adopt the simplest, least expensive and most expeditious process for fixing costs after receiving written submissions. Rule 57.01(6) requires that a party seeking its costs of a proceeding &ldquo;<EM>shall</EM>&rdquo; submit a Cost Outline identifying the costs sought, the work performed, and the hourly rate to be applied to each counsel for whom fees are requested. Schembri has complied with these Rules.</P>
<P>11. Way complains that time dockets and invoices were not provided. The Rule does not require this. Since Way has failed to provide any information regarding his costs, his position should be seen for what it is&mdash;nothing more than &ldquo;<EM>an attack in the air</EM>.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Higgins Cohn Brand Management v. Kinnikinnick Foods Inc.</SOC><CITE>2016 ONSC 2701</CITE><PARANUM>38&ndash;40</PARANUM></CASEREF> <BOLD>(Tab 2)</BOLD></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI><UNDER>Withdrawal of Allegations Mischaracterized</UNDER></TI>
<P>12. It was Schembri's primary position at the Motion that the Non-Competition Clause was void as a matter of law (&ldquo;Primary Position&rdquo;). Schembri's fallback position was that the Non-Competition Clause should not be enforced by Way given his &ldquo;bad&rdquo; conduct (&ldquo;Fallback Position&rdquo;).</P>
<P>13. Way wrongly says that Schembri withdrew fraud allegations. Schembri's allegations of fraud and bad behaviour were not withdrawn, rather the legal Fallback Position was withdrawn. Had Schembri been unsuccessful at the Motion, the allegations of Way's bad behaviour would have been pursued at Trial. These allegations will also be front and center at the Trial of the Main Action. Way will have his chance to seek vindication if the allegations are not proven.</P>
<P>14. Schembri's withdrawal of the Fallback Position at the Motion was intended to facilitate and expedite the hearing of the Motion. Such decisions ought to be commended not condemned by the Court. In any event, given Justice Sloan's decision, the Fallback Position would not have been even necessary to argue because Schembri was entirely successful at the Motion on his Primary Position. The withdrawal therefore saved everyone time and money.</P>
<P>15. Way submits that Schembri's withdrawal of the Fallback Position requires &ldquo;<EM>serious cost consequences</EM>.&rdquo; Each of the cases relied upon by Way are not applicable because the Court grappled with the issue of whether or not costs should be awarded on a substantial indemnity where a party withdrew or was unsuccessful in their claim for, among other things, breach of fiduciary duty, conspiracy, unlawful conduct, and inducing breach of contract.</P>
<P>16. Schembri withdrew the Fallback Position (being a legal position) for the purposes of the Motion only. This does not attract cost consequences. Way, on the other hand, pursued the ROFR Action for over 6 years alleging that Schembri committed <UNDER>conversion, misappropriation, breach of fiduciary duty, and conspiracy</UNDER>. Those allegations were unfounded and have been determined to be <UNDER>unmeritorious</UNDER> by Justice Sloan. Although he could have, Schembri did not seek his costs on a substantial indemnity basis.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Future Health Inc. (Trustee of) v. General Accident</SOC><CITE>2016 ONSC 4834</CITE><PARANUM>9&ndash;12</PARANUM></CASEREF>, <BOLD>Appendix I</BOLD> to Way's Responding Cost Submissions.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Such an award remains in the discretion of the Court.</P>
<P>17. Way has produced no authority that there should be &ldquo;<EM>serious cost consequences</EM>&rdquo; because Schembri withdrew a legal position, that in the end, would have been moot given the Courts decision on Schembri's Primary Position.</P>
<P>March 5, 2019</P>
