</PARTYBLOCK>
<COUNSELBLOCK>
<P>Counsel not indicated.</P>
</COUNSELBLOCK>
<FREEFORM>
<P>1. The within action (the &ldquo;ROFR Action&rdquo;) is a companion action to Court File No. C-42-11 wherein Schembri sued Way for fraud (the &ldquo;Main Action&rdquo;).<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Reference to &ldquo;Schembri&rdquo; and &ldquo;Way&rdquo; include reference to the various relevant corporations that the parties control.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> In response to the Main Action, Way commenced the ROFR Action seeking to enforce a non-competition clause. <UNDER>Way sought damages from Schembri in the amount of $30,500,000.00</UNDER> based upon allegations of breach of contract, and intentional torts of conversion, misappropriation, breach of fiduciary duty and conspiracy.</P>
<P>2. The Actions were ordered to be tried together by Justice Broad.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Order of the Honourable Justice Broad dated September 4, 2014 <BOLD>(Tab 1)</BOLD>.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> The actions are complex and the issues interwoven. There has been 36.5 days of examinations in the Actions.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Not including the examinations for discovery conducted with respect to the Defendants Faye Patterson and the Way Family Trust.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>3. This summary judgment motion (&ldquo;Motion&rdquo;) was heard over four days. Schembri was entirely successful in having Way's $30,500,000.00 claim dismissed. Costs of the entire ROFR Action should follow the event. Schembri seeks the sum of $411,180.00 for fees, $53,453.40 for H.S.T., and $31,299.66 for disbursements, for a total of $499,933.06 with respect to the dismissal of the ROFR Action.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Mo v. Johnson</SOC><CITE>2012 ONSC 6307</CITE><PARANUM>24</PARANUM></CASEREF> <BOLD>(Tab 2)</BOLD>; Bill of Costs of Teplitsky, Colson LLP <BOLD>(Appendix A)</BOLD>.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<BLOCK2><TI><UNDER>Rule 57.01(1)&mdash;The Factors</UNDER></TI>
<P>4. Section 131 of the <EM>Courts of Justice Act</EM> gives the Court broad discretion to award costs. This discretion is informed by the factors in Rule 57.01(1).<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Courts of Justice Act</EM>, RSO 1990, cC43, s. 131; <EM>Rules of Civil Procedure</EM>, RRO 1990, Reg 194., R.57.01(1).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Schembri's costs are fair, reasonable and proportionate in light of these factors, and in particular, the principle of indemnity, what the unsuccessful party could reasonably expect to pay, the amount claimed; the complexity of the proceeding; the importance of the issues, conduct tending to lengthen the proceeding unnecessarily, and the fact that Way made serious allegations of illegal conduct against Schembri, including allegations of conversion, misappropriation and conspiracy.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI><UNDER>The Amount and Importance of the Issue</UNDER></TI>
<P>5. The issue raised at the motion was of critical importance to Schembri. Way sought over $30,500,000.00 in damages. Way's position in the ROFR Action was that he was entitled to participate with Schembri on all real estate developments in &ldquo;Waterloo&rdquo; forever and on an undetermined and undefined basis. Way sought an interest in properties Schembri had developed over 10 years. Not only was Schembri facing a claim of $30,500,000.00 in damages, his business interests were at considerable risk over the past 10 years and forever thereafter.</P>
<P>6. In addition to the quantum of the damages sought in the ROFR Action and its impact on Schembri's continuing business endeavours and upon his family, the summary dismissal of the ROFR Action is also important as it will lead to the Main Action's more orderly resolution and to judicial efficacy.</P>
<P>7. The ROFR Action's dismissal is one step towards ending the <EM>war</EM> between the parties and:
<P1>(a) Will allow the parties to focus on moving the Main Action towards Trial;</P1>
<P1>(b) Will streamline the issues that require adjudication;</P1>
<P1>(c) Has alleviated the necessity of countless further productions and days of examinations; and</P1>
<P1>(d) Limits the need for further Court intervention. As set out above, there was already 36.5 days of examinations between Schembri and Way. This took place over nearly 4 years and required significant Court intervention.</P1></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI><UNDER>The Complexity of the Issue/ The Parties' Conduct</UNDER></TI>
<P>8. While the issue advanced by Schembri was narrow, Way expanded them. The allegations in the ROFR Action were serious, widespread and complex. Way sought $30,500,000.00 in damages arising from the profits related to Schembri's development of 26 properties. In defence of the ROFR Action, Schembri had to rely on Way's &ldquo;bad conduct&rdquo; which meant that the issues in the Main Action were inextricably intertwined with the ROFR Action.</P>
<P>9. Despite the significance of the claim amount and the fact that the ROFR Action was with respect to, <EM>inter alia</EM>, 26 properties, the main issue at the motion &ldquo;<EM>boil[ed] down to the contractual interpretation of Clause 13 of the Shareholders Agreement</EM>.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Decision of the Honourable Mr. Justice Sloan dated February 1, 2019 at para 101.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>10. Schembri's position on the Motion was thorough, detailed and focused on the law surrounding restrictive covenants and its application to the facts of this case. Way's conduct, on the other hand, unnecessarily lengthened the proceeding and added significantly to the costs of the Motion. This ought to be considered in addressing the appropriate quantum of costs.</P>
<P>11. In compliance with his obligation to &ldquo;<EM>lead trump or risk losing</EM>&rdquo; on the Motion, Schembri filed a succinct Motion Record that focused on the application of Clause 13 of the Shareholders Agreement. Way, on the other hand, served a 10-volume Responding Motion Record that included a 111 page, 404 paragraph affidavit, and which appended 154 exhibits. Way's Responding Record did not respond to Schembri's position on the Motion (with less than 15% of the 404 paragraphs related to the Motion). Rather, Way, through an affidavit (with no Notice of Motion), sought significant relief (some of which related to the Main Action) that was not contemplated when the Motion was scheduled, raised irrelevant matters and unduly complicated and lengthened the hearing. Schembri had no option but to prepare substantive responding materials given Way's insistence on pursuing such relief.</P>
<P>12. Schembri served a factum in compliance with the Rules that focused squarely on the enforceability of Clause 13. Way waited until the afternoon before the return of the Motion to serve <UNDER>a 63 page factum that ignored Schembri's entire legal position</UNDER> and instead argued a brand new position that Schembri had breached a fiduciary duty owed to Way under section 134 of the <EM>OBCA</EM>. That was &ldquo;<EM>the first time [that] Schembri became aware of any allegation concerning section 134</EM>,&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Ibid</EM> at para 143 and 154.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> a position that was never pleaded by Way, that was not supported by any evidence, and that was untenable in law. The argument was an &ldquo;<EM>afterthought</EM>&rdquo; without merit.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Ibid</EM> at paras. 180.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> This position was taken by Way because Way knew that Clause 13 was unenforceable. The <EM>afterthought</EM> argument was nothing more than an attempt to obfuscate the matters at issue on the Motion in an attempt to avoid summary dismissal.</P>
<P>13. Despite Way's breach of the Rules, Schembri was intent on having the Motion heard. Mr. Wortzman concluded his oral argument in one day (as contemplated when the Motion was scheduled on consent). It quickly became apparent that Mr. Whiteley's submissions were going to take &ldquo;<EM>more than a day or two</EM>&rdquo; as he intended to take the Court through Way's 10-volume Responding Record.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Ibid</EM> at paras 96-97.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Mr. Wortzman advised that Court that in an effort to expedite the Motion, Schembri was prepared to withdraw his fallback legal position of bad conduct, <EM>&ldquo;except for the general purpose of saying that Schembri did not want to proceed with any business arrangements with Mr. Way</EM>.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Ibid</EM> at paras 97.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Those issues were still alive if the ROFR Action went to Trial.</P>
<P>14. Following the first two days of submissions, Way served a supplementary factum that for the first time attempted to address the enforceability of Clause 13. Through Way's supplementary factum he also again attempted to obfuscate the matters at issue on the Motion through a new argument that the Motion ought to be dismissed to &ldquo;<EM>condemn</EM>&rdquo; Schembri's conduct (being the withdrawal of his fallback position to expedite the Motion).<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Ibid</EM> at para 139.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Again, Schembri was forced to prepare responding materials to reply to Way's ever changing position at the Motion and costs were further increased.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI><UNDER>Reasonable Expectations/ The Principle of Indemnity</UNDER></TI>
<P>15. Way is no stranger to the costs of litigation. In this highly contentious litigation between Schembri and Way alone, the Courts have, <EM>inter alia</EM>, ordered costs against Way in the Main Action in the total amount of at least $338,052.33 and he has posted another $100,000 into Court because &ldquo;<EM>the court has to have some means of enforcing its processes, particularly where there is a wealthy party who does not follow court orders and appears to this court, that he would rather pay legal fees to complicate and delay matters than simply get on with the action</EM>&rdquo;.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Decision of the Honourable Justice Sloan dated December 23, 2016 at para 207.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>16. Way has vigorously pursued this Action. Way is a sophisticated litigant who had three gowned lawyers at the Motion, while Schembri had one. Way knows the costs of commencing and pursing such an Action and the consequences of failure. As set out by Justice Sloan, the parties have been at <EM>war</EM> since 2010. Way's Motion materials make it clear that he was prepared to defend his position in the ROFR Action at all costs and on any basis, reasonable or not. Way lost this &ldquo;war&rdquo; and accordingly, must now bear the burden.</P>
<P>17. Way sought $30,500,000.00 from Schembri arising from serious allegations of wrongdoing. It was reasonable for Schembri to defend himself, his family and his businesses from such unsubstantiated allegations.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI><UNDER>Quantum of Costs</UNDER></TI>
<P>18. As set out above, the ROFR Action was ordered tried together with the Main Action and common discoveries were ordered. The matters at issue in both Actions are interrelated and complex and to sever the costs associated with each Action and each step of the proceedings is, at times, impossible to do with precision.</P>
<P>19. The Bill of Costs is conservative and has been prepared to carefully reflect only time spent and costs incurred in relation to the ROFR Action. Certain costs, such as discoveries and the costs related to both Actions were shared 50%&mdash;50% with the Main Action in the Bill of Costs.</P>
<P>20. The amounts claimed by Schembri with respect to the ROFR Action and the Motion are reasonable, in accordance with the principles of indemnity, and should come as no surprise to Way. While such unfounded allegations typically result in substantial indemnity costs being awarded, Schembri seeks his costs on a partial indemnity scale.</P>
<P>21. Schembri is, <EM>prima facie</EM>, entitled to the entirety of his costs of the Action.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Mo v. Johnson</SOC><CITE>2012 ONSC 6307</CITE><PARANUM>23-24</PARANUM></CASEREF> (Tab 2).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> There is no reason to depart from the general rule or from the mandatory wording of Rule 57.03(1) which requires that the cost of a motion be paid within 30 days. The Defendants respectfully request the payment of their costs forthwith.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Rules of Civil Procedure</EM>, RRO 1990, Reg 194, R.57.03; <CASEREF><SOC>Net Connect v. Mobile Zone</SOC><CITE>2017 ONSC 1097</CITE><PARANUM>11</PARANUM></CASEREF> (Tab 3).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></BLOCK2>
</FREEFORM>
