<BLOCK1><TI>NOTICE OF MOTION (returnable February 8, 2018)</TI>
<P>The plaintiffs (collectively, the <BOLD>&ldquo;Way&rdquo;</BOLD>) will make a motion before Mr. Justice Sloan on February 8, 2018 at 10:00 a.m. or as soon after that time as the motion can be heard at the court house at 85 Frederick Street, Kitchener, Ontario, N2H 0A7.</P>
<P><BOLD>PROPOSED METHOD OF HEARING:</BOLD> The motion is to be heard orally.</P>
<P><BOLD>THE MOTION IS FOR:</BOLD></P>
<P><BOLD>1.</BOLD> A hearing together with a parallel motion (the <BOLD>&ldquo;Parallel Motion&rdquo;)</BOLD> in a related action bearing Court File No. CV-42-12 (the <BOLD>&ldquo;Main Action&rdquo;)</BOLD>;</P>
<P><BOLD>2.</BOLD> An Order:
<P1>(a) setting aside the order of the Local Registrar dated May 25, 2017 dismissing the within action for delay;</P1>
<P1>(b) requiring the defendant, Gordon Schembri <BOLD>(&ldquo;Schembri&rdquo;)</BOLD> to attend an examination for discovery in the within action and the Main Action from February 12 to 23, 2018, inclusive, or such further and/or other dates as fixed by this Honourable Court;</P1>
<P1>(c) costs of this motion on a substantial indemnity basis payable forthwith; and</P1>
<P1>(d) such further and other relief as counsel may advise and this Honourable Court deem just.</P1></P>
<P><BOLD>3.</BOLD> The motion is being brought as efforts by counsel for the plaintiffs to reach a resolution with counsel for the defendants in respect of the foregoing relief have been unsuccessful;</P>
<P><BOLD>THE GROUNDS FOR THE MOTION ARE:</BOLD></P>
<BLOCK2><TI>Background</TI>
<P><BOLD>4.</BOLD> Schembri commenced the Main Action in Toronto in February, 2010;</P>
<P><BOLD>5.</BOLD> The Main Action was transferred to Kitchener in 2011;</P>
<P><BOLD>6.</BOLD> Schembri amended the Statement of Claim in the Main Action in 2012 and again in 2013;</P>
<P><BOLD>7.</BOLD> Presently in the Main Action, Schembri and his companies are claiming relief including damages for tens of millions of dollars;</P>
<P><BOLD>8.</BOLD> The Main Action is defended;</P>
<P><BOLD>9.</BOLD> In addition, Way asserts a counterclaim, in part, to the effect that Schembri breached a shareholders' agreement by failing to comply with the right of first refusal provisions contained therein (the <BOLD>&ldquo;ROFR Provisions&rdquo;)</BOLD> so as to allow Way to participate in the acquisition and development of other properties located in Waterloo;</P>
<P><BOLD>10.</BOLD> Schembri's breach of the ROFR Provisions are now the subject matter of the ROFR Action;</P>
<P><BOLD>11.</BOLD> There are orders, on consent, in both the Main Action and the ROFR Action that these actions are to be tried together;</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI>Documentary Disclosure</TI>
<P><BOLD>12.</BOLD> Way swore an affidavit of documents on February 27, 2014.</P>
<P><BOLD>13.</BOLD> Counsel for Way notified Wortzman counsel for Schembri on February 20, 2014 of the types of documents Way expected Schembri to produce.</P>
<P><BOLD>14.</BOLD> Schembri swore an affidavit of documents on September 30, 2014 (the <BOLD>&ldquo;Schembri AoD&rdquo;)</BOLD>.</P>
<P><BOLD>15.</BOLD> The Schembri AoD ignored the outline set out in Exhibit &ldquo;A&rdquo; and, for the most part, lists court documents in the Main Action;</P>
<P><BOLD>16.</BOLD> Of note, Schembri did not even list the agreements of purchase and sale for the properties that are the subject matter of the ROFR Action (which would reveal the dates on which Schembri offered to purchase the properties);</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI>Schembri's Deception</TI>
<P><BOLD>17.</BOLD> Counsel for Way made extensive efforts, unsuccessfully, over several months to conclude an agreement with Schembri in respect of numerous procedural matters in both the Main Action and the ROFR Action;</P>
<P><BOLD>18.</BOLD> During the course of those extensive efforts, counsel for Schembri represented that Schembri would be bringing the Schembri ROFR SJ Motion;</P>
<P><BOLD>19.</BOLD> Consequently, Way caused motions to be brought in both the Main Action and the ROFR Action for various relief, including another revised timetable in the Main Action and a timetable in connection with the Schembri ROFR SJ Motion;</P>
<P><BOLD>20.</BOLD> Despite suggesting otherwise, Schembri did not serve any responding materials or conduct any cross-examination, and the orders in the Main Action and the ROFR Action were issued on consent</P>
<P><BOLD>21.</BOLD> By Order of Justice Broad dated September 4, 2014 (the <BOLD>&ldquo;ROFR Timetable Order&rdquo;)</BOLD>, the Court, among other things, imposed a timetable for the conduct of the Schembri ROFR SJ Motion, including the requirement that the motion record had to be served on or before September 30, 2014;</P>
<P><BOLD>22.</BOLD> The timetable in Main Action (for the examinations for discovery) had to accommodate the timetable for the Schembri ROFR SJ Motion (including the cross-examinations in connection therewith);</P>
<P><BOLD>23.</BOLD> Schembri breached the ROFR Timetable Order by failing to serve his motion record by September 30, 2014;</P>
<P><BOLD>24.</BOLD> Notwithstanding his breach, Schembri continued to represent he would be bringing the Schembri ROFR SJ Motion;</P>
<P><BOLD>25.</BOLD> Schembri deceived Way and this Honourable Court for the purpose of avoiding his examination for discovery in the Main Action and increasing the amount of costs being incurred by Way;</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI>Examinations for Discovery</TI>
<P><BOLD>26.</BOLD> Way has been examined over eighteen days and asked more than 15,000 questions in connection with both the Main Action and the ROFR Action (the <BOLD>&ldquo;Way Examination&rdquo;);</BOLD></P>
<P><BOLD>27.</BOLD> Following the completion of the Way Examination on April 26, 2017, Schembri subsequently set the Main Action down for trial, and, as a result, the Main Action was placed on the To Be Spoken To Court list for October 27, 2017;</P>
<P><BOLD>28.</BOLD> After various delays and cancellations by Schembri, the examination for discovery of Schembri finally commenced on June 28, 2017;</P>
<P><BOLD>29.</BOLD> Following extensive efforts over many months, the Parallel Motion is being brought to fix dates for the continuation of the examination for discovery of Schembri;</P>
<P><BOLD>30.</BOLD> The dates being sought in the Parallel Motion are from February 12 to 23, 2018, inclusive;</P>
<P><BOLD>31.</BOLD> Further and other dates available to the counsel for the plaintiffs are the weeks of February 26<SUP>th</SUP> and March 19<SUP>th</SUP>;</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI>The Registrar's Dismissal Order</TI>
<P><BOLD>32.</BOLD> By Order dated May 25, 2017, the ROFR Action was dismissed by the Registrar for delay (the <BOLD>&ldquo;Dismissal Order&rdquo;)</BOLD>;</P>
<P><BOLD>33.</BOLD> Upon learning of the Dismissal Order, counsel for the plaintiffs requested promptly that counsel for the defendants consent to an order setting aside the Dismissal Order;</P>
<P><BOLD>34.</BOLD> The defendatns are willing to consent to setting aside the Dismissal Order provided that a timetable be set for the Schembri ROFR SJ Motion;</P>
<P><BOLD>35.</BOLD> The plaintiffs object to a timetable being set for the Schembri ROFR SJ Motion as:
<P1>(a) It ignores the relief sought in the September 2016 Affidavit;</P1>
<P1>(b) the examination for discovery of Schembri in the Main Action and the ROFR Action has yet to be completed; and</P1>
<P1>(c) the plaintiffs have failed to comply with the Rules of Civil Proceeding concerning documentary disclosure;</P1></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI>Relief Sought</TI>
<P><BOLD>36.</BOLD> The palintiffs seek an Order:
<P1>(a) setting aside the Dismissal Order;</P1>
<P1>(b) requiring Schembri to attend an examination for discovery in the Main Action and in the ROFR Action from February 12<SUP>th</SUP> to 23<SUP>rd</SUP>, inclusive, or such other and/or further dates as may be fixed by this Honourable Court;</P1>
<P1>(c) costs of this motion on a substantial indemnity basis forthwith;</P1></P>
<P><BOLD>37.</BOLD> Rules 1.04, 1.05, 30, 31, 37, 60.12 of the <EM>Rules of Civil Procedure</EM>; and</P>
<P><BOLD>38.</BOLD> Such further and other grounds as counsel may advise and this Honourable Court deems just.</P>
<P><BOLD>THE FOLLOWING DOCUMENTARY EVIDENCE</BOLD> will be used at the hearing of motion:</P>
