<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="I">AFFIDAVIT</TI>
<P>I, John Paul Ventrella, of the City of Toronto, in the Province of Ontario, MAKE OATH AND SAY:</P>
<P>1. I am a Lawyer with the law firm of Teplitsky, Colson LLP, the lawyers for the Plaintiffs in the Main Action (as that term is hereinafter defined) and the Defendants to the ROFR Action (as that term is hereinafter defined) (collectively &ldquo;Schembri&rdquo;), and, as such, have knowledge of the matters contained in this affidavit. Where I do not have personal knowledge, I have stated the source of my knowledge and do verily believe it to be true.</P>
<P>2. There are two companion actions being case-managed by the Honourable Mr. Justice Sloan:
<P1>(a) The &ldquo;Main Action&rdquo; bearing Court File no. C-42-11 which was commenced in Toronto in 2010 and transferred to Kitchener in 2011; and</P1>
<P1>(b) The &ldquo;ROFR Action&rdquo; bearing Court File No C-457-12, which was commenced by way of Notice of Action dated May 25, 2012.</P1></P>
<P>3. On September 4, 2014, the Honourable Mr. Justice Broad ordered on consent, <EM>inter alia</EM>, that the Main Action and the ROFR Action be tried together. Attached hereto and marked as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;A&rdquo;</BOLD> to this my affidavit are true copies of the Orders of Justice Broad dated September 4, 2014 in both the Main Action and ROFR Action (&ldquo;Broad Order&rdquo;).</P>
<P>4. Pursuant to the Broad Order in the ROFR Action, a timetable was set for the delivery of materials related to the Plaintiffs' proposed motion for Summary Judgment.</P>
<P>5. I am advised by Mr. Wortzman and do verily believe that Schembri did not pursue the summary judgment motion in the ROFR Action at that time, and instead proceeded to examine the Defendants in the Main Action for discovery. I am further advised by Mr. Wortzman and do verily believe that Schembri never abandoned their intention to pursue the summary judgment motion.</P>
<BLOCK2><TI><UNDER>PROCEEDING IN THE MAIN ACTION</UNDER></TI>
<P>6. Between late 2014 and late 2016, the Plaintiffs experienced significant difficulty in proceeding with the Main Action as a result of, <EM>inter alia</EM>, Way's conduct throughout examinations for discovery. A more complete and particularized history of the delay experienced as a result of Way's conduct is outlined in my affidavit sworn on January 23, 2018, and filed in support of the Plaintiffs' motion returnable on February 8, 2018, with respect to the Main Action (&ldquo;Original Affidavit&rdquo;).</P>
<P>7. The &ldquo;<EM>tortured</EM>&rdquo; history of this matter is also clearly summarized in various Endorsements of the Honourable Justice Sloan, including His Honour's Endorsement dated December 23, 2016 at, <EM>inter alia</EM>, paragraphs 181 through 197, wherein Justice Sloan found, among other things, that:
<P1>(a) &ldquo;<EM>trying to get the defendants' undertakings answered has been akin to &lsquo;pulling teeth&rsquo;</EM>&rdquo;;</P1>
<P1>(b) &ldquo;<EM>It is evident an I find as fact, that Mr. Way did not fulfill his obligations to answer his undertakings in anything close to an appropriate fashion and in an appropriate time frame</EM>&rdquo;; and</P1>
<P1>(c) &ldquo;<EM>Mr. Way put in an extremely lacklustre effort to comply with his obligations with respect to his undertakings and refusals</EM>.&rdquo;</P1></P>
<P>8. Attached hereto and marked collectively as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;B&rdquo;</BOLD> to this my affidavit is a true copy of the Endorsement of Mr. Justice Sloan dated December 23, 2016 (&ldquo;December 23<SUP>rd</SUP> Endorsement&rdquo;) along with a copy of the corresponding Cost Endorsement of Justice Sloan dated January 30, 2017 (&ldquo;Cost Endorsement&rdquo;).</P>
<P>9. The December 23<SUP>rd</SUP> Endorsement, and Cost Endorsement were released by Justice Sloan following, <EM>inter alia</EM>, the hearing of a Motion to Strike Way's pleadings in the Main Action. The said motion was argued over 5 days in September, November and December 2016 (&ldquo;Motion to Strike&rdquo;).</P>
<P>10. In preparation for the Motion to Strike, the parties participated in a conference call with Justice Sloan on or about August 25, 2016, at which time a timetable was established for the hearing of Schembri's Motion to Strike.</P>
<P>11. In this regard, attached hereto and marked as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;C&rdquo;</BOLD> to this my affidavit is true copy of a letter from Mr. Kulathungam to Mr. Whiteley dated August 25, 2016, clearly setting out the timetable for the Motion to Strike as confirmed by Justice Sloan as follows, <EM>inter alia</EM>:
<P1>(a) Schembri to serve motion materials by August 29, 2016;</P1>
<P1>(b) Way to serve responding materials by September 6, 2016;</P1>
<P1>(c) Motion returnable on September 21, 2016.
<P2>(the &ldquo;Timetable&rdquo;)</P2></P1></P>
<P>12. I am advised by Mr. Kulathungam that at the time of the August 25, 2016, conference call, Way did not in any way advise Justice Sloan or our office that they intended to proceed with any motions with respect to the Main Action, ROFR Action or otherwise.</P>
<P>13. In accordance with the Timetable, Schembri served their materials with respect to the Motion to Strike returnable September 21, 2016. Attached hereto and marked as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;D&rdquo;</BOLD> to this my affidavit is a true copy of a letter from myself to Mr. Whiteley dated August 29, 2016, serving the said motion materials (without attachments).</P>
<P>14. Way breached the Timetable in that they failed to serve any responding materials with respect to the Motion to Strike by September 6, 2016.</P>
<P>15. On or about September 8, 2016, our office received a letter by way of e-mail from Mr. Whiteley, <EM>inter alia</EM>, serving:
<P1>(a) a Notice of Motion in the Main Action for a motion returnable on September 21, 2016; and</P1>
<P1>(b) the affidavit of Way sworn September 6, 2016 (without attachments) in support of Way's proposed motion.</P1></P>
<P>16. Attached hereto and marked as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;E&rdquo;</BOLD> to this my affidavit is a true copy of Mr. Whiteley's letter of September 8, 2016 (with Notice of Motion only).</P>
<P>17. On or about September 9, 2016, Mr. Wortzman wrote to Mr. Whiteley, among other things:
<P1>(a) Confirming that his office's never previously advised our office or Justice Sloan that Way would be bringing a motion on September 21, 2016; and</P1>
<P1>(b) Advising that our office would be objecting to Way's proposed motion being heard on September 21, 2016.</P1></P>
<P>18. Attached hereto and marked as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;F&rdquo;</BOLD> to this my affidavit is a true copy of Mr. Wortzman's letter dated September 9, 2016 to Mr. Whiteley.</P>
<P>19. Following service of Way's motion materials for a motion returnable on September 21, 2017, with respect to the Main Action, Mr. Whitely also served a Motion Record with respect to a motion in the ROFR Action which was also to be returnable on September 21, 2016.</P>
<P>20. Way's proposed motion with respect to the ROFR Action sought, among other things, that Schembri be barred from bringing a summary judgment motion, in whole or in part, in the ROFR Action. An affidavit sworn by Way on September 16, 2016 was provided in support of Way's proposed motion.</P>
<P>21. Again, Way's proposed motion in the ROFR Action was not canvassed during the August 25, 2016, conference call with Justice Sloan or contemplated when the September 21, 2016 motion date was set. Attached hereto and marked as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;G&rdquo;</BOLD> to this my affidavit is a true copy of the Notice of Motion with respect Mr. Whiteley's proposed motion in the ROFR Action (&ldquo;ROFR Motion&rdquo;)</P>
<P>22. Ultimately, Justice Sloan refused to hear any arguments with respect to Way's ROFR Motion during the hearing of the Motion to Strike and adjourned the said motion to a date to be set by the Trial Coordinator.</P>
<P>23. After arguing the Motion to Strike over a 4 <TEXTFRAC>1/2</TEXTFRAC> day period and the release of Justice Sloan's December 23<SUP>rd</SUP> Endorsement, Mr. Whitley has taken no steps whatsoever to have Way's ROFR Motion heard. It would appear that the said motion has been abandoned and that Way was no longer seeking an Order to bar Schembri from bringing a summary judgment motion in the ROFR Action.</P>
<P>24. Way's ROFR Motion, while served in September 2016, was never again pursued. It has been dormant for about 15 months.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI><UNDER>MAY 19, 2017 CONFERENCE CALL</UNDER></TI>
<P>25. Following issuance of the December 23<SUP>rd</SUP> Endorsement and Cost Endorsement, Schembri continued to encounter difficulties in moving the Main Action forward. Particulars of the difficulties encountered by Schembri in moving the Main Action forward are set out in my Original Affidavit beginning at paragraph 31.</P>
<P>26. A conference call was scheduled before Justice Sloan on May 19, 2017.</P>
<P>27. One of the main issues that Schembri sought to address during the said conference call was with respect to obtaining an Order from the Court allowing Schembri to set the Main Action down for Trial <UNDER>without prejudice to their rights to bring a summary judgment motion in the ROFR Action.</UNDER></P>
<P>28. In this regard, on or around May 18, 2017, our office served Mr. Whiteley's office with a Motion Record in support of Schembri's summary judgment motion in the ROFR Action (&ldquo;ROFR SJ Motion&rdquo;) and advised Mr. Whitely that we would be seeking a return date for the said motion during the May 19, 2017, conference call. Attached hereto and marked as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;H&rdquo;</BOLD> to this my affidavit is a true copy of our letter to Mr. Whiteley (without attachments).</P>
<P>29. On or around May 19, 2017, the parties participated in a telephone conference call with Justice Sloan to address various issues with respect to the Main Action and ROFR Action. I was a participant in the conference call along with Messrs. Wortzman, Kulathungam and Whiteley.</P>
<P>30. During the May 19 conference call, the parties specifically addressed Schembri's proposed ROFR SJ Motion. At the conclusion of the May 19 conference call, Justice Sloan, <EM>inter alia</EM>:
<P1>(a) Ordered that Schembri be entitled to set the Main Action down for Trial without prejudice to their rights to bring the ROFR SJ Motion;</P1>
<P1>(b) Directed Mr. Wortzman to circulate a draft Order with respect to setting the Main Action down for Trial without prejudice to bring the ROFR SJ Motion; and</P1>
<P1>(c) Advised counsel to seek the assistance of the Trial Coordinator to schedule the return date for the ROFR SJ Motion.</P1></P>
<P>31. Justice Sloan's Order with respect to the ROFR SJ Motion was partly confirmed in a letter to our office from Mr. Whiteley's office dated May 19, 2017, which stated, <EM>inter alia</EM>:
<QUOTE><P><EM>I confirm that Justice Sloan has directed you to prepare and circulate a draft Order providing for the matter to be set down for trial, subject to a carve out for the Motion Record in the ROFR Action containing the Notice of Motion dated May 11, 2017 and the affidavit of Mr. Schembri sworn May 17, 2017</EM>.</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>32. Attached hereto and marked as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;I&rdquo;</BOLD> to this my affidavit is a true copy of Mr., Whiteley's letter dated May 19, 2017.</P>
<P>33. On or about May 23, 2017, I provided Mr. Whiteley with a draft Order in accordance with Justice Sloan's direction of May 19, 2017. Attached hereto and marked as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;J&rdquo;</BOLD> to this my affidavit is a true copy of my said letter to Mr. Whiteley with draft Order attached.</P>
<P>34. On or about May 24, 2017, Mr. Wortzman also wrote to Ms. Cox, being the Trial Coordinator seeking available dates for the ROFR SJ Motion. Attached hereto and marked as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;K&rdquo;</BOLD> to this my affidavit is a true copy of Mr. Wortzman's letter to Ms. Cox.</P>
<P>35. Mr. Whiteley disagreed with the draft Order provided by our office and, in this regard, served us with a copy of his proposed draft Order. Attached hereto and marked as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;L&rdquo;</BOLD> to this my affidavit is a true copy of Mr. Whiteley's letter dated May 24, 2017, including draft Order.</P>
<P>36. It is important to note that Mr. Whiteley's proposed draft Order expressly provided for leave for Schembri to set the matter down for trial without prejudice to the ROFR SJ Motion. Of contention was the fact that Mr. Whiteley's preamble to the proposed draft Order was inaccurate and the Order sought to include, <EM>inter alia</EM>, relief that was not granted by Justice Sloan, including an Order that Schembri set the matter down for Trial by no later than May 31, 2017.</P>
<P>37. Attached hereto and marked as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;M&rdquo;</BOLD> to this my affidavit is a true copy of Mr. Wortzman's letter written to Mr. Whiteley dated May 25, 2017, in response to Mr. Whiteley's May 24 letter which states, <EM>inter alia</EM>:
<QUOTE><P><EM>Your Order makes it seem as though a motion was heard on May 19, 2017 to compel Mr. Schembri to set the action down for trial. That never happened</EM>.</P>
<P><EM>Furthermore, paragraph 2 of your</EM> <UNDER><EM>draft</EM></UNDER> <EM>Order is not sufficient</EM>. <BOLD><EM>What we requested and what we received, was an Order granting Mr. Schembri leave to continue with the summary judgment motion and the ROFR action notwithstanding the fact that he sets the main action down for trial</EM>.</BOLD></P>
<P><EM>Please approve the</EM> <UNDER><EM>draft</EM></UNDER> <EM>Order we sent to you as to form and content so that we can set the main action down for trial</EM>.</P>
<P>[emphasis added]</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>38. Mr. Whiteley would not approve the draft Order dated May 19, 2017 prepared by our office as to form and content. The draft Order remains unissued and un-entered.</P>
<P>39. Attached hereto and marked collectively as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;N&rdquo;</BOLD> to this my affidavit is further correspondence as between our office and Mr. Whiteley's office with respect to the draft Order. In an attempt to resolve matters and have the draft Order issued, Mr. Wortzman expressly advised Mr. Whiteley that the Order could be &ldquo;<EM>without prejudice to you seeking whatever order you want, if and when you formally bring on for hearing the motions that had been adjourned last September</EM>.&rdquo;</P>
<P>40. On or about May 31, 2017, Mr. Wortzman also wrote further to Ms. Cox, <EM>inter alia</EM>, again seeking return dates for the ROFR SJ Motion. Attached hereto and marked as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;O&rdquo;</BOLD> to this my affidavit is a true copy of Mr. Wortzman's letter to Ms. Cox dated May 31, 2017.</P>
<P>41. We never received motion dates from Ms. Cox and this may be, as will be set out below, because the ROFR Action was dismissed for delay.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI><UNDER>THE ROFR ACTION IS DISMISSED</UNDER></TI>
<P>42. Schembri intended to set the Main Action down for Trial. Out of an abundance of caution, they could not do so as Way would not approve the draft Order of Justice Sloan dated May 19, 2017, allowing Schembri to set the matter down for Trial without prejudice to their rights to bring a summary judgment motion in the ROFR Action.</P>
<P>43. Schembri's Trial Record was served upon counsel for the Defendants on or about June 6, 2017. I specifically advised Mr. Whiteley that we would not be filing the Trial Record with the Court until such time as the draft Order was approved as to form and content and issued and entered by the Court. Attached hereto and marked as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;P&rdquo;</BOLD> to this my affidavit is a true copy of my letter to Mr. Whiteley in this regard.</P>
<P>44. In or around June of 2017, our office received an Order dismissing the ROFR Action for delay by mail from the Court. I cannot recall the exact date that the Order was received. Attached hereto and marked as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;Q&rdquo;</BOLD> to this my affidavit is a true copy of the Registrar's Order dated May 25, 2017 (&ldquo;Dismissal Order&rdquo;).</P>
<P>45. Given that the ROFR Action was dismissed for delay, the ROFR SJ Motion was no longer necessary. Schembri filed the Trial Record with respect to the Main Action. Attached hereto and marked collectively as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;R&rdquo;</BOLD> to this my affidavit are true copies of correspondence from Mr. Wortzman to Mr. Whiteley dated July 5 and 10, 2017.</P>
<P>46. Schembri has continually and consistently advised Way that they would consent to an Order setting aside the Dismissal Order subject to Way agreeing to a reasonable timetable for the hearing of the ROFR SJ Motion. Way refused to do so.</P>
<P>47. Attached hereto and marked collectively as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;S&rdquo; to</BOLD> this my affidavit are true copies of correspondence from our office to Mr. Whiteley's office, <EM>inter alia</EM>, with respect to setting aside the registrars dismissal and establishing a timetable for the ROFR SJ Motion.</P>
<P>48. Despite the fact that Schembri's motion materials for the ROFR SJ motion were served in May of 2017, Way will not agree to a timetable for the said motion and has not bothered to serve any responding materials.</P>
<P>49. Way had also not served any motion material to set aside the Dismissal Order until last week.</P>
<P>50. Schembri remains prepared to consent to set aside the Dismissal Order, subject to a timetable for the ROFR SJ Motion being agreed upon or ordered.</P>
<P>51. I swear this affidavit in response to the motions brought by the Defendants returnable on February 8, 2018, and in support of the Plaintiffs' cross-motion, and for no other or improper purpose.</P>
